[White "Quickstarter Guide: Sveshnikov"]
[Black "Sveshnikov 9.Nab1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B33"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2123892846829640"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Bg5 {The main move by far and very logical. White wants to occupy the beautiful [d5]-square without exchanging their knight.} a6 8. Na3 b5 (8... b5 {Again, White has two main options. So far, we have seen} 9. Nd5 {in quite detail. Let's see another knight jump that has gained some popularity recently.}) 9. Nab1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga2a4] This new fashionable line has been tried by many top players who are searching for some less explored paths in the Sveshnikov Defence and, most notably, has been recommended by Anish Giri in his Chessable course. The idea is to unblock the a-pawn to be able to go [a4] fast and also to get firm control of the [d5]-square by playing [Bxf6], followed by [Nd5] and [Nbc3] in some lines. If after [a4], Black continues with ...[b4], then the [b1]-knight can sometimes head to [c4].} Be7 10. Bxf6 {[%cal Gc3d5] White is preparing the [Nd5] jump.} Bxf6 11. a4 $1 {The critical continuation. White wants to create some weaknesses and get the [c4]-square for his bishop or knight.} b4 12. Nd5 Bg5 13. Bc4 O-O 14. O-O {Here, many moves have been tried. My suggestion is finishing development.} Be6 $1 {[%cal Ga6a5,Ga8c8] Followed by ...[a5] and ...[Rc8].} 15. Qd3 a5 16. c3 Rc8 17. Rd1 h5 {This novelty is a useful move, taking space and waiting for White to show their intentions. We'll take on [c3] later.} *

