1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Bg5 {The main move by far and very logical. White wants to occupy the beautiful [d5]-square without exchanging their knight.} a6 8. Na3 b5 (8... b5 {White has two main options} 9. Bxf6 {and Nd5 . Though 9.Nab1 (has also gained some popularity recently, thanks to a course by Anish Giri on this very website! But we will be well prepared and have a nice solution including a very interesting novelty hey Anish, you have to click on buy if you wanna know!.)}) 9. Nd5 {That's the main and most logical move. There is no hurry to take on [f6] as the knight is pinned.} (9. Bxf6 {is also a main move as it forces Black to damage their structure.}) 9... Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 {A very popular alternative to the previously covered [c3], leading to solid positions.} b4 12. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2b4,Gd5b4]} a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Here, White has tried many different moves.} 13. g3 {Clearly, the most played.} h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4] A rarely met continuation, played by Magnus Carlsen himself! Black is asking White to make a decision: whether allowing ...[h4] or stopping it, but that weakens the light squares on the kingside.} 14. h4 g6 {Getting ready for castle.} 15. Bh3 {And now it is important to sidestep the trade.} Bb7 $1 {[%csl Gb7] We have already learnt that the exchange of light-squared bishops favours White. The only exception is when we can bring the bishop to [e6] and recapture ...[fxe6]. Here, however, after playing ...[h5] and ...[g6], we cannot weaken the kingside anymore, and thus, ...[Bb7] remains our only sensible option.} 16. O-O Bg7 {[%cal Gc6e7] Preparing the thematic ...[Ne7].} 17. a3 $6 ({This is premature, as we'll see now. White's best is} 17. Qd3 {taking control of [b3] to be able to go [a3]. Instead,} O-O 18. a3 bxa3 19. Rxa3 {. transposes to the main line.}) 17... b3 $1 18. Nce3 a4 {[%cal Gc6d4] Black is already better as White cannot prevent ...[Nd4].} *

