1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Bg5 {The main move by far and very logical. White wants to occupy the beautiful [d5]-square without exchanging their knight.} a6 8. Na3 b5 (8... b5 {White has two main options} 9. Bxf6 {and Nd5 . Though 9.Nab1 (has also gained some popularity recently, thanks to a course by Anish Giri on this very website! But we will be well prepared and have a nice solution including a very interesting novelty hey Anish, you have to click on buy if you wanna know!.)}) 9. Nd5 {That's the main and most logical move. There is no hurry to take on [f6] as the knight is pinned.} (9. Bxf6 {is also a main move as it forces Black to damage their structure.}) 9... Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. a4 {The most critical try.} bxa4 {[%cal Gb8b2] Now we can see one of the advantages of placing the rook on [b8].} 14. Ncb4 Nxb4 {Here, both recaptures are equally popular.} 15. cxb4 Bd7 {We prefer to keep the [a4]-pawn alive rather than [a6].} 16. Rxa4 {This is still possible!} a5 $1 {My suggestion.} 17. h4 {An important intermediate move to force the bishop to retreat to a more passive position.} Bh6 18. Rxa5 Rxb4 {[%csl Ra5] The point.} 19. Nxb4 Qxa5 20. Qxd6 Qa1+ 21. Qd1 Qxb2 $10 {[%cal Ge8g8] With equality.} *

