1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Bg5 {The main move by far and very logical. White wants to occupy the beautiful [d5]-square without exchanging their knight.} a6 8. Na3 b5 (8... b5 {White has two main options} 9. Bxf6 {and Nd5 . Though 9.Nab1 (has also gained some popularity recently, thanks to a course by Anish Giri on this very website! But we will be well prepared and have a nice solution including a very interesting novelty hey Anish, you have to click on buy if you wanna know!.)}) 9. Nd5 {That's the main and most logical move. There is no hurry to take on [f6] as the knight is pinned.} (9. Bxf6 {is also a main move as it forces Black to damage their structure.}) 9... Be7 {White has tried a number of different moves here, but many of them are simply dubious or even losing. Let's see an example.} 10. Nxe7 {A solid option, but we will definitely have an easier life after exchanging our passive bishop for the strong [d5]-knight.} Nxe7 {[%cal Gf6e4] Here, White has a choice between eliminating the [f6]-knight or trying to protect the central pawn.} 11. Bxf6 {The most played, solving the [e4]-problem and damaging our pawn structure. However, we have already seen in the previous variations that having doubled pawns on the f-file gives us a good dynamic play with ...[f5] and ...[d5] ideas.} gxf6 12. c4 {Making sure ...[d5] is not coming anytime soon. This might be the case, but we have another pawn willing to advance.} f5 $1 {It is important to challenge White's centre quickly.} 13. cxb5 $2 {This is bad as it allows Black to totally dominate the centre.} fxe4 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 14. Nc4 ({We literally don't care about} 14. bxa6 {, when we'll just go} O-O {and soon ...[d5].}) 14... Nf5 {[%cal Gf5d4]} 15. bxa6 Nd4 {[%csl Ge5,Ge4,Gd6][%cal Ge8g8,Gd6d5] The knight is very powerful on [d4], and the d-pawn is ready to advance. White's life is extremely difficult here.} *

