1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Bg5 {The main move by far and very logical. White wants to occupy the beautiful [d5]-square without exchanging their knight.} a6 8. Na3 b5 (8... b5 {White has two main options} 9. Bxf6 {and Nd5 . Though 9.Nab1 (has also gained some popularity recently, thanks to a course by Anish Giri on this very website! But we will be well prepared and have a nice solution including a very interesting novelty hey Anish, you have to click on buy if you wanna know!.)}) 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. c3 ({White's main choice together with} 11. Bd3 {, and may transpose to the same line.}) 11... f5 (11... f5 {Of course, when allowed, we seize our chance to push the f-pawn. Note that now} 12. Bd3 Ne7 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 {transposes to the 11.Bd3 line.}) 12. exf5 {Clearly, the most played.} Bxf5 13. Nc2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc2e3] White is executing the standard knight manoeuvre heading to [e3], from where it will support the centralised [d5]-knight.} O-O 14. Nce3 Be6 {[%csl Ge6] The bishop should be kept on this diagonal, as going to [g6] would invite a [h4]-[h5] push.} 15. Bd3 f5 16. O-O e4 $5 {[%cal Gf5f4]} (16... Kh8 {is also a very decent option with similar ideas. I offer it as an alternative.}) 17. Nf4 {White cannot allow Black to expand further with ...[f4].} Bf7 18. Bc2 Be5 19. Nfd5 Qg5 {[%cal Gf5f4] Preparing ...[f4].} 20. f4 {The most principled reply.} exf3 21. Qxf3 Bh5 22. Qh3 f4 (22... f4 {White has a choice here.} 23. Nf5 {can be met by} Ra7 {making sure the h-pawn is protected.}) (22... f4 23. Nc7 {leads to this crazy line.}) *

