1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Bg5 {The main move by far and very logical. White wants to occupy the beautiful [d5]-square without exchanging their knight.} a6 8. Na3 b5 (8... b5 {White has two main options} 9. Bxf6 {and Nd5 . Though 9.Nab1 (has also gained some popularity recently, thanks to a course by Anish Giri on this very website! But we will be well prepared and have a nice solution including a very interesting novelty hey Anish, you have to click on buy if you wanna know!.)}) 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 {Stopping ...[f5] for now.} Ne7 {Insisting on pushing the f-pawn. White has tried many different moves here, but to tell you the truth, only two are decent. The general rule is that if White allows us to exchange on [d5] and is forced to take back with the pawn, we get an immediate advantage as we can comfortably advance our f-pawn.} 12. Nxe7 {The best, as will become clear after checking all the sidelines in the main chapter.} Qxe7 13. O-O {A logical developing move, but here we get a chance to go ...[d5] again.} d5 $5 ({This is rare compared to} 13... O-O {. However, I do not see how White can take advantage of this move order, which can later transpose to our main line.}) (13... d5 {For instance, if White continues with} 14. c3 O-O 15. Nc2 f5 16. exf5 {, we'll reach the main line with 14.O-O. 16.exd5 is also a transposition. See here.}) 14. exd5 f5 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ge5e4] Of course! This is the whole point behind the pawn sacrifice.} 15. d6 {This can be tried, taking into account that our king is still in the centre and grabbing the pawn would be bad.} Qe6 16. c4 ({An interesting try to open up the position and exploit our weaknesses. In case of} 16. Be2 {, we continue our usual plan with} e4 {hitting the [b2]-pawn.} 17. c3 {and now simply} O-O {with a very pleasant position. The [d6]-pawn becomes a weakness and ...[Rd8] is coming. Our two bishops compensate for the structural inconveniences and a material deficit.}) 16... e4 17. cxb5 {Now that the pawn has occupied the [b5]-square, we get a chance of taking on [d6].} Qxd6 18. Bc4 Qxd1 19. Raxd1 Ke7 $1 {The king is feeling safe in the centre. Now, of course, White has a choice.} 20. Rd2 {One of the possible ways to continue.} axb5 21. Nxb5 ({Or} 21. Bxb5 Be6 {taking control of the important diagonal and putting pressure on the white pawns.}) 21... Be6 22. Bxe6 fxe6 23. b3 Be5 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gh8b8] White has two connected passed pawns, but they are not really advancing. Besides, the knight is terribly restricted by our bishop and rook, offering us decent play.} *

