1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Bg5 {The main move by far and very logical. White wants to occupy the beautiful [d5]-square without exchanging their knight.} a6 8. Na3 b5 (8... b5 {White has two main options} 9. Bxf6 {and Nd5 . Though 9.Nab1 (has also gained some popularity recently, thanks to a course by Anish Giri on this very website! But we will be well prepared and have a nice solution including a very interesting novelty hey Anish, you have to click on buy if you wanna know!.)}) 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 {Stopping ...[f5] for now.} Ne7 {Insisting on pushing the f-pawn. White has tried many different moves here, but to tell you the truth, only two are decent. The general rule is that if White allows us to exchange on [d5] and is forced to take back with the pawn, we get an immediate advantage as we can comfortably advance our f-pawn.} 12. Nxe7 {The best, as will become clear after checking all the sidelines in the main chapter.} Qxe7 13. c4 $5 {An interesting option taking firm control not for long, though! of [d5] and trying to destroy our queenside at some point.} f5 {We cannot wait and watch White consolidating their position. Dynamic play is our main gun as from the strategical point of view, our position is not good, to put it mildly.} 14. O-O (14. cxb5 {would give us a dream position after} d5 {∓ , White will no longer be able to keep the centre closed.}) 14... O-O {Here, White has a wide choice of options, and we have to check at least some of them.} 15. Qh5 {The most ambitious option, tried by some very strong grandmasters. Here, I recommend you continue with quite a rare idea played by Magnus himself.} d5 $5 {It looks crazy to put the pawn on a square defended twice, but we have already seen that in the Sveshnikov, we do not count the pawns.} 16. cxd5 Qd8 $1 {[%cal Gf5e4,Gf7f5] Removing the queen to make ...[fxe4] and ...[f5] work. With the queen on [e7], this is not possible due to [d6] ideas. Another point is that Black is targeting the d-pawn, so after [exf5], we can take back on [d5]. White is not able to prevent both and needs to make a choice.} 17. exf5 {The most popular.} Qxd5 18. Rad1 {Probably the most unpleasant, forcing us to transpose to an endgame where some precise moves from our side will be required.} e4 19. Bxb5 Qxf5 20. Qxf5 Bxf5 (20... Bxf5 {It makes sense for White to exchange one of the bishops with} 21. Bd7 {and try to put some pressure in the endgame with active rooks. However, after a few precise moves, we should not face any serious trouble. After} Bxd7 22. Rxd7 Bxb2 23. Nc4 Bg7 24. Rfd1 {and now I believe I found the easiest way to achieve draw.} Rab8 {has never been tried in an over-the-board game. You can see more details here.}) *

