1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c4 {[%cal Gd1a4] By far, the most played. White protects the [d5]-pawn and opens up the way for his queen. Here, [Qa4] is already a threat, so we need to move the knight to make sure our [d6]-pawn is protected by the bishop.} (9. Be2 {is too slow and allows us to solve all the problems with} a6 {. Now, both retreats have their drawbacks.} 10. Na3 {allows} Qa5+ {and the [d5]-pawn is falling. 10.Nc3 Ng6 followed by ...[Be7], ...[O-O] and ...[f5] with an easy game.}) (9. Qf3 {is an attempt to be tricky, having in mind [Qc3] or [Qa3], but we can easily get a comfortable position with} a6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Qa4 {The most critical.} Bd7 11. Qb4 {White needs to unpin because ...[a6] was a threat.} Qb8 $5 {This looks passive, but it's the best way to protect [d6].} 12. Be3 {[%cal Gc4c5] This used to be the main line, with similar ideas as after [h4]. The threat is [c5].} a6 13. Nc3 a5 {My suggestion.} 14. Qa3 $5 ({This looks smarter, avoiding ...a4 coming with a tempo. Compare this line to} 14. Qb3 a4 {, covered here.}) 14... Be7 15. O-O-O O-O 16. Kb1 ({After} 16. Bd3 {, we have a nice jump} Nh4 {heading to [f5] and maybe [d4].}) (16. g3 {restricts the knight but weakens the light-squares.} Bg4 17. Rd2 {and now the typical} e4 {followed by ...[Ne5].}) 16... Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4f5,Gf5d4]} 17. Na4 {The already well-known manoeuvre of our line. Here we have an interesting bishop regrouping.} Bf5+ 18. Ka1 Bc2 {It is not obvious at first sight why we need to bring the bishop here.} 19. Rc1 {An obvious reply. Here, we have no choice.} Bxa4 {Now, the natural question is why we didn't take on [a4] immediately but played ...[Bf5]-...[Bc2] first.} 20. Qxa4 Nf5 21. Bd2 Qa7 22. Bd3 Qxf2 {[%csl Rc1,Rd2] And the bishop is hanging on d2. If we had played exactly the same line with 17...Bxa4 immediately, then the rook would be on [d1] protecting the bishop, and 20...Qxf2 would lose due to 21.Rhf1 .} *

