6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Qa4 {The most critical.} Bd7 11. Qb4 {White needs to unpin because ...[a6] was a threat.} Qb8 $5 {This looks passive, but it's the best way to protect [d6].} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] The inclusion of this move, which came into fashion after the Carlsen-Caruana match, forces Black to slightly weaken his kingside.} h5 {Black should not allow White to advance any further. White's idea is to have a target on [h5] once Black goes for short castle. It is true that we will not be able to save this pawn, but in exchange, we get enough counterplay. It should also be mentioned that just as our [h5]-pawn, the one on [h4] might also become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. g3 {White wants to stabilise first and then start to attack the [h5]-pawn.} O-O 16. Be2 {Here, we accept the fact that the [h5]-pawn is going to be lost. In exchange, we can get a decent initiative by playing energetically.} b5 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Bxh5 Bd8 {[%cal Gd8a5,Gg6e7,Ge7f5] Trying to activate the bishop via [a5] and liberating the [e7]-square for our knight, which can jump further to [f5]. The line continues here.} *

