6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Qa4 {The most critical.} Bd7 11. Qb4 {White needs to unpin because ...[a6] was a threat.} Qb8 $5 {This looks passive, but it's the best way to protect [d6].} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] The inclusion of this move, which came into fashion after the Carlsen-Caruana match, forces Black to slightly weaken his kingside.} h5 {Black should not allow White to advance any further. White's idea is to have a target on [h5] once Black goes for short castle. It is true that we will not be able to save this pawn, but in exchange, we get enough counterplay. It should also be mentioned that just as our [h5]-pawn, the one on [h4] might also become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. Na4 {A logical follow-up after we have weakened our [b6]-square.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ga4b6,Ga8d8] Liberating the rook. Here, White has a few interesting options.} (15... Nxh4 $2 {is not a good idea due to} 16. Nb6 Nf5 17. Bd2 $1 Ra7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. O-O-O {and our king cannot find a safe shelter.}) 16. Nb6 Rd8 {Now again White has a choice and has to decide where to put his king.} 17. Nxd7 ({Grabbing the bishop might look attractive, but we are relieved to exchange some pieces due to our lack of space. White can also try} 17. g3 {when, as usual, we prepare ...[Ne5] with} e4 {and after} 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19. Be2 Ne5 {, the white king would look for a home in the kingside. See here.}) 17... Qxd7 18. O-O-O (18. g3 {is a consolidating move, but as usual, its drawback are the weakened light-squares.} O-O {bringing the king to the queenside is interesting, but we'll meet} 19. O-O-O {with} e4 {followed by ...[Ne5]. ...[Rb8] and ...[b5] could be our next steps.}) {Note that 19.Be2 is not winning a pawn as we have 19...Qf5 20.Kf1 and, of course, we go for 20...e4 21.Kg2 Bf6 22.Rad1 Ne5 with a complicated position.} 18... O-O (18... Rc8 {is somehow more useful for White as he wanted to go} 19. Kb1 {anyway. Though} Nxh4 {is possible, I don't like it much as it gives White some initiative. After} 20. g3 Nf5 21. Bh3 g6 22. f4 {, our position looks dangerous.}) 19. g3 e4 {[%cal Gg6e5] As usual. Once the pawn moves to [g3], ...[e4] works perfectly. We have a nice game, interesting to play for a win for both sides. Here, I check different options for White. Our coverage continues here.} *

