1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c3 (9. c3 {This is considered less dangerous than 9.c4, the main move we have seen so far, but still needs to be taken seriously as there are some tricks we need to be aware of. For example,} a6 $4 {is premature due to} 10. Qa4 {, and we don't have a good defence against the discovered check.}) 9... Nf5 $1 {It's a bit counter-intuitive to bring the knight to [f5] with a pawn on [c3], but it's the best choice. As I'll explain in this informational, ...[Ng6] is not working due to concrete reasons, and we need to develop fast, so [f5] is the only sensible square for the knight.} 10. a4 Be7 11. Bd3 ({This looks the most natural, keeping an eye on the f5-knight.} 11. g3 {, here and in some other positions, can be met with} h5 $5 {, and if White stops our pawn from further advancing with} 12. h4 {, then simply} g6 {, followed by castling with a balanced position.}) 11... O-O 12. O-O Bd7 (12... Nh4 {is the most played, but I believe it's not the most precise as this line works less well with the bishop on [d3].} 13. f4 $1 {gives White some initiative. More details here.}) 13. Kh1 $5 {White tries to slowly prepare [f4].} a6 14. Na3 b5 $1 {[%csl Ra1] Taking advantage of the pinned knight on [a3].} 15. Nc2 ({This looks the most decent, as the knight on a3 is just too passive.} 15. axb5 {is not a problem.} axb5 16. Rb1 {and we can simply protect the pawn with} Rb8 {followed by ...[Bg5].}) (15. f4 {should be met by} g6 {defending the knight, and if} 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rb1 {, we go again} Rb8 {and ...[Re8].}) 15... Bg5 {Black's best. Now White has several options of exchanges, but we are fine everywhere.} 16. axb5 Bxc1 {It's important to start with this trade.} 17. Qxc1 axb5 {Only now do we recapture.} 18. Nb4 Qb6 $10 {With an equal position.} *

