1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. a4 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Ga4a5,Gc1e3] This has been tried by some elite players, so we should definitely check how to react here. White's plan is quite simple: to push [a5] and then continue with [Be3] provoking ...[a6] and taking full control over the [b6]-square.} a6 $1 ({It is important to start with this move to force White's hand.} 9... Ng6 {is not working well due to} 10. Be3 a6 11. Na3 $1 {, and now the [d5]-pawn is not hanging after ...[Qa5]+. White gets a good advantage thanks to the weakness of the [b6]-square.}) 10. Nc3 (10. Na3 {is not working here as after} Qa5+ {, the [d5]-pawn is lost.}) 10... Ng6 11. a5 {White continues with the plan, fixing our pawns and trying to exploit the [b6]-square later on.} (11. Be2 {is harmless:} Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. a5 Bd7 {followed by ...[f5] and ...[b6].}) 11... Be7 12. Be3 O-O 13. h4 ({Pushing immediately makes more sense than preparing it with} 13. g3 {, where we can immediately react with} f5 {, as seen here.}) 13... b5 {An unexpected pawn advance! Of course, the question is what happens if White takes en passant.} 14. h5 {This is objectively better, but even here our position remains decent.} Nh8 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gh8f7] The only decent plan for Black now is to reroot the knight via [f7] by pushing ...[f5].} 15. h6 g6 16. g3 {[%cal Gg3f4,Gf1h3] Anticipating a future ...[f4] for Black and also keeping the option for their light-squared bishop to develop on [h3].} f5 {[%cal Gf5f4]} 17. Qd2 Bf6 {[%cal Gh8f7] Followed by ...[Nf7] with a complicated position.} *

