1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 ({After} 4. c3 {, the most logical for us is to continue with} Nf6 {and after} 5. e5 Nd5 {, we transpose to our Alapin lines.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 {Here, White has tried all the possible moves with the knight and we will briefly check each of them.} 6. Nf5 {This should be challenged with central play.} d5 {Leading to a forced sequence of moves.} 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 {The only thing White has achieved is our slightly damaged pawn structure on the queenside, but as we will see this is not a big problem. Our piece activity will compensate for that.} 10. Ne3 Be6 {[%csl Rc6,Ra7,Ge5][%cal Gf8c5,Gf6d5,Gf7f6,Ge8f7] Our general plan is ...[Nd5], ...[f6] and ...[Kf7]. Black is fine despite the queenside weaknesses. White's pieces struggle to find good squares.} *

