1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Bc4 $5 (9. Bc4 {It seems as if the bishop is better placed here than on a4, but the disadvantage of this move is that it allows us to continue with} d6 {.}) 9... d6 $1 {Taking advantage of White's last move. The bishop changed the diagonal and does not pin our [c6]-knight anymore; thus, this move becomes possible} 10. Qb3 ({White's strategy is correct. After sacrificing a central pawn, they need to play dynamically as otherwise, their compensation will evaporate.Slow play by White favours us, as we get comfortable development with} 10. Nbd2 Nf6 {followed by ...[O-O] and ...[Re8] attacking the [e4]-pawn.}) 10... Na5 $1 ({The right way to continue.} 10... Qd7 $2 {is too passive.} 11. Nbd2 $1 {and White is better as our queen is too awkwardly placed blocking the bishop. Moreover, White gets a chance to play [Qa3] and put pressure on the [d6]-pawn.}) 11. Bxf7+ Ke7 $7 ({The only move to stay in the game. After} 11... Kf8 {, the problem is} 12. Qd5 {and the loss of the [d6]-pawn will have terrible consequences.}) 12. Bg5+ Nf6 $7 13. Qd5 {This might look scary, but if we know what we are doing, we are completely fine.} Rf8 14. e5 {This looks as the most critical try.} dxe5 {White's response is forced.} 15. Qxd8+ Kxd8 (15... Rxd8 16. Nxe5 {is just a transposition after} Rf8 {.}) 16. Nxe5 Ke7 17. Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c7] White's play is not forced here but this looks to me like the most decent try, preventing ...[Rxf7] for now.} Nc6 {There are too many active pieces around our king, so it's time to go for some simplifications.} 18. Nxc6+ Kxf7 {Of course, we want to take the bishop bringing our king into safety.} 19. Nxd4 Ng4 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Rb2] It turns out that the white knight cannot move. See the rest of the line here.} *

