1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Ba4 {The most precise as it does not give us a chance to play ...[d6].} Nge7 $1 ({The correct move order, and you will soon see why. Not} 9... d6 $2 10. Nxd4 {and White is taking over.}) 10. Bd6 {The critical try.} b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7c8] Another important move. We prepare ...[Bb7] and ...[Nc8] to get rid of the annoying dark-squared bishop.} (10... O-O $6 {is not precise as after} 11. Nbd2 b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 13. Re1 {, White's bishop on [d6] is too powerful.}) 11. Bb3 Bb7 $1 {[%cal Ge7c8,Gc6a5]} (11... Bb7 {Preparing ...Nc8 and ...Na5 taking care of both bishops. Now} 12. a4 {is not an issue anymore as we have} Nc8 {kicking off the bishop from his comfortable throne.}) (11... O-O {is once again inaccurate, and after} 12. Nbd2 {it transposes to the 10...O-O?! line mentioned in the note to Black's 10th move.}) 12. Re1 {And now we should go for our idea.} Nc8 13. e5 {The most coherent to support the bishop.} Nxd6 14. exd6+ Kf8 (14... Kf8 {We have reached a very unconventional position. Black is a pawn up, but White obviously has enough compensation due to the awkward position of our king. The d6-pawn can be both White's strength and weakness. Here, to my mind, the most critical is} 15. h4 {, and it's covered in detail in the theory section.}) 15. Nbd2 {The most frequent in practice. Our next move is important to remember.} f5 $1 {Preventing [Ne4] and preparing ...[Bf6]-...[Kg7].} 16. Rc1 Bf6 17. Bd5 Rc8 ({It is important to have ...Na5 ready.} 17... Kg7 {is too premature as now after} 18. Nb3 {eyeing the [a5] and [c5]-squares, we are in serious trouble; for example, it is too late for} Rc8 {due to} 19. Nc5 Ba8 20. Be6 $1 {with a crushing advantage.}) 18. h4 Kg7 19. Nb3 Na5 (19... Na5 {White can go for simplifications with} 20. Re7+ Bxe7 21. Rxc8 {as seen in the theoretical chapter.}) *

