1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we'll use after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. Bxc6 {Clearly the most popular choice and White's last chance to double our pawns; otherwise, we will continue with ...[Ne7]-...[Nxc6]. Now it is important how to recapture.} dxc6 (6... bxc6 $6 {is dubious as after} 7. c3 $1 {we are not in time to meet [d4].}) 7. d3 {Here, we have an interesting setup to finish our development.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg8f6] The idea is simple: we protect the [e5]-pawn to be able to develop the knight to [f6] or to [h6], depending on White's play.} (7... Ne7 {was tried by many players, myself included, but I believe our knight is not greatly placed here.} 8. a3 {and White will continue with their usual plan with [b4].}) 8. Nbd2 (8. Nbd2 {The most common reply, and here I believe the best is} Nh6 {.}) 8... Nh6 $5 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gf7f6] As White's knight is heading to [c4], it makes sense for us to keep the possibility of ...[f6] to reinforce the defence of the [e5]-pawn.} 9. Nc4 f6 {[%cal Gh6f7] Not only protecting the pawn but also liberating the [f7]-square for the knight's improvement.} 10. a4 b6 {A good prophylactic move to be ready to meet the advance of White's a-pawn.} 11. a5 b5 {The point.} 12. Ncd2 Be6 {This is a good square for the bishop as in some situations, after [Nb3], we will be happy to exchange this knight against our bishop.} 13. a6 Nf7 14. Nb3 {And now it is important to take.} Bxb3 15. cxb3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gf7d8,Gd8e6,Ga1c1] Of course, the disadvantage of this exchange is the semi-open c-file and that White has a target on [c5]. On the other hand, our pieces lack space, and after exchanging our bishop, we get the [e6]-square for our knight.} Rc8 {This might seem strange at first glance, but is actually a preparation for a [c5]-pawn loss, which we unfortunately cannot avoid. Once White grabs this pawn, we will need to make sure our [c6]-pawn is well protected.} 16. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5] Here comes an important move.} Bh6 $1 {We absolutely need to remove the dark-squared bishop in order to release the pressure on [c5].} 17. Bxh6 Nxh6 18. Rc1 Nf7 {[%cal Gf7d8,Gd8e6] We need to hurry to [e6] with our knight. We shouldn't be worried about our [c5]-pawn. Here you can see what happens if White grabs it.} *

