1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 {A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. Nc3 e5 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7] Once the knight has jumped to [c3], we can push ...[e5] without any worries. As I?ll explain here, with the knight still on [b1], the [a3]-[b4] plan is more effective.} (7... Nf6 {would be met by} 8. Be3 {and we'll see here that there is no time for ...[e5] and ...[b6].}) 8. Be3 Ne7 ({We can also start by} 8... h6 $5 {when} 9. O-O Ne7 {transposes here and 9.Qd2 Ne7 transposes to our main line.}) (8... Nf6 $2 {was played by Magnus himself but is not recommended as after} 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 {White has a refutation:} 10. Qf3 $1 {, and Black's position will start collapsing soon.}) 9. Qd2 ({For} 9. O-O {see here.}) (9. a4 a5 {as usual.} 10. Qe2 h6 {preparing ...[Be6].}) 9... h6 {As usual, we need to avoid [Bh6].} 10. Nh2 {The most popular move. That position has been reached more than 60 times via different move orders.} Be6 {[%cal Gf7f5] Develop first! Then, ...[f5] will come!} 11. f4 {A very logical move, but Black gets a good game by very logical means.} exf4 12. Bxf4 g5 $1 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gf7f5]} 13. Be3 f5 $1 {[%cal Gg7c3,Ge6a2] As good as it gets, we get an excellent game with powerful bishops.} 14. O-O-O f4 $1 {Grabbing some space.} 15. Bf2 Ng6 {[%cal Gg6e5,Gd8e7,Ge8c8]} 16. Nf3 h5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gg6e5] The ambitious and good way to play. Black is just much better.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Fressinet’s Sveshnikov Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
