1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 Nf6 {will be covered via 4.Nd5.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. Bg5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gg5f6] With the idea of taking on [f6] and occupying the [d5]-square comfortably.} O-O 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Nd5 g6 {[%cal Gf6g7,Gf7f5] My suggestion, which is not the most played, but I like it because it offers a clear plan: we want to put our bishop on [g7] and push ...[f5].} 10. c3 Bg7 11. a4 {White's play will obviously be on the queenside.} Kh8 {Some prophylaxis is needed before proceeding with ...[f5].} 12. Qd2 Bd7 13. b4 f5 {This brings us to an interesting position where White is trying to put pressure on the queenside while we play on the kingside.} 14. bxc5 {This looks like a more ambitious try.} dxc5 15. Qe3 {And now I suggest a novelty.} Na5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ga5c4]} (15... Na5 {Indirectly protecting the c5-pawn, as} 16. Qxc5 {is not good due to} fxe4 17. dxe4 Rc8 {winning a piece.}) 16. Ba2 fxe4 {[%csl Gf8] The simplest, opening up the file for our rook.} 17. dxe4 b6 {[%csl Ra4,Gc5] Protecting [c5] and targeting the [a4]-pawn.} 18. Ng5 {White is trying to provoke some weakening.} h6 19. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3e5,Ge3h6] Here, we only need to bear in mind the [Nxe5] threat, which can be easily parried.} Kh7 $1 {With equal chances.} *

