1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 Nf6 {will be covered via 4.Nd5.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. Ng5 {The most popular by far. White's idea is to attack [f7] to win time for [f4].} O-O 8. f4 Bg4 {We are following a well-known theoretical line.} 9. Qe1 exf4 10. Bxf4 Nd4 11. Qd2 Qd7 {[%cal Gb7b5] Connecting the rooks and threatening ...[b5] at some point.} 12. a4 $5 {A thematic move in this opening. The main goal is to prevent Black's possible expansion with ...[b5].} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] This is quite rare in this position. We still want to organise ...[b5], and we delay the most tempting ...[h6] for now.} 13. e5 {Generally, this push does not give White anything. However, there is one moment where we need to be precise.} dxe5 14. Bxe5 Rae8 15. Bxf6 {With an important twist here.} gxf6 ({This is very strong.} 15... Bxf6 {is what White is hoping for.} 16. Rxf6 {comes with a dangerous attack.}) 16. Nge4 f5 17. Ng3 b5 {Pushing away all the white pieces.} 18. axb5 axb5 $19 19. Ba2 Bh4 $1 {[%csl Ra2,Rg3,Rc3,Gd4,Gg4,Gh4][%cal Gd7d6] With a crushing advantage.} *

