[PlyCount "40"]
[GameId "2123892864548977"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 ({(The Alapin is a tricky system which, from White’s perspective, has the upside of sidestepping all the sharpest Sicilians Sveshnikov, Najdorf, Richter-Rauzer and to dictate the playing area from the very beginning.)} 2. c3 {is the standard introduction to the Alapin, but it usually doesn't make any difference and we will transpose.}) 2... Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is the other move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({I have devoted one chapter to the sidelines and this move, while the lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in another chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. Bc4 ({This is less popular than the natural} 6. cxd4 {but still widely played. By including [d4] first, White removes Black's possibility of pushing the [c4]-pawn and attacking the bishop as in our main line. However, Black has now other options.}) 6... Nb6 {We'll continue in the same manner as in our main line, asking the bishop to choose a square.} 7. Bb3 d5 ({A very natural move taking the centre and opening up our light-squared bishop.} 7... dxc3 $6 {would be a mistake as it allows White to get a very comfortable play and an excellent compensation for a pawn. After} 8. Nxc3 {, Black struggles to complete development.}) 8. exd6 {The best choice, as otherwise, Black would simply play ...[Bg4] followed by ...[e6] and get a nice French structure with the light-squared bishop already developed.} Qxd6 9. O-O {White can try to continue playing a pawn down, as it is not a good idea for Black to try to keep the extra pawn by taking on [c3] now. We should try to finish our development as soon as possible.} Be6 {[%cal Ge6b3,Gb3e6]} ({This is our standard reaction in this line and easy to remember: we need to neutralise White's strong b3-bishop.} 9... Bg4 {would be nice if not for} 10. Bxf7+ $1) 10. Na3 {White might continue to play for the initiative, but here we are well enough developed to finally take on [c3].} (10. Bxe6 Qxe6 {brings our queen to an awkward place, but we still have time to improve her position. After} 11. cxd4 Qd7 {, the queen gets on a safe square, and we will proceed with ...[e6] next developing our dark-squared bishop.}) 10... dxc3 11. Qe2 ({The most consistent, preparing Rd1.} 11. Bxe6 {can be met by} Qxd1 12. Rxd1 fxe6 {with an atypical but interesting pawn structure. We'll complete development with ...[g6], ...[Bg7] and ...[Rc8].}) 11... Bxb3 12. Nb5 {White plays very aggressively, but with precise play, we should not face any problems.} Qb8 {The best and the most logical as we need to keep an eye on the [c7]-square. The queen is better placed here than on [d7] or [d8] as there is no possibility for White to bother us with [Rd1].} 13. axb3 {Here, we have several good-looking options, and it is just a question of taste which one to choose.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] Preparing the fianchetto.} 14. Be3 {[%cal Ge3b6,Ga1a8] Threatening [Bxb6].} Nc8 {Defending everything and taking away any chances of tactical tricks.} 15. Ra4 {[%cal Ge3f4] It is true that since the knight moved away, White got this option of [Ra4] preparing [Bf4], but we still have a good antidote.} Bg7 {With a concrete idea to meet [Bf4].} 16. Bf4 e5 {Forcing simplifications.} 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Bxe5 19. Re4 {And we are just in time to castle.} O-O 20. Rxe5 cxb2 {[%cal Gc8b6,Ga7a6] Grabbing a pawn, and I don't see why not? White probably has some compensation as their pieces are more active than ours, but we should not be in any danger here.} *

