1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 ({(The Alapin is a tricky system which, from White’s perspective, has the upside of sidestepping all the sharpest Sicilians Sveshnikov, Najdorf, Richter-Rauzer and to dictate the playing area from the very beginning.)} 2. c3 {is the standard introduction to the Alapin, but it usually doesn't make any difference and we will transpose.}) 2... Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is the other move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {Since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 {This is not the most played, but definitely the most challenging.} Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. Re1 {The most popular choice, trying to prevent ...[Ne5] ideas, but it turns out that we can still play it!} Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5d3] A very interesting continuation tried by some well-known players, such as Gelfand and Bacrot.} 11. Rxe5 {This is more or less forced as otherwise, the knight could jump to [d3].} Bxf3 12. Qe1 Bc6 $1 ({The most harmonious square for the bishop.} 12... Bd5 {is somehow less logical as it blocks the queen and takes the square we could use for our knight.} 13. b3 g6 14. Ba3 Qd7 {The best as, on any other square, Black faces some concrete problems.} 15. Bc5 {The computer claims that this position is playable for Black, but I believe that in practice, it might be more challenging than after ...[Bc6].}) 13. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] Willing to exchange on [c4] and to put some pressure on [e7] by playing [Ba3].} g6 14. Ba3 Qc7 15. Be4 ({Trying to exchange our active bishop looks logical. If} 15. Re2 {, now} e6 {is possible as after} 16. Bxf8 Kxf8 {, the king can safely get to [g7].}) 15... e6 {...[Bg7] is not possible, but we still need to develop, so this is necessary.} 16. Bxf8 Kxf8 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ga8d8,Gh8e8] The [g7]-square will be useful for our king. We have time to consolidate while White completes development.} *

