1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 ({(The Alapin is a tricky system which, from White’s perspective, has the upside of sidestepping all the sharpest Sicilians Sveshnikov, Najdorf, Richter-Rauzer and to dictate the playing area from the very beginning.)} 2. c3 {is the standard introduction to the Alapin, but it usually doesn't make any difference and we will transpose.}) 2... Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is the other move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {Since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 {This is not the most played, but definitely the most challenging.} Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] White is not only willing to exchange the [c4]-pawn but also might consider [Ba3] attacking our queen.} Qf6 {[%cal Gh5f3,Gf6f3] Therefore, moving the queen is logical.} 13. Na3 $5 {Suggested by Norwegian GM Christiansen in his course 'High-Pressure Alapin Sicilian' and also quite popular in my database. White attacks the pawn on [c4] while not really caring about taking twice on [f3] and getting an endgame where White will get bet the bishop pair.} Nd5 $1 {I like this one attacking the [c3]-pawn and centralising the knight. Also, we may jump to [f4] at some point...} 14. Nxc4 $1 {That's GM Christiansen's point. White doesn't care about sacrificing their queen and just grabs a pawn.} e6 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh8g8,Gd5f4] A strong novelty in terms of objective merits and practical value. Black just ignores the Greek Gift on [c3] and just develops. We will continue with a strong attack on the kingside with ...[g5]-...[Rg8]-...[Nf4]. Yes, White is a pawn up, but what's next?} ({This novelty is not considered in GM Christiansen's course. He is showing nice ideas after} 14... Nxc3 {and 14...b5 . Basically, it's a sharp mess ending in draws where Black has to find a lot of only moves. Not the case at all after 14...[e6]!N where there is more high pressure on White!After 14...Nxc3 15.dxc3 Rxd1 16.Bxd1 , indeed, White has full compensation for the queen, and the position is not easy to play for Black, who lacks kingside development.}) 15. Bb2 {Developing and protecting [c3]. This looks like the most logical to me. On the other hand, it is very far from the main action, which will happen on the kingside!} g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gd5f4,Gh8g8] And immediately it looks tough for White to defend.} 16. d4 {That was the purpose of 15.Bb2.} Rg8 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gd5f4] Bringing one more attacker into the action!} 17. Be4 Nf4 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gf4g2] After the rook, it is time for the knight to jump into the attack. White can stop ...g4 or attack our knight, but they're in trouble.} *

