1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Bc4 {Most people don't want to give up their bishop pair that easily, but the bishop is misplaced here.} e6 $1 {[%cal Gc4e6] As simple as that, we just want to close the [c4]-bishop's diagonal and also prepare ...[d7]-[d5], making the life of White's light-square bishop as uncomfortable as possible. Now White has to challenge the annoying knight on [d4] and has a couple of options in order to achieve that.} 5. Nge2 {The most popular.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ({Of course,} 5... Nf6 {is also a perfectly logical and playable move, but the concept is to harass the light-squared bishop and make White regret having developed their bishop that early.}) 6. a4 Nf6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 7. O-O (7. e5 d5 {anyway works like a charm for Black!}) 7... d5 8. exd5 exd5 9. Ba2 Bd6 {[%cal Gd6h2,Ge8g8] Finishing the development and keeping an eye on White's kingside.} 10. d3 Ne6 {[%cal Ge6g5] I like this move avoiding exchanges after all, we have more space in the center and preventing an annoying pin on [g5].} 11. Kh1 {[%cal Gc3d5] Now threatening to take on [d5].} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 12. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f5]} b5 $1 {[%cal Ga8a1] Strangely enough, there are still 20 games with that position.} 13. Nf5 b4 14. Nxe7 (14. Ne2 Ra7 {activating the rook by planning to take back on [e7] with the rook and preparing to castle.}) 14... Kxe7 15. Ne2 Re8 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gc8b7] Black will castle artificially, and the nice center we got guarantees a good game. See more here.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Fressinet’s Sveshnikov Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
