1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. f4 {This feels too early to me.} e6 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5] I always like to start with ...[e6] before going ...[d6] as in some cases we can push ...[d5] in one go. I would say it is especially true in this particular line as 5.f4 gives us some time to organize that push.} 6. Nf3 Nge7 7. d3 (7. O-O O-O 8. d3 {is another move order.}) 7... O-O 8. Be3 d6 9. O-O Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] Expanding on the queenside and putting pressure on the [b2]-pawn is a typical plan in the Closed Sicilian. There's not much White can do about it in this particular line.} 10. d4 {This looks like a good try, as we normally play ...[Nd4] to prevent that push.} d5 $1 {[%cal Gd4c5,Gd5d4] Using the fact that, with the knight on [f3], White doesn't control the [d5]-square.} 11. exd5 exd5 12. Bf2 {[%cal Gd4c5]} b6 $1 13. dxc5 d4 14. Ne4 bxc5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gb8b2,Ge7f5]} (14... bxc5 {Black is doing excellently!} 15. Nxc5 {wouldn't really help White. We first improve our knight with} Nf5 $1 {before taking on [b2]. To be fair, taking on [b2] immediately was also good, but this is even better.} 16. Nb3 a5 {intending ...[a4], and if White stops it with} 17. a4 {, we go} Qb6 {followed by ...[Ne3]. Black is crushing.}) *

