1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In the Closed Sicilian, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. O-O Nge7 7. d3 O-O 8. f4 Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 9. Be3 b6 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 10. d4 {This is most logical way and prevents ...[d5].} Ba6 {[%cal Gc5d4,Ga6f1]} 11. Re1 d5 $1 12. exd5 Nf5 {[%cal Gf5e3,Gc6d4,Gc5d4] A nice intermediate move making sure we will get the [d4]-pawn and get a better position.} 13. Bf2 Ncxd4 {[%cal Ga6e2,Gg7b2] The pressure of our bishop pair is very strong.} *

