1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In the Closed Sicilian, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. O-O Nge7 7. d3 O-O 8. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5,Gd3d4]} Nd4 {Stopping both threats at once!} 9. Qd2 d6 (9... d6 10. f4 {is another way of playing, transposing to 9.f4.}) 10. Nd1 {[%cal Gc2c3]} Nxe2+ 11. Qxe2 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gd8d7,Gd6d5,Gf7f5] Simple and good plan!} 12. f4 Bb7 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gf7f5,Gd6d5]} 13. c3 Qd7 14. Nf2 d5 {[%cal Gd5d4]} (14... f5 {is the move exclusively played in the games from my database and a very decent choice. I like 14...d5 a bit more, though.}) 15. e5 Nf5 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gd5d4,Gh7h5] Black has grabbed space in the center, and all their pieces are on excellent squares, while White's setup is more questionable.} *

