1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6 6. Be3 (6. f4 Nge7 {transposes here.}) (6. Nge2 Nge7 {transposes here.}) 6... d6 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6]} (7. Nge2 Nd4 {the standard way to stop White's [d4].} 8. Qd2 Ne7 {will be covered here and 8.h4 h5 9.Bg5 Ne7 will be covered here.}) 7... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] It makes sense not to develop the [g8]-knight yet, as it is still preventing [Bh6], and start the queenside expansion instead.} 8. Nge2 b5 9. O-O b4 10. Nd1 Qb6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gb6d4] Making sure [d4] never happens.} 11. a3 ({After} 11. c3 bxc3 12. bxc3 Ba6 {, the lack of activity of the white pieces is quite obvious. Black will follow up with ...[Nge7] and castle, and White can never push [d4] with such knights.}) 11... b3 $5 ({Going for asphyxia!} 11... a5 {followed by ...[Nge7] and castle is the classical solution and also very decent for Black.}) 12. c3 Ba6 {[%cal Ga6e2]} (12... Bb7 $5 {followed by ...[Nge7] is also very possible, keeping in mind that} 13. d4 {is not really good because of} Na5 $1 {eyeing the [c4]-square.}) 13. f4 Nge7 {[%cal Gd6d5] I guess White has to do something very concrete very fast as their position is really cramped, but we are ready for direct action from White, as shown here.} *

