[Result "*"]
[ECO "B20"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[GameId "2123892864725120"]

1. e4 c5 2. b4 {The Sicilian Wing Gambit. It's not really dangerous if we know what we are doing.} cxb4 {Accepting the gambits is generally the only way to refute them!} 3. a3 e5 $5 {[%cal Gf8b4] Not a popular move, but I like it and thought that having a pawn on [e5] will suit the Sveshnikov spirit well!} (3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nf3 e5 6. c4 {is the main line and also good for Black.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gd6e5,Gg8f6]} (4. axb4 $6 Bxb4 5. Nf3 Nc6 {looks like an Evans gambit but without the bishop on [c4] for White, which obviously diminishes their attacking potential.} 6. Bb2 d6 {and once again, it is hard to imagine that White will get any kind of compensation for the pawn. If 6.Bb5 Nf6! , we got a Berlin with an extra pawn, and the dark-squared bishop developed. That's obviously a very good deal for Black.}) 4... Nc6 5. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2e5] This makes sense as it immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn.} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb4a3,Gf8c5] Eyeing the bishop on [b2] and threatening ...[Bc5].} 6. Nxe5 {Indeed, it looks like we didn't defend our central pawn!} bxa3 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gc6e5]} 7. Bc3 a2 $1 {Nice move, easy to miss.} 8. Nxf7 $5 {Mentioned by GM Simon Williams and IM Palliser in their course 'Grandmaster Gambits'. It is indeed an interesting practical try and might work against an unprepared opponent but not against us!} Kxf7 9. Bc4+ Ke8 10. Rxa2 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Re8] That's the point. White has a nice lead in development, and our king is slightly open. However, we do have a full extra piece. The engine and myself have trouble believing that this can be any good.} Nf6 11. O-O Kd8 $1 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gf6e4] Logical and best! The king is hiding on the queenside. The [e4]-pawn also becomes a target.} 12. Qf3 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gc3f6]} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb6f6,Gb4a2] Defending and attacking!} 13. Rb2 a5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Both black knights are now well protected. It is tough for White to keep the attack going. Reminder: Black is a piece up!} 14. Be5 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ge5c7] Played twice in correspondence chess, and it makes a lot of sense as it cuts the black king from hiding on the queenside and threatens [c3] getting back the piece. Black won both games, though.} (14. e5 {is a pseudo-active move that helps Blacks regroup.} Ne8 {followed by some natural moves as ...[Qc6] and ...[Nc7]-...[Ne6]. Black is objectively winning.}) 14... Be7 $1 {[%cal Gh8f8] Slowly getting out using a nice tactical pattern.} 15. c3 Qc6 {[%cal Gc6c4]} (15... Qc6 {That was the point, counterattacking the bishop on c4 and stepping out of the pin.} 16. Be2 Na6 {and suddenly everything is in order. Black has managed to develop the last few moves, while White's attack didn't go anywhere. And we are still a piece up... The line continues here in the theoretical chapter.}) *

