[ECO "B33"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[GameId "2123892864843906"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Bg5 {The main move by far and very logical. White wants to occupy the beautiful [d5]-square without exchanging their knight.} (7. Nd5 {That was the choice of Caruana in his match vs Carlsen in 2018. It became very popular afterwards.} Nxd5 8. exd5 {Now we get a very interesting pawn structure. White has a pawn majority on the queenside while Black has a pawn majority on the kingside. We will definitely have play on the kingside.} Nb8 {is definitely a sound move and the most popular; that's a solid choice keeping an eye on the queenside.Suggested by Dubov during the 2018 match, Magnus played 8...Ne7 in game 12 and got a great position. I immediately liked that proposal and didn't hesitate much about my recommendation while preparing for this course. After 8...Ne7 (, the knight is heading to [g6] and the kingside. We will always try to make the push ...[e5]-...[e4] followed by ...[Ng6]-...[Ne5] dream square for the knight! work. Obviously, that makes the play very double-edged and puts a lot of pressure on your opponent, who is risking a lot as well.)}) 7... a6 8. Na3 b5 (8... b5 {Again, White has two main options.} 9. Nab1 {(has gained some popularity recently, though, thanks to a course by Anish Giri on this very website! But we are well prepared and have a nice solution including a very interesting novelty hey Anish, you have to click on buy if you wanna know!)}) 9. Nd5 {That's the main and most logical move. There is no hurry to take on [f6] as the knight is pinned.} (9. Bxf6 {is also a main move as it forces Black to damage their structure.} gxf6 10. Nd5 Bg7 {(And now it is pretty clear that Black's plan is simple: attacking White's centre pawn on [e4] and knight on [d5] ...[f5] and ...[Ne7] are on the agenda! And now:A)} 11. c3 f5 {and we get what we want. Obviously, White is doing well on the light squares, but we get a lot of play with bishops, a strong centre and another black pawn appearing on [f5] very soon.B 11.Bd3 this at least prevents ...[f5] for the moment. Magnus had a few games here showing Black's potential. 11...Ne7 12.Nxe7 Qxe7 13.c4 f5! White doesn't manage to stop ...[f5] for very long. 14.O-O O-O 15.Qh5 d5 16.cxd5 Qd8! Nice one! Removing the queen to make ...[fxe4] and ...[f5] work. With the queen on [e7], this is not possible due to [d6] ideas. Another point is that Black is targeting the d-pawn, so after [exf5], we can take back on [d5].}) 9... Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 {[%cal Ga3c2] Rerouting the knight via [c2] is the most sensible and popular choice.} (11. c4 {A very solid choice, ensuring firm control over the light square. Here again, I give an interesting option to make the game unbalanced.} b4 12. Nc2 a5 13. g3 h5 $5 {A very interesting, aggressive and rare approach, tried by Magnus.}) 11... Rb8 $1 {As I explain in the first chapter, I think this is the best move order as it limits White's options. It works as good prophylaxis to make a future [a4] more difficult as [b2] will hang. We want ...[Bg5] next, and we managed to avoid the interesting [h4].} (11... Bg5 12. h4 $5 {is why 11...Rb8 is more precise than 11...Bg5. No more fork on [c7]!} Bxh4 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+) 12. Nc2 Bg5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf7f5] It is very hard to say which exact plan Black will choose as it very much depends on which setup White will adopt. But it is safe to say that it is very likely that short castle and ...[f5] will appear on the board. Overall, Black has a good game.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Fressinet’s Sveshnikov Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
