[White "Overview & Model Games: Sveshnikov"]
[Black "Fressinet, Laurent vs. Gelfand"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B33"]
[PlyCount "64"]
[GameId "2123892864860291"]

{One of my first top tournaments, where I had the chance to play some of the best players in the world. This game taught me two very good lessons for the future: it is simply way too risky and unprofessional to be poorly prepared in the opening, as these guys are merciless and punish every mistake. Also, I didn't take too seriously the Sveshnikov, clearly underestimating the dynamic resources it offers Black.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 {At that time, Boris was playing the Najdorf he was one of the main experts with Kasparov and the Petrov in which he had beaten me the previous year!, and for some reason, I didn't expect him to play the Sveshnikov. I just thought that I would figure out something over the board.} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 f5 11. c3 Bg7 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Nc2 O-O 14. Nce3 Be6 15. Bd3 {[%csl Rd5,Rf5] One of the very main lines. For some reason, I believed in White there, not entirely buying that Black could compensate for their weak light squares.} f5 16. Qh5 e4 17. Bc2 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] Very logical and good. Black is trying to get rid of that annoying knight on [d5].} 18. Rd1 b4 $1 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gb4c3] That's the solution of this line. The pawn sacrifice just works tactically. The main point is that White hasn't castled yet.} 19. Nxb4 (19. cxb4 {doesn't really lead anywhere.} Bxb2 {Black wants to take twice on [d5] and give a check on [c3].} 20. O-O Kh8 {And Black has a nice centre and the bishop pair. Also, ...[f4] will always be in the air. Black is just doing well here.}) 19... a5 $1 20. Nbd5 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b2] This was Black's point. There is simply no way to defend the [b2]-pawn. It is actually not about the pawn; it is about the black rook invading the second rank.} 22. Bb3 a4 $1 23. Bxa4 Rxb2 {[%cal Gb2a2]} 24. Bb3 {[%cal Gb3a2] Protecting the pawn. I understood my position was not great, but I thought that having an extra pawn for it wouldn't harm...} Kh8 {[%cal Gf5f4,Ge6d5,Gg7c3]} 25. O-O f4 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf8f5] Not only are the pawns pushing forward, but also ...[Rf5] is a big threat, as the knight on [d5] is loose.} 26. Rfe1 (26. Rb1 {was the only way to stay in the game. Black is better, but White has a very good chance of saving the game after the forced sequence} Rxb3 27. Rxb3 Rf5 28. Qg4 $1 {putting pressure on the diagonal.} Re5 29. Qxf4 Bxd5 {It will be difficult for White to save the game against the bishop pair, but the game is worse.}) 26... Rf5 $1 27. Qg4 e3 $1 {Oops! That was missed. The game is already over. A poor choice of line in the opening, a mistake in the middlegame, and that's it against such a dynamic and strong player as Boris.} 28. Rxe3 (28. fxe3 f3 {and the combined threats of ...[f2]+ and ...[Rxg2] force White's hand.} 29. gxf3 Rg5 {is the tactical point I missed when playing 26.Rfe1.}) 28... fxe3 29. Nxe3 h5 $1 {The last precise move. I have a few pawns for the rook, but that's simply not enough as the initiative for Black is still going on.} 30. Qg6 (30. Qh3 Bxb3 {is also completely winning for Black.}) 30... Rf6 31. Qxh5+ Rh6 32. Qf3 Qh4 {[%cal Gh4h2,Gh4f2,Gh6f6] Too many threats, as the arrows show. I resigned. A great game by Boris. Can't say my poor prep and poor play in the middlegame gave a lot of resistance, but he was very well prepared and very precise in punishing my inaccuracies.} 0-1

