{Here's the second game of the tie-breaks of the World Championship match in London in 2018. After 12 draws in the classical games, Magnus eventually managed to win the first game of the TB. Even if that was a 4-game TB, it is pretty clear that it would be very desirable for Caruana to strike back immediately.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 {That's the line Caruana was using in the second part of the match, and it gave unbalanced positions which suited him.} Nxd5 8. exd5 Ne7 {The surprise choice of game 12! We did have one day to prepare the TB, but we felt it was just good and very playable.} 9. c4 Ng6 10. Qa4 Bd7 11. Qb4 Qb8 12. h4 h5 13. Be3 a6 14. Nc3 {Going for the sharpest and most dangerous set-up is Caruana's trademark.} a5 $6 {Not exactly best blame Magnus seconds! and hardly repeated after, but it shows that even if you don't remember all the details in the line, you will still have counterplay.} (14... Be7 {is our repertoire.}) 15. Qb3 a4 16. Qd1 $1 {The white queen got help to go back to a more central square. Also, Black has weakened the [b5]-square, which could be a nice outpost for the white knight. And very unsure of what Black has gained by pushing his a-pawn forward.} Be7 {[%cal Ge7h4]} 17. g3 Qc8 {[%cal Gd7g4] Trying to get some counterplay on the light squares.} 18. Be2 Bg4 19. Rc1 (19. a3 $1 {fixing the queenside structure would have given Magnus a hard time.} Bxe2 20. Qxe2 Qf5 21. f3 $1 {White is simply much better and has a clear plan. The king will go queenside, where Black doesn't have any pawn breaks, and White has ideas with [g4] or [Ne4] or both!}) 19... Bxe2 20. Qxe2 Qf5 {White has lost the option of castling long and keeping a very safe king , but the engine shows a beautiful way to keep an edge.} 21. c5 (21. Nb5 $1 {forcing Black to keep an eye on the [d6]-pawn.} O-O 22. Kd1 $3 {(That's just brilliant stuff. The white king is never safe on the kingside as White already weakened themselves with [g3]-[h4]; White can't castle long, so the solution is to stay in the centre which is closed but in order to get closer to the queenside.)} Rac8 23. Rg1 $1 {The final touch! White activates the rook, and [g4] will come. The pawn on [h4] will never be hanging as White has counterplay on [d6].}) 21... O-O $1 {It looks like White didn't do anything and followed a logical plan. True, but they clearly neglected their king's safety and that is already a problem, as the centre is opening.} 22. c6 (22. cxd6 {was the best, but Black's position is already pleasant.} Bxd6 23. O-O e4) 22... bxc6 23. dxc6 Rfc8 {[%csl Rc6]} 24. Qc4 {[%cal Gc4c6]} ({The natural} 24. Nd5 {fails to} Qe4 {with a double threat on [h1] and [d5].}) 24... Bd8 {[%cal Gg6e7,Gd8a5]} ({This looks very natural, but the concrete} 24... Qe6 $1 {was just collecting the [c6]-pawn.} 25. Nd5 Ra5 {putting pressure on the knight.} 26. Nxe7+ Nxe7 {and Black wins a pawn.}) 25. Nd5 (25. Ne4 $1 {was best and would keep the game very unclear.} Ba5+ 26. Ke2 Rab8 27. b3 Rd8 {A sad necessity, as [d6] can't be lost.} 28. Qd5 {stopping ...[d5] with a tempo on the bishop.} Bc7 29. Bg5 Re8 {Hard to assess what's going on. It's pretty clear that White managed to activate over the last few moves, but their king is still in the centre.}) 25... e4 {[%cal Gg6e5]} 26. c7 $2 (26. Bd4 $1 {controlling the [e5]-square was the last chance!} Ra5 {again this move to kick the [d5]-knight.} 27. Ne3 Qf3 {Now White had to find computeresque moves.} 28. O-O $1 Bxh4 29. Rc3 $3 {, and the rook comes in White's king rescue via the third rank. The position remains unclear. Instead, 29.gxh4?? Nxh4 is just mate in the next few moves. The rook joins the attack!}) 26... Bxc7 $1 27. Nxc7 Ne5 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ge5c4,Ge5d3,Gf5f3] That's a disaster for White.} 28. Nd5 Kh7 $1 {[%csl Rc1,Rc4,Rd5][%cal Ge5d3,Gf5f3] Nice final touch. White can't avoid massive material losses. Caruana resigned and lost the third game as well. Magnus retained his title!} 0-1

