{In this game, White played a very long theoretical variation. Magnus knew his lines and showed how to deal with the line. Let's be fair: he didn't have any winning chances. That's what happens from time to time against a strong and well-prepared opponent at the elite level.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 Ne7 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Gf6f5]} 13. c4 f5 {We must react immediately in the centre.} 14. O-O O-O 15. Qh5 d5 16. cxd5 Qd8 $3 {A very important move still following our repertoire. Black wants to take on [e4] and play ...[f5] without allowing a nasty [d6] intermezzo.} 17. exf5 Qxd5 18. Rad1 e4 19. Bxb5 Qxf5 20. Qxf5 Bxf5 21. Bd7 Bxd7 22. Rxd7 Bxb2 23. Nc4 {All this is discussed in my course even further! here. Black has to be careful in order to avoid major difficulties.} Bg7 24. g3 Rfd8 25. Rfd1 Rxd7 26. Rxd7 Rc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8c1,Gc8c2] That's the way to play endgames: be active!} 27. Nd6 Rc1+ 28. Kg2 Rc2 {[%cal Ge4e3,Gc2a2]} 29. Nxe4 Rxa2 {Now it is even more clear that the game should end in a draw.} 30. Rd8+ Bf8 31. Nf6+ Kg7 32. Nh5+ Kg8 33. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5] A clever try, as White always has the perpetual available.} a5 {This gives Black unnecessary problems, but we are still within the drawing margin.} (33... h6 $1 {would have stopped White's expansion on the queenside and drawn easily.}) 34. g5 a4 35. h4 Rb2 36. Nf6+ Kg7 37. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6] That's the concept, and it looks like Black is in major trouble. But Magnus finds once again! the right and complicated path to a draw.} Rb5 {[%cal Gb5g5]} 38. f4 h6 39. Ng4 {[%cal Gh5h6]} Ba3 $1 40. Nxh6 Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge7g5,Ge7d8] That’s the fantastic defence found by Magnus. He wants to sacrifice his bishop for the remaining white pawns.} 41. Rd7 Bxg5 {[%cal Gf4g5,Gb5g5,Gg5h5]} 42. Nxf7 Rb2+ 43. Kf3 Bxf4 44. Ne5+ (44. Kxf4 Rf2+ {wins the piece back with a draw.}) 44... Kh6 45. Kxf4 a3 {Luckily, the a-pawn is strong enough to divert White and collect their h-pawn.} ({It's a tad too early for} 45... Kxh5 {due to} 46. Rh7# {Oops!}) 46. Rd5 Rb4+ 47. Kg3 a2 48. Ra5 a1=Q 49. Rxa1 Kxh5 50. Ra5 Rb1 51. Kf4 Rf1+ 52. Nf3+ {Sarana just offered a draw here. He rightfully! trusted Magnus to hold that endgame. That’s the privilege of a World Champion!} 1/2-1/2

