[GameId "2123892864901254"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. a3 $5 {A rare but interesting move trying to prove that Black's last move was not that useful.} O-O 14. h4 $5 {Once we castle, White always has this option.} Bh6 15. Ncb4 {We should address this.} Bb7 $1 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Be2 Qd7 18. Qb3 Kh8 {[%cal Gf7f5] Preparing our standard ...[f5] plan. White can try to prevent it.} 19. g4 Bf4 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ga6a5] This is our usual reaction, reaching an interesting position. White has compromised their kingside, and it will not be easy to find a safe shelter for the king now as castling long is also dangerous due to ...[a5]-...[b4] plan.} *

