1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. a3 $5 {A rare but interesting move trying to prove that Black's last move was not that useful.} O-O 14. h4 $5 {Once we castle, White always has this option.} Bh6 15. g4 {We have a standard reply to this.} Bf4 $1 16. Qf3 {And now, it is important to go for a rapid counterplay on the queenside.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4]} 17. Nxf4 {White can delay this capture, but it is similar.} exf4 {[%cal Gd8f6]} 18. Qxf4 b4 {We are just in time to create problems on the queenside.} 19. axb4 axb4 20. c4 b3 21. Ne3 Nd4 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gd4e6,Ge6c5] With nice compensation for a pawn. As usual, White is struggling with their king's safety, and we can continue with the ...[Ne6]-...[Nc5] manoeuvre.} *

