1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. a3 $5 {A rare but interesting move trying to prove that Black's last move was not that useful.} O-O 14. h4 $5 {Once we castle, White always has this option.} Bh6 15. g4 {We have a standard reply to this.} Bf4 $1 16. Qf3 {And now, it is important to go for a rapid counterplay on the queenside.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4]} 17. Be2 Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5] The idea is obvious: we want to eliminate the strong knight to make the ...[b5]-...[b4] plan possible.} 18. Nxf4 exf4 19. Qxf4 {And of course, now it's time for our queenside push.} b4 20. axb4 axb4 21. Nd4 {We do not want to exchange on [d4] and improve White's structure, so the logical follow-up is to centralise our knight.} Ne5 22. Qg3 {[%cal Gf2f4]} bxc3 23. bxc3 Qc8 $1 {[%csl Rg4] Indirectly preventing [f4] ideas as now the [g4]-pawn is under attack.} 24. g5 Qb7 {[%cal Gb7e4] Once again not giving time for [f4].} 25. O-O {This is possible.} Qxe4 $10 {We just take back the material and do not have any problems. For example:} 26. f4 Nc6 $1 27. Bd3 (27. Bf3 {is the same:} Nxd4 $1 {with the ...[Ne2]+ resource.}) 27... Nxd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4e2] A nice counter, leading to an equal endgame.} *

