1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. a3 $5 {A rare but interesting move trying to prove that Black's last move was not that useful.} a5 $5 {An interesting option, preventing [Nb4] and delaying castle to avoid the [h4] ideas.} 14. Bd3 Ne7 15. Nxe7 Qxe7 16. Qe2 {Attacking [b5], but we can ignore it.} O-O 17. Bxb5 {This can easily be met.} f5 18. O-O f4 {[%cal Gf4f3] With a good compensation as White's pieces are quite passive.} *

