1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf1h3] This is quite harmless. White's idea is to prepare [h4] and exchange the bishops via [h3].} O-O 14. h4 Bh6 15. Bh3 {White's light-squared bishop is often passive, so it makes sense to try to exchange it. Besides, after exchanging the bishops, Black might have trouble with the light squares. We might say that [Bxc8] is already a positional threat, so our next move is important.} (15. g4 {is always met with} Bf4 {followed by ...[Be6] and ...[a5]-...[b4].}) 15... Be6 {The point is exchanging bishops on our terms.} 16. Bxe6 fxe6 {The pawn gets to [e6] and chases White's knight away. This is a very important condition if we exchange the light-squared bishops, as otherwise, our position would be strategically bad due to the [d5]-hole.} 17. Nde3 {[%cal Ge3g4] Here comes another important idea seen in some other Sveshnikov lines.} Bxe3 $1 {It is often a good deal to for us to exchange the bishop against this knight. Usually, we do this to minimise the control of the [d5]-square, but here, [Ng4] was the unpleasant threat attacking the bishop on [h6].} 18. Nxe3 {After solving some important issues on the kingside, we can move on with our counterplay on the queenside.} b4 19. O-O bxc3 20. bxc3 Na5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gd8c7] With a balanced position. We should try to bring the pieces to the c-file and put pressure on the [c3]-weakness.} *

