1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. Bd3 {[%csl Rd3] A developing move which cannot be criticised, but this is clearly not the best square for the bishop.} O-O {Now White can try the standard [h4] plan.} 14. O-O Be6 15. a4 ({Here, we should take, as it's one of the ideas of placing the rook on b8. For} 15. Nce3 {, see the 13.Nce3 line.}) 15... bxa4 {[%cal Gb8b2]} 16. Ncb4 Nxb4 17. Nxb4 Bb3 {Simple chess.} 18. Qe2 ({Now, we can try to improve our queen. Alternative, White can play} 18. Bc2 Bc4 19. Bd3 Bb3 {with a repetition.}) 18... Qc8 19. Nxa6 Rb6 20. Nb4 Qc5 {With a balanced position.} *

