1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. Bd3 {[%csl Rd3] A developing move which cannot be criticised, but this is clearly not the best square for the bishop.} O-O {Now White can try the standard [h4] plan.} 14. h4 Bh6 15. g4 {This is met by our usual response.} Bf4 16. Qf3 Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5] Giving White the last chance to take on [f4]; otherwise, we will exchange on [d5] ourselves.} 17. Nxf4 exf4 18. Qxf4 b4 $15 {[%csl Gb8] We need to create counterplay on the queenside, and you may see how useful our rook is on [b8].} 19. Nxb4 Nxb4 20. cxb4 Rxb4 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gb4b2,Gd6d5] With a very good counterplay as White is having some issues with his king's safety. We will gladly take the [b2]-pawn if White allows us; if not, we will go for ...[d5].} *

