[ECO "B33"]
[PlyCount "40"]
[GameId "2123892865040534"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. a4 {The most critical try.} bxa4 {[%cal Gb8b2] Now we can see one of the advantages of placing the rook on [b8].} 14. Ncb4 Nxb4 {Here, both recaptures are equally popular.} 15. Nxb4 Bd7 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gd7a4] Preventing both [Nc6] and [Qxa4].} 16. Qxd6 $2 {Looks tempting but is, in fact, a very dangerous choice for White.} Be7 {Offering White the second central pawn! The point is, of course, to be able to castle after its capture.} 17. Qxe5 O-O {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf8e8] Now, just compare the position of White's and Black's pieces. Clearly, with such an activity, only Black is playing for an advantage here.} 18. Nd5 {The lesser evil but we'll still have pressure.} Bc5 $5 {A good alternative if you enjoy playing messy positions.} 19. O-O-O a3 20. b4 Ba4 $40 {With a sharp position where White needs to be very cautious.} *

