1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. a4 {The most critical try.} bxa4 {[%cal Gb8b2] Now we can see one of the advantages of placing the rook on [b8].} 14. Ncb4 Nxb4 {Here, both recaptures are equally popular.} 15. Nxb4 Bd7 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gd7a4] Preventing both [Nc6] and [Qxa4].} 16. Bxa6 Qa5 $1 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gb8b4] We need to keep playing dynamic chess. ...[Rxb4] is a threat.} 17. Qxd6 {[%csl Rb8] This is now smarter because the rook is hanging, and we have no time for ...[Be7] and ...[O-O].} Rb6 18. Qd3 {To keep the bishop well protected.} Be6 {Preparing castle.} 19. O-O O-O 20. Bc4 {This is universally played, intending [Bd5]. Here comes a very important move.} Rd8 {Allowing us to win back material in the case of [Bd5].} 21. Bd5 Bxd5 22. exd5 ({Delaying the recapture does not change much.} 22. Rfd1 h6 {is always useful.} 23. exd5 Be7 {with the same ideas as after the immediate [exd5].}) (22. Rad1 {is again met by} h6 23. exd5 Be7 {followed by ...[Bxb4].}) 22... Be7 {[%cal Ge7b4] The point, getting rid of the strong knight next.} 23. Qc2 (23. Qd1 {will most likely transpose to the same line after} Bxb4 24. Rxa4 Qxd5 25. Qxd5 Rxd5 {with equality.}) 23... Bxb4 24. Rxa4 Qc5 {'Protecting' the bishop.} 25. Qd2 {And now we can go into an equal endgame.} Qxd5 (25... Qxd5 26. Qxd5 Rxd5 27. Rxb4 Rxb4 28. cxb4 Kf8 {We'll soon restore material balance, and the draw is near.}) *

