1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. a4 {The most critical try.} bxa4 {[%cal Gb8b2] Now we can see one of the advantages of placing the rook on [b8].} 14. Ncb4 Nxb4 {Here, both recaptures are equally popular.} 15. cxb4 Bd7 {We prefer to keep the [a4]-pawn alive rather than [a6].} 16. Bxa6 O-O 17. O-O Kh8 {[%cal Gf7f5] Preparation for ...[f5].} 18. Qe2 {[%cal Gb4b5] White would like to advance further with [b5] so here I like to address that idea.} Qe8 {[%cal Gd7b5,Ge8b5]} 19. Nc7 Qd8 20. Qc4 ({If} 20. Nd5 {, we can repeat the moves with} Qe8 {.}) 20... f5 21. exf5 Rxf5 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gf5f4] The rook gets activated and the immediate threat is ...[Rf4] taking on [b4] next.} *

