1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. a4 {The most critical try.} bxa4 {[%cal Gb8b2] Now we can see one of the advantages of placing the rook on [b8].} 14. Ncb4 Nxb4 {Here, both recaptures are equally popular.} 15. cxb4 Bd7 {We prefer to keep the [a4]-pawn alive rather than [a6].} 16. Bxa6 O-O 17. O-O Kh8 {[%cal Gf7f5] Preparation for ...[f5].} 18. Rxa4 {White can always consider this sacrifice.} Bxa4 19. Qxa4 {Thanks to the b-pawn and a strong knight, White can get sufficient compensation. But things are not that simple.} f5 20. exf5 e4 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gf8f5,Gf5d5] I like this sequence to prevent [Bd3] ideas and follow with ...[Rxf5].} ({The immediate} 20... Rxf5 {allows} 21. Bd3 $1 {, and now White can push the b-pawn without blocking the bishop on [a6].}) 21. g4 {We have an interesting idea.} g6 22. fxg6 {And now the surprising touch.} Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gd8h4] It turns out White's king is not that comfortable. The queen and the bishop are far away, whereas our queen is coming to [h4] next.} *

