1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 {White is giving away the bishop to get firm control of the [d5]-square} Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 $1 {This is the best move order, as it limits White's options. There are a few ideas here: first of all, we are preparing for the future [a4] plan from White's side, when we will be able to capture on [a4] and have an active rook attacking [b2]. Secondly, we are delaying the castle to avoid certain attacking ideas on the kingside. Besides, you will see that in some lines, the rook is useful for creating a counterattack by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} (11... Bg5 {is possible, but why give White some extra options, such as} 12. h4 $5 {, which is definitely a decent try?}) 12. Nc2 (12. Be2 Bg5 13. Nc2 {is just a transposition.}) (12. h4 $2 {is one of the lines to illustrate why ...[Rb8] is a smart move:} Bxh4 $1 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ {and there is no fork with the rook on [b8].}) 12... Bg5 {Here, White has a wide choice.} 13. a4 {The most critical try.} bxa4 {[%cal Gb8b2] Now we can see one of the advantages of placing the rook on [b8].} 14. Ncb4 Nxb4 {Here, both recaptures are equally popular.} 15. cxb4 Bd7 {We prefer to keep the [a4]-pawn alive rather than [a6].} 16. Bxa6 O-O 17. O-O Kh8 {[%cal Gf7f5] Preparation for ...[f5].} 18. Bc4 ({For} 18. b3 axb3 19. Qxb3 {see the 17.b3 line.}) 18... Qe8 $1 {[%cal Gg5d8,Gf7f5,Gd8b6] Preparing the typical ...[Bd8]-...[Bb6] manoeuvre as well as ...[f5].} 19. b3 axb3 20. Qxb3 {And now it's a good time for ...[f5].} f5 21. exf5 Bxf5 22. b5 Bd8 {As planned.} 23. Ra6 {[%csl Rd6] Attacking our weakness, but we can counterattack.} Bd7 {[%csl Rb5] The pawn on [b5] is also vulnerable.} 24. Rb1 (24. Rxd6 {leads to simplifications:} Bxb5 25. Bxb5 Qxb5 {with equality. But we also have a good response to the text move.}) 24... Qg6 {[%cal Gg6d6,Gg6b1] Protecting [d6] and keeping an eye on the rook just to make sure that the queen is tied to his defence.} *

