1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Be2 {A logical but not very ambitious way of playing.} O-O 12. O-O {Here, we continue as usual.} Bg5 {Improving our passive bishop.} 13. c3 {Here, I like the idea of taking advantage of White not bringing the [a3]-knight to the centre yet.} (13. c4 b4 14. Nc2 a5 {is just a transposition to 11.c4.}) 13... Ne7 {Exchanging White's most active piece.} 14. Nc2 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 Be6 16. Qd3 {Now we can restrict White's knight.} a5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Moreover, the [a5]-pawn will be useful later when searching for a counterplay by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} 17. Rfd1 {The most natural follow-up, and here we can ignore the [d6]-pawn.} (17. Qxb5 {is just wrong for White due to} Rb8 {followed by ...[Rxb2], as we get back the pawn and activate our rook. Black is much better.}) 17... Rc8 $1 {[%csl Rc2]} 18. Qxd6 {The point is that this does not work well for White.} Qxd6 19. Rxd6 b4 $1 {[%csl Rc2,Ga5,Ge6,Gg5][%cal Gb4c3] Now we see how useful our pawn on [a5] is. White cannot capture and will lose the [c3]-pawn next. We are happy to exchange our weak [d6]-pawn against the c-pawn. The position remains balanced, but I think Black has a more pleasant game with two bishops.} *

