1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Be2 {A logical but not very ambitious way of playing.} O-O 12. O-O {Here, we continue as usual.} Bg5 {Improving our passive bishop.} 13. c3 {Here, I like the idea of taking advantage of White not bringing the [a3]-knight to the centre yet.} (13. c4 b4 14. Nc2 a5 {is just a transposition to 11.c4.}) 13... Ne7 {Exchanging White's most active piece.} 14. Nc2 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 Be6 16. Qd3 {Now we can restrict White's knight.} a5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Moreover, the [a5]-pawn will be useful later when searching for a counterplay by means of ...[b5]-...[b4].} 17. Rfd1 {The most natural follow-up, and here we can ignore the [d6]-pawn.} (17. Qxb5 {is just wrong for White due to} Rb8 {followed by ...[Rxb2], as we get back the pawn and activate our rook. Black is much better.}) 17... Rc8 $1 {[%csl Rc2]} 18. Ne3 {Once the knight leaves the [c2]-square, we can push our b-pawn.} b4 19. cxb4 axb4 {With a very solid position. Let's see what happens if White gets greedy.} 20. Qxd6 {We get a crushing advantage.} Qxd6 21. Rxd6 Bxe3 22. fxe3 Rc2 {[%csl Re2,Rb2] White's position is falling apart.} *

