1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Be2 {A logical but not very ambitious way of playing.} O-O 12. c3 {[%cal Ga3c2] The idea of delaying castle is to activate the passive [a3]-knight as quickly as possible.} Bg5 13. Nc2 {Here, we have a pleasant choice.} Ne7 {Probably the simplest.} 14. Nce3 Be6 {Preparing for the exchanges on [d5].} 15. a4 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Qb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8b7,Ge6d5,Gg5d8,Gd8b6] An important move liberating the [d8]-square for the bishop. We have already seen this strong manoeuvre in the previous chapter!} 17. axb5 axb5 18. Rxa8 Qxa8 {[%cal Ge6d5] Followed by ...[Bxd5]. As usual, being greedy in the Sveshnikov is rarely a good idea. For example:} 19. Bxb5 Bxd5 20. exd5 Qa2 {Black will win back the pawn and get a nice activity.} *

