1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. g3 {This is always a possibility for White, preparing [h4] and [Bh3]. Here, we can play similarly to what we studied in the previous chapter.} O-O 12. h4 Be6 13. c3 {This is logical, to prevent ...[Nd4], but here we get another possibility.} b4 $1 {It seems like we are just giving away the pawn, but it works tactically well for us.} 14. cxb4 (14. Nxb4 {is bad due to} Nxb4 15. cxb4 d5 {with a great compensation for a pawn.}) 14... Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Nxb4 16. Qd2 Rb8 {[%cal Gd6d5] Followed by our thematic idea of ...[d5].} 17. Bg2 {A logical developing move taking control of [d5], but we already know that in the Sveshnikov, it is usually not a problem to sacrifice a pawn or two, so...} d5 $1 {With the following point:} 18. exd5 e4 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb4d3,Gf6b2,Gd8d5]} (18... e4 {Of course! Closing the opponent's bishop and at the same time activating ours. ...Nd3 is a big threat and} 19. Bxe4 {will lose material after} Qe7 {, due to the pin, so White needs to do something about his king, which will allow us to win back the pawn on [d5] and then grab [b2].}) *

