1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Bd3 {This is similar to the [Be2] line.} O-O 12. O-O Bg5 13. c3 {I suggest to follow the same plan as in the [Be2] line.} Be6 14. Nc2 Ne7 ({We want to exchange the powerful knight.} 14... Rb8 {is actually a transposition to this 11.c3 line which is not dangerous for Black. While 14...Rb8 would be an acceptable move, challenging the knight with 14...Ne7 makes much more sense.}) 15. a4 ({Trying to hold the outpost with} 15. Nce3 {doesn't change much. We simply take, and White will have to take back with the pawn. Then we will have our pawn majority on the kingside and we can start pushing and having some initiative on White's king.} Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. exd5 f5 $1 {We have a nice pawn majority on the kingside and our bishop is stronger. It may end up on the beautiful [e5]-square after ...[e4] and ...[Bf6], controlling the kingside and the queenside at the same time.}) 15... Nxd5 16. exd5 (16. exd5 {Unfortunately,} Bxd5 {is not good for us due to} 17. Bxh7+ {, so it's better to retreat.}) 16... Bd7 17. Nb4 g6 {Making sure White does not create us any problems with the light-squared bishop.} 18. Nc6 Qb6 {We need to keep the [b5]-pawn protected.} 19. axb5 axb5 20. Qe2 {Here, everything is good. I like the simple approach.} Bxc6 21. dxc6 Qxc6 22. Bxb5 Qb7 {With an equal position.} *

