1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nb1 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gb1c3] A strange-looking and rare continuation. White's idea is to play with [a4] fast and activate the knight by bringing it to [c3] rather than to [e3] via [c2].} O-O 12. a4 {Now I like a move which has never been tried in practice.} Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5] The idea is simple: we want to go ...[Bxd5]. I believe many players rejected this move mostly because of the following sequence.} 13. axb5 axb5 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15. Nxf6+ {The catch. White damaged our pawn structure around the king.} gxf6 16. Bxb5 {And takes a pawn! Indeed, this looks like a strange choice by Black, but actually, we have enough compensation here due to our more active pieces.} Rb8 17. Nc3 Nd4 18. Bd3 Rxb2 {Taking back the pawn, and White cannot create any serious threats on the kingside as their pieces are simply too far.} 19. O-O Qc8 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. exd5 Kg7 {[%cal Gc8c3,Rd1h5,Rh7h6] The idea of ...[Kg7] is to have ...[h6] in case of [Qh5]. We have a good play on the dark squares. Also ...[f5] can be considered. The queen on [c8] is doing an important job preventing [c3].} *

