1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 {A very popular alternative to the previously covered [c3], leading to solid positions.} b4 12. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2b4,Gd5b4]} a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Here, White has tried many different moves.} 13. Qf3 {This has been tried by some very strong grandmasters, so it definitely deserves attention.} O-O {Most players go for ...[Bg5] after [Qf3] avoiding [Nxf6], but I don't see a problem in allowing White to capture our bishop.} 14. Nxf6+ {Let's see it!} Qxf6 15. Qxf6 gxf6 16. O-O-O Rd8 {[%cal Gf6f5,Ga5a4] Our pawn structure is damaged, but we will succeed in pushing ...[f5] and exchanging the doubled pawns. Besides, we also have ...[a4] as an idea.} *

