1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 {A very popular alternative to the previously covered [c3], leading to solid positions.} b4 12. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2b4,Gd5b4]} a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Here, White has tried many different moves.} 13. Qf3 {This has been tried by some very strong grandmasters, so it definitely deserves attention.} O-O {Most players go for ...[Bg5] after [Qf3] avoiding [Nxf6], but I don't see a problem in allowing White to capture our bishop.} 14. Be2 ({Here, I suggest the same idea as after} 14. Rd1 Be6 15. Be2 {.}) 14... Be7 (14... Bg5 $6 {is a bit dangerous.} 15. h4 $1 Bh6 16. g4 {White is successfully expanding on the kingside and after} f6 17. Qg3 {, I think this position might be a bit unpleasant for Black.}) 15. O-O (15. Rd1 Be6 {transposes here.}) 15... Bg5 $1 {Since White castled, [h4] is no longer possible, and we can activate our bishop.} 16. Rad1 g6 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gf7f5] Preparing ...[f5]. White's queen looks misplaced, and we have a comfortable position.} *

