1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 {A very popular alternative to the previously covered [c3], leading to solid positions.} b4 12. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2b4,Gd5b4]} a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Here, White has tried many different moves.} 13. h4 {This should be met with a tricky move.} Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb4b3,Gf6h4] Intending ...[b3].} 14. Nce3 ({Stopping Black's idea for now but allowing a powerful knight jump. The point of our rook move can be seen if White tries to stop Black's idea with} 14. b3 {, when we get a chance of playing} Bxh4 {and after} 15. Rxh4 Qxh4 {, the check} 16. Nc7+ {is no longer a fork! We saw the same idea in the 11.c3 chapter.}) 14... Nd4 {[%cal Gb4b3] We still want to push ...[b3] next. The position is balanced.} *

