1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 {A very popular alternative to the previously covered [c3], leading to solid positions.} b4 12. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2b4,Gd5b4]} a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Here, White has tried many different moves.} 13. g3 {Clearly, the most played.} h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4] A rarely met continuation, played by Magnus Carlsen himself! Black is asking White to make a decision: whether allowing ...[h4] or stopping it, but that weakens the light squares on the kingside.} 14. Bg2 $5 {White can, of course, ignore the h-pawn, but then we take space by pushing it further.} h4 15. O-O ({Here, I like a provocative move. Note that} 15. Qd3 {is the move played in practice, but after} Bg5 16. O-O {is just a transposition.}) 15... Bg5 $5 {Inviting White to push the f-pawn.} 16. Qd3 {This quiet move allows us to choose between various options.} h3 {This is one of them.} 17. Bf3 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] As usual, trying to exchange the active knight.} 18. Nde3 O-O 19. Rad1 {And now again a typical exchange.} Bxe3 {With an important idea.} 20. Nxe3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4] White can jump to [d5], but then our knight will go to [d4] with a balanced position.} 21. Qxd6 {The pawn is taboo, as the knight jump to [d4] is extremely unpleasant to meet.} Nd4 22. Qxd8 Rxd8 {[%csl Rf3] White has to address the threat to the [f3]-bishop.} 23. Kh1 ({The best move, according to the engine, but White's problems are not over.} 23. Bh1 {is a very unfortunate try due to} Ne2#) (23. Bg4 Bxg4 24. Nxg4 Nf3+ 25. Kh1 Nd2 {Hitting the rook and the [e4]- and [c4]-pawns. Black gets back the pawn and is better, as the white king is stuck on [h1] thanks to our advanced pawn on [h3].}) 23... Be6 24. Bg4 a4 {[%cal Gb4b3]} 25. Bxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Gb4b3,Gd4c2] Followed by ...[b3]. Black has fantastic compensation for the missing pawn. The king on [h1] is still stuck and we have a nice control of the central squares. We can proceed with our plan on the queenside.} *

