1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 {A very popular alternative to the previously covered [c3], leading to solid positions.} b4 12. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2b4,Gd5b4]} a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Here, White has tried many different moves.} 13. g3 {Clearly, the most played.} h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4] A rarely met continuation, played by Magnus Carlsen himself! Black is asking White to make a decision: whether allowing ...[h4] or stopping it, but that weakens the light squares on the kingside.} 14. h4 g6 {Getting ready for castle.} 15. Bh3 {And now it is important to sidestep the trade.} Bb7 $1 {[%csl Gb7] We have already learnt that the exchange of light-squared bishops favours White. The only exception is when we can bring the bishop to [e6] and recapture ...[fxe6]. Here, however, after playing ...[h5] and ...[g6], we cannot weaken the kingside anymore, and thus, ...[Bb7] remains our only sensible option.} 16. O-O Bg7 {[%cal Gc6e7] Preparing the thematic ...[Ne7].} 17. a3 $6 ({This is premature, as we'll see now. White's best is} 17. Qd3 {taking control of [b3] to be able to go [a3]. After} O-O 18. a3 bxa3 19. Rxa3 {. we have transposed to the main line.}) 17... b3 $1 18. Nce3 a4 {[%cal Gc6d4] Black is already better as White cannot prevent ...[Nd4].} *

