1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Bxf6 {This can be played with a very concrete idea.} gxf6 9. Na3 b5 10. Nab1 ({However, this looks artificial. White is losing a lot of time jumping with the knight, and we can already take some active measures in the centre.} 10. Nd5 {is the most played move, and it transposes to one of the main Sveshnikov lines with 9.Bxf6.}) 10... f5 $1 11. Bd3 Ne7 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gd6d5] Preparing ...[d5]. If needed, we can first chase away the knight with ...[b4].} 12. exf5 d5 {[%cal Ge5e4] Recapturing the pawn can wait as we have more important things to do.} 13. f6 {This only makes things worse for White.} Nc6 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gd8f6]} 14. O-O b4 15. Na4 {Here, we cannot capture on [f6] immediately due to [Nb6] followed by [Nxd5].} Rg8 $1 {[%cal Gc8h3] The best, creating an unpleasant threat of ...[Bh3].} 16. g3 Bh3 17. Re1 {And now we can recapture.} Qxf6 {[%csl Ra4,Rb1,Gd5,Ge5,Rg1]} (17... Qxf6 {This becomes possible as after} 18. Nb6 {we have} Bc5 {winning on the spot. In any case, White's position is already very unpleasant for multiple reasons: a weakened king, poorly placed knights, and Black's strong centre.}) *

