1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nab1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga2a4] This new fashionable line has been tried by many top players who are searching for some less explored paths in the Sveshnikov Defence. The idea is to unblock the a-pawn to be able to go [a4] fast and also to get firm control of the [d5]-square by playing [Bxf6], followed by [Nd5] and [Nbc3] in some lines. If after [a4], Black continues with ...[b4], then the [b1]-knight can sometimes head to [c4].} Be7 10. Nd2 {Playing this immediately is not really the idea of [Nb1] because White is not ready yet.} b4 {The knight cannot jump to [d5] and is forced to go to the rim.} 11. Na4 O-O 12. Bxf6 {[%csl Ra4] This makes less sense now because the [d5]-square can no longer be occupied by the knight.} Bxf6 13. Bc4 Rb8 {[%cal Ga6a5,Gc6d4,Gc8e6] With better chances for Black. ...[a5] can be played next, followed by ...[Nd4] and ...[Be6].} *

