1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nab1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga2a4] This new fashionable line has been tried by many top players who are searching for some less explored paths in the Sveshnikov Defence. The idea is to unblock the a-pawn to be able to go [a4] fast and also to get firm control of the [d5]-square by playing [Bxf6], followed by [Nd5] and [Nbc3] in some lines. If after [a4], Black continues with ...[b4], then the [b1]-knight can sometimes head to [c4].} Be7 10. Bxf6 {[%cal Gc3d5] White is preparing the [Nd5] jump.} Bxf6 11. Nd5 {Jumping right away is possible but gives us time to prepare for [a4].} Rb8 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb5a4] Getting ready to open the b-file.} 12. a4 bxa4 13. Rxa4 Rxb2 14. Bxa6 {Only Black can be happy about the pawn exchanges on the queenside and can continue to play actively.} Bg4 $1 15. Qxg4 {An interesting practical try, but Black is fine after some precise defensive moves.} Rxb1+ 16. Ke2 Rxh1 17. Bb5 O-O 18. Bxc6 {[%cal Ga4a8] Here comes an important move.} Bh4 $1 {[%cal Gd8g5] Preparing ...[Qg5]. White can try to stop it.} 19. g3 {[%cal Gg4h4] But we should still go for it!} Qg5 20. Qxh4 {The point is that we have a strong reply here.} Qc1 $1 {[%cal Gc1d1,Gc1c2]} 21. Ne3 {The only move, and now we can force a draw.} Re1+ 22. Kd3 {[%csl Gc2] This is the right way to continue, keeping the [c2]-pawn protected.} Rxe3+ ({The simplest, blocking the way for the king.} 22... Rd1+ {is another way to force draw, but it looks a bit more complicated.} 23. Nxd1 Qxd1+ {should also end with a perpetual check.}) 23. fxe3 Qd1+ 24. Kc3 Qe1+ $10 {And White is obliged to repeat.} *

