1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nab1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga2a4] This new fashionable line has been tried by many top players who are searching for some less explored paths in the Sveshnikov Defence. The idea is to unblock the a-pawn to be able to go [a4] fast and also to get firm control of the [d5]-square by playing [Bxf6], followed by [Nd5] and [Nbc3] in some lines. If after [a4], Black continues with ...[b4], then the [b1]-knight can sometimes head to [c4].} Be7 10. Bxf6 {[%cal Gc3d5] White is preparing the [Nd5] jump.} Bxf6 11. a4 $1 {The critical continuation. White wants to create some weaknesses and get the [c4]-square for his bishop or knight.} b4 12. Nd5 Bg5 13. Nd2 {[%csl Gc4] This makes more sense with the pawn already on [b4], as the [c4]-square has become available.} O-O 14. Nf3 {I believe this is not the right direction.} Bh6 {[%cal Gg8h8,Gf7f5] Now, we can slowly prepare ...[f5].} 15. Bc4 Kh8 16. O-O f5 {And now, the best is to come back.} 17. Nd2 {Proof that the knight was not ideally placed on [f3].} Bb7 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 18. exf5 {And now, we don't have to recapture on [f5] immediately, but can firstly improve our pieces.} Rc8 {[%csl Rc4,Rd5][%cal Gc6d4] Preparing ...[Nd4]. I think Black's chances are superior.} *

