1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nab1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga2a4] This new fashionable line has been tried by many top players who are searching for some less explored paths in the Sveshnikov Defence. The idea is to unblock the a-pawn to be able to go [a4] fast and also to get firm control of the [d5]-square by playing [Bxf6], followed by [Nd5] and [Nbc3] in some lines. If after [a4], Black continues with ...[b4], then the [b1]-knight can sometimes head to [c4].} Be7 10. Bxf6 {[%cal Gc3d5] White is preparing the [Nd5] jump.} Bxf6 11. a4 $1 {The critical continuation. White wants to create some weaknesses and get the [c4]-square for his bishop or knight.} b4 12. Nd5 Bg5 13. Nd2 {[%csl Gc4] This makes more sense with the pawn already on [b4], as the [c4]-square has become available.} O-O 14. Nc4 Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5] Black has a lead in development and a safer king, so it makes sense to try to open up the centre by taking on [d5].} 15. Ncb6 Ra7 {[%cal Gd8b8,Gg5d8] Now we have a clear plan in order to chase the knight, namely ...[Qb8] followed by ...[Bd8].} 16. a5 Nxa5 {A nice little trick.} 17. Rxa5 Bxd5 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gb6a5] We get back the piece.} 18. Rxd5 Qxb6 $10 {Black is definitely not worse.} *

