1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nab1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga2a4] This new fashionable line has been tried by many top players who are searching for some less explored paths in the Sveshnikov Defence. The idea is to unblock the a-pawn to be able to go [a4] fast and also to get firm control of the [d5]-square by playing [Bxf6], followed by [Nd5] and [Nbc3] in some lines. If after [a4], Black continues with ...[b4], then the [b1]-knight can sometimes head to [c4].} Be7 10. Bxf6 {[%cal Gc3d5] White is preparing the [Nd5] jump.} Bxf6 11. a4 $1 {The critical continuation. White wants to create some weaknesses and get the [c4]-square for his bishop or knight.} b4 12. Nd5 Bg5 13. Nd2 {[%csl Gc4] This makes more sense with the pawn already on [b4], as the [c4]-square has become available.} O-O 14. Nc4 Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5] Black has a lead in development and a safer king, so it makes sense to try to open up the centre by taking on [d5].} 15. a5 {[%cal Gc4b6] Preventing Black's ...[a5] and making sure to control the [b6]-square. A knight could land there.} Bxd5 16. exd5 {This makes little sense, in my opinion.} Nd4 17. c3 bxc3 18. bxc3 Nf5 {[%csl Rc3,Gd6][%cal Ge5e4,Ga8c8,Ge4e3] We are getting our usual play without the weakness on [d6].} *

