1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nab1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga2a4] This new fashionable line has been tried by many top players who are searching for some less explored paths in the Sveshnikov Defence. The idea is to unblock the a-pawn to be able to go [a4] fast and also to get firm control of the [d5]-square by playing [Bxf6], followed by [Nd5] and [Nbc3] in some lines. If after [a4], Black continues with ...[b4], then the [b1]-knight can sometimes head to [c4].} Be7 10. Bxf6 {[%cal Gc3d5] White is preparing the [Nd5] jump.} Bxf6 11. a4 $1 {The critical continuation. White wants to create some weaknesses and get the [c4]-square for his bishop or knight.} b4 12. Nd5 Bg5 13. Nd2 {[%csl Gc4] This makes more sense with the pawn already on [b4], as the [c4]-square has become available.} O-O 14. Nc4 Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5] Black has a lead in development and a safer king, so it makes sense to try to open up the centre by taking on [d5].} 15. a5 {[%cal Gc4b6] Preventing Black's ...[a5] and making sure to control the [b6]-square. A knight could land there.} Bxd5 16. Qxd5 Rc8 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gc6d4] Very concrete and dynamic play, basing our hope on dynamism, and it works! It is funny but not surprising that both captures on [d6] are simply losing for White.} 17. Bd3 {The best and most reasonable move.} Ne7 18. Qb7 {That's really asking for trouble!} d5 $1 {What else? The king is still in the centre, and the queen is fishing on the queenside. It is rather obvious that Black should open the centre.} 19. exd5 e4 20. Be2 Nf5 {[%cal Gf5d4,Ge4e3] ...[Nd4] is a big threat. White is likely to prevent it, but then we will go for the other threat: ...[e3]. It will be very difficult for White to deal with that.} *

