1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nab1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga2a4] This new fashionable line has been tried by many top players who are searching for some less explored paths in the Sveshnikov Defence. The idea is to unblock the a-pawn to be able to go [a4] fast and also to get firm control of the [d5]-square by playing [Bxf6], followed by [Nd5] and [Nbc3] in some lines. If after [a4], Black continues with ...[b4], then the [b1]-knight can sometimes head to [c4].} Be7 10. Bxf6 {[%cal Gc3d5] White is preparing the [Nd5] jump.} Bxf6 11. a4 $1 {The critical continuation. White wants to create some weaknesses and get the [c4]-square for his bishop or knight.} b4 12. Nd5 Bg5 13. Bc4 O-O 14. O-O {Here, many moves have been tried. My suggestion is finishing development.} Be6 $1 {[%cal Ga6a5,Ga8c8] Followed by ...[a5] and ...[Rc8].} 15. Nd2 {Here, we can start by retreating our bishop.} Bh6 16. Nf3 {Then, we continue with a plan we have already seen.} Kh8 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 17. Qd3 f5 18. Ne3 {This leads to simplifications.} fxe4 19. Qxe4 Bxc4 20. Qxc4 Rc8 21. Qxa6 {This should be met with energetic play.} e4 22. Nd2 d5 {[%cal Gd5d4] White won a pawn, but in exchange, we got a strong mobile centre, which is not easy to deal with.} 23. Nb3 d4 24. Rad1 {Several continuations are possible, but let's go for the most tempting one.} Rxf2 $1 (24... Rxf2 25. Kxf2 {looks courageous, but after} Bxe3+ 26. Ke1 h6 {, we have a fantastic initiative.}) 25. Nc4 Rxc2 {It looks like Black is getting close to a winning position, but White still has some tricks at his disposal, allowing them to keep the balance.} 26. Nd6 {[%cal Ga6c8,Gd6f7]} Be3+ 27. Kh1 Rc7 {The only move, but quite an obvious one. We need to avoid the [Nf7] fork and remove the rook from being attacked.} 28. Nf7+ Rxf7 29. Rxf7 Ne5 {[%cal Ge5f7,Ge5g4]} 30. Ra7 {The only good move.} Ng4 {[%cal Gg4f2]} (30... Ng4 {And the game ends in a draw after} 31. Ra8 Nf2+ 32. Kg1 Nd3+ {.}) *

