1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 (9... Be7 {White has tried a number of different moves here, but many of them are simply dubious or even losing. Note that} 10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 {transposes to a 9.Nd5 followed by 10.Bxf6 line discussed in one of the previous chapters.}) 10. Nxe7 {A solid option, but we will definitely have an easier life after exchanging our passive bishop for the strong [d5]-knight.} Nxe7 {[%cal Gf6e4] Here, White has a choice between eliminating the [f6]-knight or trying to protect the central pawn.} 11. Bd3 {This always has the drawback for White of losing control over the [d5]-square as it blocks the queen, and we can immediately strike.} d5 {[%cal Gd5e4]} 12. Bxf6 {This is another possibility.} gxf6 13. c3 Bb7 14. Qe2 ({We have a thematic response.} 14. Qf3 $2 {is a mistake as after} f5 $1 {White has a problem with the fork on [e4].}) 14... f5 15. f3 {An attempt to consolidate the centre.} fxe4 16. fxe4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 {Now, we have a simple continuation.} Qd5 19. Qe2 (19. Qxd5 Nxd5 {leads to a balanced endgame where Black's knight is much better than White's.}) 19... O-O 20. O-O Ng6 $10 {[%cal Gg6f4,Gf7f5,Ga8d8] With ...[Nf4] or ...[f5] ideas. The position is equal.} *

