1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 (9... Be7 {White has tried a number of different moves here, but many of them are simply dubious or even losing. Note that} 10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 {transposes to a 9.Nd5 followed by 10.Bxf6 line discussed in one of the previous chapters.}) 10. Nxe7 {A solid option, but we will definitely have an easier life after exchanging our passive bishop for the strong [d5]-knight.} Nxe7 {[%cal Gf6e4] Here, White has a choice between eliminating the [f6]-knight or trying to protect the central pawn.} 11. Bd3 {This always has the drawback for White of losing control over the [d5]-square as it blocks the queen, and we can immediately strike.} d5 {[%cal Gd5e4]} 12. exd5 {We should recapture with the queen.} Qxd5 {[%cal Gd5g2]} (12... Qxd5 {And White already needs to be precise. E.g.} 13. O-O {is dubious due to} Bb7 14. f3 Qd4+ 15. Kh1 Qxb2 {and White does not have compensation for the lost pawn.}) 13. f3 {For example, this gives us a good chance.} e4 {[%cal Gd5g5,Ge4d3]} 14. Bxe4 {[%cal Re4a8] A very dangerous try to win material.} Qxg5 15. Bxa8 Qxg2 16. Rf1 Qxh2 {[%csl Ra3,Re1]} (16... Qxh2 {With great compensation for an exchange.} 17. Qe2 {looks like a sensible move, offering a queen trade and preparing to castle long.} Qd6 {Preventing White from getting a safe place for their king. The position is just very difficult to play for White.} 18. Rd1 Qc5 {Black keeps protecting their knight on [e7] and will follow up with ...[Be6] to make castle possible, while the White's king is stuck in the centre. White's pieces have no coordination whatsoever. Black is just much better.}) *

