1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 (9... Be7 {White has tried a number of different moves here, but many of them are simply dubious or even losing. Note that} 10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 {transposes to a 9.Nd5 followed by 10.Bxf6 line discussed in one of the previous chapters.}) 10. Nxe7 {A solid option, but we will definitely have an easier life after exchanging our passive bishop for the strong [d5]-knight.} Nxe7 {[%cal Gf6e4] Here, White has a choice between eliminating the [f6]-knight or trying to protect the central pawn.} 11. Bxf6 {The most played, solving the [e4]-problem and damaging our pawn structure. However, we have already seen in the previous chapters that having doubled pawns on the f-file gives us a good dynamic play with ...[f5] and ...[d5] ideas.} gxf6 (11... gxf6 {Now,} 12. Bd3 d5 {takes us to 11.Bd3.}) 12. Qf3 {This does not give us time for ...[d5], but as usual in that case, we continue with ...[f5].} f5 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Bd3 Be6 {[%cal Gd6d5] I like this retreat as now we have both ...[d5] and ...[f5] at our disposal. Once we push one of these pawns, the ...[e4] threat will be annoying for White.} 15. O-O {This is very natural, but flawed.} d5 {[%cal Ge5e4] White's position is already dangerous.} 16. Rfd1 Qc7 {Renewing the threat of ...[e4].} 17. Qf6 {This can be calmly met.} O-O-O $1 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Ge5e4,Gh8g8] With a fantastic position for Black. As usual, White lacks space and coordination.} *

