1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 (9... Be7 {White has tried a number of different moves here, but many of them are simply dubious or even losing. Note that} 10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 {transposes to a 9.Nd5 followed by 10.Bxf6 line discussed in one of the previous chapters.}) 10. Nxe7 {A solid option, but we will definitely have an easier life after exchanging our passive bishop for the strong [d5]-knight.} Nxe7 {[%cal Gf6e4] Here, White has a choice between eliminating the [f6]-knight or trying to protect the central pawn.} 11. Bxf6 {The most played, solving the [e4]-problem and damaging our pawn structure. However, we have already seen in the previous chapters that having doubled pawns on the f-file gives us a good dynamic play with ...[f5] and ...[d5] ideas.} gxf6 (11... gxf6 {Now,} 12. Bd3 d5 {takes us to 11.Bd3.}) 12. c4 {Making sure ...[d5] is not coming anytime soon. This might be the case, but we have another pawn willing to advance.} f5 $1 {It is important to challenge White's centre quickly.} 13. exf5 {Here, I suggest a very rare continuation.} O-O $1 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gc8f5] I believe it's better to delay the pawn recapturing. White does not have a smart way to save this pawn, and we keep both possibilities of ...[Nxf5] and ...[Bxf5].} 14. Bd3 {Now, we can continue with our usual idea.} Qa5+ $1 15. Qd2 Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 {The point is that here we have the possibility of recapturing with the bishop.} Bxf5 17. cxb5 Bxd3 18. Kxd3 Rfb8 {[%cal Gb8b2,Gd6d5] With a good endgame. This time, our [d6]-pawn is not fixed, and we will be able to advance it further.} *

