1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 {Stopping ...[f5] for now.} Ne7 {Insisting on pushing the f-pawn. White has tried many different moves here, but to tell you the truth, only two are decent. The general rule is that if White allows us to exchange on [d5] and is forced to take back with the pawn, we get an immediate advantage as we can comfortably advance our f-pawn.} 12. Ne3 {Quite rarely met in practice but possible. The idea is to avoid the exchange on [d5], which favours Black, and try to prevent Black's main idea connected with [f5]} f5 {Still!} 13. exf5 (13. Nxf5 {is bad, and we already know why:} Bxf5 14. exf5 e4 {and White is losing material.}) 13... d5 {[%cal Ge5e4] Insisting on ...[e4]. Here, White has some time to avoid the disaster but still after the necessary [c3], we can push.} ({The immediate} 13... e4 {is not good because after} 14. Bxe4 {, we do not have ...[d5] as the [e3]-knight controls the square.}) 14. c3 e4 15. Be2 d4 {Creating threats with every move.} 16. cxd4 Qa5+ 17. Kf1 (17. Qd2 {leads to a complicated middlegame after} Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2 Bxd4 {and if} 19. Nac2 {we can take} Bxb2 {with superior chances.}) 17... Bxf5 {[%cal Ge8g8] Followed by short castle with powerful compensation.} *

