1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 {Stopping ...[f5] for now.} Ne7 {Insisting on pushing the f-pawn. White has tried many different moves here, but to tell you the truth, only two are decent. The general rule is that if White allows us to exchange on [d5] and is forced to take back with the pawn, we get an immediate advantage as we can comfortably advance our f-pawn.} 12. Qf3 ({This prevents ...f5 but does not change our plans.} 12. Qh5 {might seem a good move preventing ...[f5], but here White faces another problem:} Nxd5 {as usual, and} 13. exd5 e4 $1 14. Bxe4 f5 15. Bxf5 Bxb2 {and White's position is collapsing.}) 12... Nxd5 13. exd5 Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gf6f5,Ge5e4] Still willing to play ...[f5].} 14. g4 {A desperate attempt to prevent our idea.} Qxg4 15. Qxg4 Bxg4 16. Rg1 {We still get to play ...[f5].} f5 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ge5e4,Gg7b2]} 17. f3 e4 $1 {[%cal Gg7b2] White's position is a disaster.} *

