1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 {Stopping ...[f5] for now.} Ne7 {Insisting on pushing the f-pawn. White has tried many different moves here, but to tell you the truth, only two are decent. The general rule is that if White allows us to exchange on [d5] and is forced to take back with the pawn, we get an immediate advantage as we can comfortably advance our f-pawn.} 12. Nxe7 {After checking all the sidelines, we can understand why this move is the best.} Qxe7 13. c4 $5 {An interesting option taking firm control not for long, though! of [d5] and trying to destroy our queenside at some point.} f5 {We cannot wait and watch White consolidating their position. Dynamic play is our main gun as from the strategical point of view, our position is not good, to put it mildly.} 14. O-O (14. cxb5 {would give us a dream position after} d5 {∓ , White will no longer be able to keep the centre closed.}) 14... O-O {Here, White has a wide choice of options, and we have to check at least some of them.} 15. Qh5 {The most ambitious option, tried by some very strong grandmasters. Here, I recommend you continue with quite a rare idea played by Magnus himself.} d5 $5 {It looks crazy to put the pawn on a square defended twice, but we have already seen that in the Sveshnikov, we do not count the pawns.} 16. cxd5 Qd8 $1 {[%cal Gf5e4,Gf7f5] Removing the queen to make ...[fxe4] and ...[f5] work. With the queen on [e7], this is not possible due to [d6] ideas. Another point is that Black is targeting the d-pawn, so after [exf5], we can take back on [d5]. White is not able to prevent both and needs to make a choice.} 17. g4 {This surprising move helps White to keep the centre solid, but now we can just simply take back the material.} fxg4 18. Rac1 Bd7 19. Nc2 Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b6,Gb6h6] We can go for the same manoeuvre with our rook offering us a very pleasant position.} *

