1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 {Stopping ...[f5] for now.} Ne7 {Insisting on pushing the f-pawn. White has tried many different moves here, but to tell you the truth, only two are decent. The general rule is that if White allows us to exchange on [d5] and is forced to take back with the pawn, we get an immediate advantage as we can comfortably advance our f-pawn.} 12. Nxe7 {After checking all the sidelines, we can understand why this move is the best.} Qxe7 13. c4 $5 {An interesting option taking firm control not for long, though! of [d5] and trying to destroy our queenside at some point.} f5 {We cannot wait and watch White consolidating their position. Dynamic play is our main gun as from the strategical point of view, our position is not good, to put it mildly.} 14. O-O (14. cxb5 {would give us a dream position after} d5 {∓ , White will no longer be able to keep the centre closed.}) 14... O-O {Here, White has a wide choice of options, and we have to check at least some of them.} 15. cxb5 {We have already seen lines when we go for ...[d5] even with a white pawn on [c4], so here our reply is obvious.} d5 16. exd5 e4 17. Qe2 Qb4 {The most logical, threatening both the bishop and the [b2]-pawn.} 18. Bc4 Qxb2 19. Nc2 axb5 20. Rab1 {The most common reply in practice.} Qf6 21. Rxb5 {Now, the most logical is to push.} f4 {[%cal Gf4f3] And ...[f3] becomes an unpleasant threat.} 22. f3 {Allowing ...[e3].} ({If White is careless and goes for} 22. Qxe4 {, then} Bf5 23. Qe2 Qc3 {-+ Surprisingly, White has no way to save material. The pieces are too poorly coordinated.}) 22... e3 23. Nb4 Kh8 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gf8g8,Gf6d6] Black has a fantastic compensation: the [e3]-pawn, two bishops and the open g-file make a perfect match.} *

