1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 {Stopping ...[f5] for now.} Ne7 {Insisting on pushing the f-pawn. White has tried many different moves here, but to tell you the truth, only two are decent. The general rule is that if White allows us to exchange on [d5] and is forced to take back with the pawn, we get an immediate advantage as we can comfortably advance our f-pawn.} 12. Nxe7 {After checking all the sidelines, we can understand why this move is the best.} Qxe7 13. O-O {A logical developing move, but here we get a chance to go ...[d5] again.} d5 $5 ({This is rare compared to} 13... O-O {. However, I do not see how White can take advantage of this move order, which can later transpose to our main line.}) (13... d5 {For instance, if White continues with} 14. c3 O-O 15. Nc2 f5 16. exf5 {, we'll reach the main line with 14.O-O. 16.exd5 is also a transposition. See here.}) 14. Re1 {This has never been tried, but it makes sense as the rook might be useful here. However, here we get a possibility of pushing ...[b4].} b4 {Forcing an ugly-looking retreat.} 15. Nb1 f5 {[%csl Gg7,Gc8] We will see this approach in other lines as well. The bishops need some air!} 16. exd5 O-O {[%cal Ge5e4] And White cannot avoid ...[e4] next.} 17. Nd2 e4 18. Nc4 {Here we have a pleasant choice. I like removing the queen from the X-ray.} Qc5 19. Bf1 Rd8 {[%csl Gc8,Gg7][%cal Gd8d5] The [d5]-pawn is doomed.} *

