1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 {Stopping ...[f5] for now.} Ne7 {Insisting on pushing the f-pawn. White has tried many different moves here, but to tell you the truth, only two are decent. The general rule is that if White allows us to exchange on [d5] and is forced to take back with the pawn, we get an immediate advantage as we can comfortably advance our f-pawn.} 12. Nxe7 {After checking all the sidelines, we can understand why this move is the best.} Qxe7 13. c3 $1 {[%cal Ga3c2,Gc2e3] Not the most played, but I believe it to be the best try for White. We have already seen in numerous lines how White is struggling with activating the knight, so here the idea is to play [Nc2]-[Ne3] fast.} f5 {We continue with the same centre-breaking plan before White gets to consolidate.} 14. O-O {Just like in the 13.O-O line, I recommend going for an immediate central push.} d5 $1 15. exf5 ({For} 15. exd5 {see the 13.O-O line.}) 15... O-O {[%cal Ge5e4]} 16. Nc2 e4 17. Be2 Rd8 18. Nd4 ({If} 18. Bg4 {trying to save material, we have} Qg5 19. f4 Qf6 20. Qd4 a5 {with a decent counterplay.}) 18... Qf6 {[%cal Gb5b4] The knight looks rock solid, but White needs to keep an eye on the ...[b4] ideas.} 19. f3 b4 20. Qe1 Bd7 {[%csl Gd7,Gg7][%cal Ga8c8] With a good game.} *

