1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 {Stopping ...[f5] for now.} Ne7 {Insisting on pushing the f-pawn. White has tried many different moves here, but to tell you the truth, only two are decent. The general rule is that if White allows us to exchange on [d5] and is forced to take back with the pawn, we get an immediate advantage as we can comfortably advance our f-pawn.} 12. Nxe7 {After checking all the sidelines, we can understand why this move is the best.} Qxe7 13. c3 $1 {[%cal Ga3c2,Gc2e3] Not the most played, but I believe it to be the best try for White. We have already seen in numerous lines how White is struggling with activating the knight, so here the idea is to play [Nc2]-[Ne3] fast.} f5 {We continue with the same centre-breaking plan before White gets to consolidate.} 14. Nc2 O-O 15. Qh5 {Here, we are not in time for ...[fxe4] and ...[d5] tricks, so our reply is forced.} (15. O-O d5 {is a transposition to 14.O-O lines. 15...f4 closing the position is premature here as our pieces are not ready to create serious threats on the kingside, whereas White can go for 16.a4 bxa4 17.Rxa4 putting pressure on [a6].}) ({After} 15. O-O {,} Bb7 {does not work due to} 16. exf5 Qg5 17. Ne3 {and White is better.}) 15... f4 16. O-O-O Be6 17. g3 {Here, we can take on [a2].} Bxa2 18. gxf4 {It is important to ask White to make a decision.} Qf6 {[%csl Rf4]} 19. f5 Bh6+ 20. Ne3 Kh8 21. Kc2 {And here, we need to eliminate the knight before it's too late.} Bxe3 22. fxe3 a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4] Black's attack on the queenside looks more promising than White's on the kingside.} *

