1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 {Stopping ...[f5] for now.} Ne7 {Insisting on pushing the f-pawn. White has tried many different moves here, but to tell you the truth, only two are decent. The general rule is that if White allows us to exchange on [d5] and is forced to take back with the pawn, we get an immediate advantage as we can comfortably advance our f-pawn.} 12. Nxe7 {After checking all the sidelines, we can understand why this move is the best.} Qxe7 13. c3 $1 {[%cal Ga3c2,Gc2e3] Not the most played, but I believe it to be the best try for White. We have already seen in numerous lines how White is struggling with activating the knight, so here the idea is to play [Nc2]-[Ne3] fast.} f5 {We continue with the same centre-breaking plan before White gets to consolidate.} 14. Nc2 O-O 15. Ne3 {[%csl Ge3] By bringing the knight fast into the centre, White got good control of the [f5] and [d5]-squares, so unfortunately, we do not get our usual counterplay with ...[fxe4] and ...[d5]. On the other hand, that manoeuvre cost White some time.} f4 {Now, White is again forced to move the knight.} 16. Nd5 Qg5 $5 17. g3 ({The most natural, but now White's king will never feel safe on the kingside.} 17. O-O {allows} Bh3 {.}) ({If} 17. Qc2 {, we can continue with} Bb7 {and exchange on [d5] next.}) 17... Be6 18. Nc7 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gc7e6,Gc7a8] After severely weakening the light squares, it makes sense to take the bishop. However, once the [d5]-square becomes vacant, we get a chance to push the pawn at some point.} Rad8 19. h4 Qe7 20. Nxe6 fxe6 {After this, we get a very solid centre.} 21. g4 f3 $132 {[%cal Gd6d5,Gb5b4,Gf8f4] A very strong reply, followed by ...[Rf4] and ...[d5].} *

