1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. c3 ({White's main choice together with} 11. Bd3 {, and may transpose to the same line.}) 11... f5 (11... f5 {Of course, when allowed, we seize our chance to push the f-pawn. Note that now} 12. Bd3 Ne7 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 {transposes to the 11.Bd3 line.}) 12. Nxb5 {This might look tempting but is not really correct.} axb5 13. Bxb5 Bb7 14. exf5 O-O 15. Qg4 Kh8 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gc6e7] White gets three pawns for a piece, but our bishop is superior with so many pieces left on the board. The simplest is to block the f-pawn by playing ...[f6] and then exchange the strong [d5]-knight by playing ...[Ne7].} *

