1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. c3 ({White's main choice together with} 11. Bd3 {, and may transpose to the same line.}) 11... f5 (11... f5 {Of course, when allowed, we seize our chance to push the f-pawn. Note that now} 12. Bd3 Ne7 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 {transposes to the 11.Bd3 line.}) 12. Nc2 {[%cal Ga2a4] White abandons the central pawn and wants to weaken our queenside, but this is not dangerous.} fxe4 13. a4 Rb8 14. axb5 axb5 15. Na3 {It looks a bit suspicious to waste so much time trying to win back the pawn.} O-O 16. Bxb5 Ne7 {[%csl Gd6,Ge4,Ge5,Gf7][%cal Gc8e6] Indeed, Black's position is already preferable with our powerful pawn centre and the bishop pair.} *

