1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. c3 ({White's main choice together with} 11. Bd3 {, and may transpose to the same line.}) 11... f5 (11... f5 {Of course, when allowed, we seize our chance to push the f-pawn. Note that now} 12. Bd3 Ne7 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 {transposes to the 11.Bd3 line.}) 12. exf5 {Clearly, the most played.} Bxf5 13. Nc2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc2e3] White is executing the standard knight manoeuvre heading to [e3], from where it will support the centralised [d5]-knight.} O-O 14. Nce3 Be6 {[%csl Ge6] The bishop should be kept on this diagonal, as going to [g6] would invite a [h4]-[h5] push.} 15. a4 {A typical approach in this structure, trying to exploit our weakened queenside. Here, I suggest pushing the b-pawn, with a twist.} b4 16. cxb4 Kh8 {[%cal Gf7f5] A novelty and a smart waiting move preparing ...[f5] and avoiding ...[Bc4]+ in the critical line.} ({In the case of an immediate} 16... f5 {White has} 17. Rc1 Nd4 18. Nc7 {, and if we try to play like in our main line with} Bb3 {, White has the saving move.} 19. Bc4+ {with a complicated position.}) 17. Rc1 {If White tries to play in the same manner as after the immediate ...[f5], we can jump to [d4].} Nd4 18. Nc7 {The point is that this would be a fatal mistake here.} Bb3 {[%csl Gh8] With the king on [g8] and the pawn on [f5], White has [Bc4]+, as we have seen above.} 19. Qd2 Ra7 20. Ncd5 f5 {[%cal Gf5f4] Followed by ...[f4] with a crushing attack.} *

