1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {This damage to our pawn structure is forced, but it gives us a possibility to go for a dynamic play with a future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. c3 ({White's main choice together with} 11. Bd3 {, and may transpose to the same line.}) 11... f5 (11... f5 {Of course, when allowed, we seize our chance to push the f-pawn. Note that now} 12. Bd3 Ne7 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 {transposes to the 11.Bd3 line.}) 12. exf5 {Clearly, the most played.} Bxf5 13. Nc2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc2e3] White is executing the standard knight manoeuvre heading to [e3], from where it will support the centralised [d5]-knight.} O-O 14. Nce3 Be6 {[%csl Ge6] The bishop should be kept on this diagonal, as going to [g6] would invite a [h4]-[h5] push.} 15. Bd3 f5 16. O-O Kh8 {This is also a very decent option with similar ideas.} 17. Qh5 e4 18. Bc2 {White managed to stop the pawn roll for now, so we should try to activate our pieces.} Ne5 19. Nf4 Bd7 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gd7b5] I like this move because the bishop can be unexpectedly activated via [b5] in some lines after pushing ...[b4].} 20. Ned5 Rb8 {[%cal Gb5b4] Starting the preparations for ...[b4].} 21. Rae1 {For example, a natural developing move like this allows us to push.} b4 $132 (21... b4 {With a good counterplay. If White takes the bait with} 22. Nxb4 {, then we get the option to play} Rf6 {intending ...[Rh6], which is normally not possible with the knight on [d5].}) 22. cxb4 {And here comes the point.} Bb5 {Winning an exchange.} 23. Ne2 {Trying to avoid material losses puts White into a very passive position.} Rc8 $17 {[%csl Ge5,Gb5,Gc8,Gg7,Rf1,Re1,Re2,Rc2] Black is dominating.} *

