1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Qh5 {[%cal Rf6f5] Bringing the queen early into play is not recommended, but here, White has some point: to prevent the unpleasant ...[f5] break.} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5,Gd6d5] The rule is simple: if White prevents ...[f5], then we always continue with this. The idea is not only to exchange the active knight but also to liberate the [d5]-square and try to play for ...[d5] at some point.} 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Gd6d5,Ge7b4] Creating a simple but effective threat of ...[d5] and ...[Qb4], so White needs to take some prophylactic measures.} 13. c3 Qb7 {[%csl Ge4] Asking how White will defend [e4].} 14. Bd3 {The most obvious, but we get a chance to push.} f5 {[%cal Gb7g2]} 15. Qg5 f6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb7g7] The black queen is doing an excellent job, putting pressure on the diagonal and successfully defending.} 16. Qh5+ Qf7 17. Qxf7+ Kxf7 18. exf5 {Losing a pawn, but not for long.} e4 19. Bc2 Bxf5 {[%csl Gf5,Gg7][%cal Gh8d8,Gd6d5,Ga8c8] Enjoying the two-bishops advantage and easy play. Our next step should be activating the rooks.} *

