1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. c4 {As usual, if White does not prevent ...[f5], we go for it immediately, even if that means that some material must be sacrificed.} f5 $1 12. Bd3 {A more solid approach. Here, we have a pleasant choice.} Nd4 $5 {My recommendation.} 13. exf5 {This should be met by our thematic check.} Qa5+ 14. Qd2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Bh6+ 16. Kd1 {This looks safer, but is disrupting White's coordination.} Bb7 {Black has enough compensation for a pawn. White might decide to take more material.} 17. Nc7+ Ke7 18. Nxa8 {But now it's our turn.} Bxg2 19. Rg1 Bf3+ 20. Ke1 Bxa8 {[%csl Re1,Ga8,Gd4,Gh6,Ra3][%cal Gd4f3] We get into an extremely messy position where our chances are not inferior due to the activity of our minor pieces and White's stuck king in the centre.} *

