1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. c4 {As usual, if White does not prevent ...[f5], we go for it immediately, even if that means that some material must be sacrificed.} f5 $1 12. cxb5 Nd4 {The position is messy, but it's White who needs to be careful. Any attempt to keep material can be punished fast.} 13. b6 ({It might give the illusion that keeping the queenside closed is a safe option, but Black gets a powerful initiative regardless after simply finishing development.Being greedy is not recommended here, as after} 13. bxa6 O-O {, we bring our monarch to safety and threaten to simply take the central pawn. White can try} 14. exf5 {but the drawback of this move is getting a lousy knight on [d5]:} Qa5+ {forcing} 15. Nc3 {and now the thematic} d5 {-+ with full domination in the centre and fantastic piece activity. Besides the three pawns deficit, Black is taking over here.}) 13... O-O {[%cal Gc8b7,Gf5e4]} 14. Bd3 Bb7 15. Nc4 {This looks very natural but is already a losing move.} fxe4 $1 16. Bxe4 Kh8 {[%cal Gf7f5] Hiding from the discovered attack with the knight. White has no way to stop ...[f5], which will cause them material losses.} *

