1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. c4 {As usual, if White does not prevent ...[f5], we go for it immediately, even if that means that some material must be sacrificed.} f5 $1 12. cxb5 Nd4 {The position is messy, but it's White who needs to be careful. Any attempt to keep material can be punished fast.} 13. Bd3 Be6 14. O-O (14. Nc2 {leads to simplifications after} Bxd5 15. exd5 Qa5+ 16. Qd2 Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 e4 18. Nxd4 Bxd4 19. Bc4 axb5 20. Bxb5+ Ke7 {(White is a pawn up, but not for long. Black will soon get back the material as the bishop is hitting two pawns, and can try to put some pressure even e.g. ...[Rhg8] though objectively, the draw should be reached with a correct play from the White's side.)}) 14... fxe4 {Several ways of playing are possible, but I like this.} 15. Bxe4 Rc8 16. Qh5 {Preventing both ...[f5] and ...[O-O], so in this case, we should take back material.} axb5 17. Rac1 ({Or} 17. Rad1 h6 {and castle next.}) 17... Rc5 18. Rxc5 dxc5 19. Ne3 h6 {[%cal Ge8g8] Preparing castle with roughly equal chances, but the position is easier to play for Black as we have two bishops and the pawns are restricting White's knights.} *

