1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. g3 $5 ({This is a decent alternative to White's main lines} 11. Bd3 {and 11.c3 , covered in the previous chapters.}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] We continue with our usual plan.} 12. Bg2 {This is, of course, possible, but we get what we want after the simple knight trade.} Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Be6 14. Qd3 (14. Qc6+ {does not achieve anything.} Ke7 15. Qb7+ Qd7 16. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {, we get an easy play with the two bishops. ...[Rab8], ...[a5] and ...[Bh6] are in the cards.}) 14... Qd7 $1 {[%cal Yf6f5,Ya8d8] Preparing for our usual ...[f5] plan.} 15. O-O O-O {With a balanced position.} *

