1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. g3 $5 ({This is a decent alternative to White's main lines} 11. Bd3 {and 11.c3 , covered in the previous chapters.}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] We continue with our usual plan.} 12. Ne3 {Trying to avoid the exchanges and still keep control on both [d5]- and [f5]-squares.} Bh6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gh6e3] One of the typical ideas in Sveshnikov is to exchange the dark-squared bishop against the annoying knight to minimize the control of the [d5]-square.} 13. Ng4 Bxg4 14. Qxg4 {The point behind trading our light-squared bishop is that we are in time to go for ...[d5].} d5 15. Rd1 ({This gives us a good advantage. The natural-looking} 15. Bg2 {is actually losing the game. After} Qa5+ 16. c3 d4 17. O-O dxc3 {, White's queenside is collapsing.}) 15... Qa5+ 16. c3 d4 {[%csl Ra3,Rc3,Rb2][%cal Ga5e1,Gd4c3] White is in big trouble here.} *

