1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. g3 $5 ({This is a decent alternative to White's main lines} 11. Bd3 {and 11.c3 , covered in the previous chapters.}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] We continue with our usual plan.} 12. Ne3 {Trying to avoid the exchanges and still keep control on both [d5]- and [f5]-squares.} Bh6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gh6e3] One of the typical ideas in Sveshnikov is to exchange the dark-squared bishop against the annoying knight to minimize the control of the [d5]-square.} 13. Qf3 Bxe3 14. Qxf6 {This is possible, but we do not mind exchanging our doubled pawns.} Bxf2+ 15. Qxf2 Be6 16. O-O-O {Not a very usual decision in Sveshnikov, but it's playable.} Rc8 17. Nb1 O-O {[%cal Gd8c7] However, Black's chances look more promising on the queenside than White's on the kingside.} *

