1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. g3 $5 ({This is a decent alternative to White's main lines} 11. Bd3 {and 11.c3 , covered in the previous chapters.}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] We continue with our usual plan.} 12. Ne3 {Trying to avoid the exchanges and still keep control on both [d5]- and [f5]-squares.} Bh6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gh6e3] One of the typical ideas in Sveshnikov is to exchange the dark-squared bishop against the annoying knight to minimize the control of the [d5]-square.} 13. Qf3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 d5 {Here we go! By trading off the bishop against the knight, we lose our two bishops' advantage, but in exchange, we get to liberate ourselves with the thematic ...[d5].} (14... d5 {Now,} 15. exd5 {is not a good idea, as we are happy after} Qxd5 {with ...[Rb8] and ...[Be6] as our follow-up.}) 15. O-O-O {Pinning the pawn, but that's not a problem.} d4 16. Qh6 ({The only sensible continuation.} 16. Qd2 {is too passive and offers us a very pleasant play after} Nc6 {.}) (16. Qf3 {is also dubious due to the same reason.} Nc6 17. Nb1 Qe7 {White is struggling to find good squares for their pieces.}) 16... Qd6 17. Be2 (17. f4 {is a logical try, but here everything is good for Black. For example:} Ng6 18. Rg1 Qf8 19. Qh5 Qc5 {with a double-edged position.}) 17... Bb7 {[%cal Ge8c8] Next, we can bring our king into safety by castling long.} *

