1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. g3 $5 ({This is a decent alternative to White's main lines} 11. Bd3 {and 11.c3 , covered in the previous chapters.}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] We continue with our usual plan.} 12. Ne3 {Trying to avoid the exchanges and still keep control on both [d5]- and [f5]-squares.} f5 $5 {A more common move in our line and is perfectly playable here as well.} 13. exf5 Rb8 {[%cal Gd6d5,Ge7f5] Removing the rook from any possible pins or double attacks with an idea to recapture on [f5] next and also making ...[d5] possible.} 14. Bg2 Nxf5 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 16. O-O O-O 17. c3 Kh8 {[%cal Gf5g6] With roughly equal chances. Black can try to retreat the bishop on [g6] and organize ...[f5] next. The [d6]-pawn is our weakness, but as usual, our bishop pair gives us enough compensation.} *

