1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. g3 $5 ({This is a decent alternative to White's main lines} 11. Bd3 {and 11.c3 , covered in the previous chapters.}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] We continue with our usual plan.} 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Bg2 d5 $5 {[%cal Ge7b4] Whenever we get a chance, we do not hesitate to go for ...[d5]. The question is what happens after White's most natural reply, capturing with the queen.} (13... d5 {Now,} 14. O-O {gives us an easy play after} d4 {, and White is struggling with his poor knight.}) 14. exd5 Qb4+ (14... Qb4+ {The obvious point.} 15. Qd2 {is met by} Qxb2 {-+ .}) 15. c3 Qxb2 {Forcing White to find the only move.} 16. Qb3 (16. Nc2 Qxc3+ 17. Kf1 {(lead to 1-0 in 24 moves in Sjugirov, S 2663-Paravyan, D 2647 Lichess.org INT 2021. However, Black is winning after)} Bh6 {-+ .}) 16... Qxa1+ 17. Ke2 Bg4+ {An important intermediate move forcing White to block his bishop.} 18. f3 Qxh1 19. Bxh1 Bd7 {[%cal Ga8c8] If allowed, we would, of course, be happy to castle, so White should prevent it.} 20. Qb4 Rc8 {[%cal Gf6f5] The position remains unclear, but somehow Black's play looks easier to me.} *

