1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. g3 $5 ({This is a decent alternative to White's main lines} 11. Bd3 {and 11.c3 , covered in the previous chapters.}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] We continue with our usual plan.} 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Bg2 d5 $5 {[%cal Ge7b4] Whenever we get a chance, we do not hesitate to go for ...[d5]. The question is what happens after White's most natural reply, capturing with the queen.} (13... d5 {Now,} 14. O-O {gives us an easy play after} d4 {, and White is struggling with his poor knight.}) 14. Qxd5 Rb8 {Renewing the ...[Qb4] threat.} 15. Qc6+ {This is playable, but Black is just fine.} Bd7 16. Qxa6 Qb4+ 17. c3 Qxb2 18. O-O O-O {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gb8a8] White's problem remains the same: a poorly placed knight.} 19. Qd6 Rfd8 20. Qb4 {Now, despite being a pawn down, we can exchange queens.} Qxb4 21. cxb4 Be6 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gg7f8,Gd8d2] Our activity is fully compensating the pawn deficit.} *

