1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. g3 $5 ({This is a decent alternative to White's main lines} 11. Bd3 {and 11.c3 , covered in the previous chapters.}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] We continue with our usual plan.} 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Bg2 d5 $5 {[%cal Ge7b4] Whenever we get a chance, we do not hesitate to go for ...[d5]. The question is what happens after White's most natural reply, capturing with the queen.} (13... d5 {Now,} 14. O-O {gives us an easy play after} d4 {, and White is struggling with his poor knight.}) 14. Qxd5 Rb8 {Renewing the ...[Qb4] threat.} 15. O-O {One might ask, what have we achieved by sacrificing the central pawn? The answer is time! We'll get to finish our development, and White will still need to move the queen away before she gets in danger on the d-file. Another problem for White is the very passive knight on [a3], which cannot get activated in the near future.} (15. O-O-O {is a very dangerous choice. After} O-O 16. Qd6 Qa7 {-+ , White is in huge trouble.}) 15... O-O {Here, White should start worrying about the queen as it might get chased on the next moves.} 16. Qd3 {White wants to keep an eye on the [f5]-square to prevent us from advancing our pawn. Here, many moves are good, but I like a simple approach.} Be6 17. c3 Rfd8 18. Qe2 Qc5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ga6a5] Preparing our minority attack on the queenside. Black's active pieces fully compensate for a pawn.} *

