1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 ({Together with} 9. Nd5 {, this is one of the main Sveshnikov lines.}) 9... gxf6 {Forced, damaging our pawn structure but giving us a possibility to go for dynamic play with the future ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. g3 $5 ({This is a decent alternative to White's main lines} 11. Bd3 {and 11.c3 , covered in the previous chapters.}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] We continue with our usual plan.} 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Bg2 d5 $5 {[%cal Ge7b4] Whenever we get a chance, we do not hesitate to go for ...[d5]. The question is what happens after White's most natural reply, capturing with the queen.} (13... d5 {Now,} 14. O-O {gives us an easy play after} d4 {, and White is struggling with his poor knight.}) 14. Qxd5 Rb8 {Renewing the ...[Qb4] threat.} 15. O-O {One might ask, what have we achieved by sacrificing the central pawn? The answer is time! We'll get to finish our development, and White will still need to move the queen away before she gets in danger on the d-file. Another problem for White is the very passive knight on [a3], which cannot get activated in the near future.} (15. O-O-O {is a very dangerous choice. After} O-O 16. Qd6 Qa7 {-+ , White is in huge trouble.}) 15... O-O {Here, White should start worrying about the queen as it might get chased on the next moves.} 16. Qd1 {This looks a bit sad, but the queen needs to search for a safer place.} f5 {A move we are always happy to play in this line.} 17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Qe2 ({After} 18. c3 Rbd8 {, it's already not so easy to find a decent square for the queen.}) 18... e4 {Finally, the second bishop enters the game.} 19. c3 Bxc3 {The simplest. Now, both possible continuations lead to a balanced endgame.} 20. bxc3 Qxa3 21. Bxe4 {White wins a pawn but not for long.} Rfe8 22. f3 Qxc3 23. Rac1 Qd4+ 24. Qf2 Qxf2+ 25. Rxf2 Bxe4 26. fxe4 Rbc8 $10 {With equality.} *

