1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c4 {[%cal Gd1a4] By far, the most played. White protects the [d5]-pawn and opens up the way for his queen. Here, [Qa4] is already a threat, so we need to move the knight to make sure our [d6]-pawn is protected by the bishop.} (9. Be2 {is too slow and allows us to solve all the problems with} a6 {. Now, both retreats have their drawbacks.} 10. Na3 {allows} Qa5+ {and the [d5]-pawn is falling. 10.Nc3 Ng6 followed by ...[Be7], ...[O-O] and ...[f5] with an easy game.}) (9. Qf3 {is an attempt to be tricky, having in mind [Qc3] or [Qa3], but we can easily get a comfortable position with} a6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4] A way to restrict our knight and prepare [h4].} Be7 11. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Now, [h5] is a threat, and we should search for new possibilities for our knight.} e4 $1 {[%cal Gg6e5,Ge5f3,Ge5d3] Liberating the central square for the knight, from where he will threaten to jump either to [d3] or [f3].} 12. Be2 O-O 13. h5 Ne5 14. h6 {This is White's idea, trying to create some weaknesses around our king.} g6 15. O-O {After this, we may see that White's push of the h-pawn has also weakened the squares around their king.} Bh3 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf7f5,Gf1e1] I like provoking the rook to [e1], as the [f2]-pawn may become a target when we get our f-pawn rolling.} 16. Re1 Bd7 17. Nd4 Rc8 {[%csl Rc4] A pragmatic move activating the rook, attacking the [c4]-pawn and therefore provoking a move to protecting that pawn, which doesn't really suit White's plan.} 18. b3 Bg5 {[%cal Gf7f5] And it's White who needs to be careful here. Our next step could be ...[f5].} *

