1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c4 {[%cal Gd1a4] By far, the most played. White protects the [d5]-pawn and opens up the way for his queen. Here, [Qa4] is already a threat, so we need to move the knight to make sure our [d6]-pawn is protected by the bishop.} (9. Be2 {is too slow and allows us to solve all the problems with} a6 {. Now, both retreats have their drawbacks.} 10. Na3 {allows} Qa5+ {and the [d5]-pawn is falling. 10.Nc3 Ng6 followed by ...[Be7], ...[O-O] and ...[f5] with an easy game.}) (9. Qf3 {is an attempt to be tricky, having in mind [Qc3] or [Qa3], but we can easily get a comfortable position with} a6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Be3 {The bishop looks nice here but is much less dangerous than in the main line.} Be7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O {Once again, we can see that if White avoids the critical lines, they cannot hope for any opening advantage.} a6 13. Nc3 Bg5 {As usual, we want to exchange the dark-squared bishops.} 14. Qd2 Bxe3 15. fxe3 {And now comes the standard push.} f5 16. b4 {It makes sense for White to expand on the queenside where they have more space, but we should not be in any trouble.} a5 17. a3 Bd7 18. c5 {This is a critical try. We have a choice here, but the simplest is just to simplify.} axb4 19. axb4 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 dxc5 21. bxc5 Qc7 {[%csl Rc5,Ga5] An important move; otherwise, White's pawn chain will promise our opponent good practical chances. The queen not only attacks the pawn but also prevents [Ra5].} 22. Na4 Bxa4 23. Rxa4 Qxc5 24. d6 {Because of the strong d-pawn, White has enough compensation but not more than that.} f4 25. d7 fxe3 26. Qa2+ Kh8 (26... Kh8 {The engine claims that the only way to keep the balance for White here is to go} 27. h4 {with the evaluation of 0.00. In the human world, this looks like a complicated position to play with all the three results possible.}) *

