1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c4 {[%cal Gd1a4] By far, the most played. White protects the [d5]-pawn and opens up the way for his queen. Here, [Qa4] is already a threat, so we need to move the knight to make sure our [d6]-pawn is protected by the bishop.} (9. Be2 {is too slow and allows us to solve all the problems with} a6 {. Now, both retreats have their drawbacks.} 10. Na3 {allows} Qa5+ {and the [d5]-pawn is falling. 10.Nc3 Ng6 followed by ...[Be7], ...[O-O] and ...[f5] with an easy game.}) (9. Qf3 {is an attempt to be tricky, having in mind [Qc3] or [Qa3], but we can easily get a comfortable position with} a6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Qa4 {The most critical.} Bd7 11. Qb4 {White needs to unpin because ...[a6] was a threat.} Qb8 $5 {This looks passive, but it's the best way to protect [d6].} 12. Be3 {[%cal Gc4c5] This used to be the main line, with similar ideas as after [h4]. The threat is [c5].} a6 13. Nc3 a5 {My suggestion.} 14. Qa3 $5 {This looks smarter, avoiding ...[a4] coming with a tempo.} Be7 15. Na4 {This is a possibility, but it is more efficient with the queen on [b4] than on [a3].} Bd8 16. Nb6 Bxb6 17. Bxb6 O-O 18. g3 (18. h4 {can be simply met with} h5 {.}) 18... e4 {[%csl Rf3,Rd3][%cal Gg6e5] A typical pawn advance once White weakens the light squares.} 19. O-O-O Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3,Gg4d1]} (19... Bg4 {After} 20. Re1 {, the lines are not forced, but play might continue} Bf3 21. Rg1 Ne5 22. Kb1 Qc8 23. Rc1 Qf5 {with a double-edged position.}) *

