1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c4 {[%cal Gd1a4] By far, the most played. White protects the [d5]-pawn and opens up the way for his queen. Here, [Qa4] is already a threat, so we need to move the knight to make sure our [d6]-pawn is protected by the bishop.} (9. Be2 {is too slow and allows us to solve all the problems with} a6 {. Now, both retreats have their drawbacks.} 10. Na3 {allows} Qa5+ {and the [d5]-pawn is falling. 10.Nc3 Ng6 followed by ...[Be7], ...[O-O] and ...[f5] with an easy game.}) (9. Qf3 {is an attempt to be tricky, having in mind [Qc3] or [Qa3], but we can easily get a comfortable position with} a6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Qa4 {The most critical.} Bd7 11. Qb4 {White needs to unpin because ...[a6] was a threat.} Qb8 $5 {This looks passive, but it's the best way to protect [d6].} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] The inclusion of this move, which came into fashion after the Carlsen-Caruana match, forces Black to slightly weaken his kingside.} h5 {Black should not allow White to advance any further. White's idea is to have a target on [h5] once Black goes for short castle. It is true that we will not be able to save this pawn, but in exchange, we get enough counterplay. It should also be mentioned that just as our [h5]-pawn, the one on [h4] might also become a target in some lines.} 13. Bd3 {Another way to develop, having [Bxg6] as a possibility. The drawback of this move is that the bishop does not attack the [h5]-pawn, so we could castle easier without worrying about the pawn.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $1 {[%csl Rh4] White has several ways to deal with the threat.} 15. g3 O-O 16. Be2 {White's idea, but it costs some time, and we have enough resources for counterplay.} e4 $36 {[%cal Gg6e5] We definitely do not count pawns in this line!} 17. O-O {Bringing the king into safety is important, but now we can continue with our favourite push.} f5 {Protecting our central pawn.} 18. Bxh5 {The knight can comfortably jump to the centre.} Ne5 {[%cal Ge5d3]} 19. Be2 f4 {[%cal Gf4f3] One more pawn sacrifice!} 20. Bxf4 {The best reply.} Rxf4 21. gxf4 Nf3+ {At first glance, we might not have a feeling that this can work for Black as the queen is still far away, but actually, we can bring her to the kingside very fast.} 22. Kh1 {This would be a huge mistake.} Qf8 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Gf8f4] White is completely lost.} *

