lso become a target in some lines.} 13. Bd3 {Another way to develop, having [Bxg6] as a possibility. The drawback of this move is that the bishop does not attack the [h5]-pawn, so we could castle easier without worrying about the pawn.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $1 {[%csl Rh4] White has several ways to deal with the threat.} 15. g3 O-O 16. Be2 {White's idea, but it costs some time, and we have enough resources for counterplay.} e4 $36 {[%cal Gg6e5] We definitely do not count pawns in this line!} 17. O-O {Bringing the king into safety is important, but now we can continue with our favourite push.} f5 {Protecting our central pawn.} 18. Bxh5 {The knight can comfortably jump to the centre.} Ne5 {[%cal Ge5d3]} 19. Be2 f4 {[%cal Gf4f3] One more pawn sacrifice!} 20. Bxf4 {The best reply.} Rxf4 21. gxf4 Nf3+ {At first glance, we might not have a feeling that this can work for Black as the queen is still far away, but actually, we can bring her to the kingside very fast.} 22. Bxf3 exf3 23. Ne4 {White urgently needs to bring some pieces to the king's defence.} Qf8 {[%cal Gf8f4]} 24. Ng3 (24. Qd2 {does not help due to} Qf5 {, and the queen is heading to [h3].}) 24... Qxf4 {[%cal Ge7h4] Black has enough compensation for an exchange as White's king is weakened.} *

