lso become a target in some lines.} 13. g3 ({Stabilising the h4-pawn.} 13. Be2 {is also often played, but after} Be7 {, White needs to protect the pawn with} 14. g3 {, transposing.}) 13... Be7 14. Be2 {It might look as if Black is getting in big trouble here, unable to castle or create any serious threats, but actually, there is a very concrete solution here to solve all our problems.} a6 15. Nc3 b5 {We cannot sit and watch our opponent consolidating their position.} 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 O-O {The idea is that now White cannot capture on [h5] immediately} 18. a4 f5 {[%cal Gf5f4] We need to continue playing energetically even though that means giving up the [h5]-pawn.} 19. Bxh5 Bxb5 {[%csl Ra1]} 20. Bxg6 Bd8 {[%cal Gd8a5]} 21. Bd2 Qb7 {[%cal Gb7d5]} 22. Qb3 Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gb5a4]} ({Every move we make creates a threat, not allowing White to breathe and giving us enough compensation for material losses.} 22... Qd7 {would allow the unpleasant} 23. Qd1 {± with a deadly threat of [Qh5].}) 23. Qd1 $4 ({However, this is not working now. Note that} 23. Qb4 {, a reasonable-looking move protecting the queen, is met by} Qa6 $1 {again playing on the pin and followed by ...[Bd3]. White's king is still in the centre and it will very hard to hide it somewhere.}) 23... Qd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4e4,Ga8a4] Suddenly, Black gets a winning position as White cannot parry all the threats.} *

