1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c4 {By far, the most played. White protects the [d5]-pawn and opens up the way for his queen. Here, [Qa4] is already a threat, so we need to move the knight to make sure our [d6]-pawn is protected by the bishop.} (9. Be2 {is too slow and allows us to solve all the problems with} a6 {. Now, both retreats have their drawbacks.} 10. Na3 {allows} Qa5+ {and the [d5]-pawn is falling. 10.Nc3 Ng6 followed by ...[Be7], ...[O-O] and ...[f5] with an easy game.}) (9. Qf3 {is an attempt to be tricky, having in mind [Qc3] or [Qa3], but we can easily get a comfortable position with} a6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Qa4 {The most critical.} Bd7 11. Qb4 {White needs to unpin because ...[a6] was a threat.} Qb8 $5 {This looks passive, but it's the best way to protect [d6].} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] The inclusion of this move, which came into fashion after the Carlsen-Caruana match, forces Black to slightly weaken his kingside.} h5 {Black should not allow White to advance any further. White's idea is to have a target on [h5] once Black goes for short castle. It is true that we will not be able to save this pawn, but in exchange, we get enough counterplay. It should also be mentioned that just as our [h5]-pawn, the one on [h4] might also become a target in some lines.} 13. g3 ({Stabilising the h4-pawn.} 13. Be2 {is also often played, but after} Be7 {, White needs to protect the pawn with} 14. g3 {, transposing.}) 13... Be7 14. Be2 {It might look as if Black is getting in big trouble here, unable to castle or create any serious threats, but actually, there is a very concrete solution here to solve all our problems.} a6 15. Nc3 b5 {We cannot sit and watch our opponent consolidating their position.} 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 O-O {The idea is that now White cannot capture on [h5] immediately.} 18. a4 f5 {[%cal Gf5f4] We need to continue playing energetically even though that means giving up the [h5]-pawn.} 19. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2b4] A very natural developing move which protects the queen and should be addressed seriously.} f4 {Of course, we need to keep going.} 20. Ra3 $1 {[%cal Ga3g3] A very clever lateral defence you often see in the King's Indian Defence.} Bd8 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gd8a5] Suddenly, Black has many threats as ...[Bb6] or ...[Ba5]. The situation looks precarious for White. Time to bail out!} 21. Nxd6 $2 {This would lose material.} Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge7b4,Gb4a3] And we will collect something on the diagonal.} 22. Qxb8 Rfxb8 {[%cal Ge7a3,Gb8b2] The problems remain for White.} *

