target in some lines.} 13. g3 ({Stabilising the h4-pawn.} 13. Be2 {is also often played, but after} Be7 {, White needs to protect the pawn with} 14. g3 {, transposing.}) 13... Be7 14. Be2 {It might look as if Black is getting in big trouble here, unable to castle or create any serious threats, but actually, there is a very concrete solution here to solve all our problems.} a6 15. Nc3 b5 {We cannot sit and watch our opponent consolidating their position.} 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 O-O {The idea is that now White cannot capture on [h5] immediately.} 18. a4 f5 {[%cal Gf5f4] We need to continue playing energetically even though that means giving up the [h5]-pawn.} 19. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2b4] A very natural developing move which protects the queen and should be addressed seriously.} f4 {Of course, we need to keep going.} 20. Ra3 $1 {[%cal Ga3g3] A very clever lateral defence you often see in the King's Indian Defence.} Bd8 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gd8a5] Suddenly, Black has many threats as ...[Bb6] or ...[Ba5]. The situation looks precarious for White. Time to bail out!} 21. Qxd6 Qxd6 22. Nxd6 Be7 23. Ne4 (23. Bb4 $2 {seems to hold everything together, but} Rf6 $1 {wins a piece thanks to the pin.}) 23... Bxa3 24. bxa3 {[%csl Ra3,Ra4][%cal Gd2b4,Ge2h5] And now we got a weird position where Black is an exchange up, but White has 2 pawns doubled a-pawns, though, a nice square on [b4] for the bishop, and our [h5]-pawn is under attack. The position is objectively balanced.} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] Immediately attacking the dangerous d-pawn.} 25. d6 Nf5 {[%cal Gf5d4]} 26. gxf4 exf4 {[%cal Ga8a4,Gf8e8] Suddenly, Black has a lot of threats.} *

