1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c4 {[%cal Gd1a4] By far, the most played. White protects the [d5]-pawn and opens up the way for his queen. Here, [Qa4] is already a threat, so we need to move the knight to make sure our [d6]-pawn is protected by the bishop.} (9. Be2 {is too slow and allows us to solve all the problems with} a6 {. Now, both retreats have their drawbacks.} 10. Na3 {allows} Qa5+ {and the [d5]-pawn is falling. 10.Nc3 Ng6 followed by ...[Be7], ...[O-O] and ...[f5] with an easy game.}) (9. Qf3 {is an attempt to be tricky, having in mind [Qc3] or [Qa3], but we can easily get a comfortable position with} a6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Qa4 {The most critical.} Bd7 11. Qb4 {White needs to unpin because ...[a6] was a threat.} Qb8 $5 {This looks passive, but it's the best way to protect [d6].} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] The inclusion of this move, which came into fashion after the Carlsen-Caruana match, forces Black to slightly weaken his kingside.} h5 {Black should not allow White to advance any further. White's idea is to have a target on [h5] once Black goes for short castle. It is true that we will not be able to save this pawn, but in exchange, we get enough counterplay. It should also be mentioned that just as our [h5]-pawn, the one on [h4] might also become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. g3 {White wants to stabilise first and then start to attack the [h5]-pawn.} O-O 16. Be2 {Here, we accept the fact that the [h5]-pawn is going to be lost. In exchange, we can get a decent initiative by playing energetically.} b5 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Bxh5 {Here comes an important move.} Bd8 {[%cal Gd8a5,Gg6e7,Ge7f5] Trying to activate the bishop via [a5] and liberating the [e7]-square for our knight, which can jump further to [f5].} 19. Bxg6 {Getting rid of the knight is just dubious:} Ba5 20. Qb3 fxg6 {We get a powerful initiative with our bishop pair.} 21. O-O {The most natural reply, but we have something up our sleeve.} g5 $3 ({An incredible resource destabilising White's position. The point is that the immediate} 21... Rf3 {does not work due to} 22. Ne4 {and White stabilises.}) 22. Bxg5 ({Worse is} 22. hxg5 {when after} Qe8 {, Black is just invading the light squares around White's king with the help of their queen/bishop tandem. It makes sense for White to control the [h5]-square with} 23. Qd1 {, but after the forced sequence} Bxc3 24. bxc3 Bh3 25. Re1 Qd7 {, White's troubles are not over, as the light squares around their king are desesperately weak and ...[Bg4]...[Bf3] is a nasty threat.}) 22... Rf3 {[%cal Gb8f8,Gb5b4] White does not have [Ne4] and needs to come back.} 23. Be3 {Allowing us to win an important tempo and develop a dangerous attack.} Bxc3 24. Qxc3 Ra4 $3 {[%cal Gb8f8,Gf8f5,Ga4g4] Suddenly, the rook enters the game, and we can bring the queen next by playing ...[Qf8]. White is still fine but needs to be extremely careful here.} *

