1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c4 {[%cal Gd1a4] By far, the most played. White protects the [d5]-pawn and opens up the way for his queen. Here, [Qa4] is already a threat, so we need to move the knight to make sure our [d6]-pawn is protected by the bishop.} (9. Be2 {is too slow and allows us to solve all the problems with} a6 {. Now, both retreats have their drawbacks.} 10. Na3 {allows} Qa5+ {and the [d5]-pawn is falling. 10.Nc3 Ng6 followed by ...[Be7], ...[O-O] and ...[f5] with an easy game.}) (9. Qf3 {is an attempt to be tricky, having in mind [Qc3] or [Qa3], but we can easily get a comfortable position with} a6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Qa4 {The most critical.} Bd7 11. Qb4 {White needs to unpin because ...[a6] was a threat.} Qb8 $5 {This looks passive, but it's the best way to protect [d6].} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] The inclusion of this move, which came into fashion after the Carlsen-Caruana match, forces Black to slightly weaken his kingside.} h5 {Black should not allow White to advance any further. White's idea is to have a target on [h5] once Black goes for short castle. It is true that we will not be able to save this pawn, but in exchange, we get enough counterplay. It should also be mentioned that just as our [h5]-pawn, the one on [h4] might also become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. Na4 {A logical follow-up after we have weakened our [b6]-square.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ga4b6,Ga8d8] Liberating the rook. Here, White has a few interesting options.} (15... Nxh4 $2 {is not a good idea due to} 16. Nb6 Nf5 17. Bd2 $1 Ra7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. O-O-O {and our king cannot find a safe shelter.}) 16. Nb6 Rd8 {Now again White has a choice and has to decide where to put his king.} 17. g3 e4 {[%cal Gg6e5] As usual, preparing ...[Ne5].} (17... O-O {is a bit imprecise due to} 18. Be2 {hitting [h5], and we are not in time to create counterplay.}) 18. Nxd7 {Of course, this is not forced here, but at some point, White will need to play this move as, otherwise, the manoeuvre of [Na4]-[Nb6] does not make much sense!} Qxd7 19. Be2 Ne5 20. Kf1 {[%cal Gf1g2] White can try to improve the king, but this plan is a bit slow, and we get good dynamic play.} Rc8 21. Kg2 O-O {[%csl Rc4,Rh5] Taking advantage of the fact that the bishop is tied to the defence of the [c4]-pawn and cannot capture on [h5].} 22. b3 Bf6 {[%cal Ge5d3] Another threat is coming, so White again does not have time for [Bxh5].} 23. Rae1 {And now comes...} b5 $5 {Almost all of our pieces took active positions, and it's a good time to offer some material in exchange for initiative.} 24. cxb5 Qf5 {[%cal Gc8c2]} 25. bxa6 {This might look a bit scary, but this is in the spirit of Sveshnikov!} Rc2 {[%cal Gc2e2,Gf5f3]} 26. Bf4 e3 {Offering a third pawn! The truth is that grabbing this pawn would allow us to obtain a winning position immediately. White only has only way to stay in the game.} 27. Rhf1 {Taking on [e3] is not an option for White:} (27. fxe3 Nd3 {-+}) (27. Bxe3 Rxe2 $1 {-+ removing the defender of the [f3]-square.}) 27... Rxa2 $132 (27... Rxa2 {With powerful counterplay. White has several options here. For example, after} 28. Kg1 {, we can already force a draw by going} Rxe2 29. Rxe2 Nf3+ 30. Kg2 Nxh4+ {and White cannot avoid the perpetual check.}) *

