lso become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. Na4 {A logical follow-up after we have weakened our [b6]-square.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ga4b6,Ga8d8] Liberating the rook. Here, White has a few interesting options.} (15... Nxh4 $2 {is not a good idea due to} 16. Nb6 Nf5 17. Bd2 $1 Ra7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. O-O-O {and our king cannot find a safe shelter.}) 16. Nb6 Rd8 {Now again White has a choice and has to decide where to put his king.} 17. g3 e4 {[%cal Gg6e5] As usual, preparing ...[Ne5].} (17... O-O {is a bit imprecise due to} 18. Be2 {hitting [h5], and we are not in time to create counterplay.}) 18. Nxd7 {Of course, this is not forced here, but at some point, White will need to play this move as, otherwise, the manoeuvre of [Na4]-[Nb6] does not make much sense!} Qxd7 19. Be2 Ne5 20. Kf1 {[%cal Gf1g2] White can try to improve the king, but this plan is a bit slow, and we get good dynamic play.} Rc8 21. b3 {[%csl Gc4,Rh5] This makes sense. By protecting [c4], White renews the threat of [Bxh5] if we castle. However, we have a way to avoid the pawn loss and castle!} Bf6 {[%csl Ra1]} 22. Rd1 Ng4 23. Bb6 O-O {[%cal Gf6e5,Gf7f5] Followed by ...[Be5] and ...[f5] with a messy position.} *

