1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c4 {[%cal Gd1a4] By far, the most played. White protects the [d5]-pawn and opens up the way for his queen. Here, [Qa4] is already a threat, so we need to move the knight to make sure our [d6]-pawn is protected by the bishop.} (9. Be2 {is too slow and allows us to solve all the problems with} a6 {. Now, both retreats have their drawbacks.} 10. Na3 {allows} Qa5+ {and the [d5]-pawn is falling. 10.Nc3 Ng6 followed by ...[Be7], ...[O-O] and ...[f5] with an easy game.}) (9. Qf3 {is an attempt to be tricky, having in mind [Qc3] or [Qa3], but we can easily get a comfortable position with} a6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Qa4 {The most critical.} Bd7 11. Qb4 {White needs to unpin because ...[a6] was a threat.} Qb8 $5 {This looks passive, but it's the best way to protect [d6].} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] The inclusion of this move, which came into fashion after the Carlsen-Caruana match, forces Black to slightly weaken his kingside.} h5 {Black should not allow White to advance any further. White's idea is to have a target on [h5] once Black goes for short castle. It is true that we will not be able to save this pawn, but in exchange, we get enough counterplay. It should also be mentioned that just as our [h5]-pawn, the one on [h4] might also become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. Na4 {A logical follow-up after we have weakened our [b6]-square.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ga4b6,Ga8d8] Liberating the rook. Here, White has a few interesting options.} (15... Nxh4 $2 {is not a good idea due to} 16. Nb6 Nf5 17. Bd2 $1 Ra7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. O-O-O {and our king cannot find a safe shelter.}) 16. Nb6 Rd8 {Now again White has a choice and has to decide where to put his king.} 17. Nxd7 {Grabbing the bishop might look attractive, but we are relieved to exchange some pieces due to our lack of space.} Qxd7 18. O-O-O (18. g3 {is a consolidating move, but as usual, its drawback are the weakened light-squares.} O-O {bringing the king to the queenside is interesting, but we'll meet} 19. O-O-O {with} e4 {followed by ...[Ne5]. ...[Rb8] and ...[b5] could be our next steps.}) {Note that 19.Be2 is not winning a pawn as we have 19...Qf5 20.Kf1 and, of course, we go for 20...e4 21.Kg2 Bf6 22.Rad1 Ne5 with a complicated position.} 18... O-O (18... Rc8 {is somehow more useful for White as he wanted to go} 19. Kb1 {anyway. Though} Nxh4 {is possible, I don't like it much as it gives White some initiative. After} 20. g3 Nf5 21. Bh3 g6 22. f4 {, our position looks dangerous.}) 19. g3 ({By now, we should have learnt the typical reaction to this move.} 19. Qb3 e4 20. Kb1 Ne5 21. g3 {is just a transposition to 21.Qb3.}) 19... e4 {[%cal Gg6e5] As usual. Once the pawn moves to [g3], ...[e4] works perfectly.} 20. Kb1 Ne5 {White has a bunch of possibilities here, but nothing critical. One of the ideas could be to improve the position of the queen.} 21. Qb3 $5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb3c2] The idea might be to go to [c2] at some point and attack [e4].} Rc8 {It's difficult to find some clear plan for both sides, so the game continues by slowly improving the position. We should, however, be alert about [c5] and make sure White does not get a convenient moment to advance this pawn.} 22. a3 Kh7 23. Be2 {[%csl Rh5]} g6 {Protecting the pawn and preparing a regrouping.} 24. Rc1 Rfe8 25. Rhd1 Bf8 {[%cal Gf8h6] Followed by ...[Bh6] with a solid game.} *

