lso become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. Na4 {A logical follow-up after we have weakened our [b6]-square.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ga4b6,Ga8d8] Liberating the rook. Here, White has a few interesting options.} (15... Nxh4 $2 {is not a good idea due to} 16. Nb6 Nf5 17. Bd2 $1 Ra7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. O-O-O {and our king cannot find a safe shelter.}) 16. Nb6 Rd8 {Now again White has a choice and has to decide where to put his king.} 17. Nxd7 {Grabbing the bishop might look attractive, but we are relieved to exchange some pieces due to our lack of space.} Qxd7 18. O-O-O (18. g3 {is a consolidating move, but as usual, its drawback are the weakened light-squares.} O-O {bringing the king to the queenside is interesting, but we'll meet} 19. O-O-O {with} e4 {followed by ...[Ne5]. ...[Rb8] and ...[b5] could be our next steps.}) {Note that 19.Be2 is not winning a pawn as we have 19...Qf5 20.Kf1 and, of course, we go for 20...e4 21.Kg2 Bf6 22.Rad1 Ne5 with a complicated position.} 18... O-O (18... Rc8 {is somehow more useful for White as he wanted to go} 19. Kb1 {anyway. Though} Nxh4 {is possible, I don't like it much as it gives White some initiative. After} 20. g3 Nf5 21. Bh3 g6 22. f4 {, our position looks dangerous.}) 19. g3 ({By now, we should have learnt the typical reaction to this move.} 19. Qb3 e4 20. Kb1 Ne5 21. g3 {is just a transposition to 21.Qb3.}) 19... e4 {[%cal Gg6e5] As usual. Once the pawn moves to [g3], ...[e4] works perfectly.} 20. Kb1 Ne5 {White has a bunch of possibilities here, but nothing critical. One of the ideas could be to improve the position of the queen.} 21. Qb6 {This looks interesting, blocking the b-pawn and ready to go to [d4] when needed.} Rb8 {[%cal Ge7d8] Preparing ...[Bd8].} 22. Rc1 Bd8 23. Qb3 {[%cal Gc4c5]} ({White would like to push c5 next.} 23. Qa7 {is possible, but we can simply play} Bf6 {⇆ .}) 23... b6 {A logical continuation.} 24. c5 {This can still be tried.} dxc5 25. Bxc5 {A dangerous choice.} bxc5 26. Qxb8 Bf6 {[%csl Rb8,Gf6,Ge5,Rd3,Rf3,Rd5] Now, this gives us some powerful initiative.} *

