lso become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. Na4 {A logical follow-up after we have weakened our [b6]-square.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ga4b6,Ga8d8] Liberating the rook. Here, White has a few interesting options.} (15... Nxh4 $2 {is not a good idea due to} 16. Nb6 Nf5 17. Bd2 $1 Ra7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. O-O-O {and our king cannot find a safe shelter.}) 16. Bb6 {[%cal Gb6a5] With an idea to regroup the bishop.} Qc8 17. Ba5 {[%cal Ga4b6] Nb6 is a threat.} Rb8 18. Nb6 Qc7 {White cannot take advantage of our queen's awkward position.} 19. Na8 {This is a way to force a draw by a move repetition.} Qc8 (19... Qc8 {Now,} 20. Nb6 Qc7 {is the logical outcome. Let's see what happens if White tries for more:}) 20. Nc7+ $2 {White can get into trouble.} Kf8 21. c5 Kg8 22. cxd6 Bf8 {[%cal Gh8h6,Gg6f4,Gf8d6] White's pieces are too badly placed, especially the knight on [c7], whereas Black has an easy game following up with ...[Rh6] and ...[Nf4]. The [d6]-pawn will fall soon.} *

