1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c4 {[%cal Gd1a4] By far, the most played. White protects the [d5]-pawn and opens up the way for his queen. Here, [Qa4] is already a threat, so we need to move the knight to make sure our [d6]-pawn is protected by the bishop.} (9. Be2 {is too slow and allows us to solve all the problems with} a6 {. Now, both retreats have their drawbacks.} 10. Na3 {allows} Qa5+ {and the [d5]-pawn is falling. 10.Nc3 Ng6 followed by ...[Be7], ...[O-O] and ...[f5] with an easy game.}) (9. Qf3 {is an attempt to be tricky, having in mind [Qc3] or [Qa3], but we can easily get a comfortable position with} a6 $1 {and if} 10. Qa3 {, we can simply go} Nxd5 $1 {with a healthy pawn up.}) 9... Ng6 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 10. Qa4 {The most critical.} Bd7 11. Qb4 {White needs to unpin because ...[a6] was a threat.} Qb8 $5 {This looks passive, but it's the best way to protect [d6].} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] The inclusion of this move, which came into fashion after the Carlsen-Caruana match, forces Black to slightly weaken his kingside.} h5 {Black should not allow White to advance any further. White's idea is to have a target on [h5] once Black goes for short castle. It is true that we will not be able to save this pawn, but in exchange, we get enough counterplay. It should also be mentioned that just as our [h5]-pawn, the one on [h4] might also become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. Na4 {A logical follow-up after we have weakened our [b6]-square.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ga4b6,Ga8d8] Liberating the rook. Here, White has a few interesting options.} (15... Nxh4 $2 {is not a good idea due to} 16. Nb6 Nf5 17. Bd2 $1 Ra7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. O-O-O {and our king cannot find a safe shelter.}) 16. g3 O-O $5 {An interesting way to continue offering White a possibility of winning the [h5]-pawn.} 17. Nb6 {This looks somehow less logical than [Nb6] immediately because now we have an extra option of bringing the rook to [e8], but the line is recommended by GM Santos in his course Play the Open Sicilian, so we should take it seriously.} Rae8 {A novelty, but this is given by Santos in his course. The rook is better placed here than on [d8] as we can create some threats on the king if White is careless.} 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 {White can get two bishops, but our knight will be very strong once we bring it to [e5].} 19. O-O-O e4 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gg6e5]} 20. Bd4 {That's what GM Santos wants. It makes a lot of sense as White has the bishop pair and a long-term plan.} Bf6 $1 {We should react immediately in order to get our knight to [e5].} 21. Bh3 Qc7 22. Bxf6 {This looks tempting as it destroys Black's pawn structure on the kingside. On the other hand, we are getting our knight to [e5].} gxf6 {[%cal Gg6e5]} 23. Kb1 Ne5 24. Bf5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5] Very interesting and sharp position where both sides have their trumps.} Ng4 $5 {[%cal Gg4f2,Ge8e5]} 25. Bxg4 hxg4 {[%cal Ge8e5,Gf6f5,Ge4e3,Gg8h7,Gb7b5] A weird position, but Black has definitely a lot of play, keeping in mind the pawn breaks ...[e3] and ...[b5] as options for the future. Also, the king on [h7] will be protected by White's ! [h4]-pawn.} *

