lso become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. Na4 {A logical follow-up after we have weakened our [b6]-square.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ga4b6,Ga8d8] Liberating the rook. Here, White has a few interesting options.} (15... Nxh4 $2 {is not a good idea due to} 16. Nb6 Nf5 17. Bd2 $1 Ra7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. O-O-O {and our king cannot find a safe shelter.}) 16. g3 O-O $5 {An interesting way to continue offering White a possibility of winning the [h5]-pawn.} 17. Nb6 {This looks somehow less logical than [Nb6] immediately because now we have an extra option of bringing the rook to [e8], but the line is recommended by GM Santos in his course Play the Open Sicilian, so we should take it seriously.} Rae8 {A novelty, but this is given by Santos in his course. The rook is better placed here than on [d8] as we can create some threats on the king if White is careless.} 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 {White can get two bishops, but our knight will be very strong once we bring it to [e5].} 19. O-O-O e4 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gg6e5]} 20. Bd4 {That's what GM Santos wants. It makes a lot of sense as White has the bishop pair and a long-term plan.} Bf6 $1 {We should react immediately in order to get our knight to [e5].} 21. Bh3 Qc7 22. Bb6 {Favourite of GM Santos.} Qb8 23. Rd2 {And Santos rightfully assesses this position as extremely complex with chances for both sides. Let's continue a bit and show the plan for Black.} Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5d3,Gg7g6,Gf6g7,Gf7f5]} 24. Kb1 g6 {[%cal Gf6g7,Gf7f5,Ge5f3,Ge5d3] Now everything becomes clear. We will retreat the bishop to [g7], push ...[f5] in order to restrict White's light-squared bishop and decide where to put the knight f3 or [d3] when White shows his intentions. Obviously, the position is very rich, and White has a lot of options. Let's have a look at a possible line which strikes me as logical.} 25. Qb3 Bg7 26. c5 {That's what this line is all about for White: push the queenside majority.} Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gf3d4]} 27. Rdd1 f5 $1 {[%csl Rh3]} 28. c6 Rc8 {[%cal Gg7b2,Gb7c6] And it is already not that easy for White to be at ease with his ambitious previous play. For instance:} 29. c7 $4 {This is very bad as Black sacks the exchange with the best compensations ever!} Rxc7 30. Bxc7 Qxc7 {[%cal Gg7b2,Gc7a5,Gf3d2] Black is simply winning here.} *

