lso become a target in some lines.} 13. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5] Here, White's idea is to push [c5], so we cannot play slowly.} a6 14. Nc3 Be7 $5 {[%csl Gh4] Developing the bishop and keeping an eye on the [h4]-pawn, which might be taken at some point.} 15. Na4 {A logical follow-up after we have weakened our [b6]-square.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ga4b6,Ga8d8] Liberating the rook. Here, White has a few interesting options.} (15... Nxh4 $2 {is not a good idea due to} 16. Nb6 Nf5 17. Bd2 $1 Ra7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. O-O-O {and our king cannot find a safe shelter.}) 16. g3 O-O $5 {An interesting way to continue offering White a possibility of winning the [h5]-pawn.} 17. Be2 Rae8 {Bringing all the pieces into play and preparing a counterattack in the centre.} 18. Nb6 {Once again, this makes much less sense when the rook is already on [e8] and the bishop can be saved.} Bf5 19. a4 {We go as usual.} e4 {[%cal Gg6e5] Now, White can take the pawn.} 20. Bxh5 {We no longer have ...[Nf4] ideas, but now the knight gets active via [e5].} Ne5 {[%cal Ge5d3]} 21. Kf1 Bf6 {[%cal Gf5g4,Ge5g4] Improving our pieces with each move.} 22. Kg2 Bg4 23. Bxg4 Nxg4 {After the bishop exchange, White's light-squares will be even more vulnerable, promising us a decent compensation for a pawn.} *

