1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c3 (9. c3 {This is considered less dangerous than the 9.c4 line but still needs to be taken seriously as there are some tricks we need to be aware of. For example,} a6 $4 {is premature due to} 10. Qa4 {, and we don't have a good defence against the discovered check.}) 9... Ng6 $4 {Here, this would be bad.} 10. Qa4 Bd7 11. Qb4 Qb8 12. Qc4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gc3][%cal Gb5c7] Now we see the difference with the main line. The [c4]-square is useful for the queen.} *

