1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c3 (9. c3 {This is considered less dangerous than the 9.c4 line but still needs to be taken seriously as there are some tricks we need to be aware of. For example,} a6 $4 {is premature due to} 10. Qa4 {, and we don't have a good defence against the discovered check.}) 9... Nf5 $1 {It's a bit counter-intuitive to bring the knight to [f5] with a pawn on [c3], but it's the best choice. As we have seen in the informational, ...[Ng6] is not working due to concrete reasons, and we need to develop fast, so [f5] is the only sensible square for the knight.} 10. a4 Be7 11. Be2 {This is, of course, playable but not harmful.} O-O 12. O-O Nh4 {[%cal Gf7f5]} ({As usual, trying to push ...f5.} 12... Bg5 $5 {is a thematic exchange in the Sveshnikov structures and a good alternative to ...[Nh4]. Play might continue} 13. Qb3 Bxc1 14. Rfxc1 Bd7 15. Qb4 {targeting [d6].} a5 16. Qe4 Qg5 {with a balanced position.}) 13. f4 a6 {Before capturing on [f4], we make sure the knight does not get the [d4]-square.} 14. Na3 exf4 15. Bxf4 Ng6 {Time to centralise the knight.} 16. Be3 Bg5 17. Bd4 Bf4 $132 {[%cal Gd8g5,Gg5h4] With nice play on the dark squares. ...[Qg5] or ...[Qh4] will follow next} *

