1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. c3 (9. c3 {This is considered less dangerous than the 9.c4 line but still needs to be taken seriously as there are some tricks we need to be aware of. For example,} a6 $4 {is premature due to} 10. Qa4 {, and we don't have a good defence against the discovered check.}) 9... Nf5 $1 {It's a bit counter-intuitive to bring the knight to [f5] with a pawn on [c3], but it's the best choice. As we have seen in the informational, ...[Ng6] is not working due to concrete reasons, and we need to develop fast, so [f5] is the only sensible square for the knight.} 10. a4 Be7 11. Bd3 ({This looks the most natural, keeping an eye on the f5-knight.} 11. g3 {, as usual, can be met with} h5 $5 {, and if White stops our pawn from further advancing with} 12. h4 {, then simply} g6 {, followed by castling with a balanced position.}) 11... O-O 12. O-O Bd7 (12... Nh4 {is the most played, but I believe it's not the most precise as this line works less well with the bishop on [d3].} 13. f4 $1 {gives White some initiative. Let's see what happens if we continue just as after 11.Be2: The line goes} a6 14. Na3 exf4 15. Bxf4 Ng6 16. Be3 Bg5 17. Bd4 {and, in comparison to the 11.Be2 line, we do not have} Bf4 {here due to} 18. Bxg6 {. The position is still playable for Black, but I think it's easier to play for White.}) 13. Re1 Nh4 {This works nicely again.} 14. f4 a6 15. Na3 {Here, we have a pleasant choice.} f5 {My preference, offering White a poisonous pawn.} 16. fxe5 dxe5 17. Rxe5 {This is bad.} Bc5+ 18. Kh1 Qf6 19. Nc4 f4 $19 {[%cal Gf4f3] And Black's attack is unstoppable.} *

