1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. a4 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Ga4a5,Gc1e3] This has been tried by some elite players, so we should definitely check how to react here. White's plan is quite simple: to push [a5] and then continue with [Be3] provoking ...[a6] and taking full control over the [b6]-square.} a6 $1 ({It is important to start with this move to force White's hand.} 9... Ng6 {is not working well due to} 10. Be3 a6 11. Na3 $1 {, and now the [d5]-pawn is not hanging after ...[Qa5]+. White gets a good advantage thanks to the weakness of the [b6]-square.}) 10. Nc3 (10. Na3 {is not working here as after} Qa5+ {, the [d5]-pawn is lost.}) 10... Ng6 11. a5 {White continues with the plan, fixing our pawns and trying to exploit the [b6]-square later on.} (11. Be2 {is harmless:} Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. a5 Bd7 {followed by ...[f5] and ...[b6].}) 11... Be7 12. Be3 O-O 13. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4] A way to prepare [h4].} f5 {This works nicely.} 14. h4 e4 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gg6e5] With good play on the dark squares.} *

