1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 ({A move which was somehow in the shadow of the main line} 7. Bg5 {for years. 2018 became the golden era for this line when Caruana played it in his World Championship match against Carlsen. Curiously, [Nd5] is the move the engines prefer, often claiming a slight advantage for White. Still, the truth is that it leads to extremely complicated positions not at all easy to play and offering enough counterplay for Black.}) 7... Nxd5 {This is obligatory.} 8. exd5 {Here, Black has two playable options. My suggestion, though less often seen in practice, is very dynamic.} Ne7 $5 9. h4 {This has never been tried but is playable. However, as our knight is still on [e7], we are not forced to reply with ...[h5] as in the main line.} a6 10. Nc3 {Now, it is more logical to place the knight on [f5].} Nf5 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8]} 11. g3 Be7 12. Ne4 O-O 13. c3 {Here, everything is playable for Black, but I like an odd-looking move.} Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5] Preparing ...[f5].} 14. Bd3 (14. Bxh6 {is not that great as after} gxh6 {, we get the bishop pair and still want to proceed with ...[f5]. Black's chances are already preferable.}) 14... f5 15. Ng5 Qb6 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gh6g4] With a comfortable position. ...[Ng4] could be played next.} *

