1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Be3 {This can be a bit tricky.} a6 8. Na3 {Now, I think the best is to play a waiting move.} Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ({Preparing ...b5. The immediate} 8... b5 {runs into} 9. Nd5 {threatening [Bb6], and after} Nxd5 10. exd5 Ne7 {, White has an option of} 11. c4 $1 {With the pawn already on [b5], this is a bit annoying as our queenside can quickly get exposed.}) 9. Nd5 ({Clearly, the most played.} 9. Bg5 {is a bit strange as after} b5 10. Nd5 Be7 {, we kind of transpose to the main line of Sveshnikov with an improved rook on [b8].}) 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Ne7 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ge7f5,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Heading to [f5].} 11. c4 {Here, we can see the difference with 8...b5. It is preferable to have the rook on [b8] rather than the pawn on [b5] as now White is not threatening anything, and we can continue improving our position.} Nf5 12. Bd2 Be7 {[%cal Ge7g5]} 13. Bd3 O-O 14. O-O Nh4 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gf7f5,Ge5e4,Gc8d7] We have our standard plan with ...[f5] and ...[e4] and can try to bring more pieces towards the white king. Black's position is preferable.} *

