1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4] White tries to be smart and regroup the knight fast via [c4]. The only thing to know here is that we do not need to waste our time on ...[a6] anymore.} Bg4 $1 ({Again, this simple move is annoying for White.} 7... a6 {is pointless now as after} 8. Nc4 $1 {, the knight will further go to [e3] and eventually [d5].}) 8. f3 Be6 {[%cal Gd6d5] Preparing ...[d5].} 9. Bg5 {Another way to stop ...[d5].} Be7 10. Bxf6 {The thematic exchange in order to control the [d5]-square, but the thing is that White has already weakened the dark squares by playing [f3], so giving away the dark-squared bishop might be a dangerous choice.} Bxf6 11. Nd5 {This looks better but still problematic.} Bg5 {[%csl Re3,Rf2] White is in danger with those weakened squares.} *

