1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. a4 {This can come as a bad surprise if we are not familiar with this position, as White simply prevents our plan with ...[b5]. Of course, Black has no problems here, and I suggest kicking the knight, followed by the annoying ...[Bg4].} a6 8. Na3 Bg4 $1 {Simple and effective. The idea is to disrupt the harmony in White's position or to make favourable exchanges.} 9. Be2 {Tthis time, we are happy to exchange our light-squared bishop.} Bxe2 10. Qxe2 {We get the immediate chance to get rid of our [d6]-weakness.} d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 {The most played, but White cannot hope for any advantage when accepting all the exchanges favourable to Black.} Qxd5 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gd5g2]} 13. O-O Nd4 14. Qd3 Rd8 {As you can see, Black's play is very easy: all our forces are joining the battle.} 15. Be3 Bc5 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 16. Bxd4 Qxd4 {[%csl Ra3,Gc5] The position is balanced, but it looks easier to play with Black.} *

