1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 ({The starting position of the Open Sveshnikov. Actually,} 5... e5 {(is a very dynamic move: it creates a threat of winning a piece should be spotted by your opponent!, therefore winning some time for our development as White will have to lose a tempo by moving the knight and, more importantly, Black has a weak square on [d5]. We will have to compensate for that with once again! dynamic play.)}) 6. Ndb5 {That's the move! It is actually quite funny that White has a bunch of options, but none of them are even close to being dangerous options.} (6. Nf5 {is probably the best of the sidelines, but Black is at least fine by precise play after} d5 $1 {.}) 6... d6 {We are threatening to go ...[a6]-...[b5] and embarrass the knights. Here is the first real crossroads.} 7. a4 {This can come as a bad surprise if we are not familiar with this position, as White simply prevents our plan with ...[b5]. Of course, Black has no problems here, and I suggest kicking the knight, followed by the annoying ...[Bg4].} a6 8. Na3 Bg4 $1 {Simple and effective. The idea is to disrupt the harmony in White's position or to make favourable exchanges.} 9. f3 {The most common reply, the drawback of which is the weakened dark squares.} Be6 10. Be3 {This looks very natural but is already an inaccuracy.} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5] ...[d5] will come next, creating a serious threat on [d4].} 11. Nc4 {This makes things even worse.} d5 12. Bb6 Qe7 {The best. The point is to leave the last rank free for the rook.} 13. exd5 Nbxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5b6]} 15. Bf2 Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d1,Gd5f4,Gd5b4] This is very strong, creating multiple threats White cannot handle.} *

