1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 ({After} 4. c3 {, the most logical for us is to continue with} Nf6 {and after} 5. e5 Nd5 {, we transpose to our Alapin lines.}) 4... Nf6 5. f3 {Here, I suggest a rarely chosen move.} d5 $1 ({Asking White concrete questions.} 5... e5 {I like less because after} 6. Nb5 d6 {, White has an option of} 7. c4 {and this leads to something that we usually do not get when playing the Sveshnikov.}) 6. Nc3 {Now, we can continue with the most tempting option.} e5 {Now, White only has one line to avoid being worse.} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Bg5 {This is not dangerous.} d4 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Ne4 Be7 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gf6f5,Ga8b8] Simple chess. The knight will soon be pushed away with ...[f5]. Black has a strong centre and can also improve the rook by playing ...[Rb8] next.} *

