1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 ({After} 4. c3 {, the most logical for us is to continue with} Nf6 {and after} 5. e5 Nd5 {, we transpose to our Alapin lines.}) 4... Nf6 5. f3 {Here, I suggest a rarely chosen move.} d5 $1 ({Asking White concrete questions.} 5... e5 {I like less because after} 6. Nb5 d6 {, White has an option of} 7. c4 {and this leads to something that we usually do not get when playing the Sveshnikov.}) 6. Nc3 {Now, we can continue with the most tempting option.} e5 {Now, White only has one line to avoid being worse.} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qe2 {Here, everything is good, but my preference is to continue with active play.} d4 {Sacrificing a pawn for fast development.} 12. Qxe5+ Be7 13. Ne2 {and now} d3 14. cxd3 O-O 15. O-O Rfe8 {[%csl Re5,Rd3] Black's pieces are much more active and fully compensate for the material deficit. The [d3]-pawn cannot be saved as White needs to take care of their poorly placed pieces.} 16. Nc3 Qxd3 (16... Qxd3 {With excellent compensation, as it is very difficult for White to coordinate their pieces with such a misplaced queen in the centre.} 17. Qb5 {is an attempt to get rid of the queens.} Qd4+ {Keeping the queens on the board is the ambitious way to treat the position.} 18. Kh1 a6 {and the white queen can't find a peaceful place. After 17...Qxb5 18.Nxb5 Bc5+ 19.Kh1 Rab8 , Black's compensation is patent. All our pieces are very active and won't be easy for White to develop without losing the [b2]-pawn due to our pressure on the b-file.}) *

