1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 ({After} 4. c3 {, the most logical for us is to continue with} Nf6 {and after} 5. e5 Nd5 {, we transpose to our Alapin lines.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 {Here, White has tried all the possible moves with the knight and we will briefly check each of them.} 6. Nb3 {This should be met the same way.} Bb4 {[%csl Ge4]} 7. Bd3 ({This allows our central push. After} 7. Bg5 {, we can continue the same way as in the 6.Nf3 line with} h6 {and, after the most logical} 8. Bxf6 {, we include} Bxc3+ $1 {in order not to give White time to protect the knight and avoid pawn doubling.} 9. bxc3 Qxf6 {with a very easy play: ...[O-O], ...[d6], ...[Be6] and ...[Rc8] to put pressure on [c3].}) 7... d5 {Here, White has two sensible moves.} 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Bd2 {Avoiding material losses, but Black's position is still preferable.} Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7 11. Qh5 {This prevents us from castling, but we have a nice regrouping.} g6 12. Qh6 Bf8 13. Qe3 Bg7 {[%cal Ge8g8] Ready to castle now so White should try something.} 14. Qc5 Qc7 {[%cal Gb7b6] Preparing ...[b6].} 15. O-O b6 16. Qa3 Ne7 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3][%cal Ge8g8] It took us some time, but we will manage to castle next and have a position with better prospects.} *

