1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 ({After} 4. c3 {, the most logical for us is to continue with} Nf6 {and after} 5. e5 Nd5 {, we transpose to our Alapin lines.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 {Here, White has tried all the possible moves with the knight and we will briefly check each of them.} 6. Nde2 {A new fashionable line tried by some top grandmasters. Since the knight on [c3] is well protected now, I prefer to develop the bishop to [c5].} Bc5 {[%cal Gf6g4] ...[Ng4] is a serious threat.} 7. Ng3 O-O (7... d6 {is premature due to} 8. Na4 $1 {and the only way to save the bishop is to go ...[Bb4]-...[Ba5]-...[Bc7] which I don't like.}) 8. Bc4 d6 9. Bg5 {This is met as usual.} h6 10. Bxf6 {White's idea behind exchanging the bishop is to take full control of the [d5]-square.} Qxf6 11. O-O Be6 12. Nd5 Qg5 {Usually, in the Sveshnikov, our dark-squared bishop is quite passive on [g5] and we often transfer it to [b6] via [d8]. Here, we don't need to bother about it.} 13. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4] White's [b4] ideas should be prevented.} a5 {[%cal Gc6e7]} 14. Kh1 Ne7 {We have already seen this thematic idea in many lines. The [Nd5] is very active, so we try to exchange it. The position remains balanced.} *

