1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 ({After} 4. c3 {, the most logical for us is to continue with} Nf6 {and after} 5. e5 Nd5 {, we transpose to our Alapin lines.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 {Here, White has tried all the possible moves with the knight and we will briefly check each of them.} 6. Nde2 {A new fashionable line tried by some top grandmasters. Since the knight on [c3] is well protected now, I prefer to develop the bishop to [c5].} Bc5 {[%cal Gf6g4] ...[Ng4] is a serious threat.} 7. Ng3 O-O (7... d6 {is premature due to} 8. Na4 $1 {and the only way to save the bishop is to go ...[Bb4]-...[Ba5]-...[Bc7] which I don't like.}) 8. Bc4 d6 9. O-O Ng4 $1 {[%cal Gd8h4]} ({I like this aggressive approach. ...Qh4 is coming next.This line will end up in a perpetual with perfect play, but} 9... a6 $5 {is just a very decent way to get an abjectively equal and playable game.} 10. a4 h6 {There are many options for both sides, but Black has a clear plan in mind with ...[Nb4] and ...[Be6], which could be followed by ...[Rc8]. Please note that, contrary to the regular Sveshnikov, our dark-squared bishop is already out of our own pawn chain.}) 10. h3 Qh4 {[%cal Gh4g3,Gg4f2] Threatening both ...[Qxg3] and ...[Nxf2].} 11. Qf3 {This is logical but allows us to activate another piece.} Nd4 12. Qd3 Be6 {Leaving the knight en prise, but if White captures it, the game finishes immediately with a perpetual check.} 13. hxg4 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Nf3+ 15. gxf3 Qxg3+ 16. Kh1 Qh3+ $10 {[%cal Gh3g3] Draw.} *

