1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 ({After} 4. c3 {, the most logical for us is to continue with} Nf6 {and after} 5. e5 Nd5 {, we transpose to our Alapin lines.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 {Here, White has tried all the possible moves with the knight and we will briefly check each of them.} 6. Nxc6 {Not very ambitious. This allows us to improve our pawn structure.} bxc6 7. Bd3 {Everything is good here, but why not to continue with the usual?} Bb4 8. O-O ({Another option is} 8. Bd2 {to make sure ...[Bxc3] is not coming, but on the other hand this is not the ideal square for the bishop. After} O-O 9. O-O {, again, there are many possibilities but I think it's logical for us to stick to the same plan as in the text after [Bg5].} Re8 {with the idea of meeting} 10. a3 {with} Bf8 {and ...[d5] next with a very comfortable position.}) 8... O-O {I don't like taking on [c3] if I am not forced or if Black doesn't get anything direct after the exchange on [c3]. Black also remains flexible and White has to keep thinking of the possible capture on [c3]. All in all, I don't see any downside keeping White in the dark concerning our possible capture on [c3] in this position.} 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 Re8 {Simply activating the rook and liberating the [f8]-square for our bishop.} 11. a3 Bf8 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gd7d5,Gg7g5] Followed by ...[g5] and ...[d5] ideas. Only Black can be better here.} *

