1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 ({After} 4. c3 {, the most logical for us is to continue with} Nf6 {and after} 5. e5 Nd5 {, we transpose to our Alapin lines.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 {Here, White has tried all the possible moves with the knight and we will briefly check each of them.} 6. Nf5 {This should be challenged with central play.} d5 {Leading to a forced sequence of moves.} 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 {The only thing White has achieved is our slightly damaged pawn structure on the queenside, but as we will see this is not a big problem. Our piece activity will compensate for that.} 10. Ne3 Be6 {Let's see what happens if White tries to harass our pawns.} 11. Nc4 e4 12. Ne5 {Now I suggest playing in the spirit of the Sveshnikov opening.} Bc5 $1 {Who cares about pawns?} 13. Ba6 {[%cal Ga6b7]} Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b6]} 14. O-O O-O {[%cal Gf6d5,Gd5b4] We have easy play and can continue with ...[Nd5]-...[Nb4] jumps.} *

