1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is actually the main choice of top players these days. The reason is simple: they can't find anything in the Sveshnikov main lines, and in the Rossolimo, the play is much less forced. We did expect Caruana to go for that in 2018 vs Magnus, and he did!} g6 {Magnus's main choice and what we prepared for the 2018 match. I clearly based this repertoire on what we planned in 2018 and, obviously, updated it with the latest novelties/ideas as theory keeps developing.} 4. Bxc6 {White has a big conceptual choice: taking on [c6] or not. They can do it now or in one of the next few moves, and both options are covered in this chapter. If White takes, they will damage our pawn structure as we are getting doubled pawns. But on the other hand, we are getting the bishops, and we generally take with the d-pawn, which makes our light-squared bishop's development easier. In case White is taking on [c6], they will try to keep the position closed as we have bishops, and we have a long strategic battle in front of us.} (4. O-O Bg7 {and here:A} 5. c3 {Very logical; White is just trying to occupy the centre.} e5 $1 {Sveshnikov spirit, we don't give up the centre that easily.} 6. d4 {The main move: opening up the position in order to speed up the development and get some long-term compensation.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 8. Bf4 a6 $1 {A very important intermezzo. The following line shows why.} 9. Ba4 Nge7 10. Bd6 b5 11. Bb3 Bb7 {(Not only did we manage to develop our light square bishop, but more importantly, we will get ...[Nc8] getting rid of the dark square bishop, which is very annoying. All of that was played in Caruana vs Carlsen 2020. We will study that in great detail. The conclusion is that the game is sharp, and Black is definitely fine.B) 5.Re1 e5 Easy to remember: we just go ...[e5] when given a chance! This is the topic of another chapter, and here:B1 6.b4!? could be an unpleasant surprise in the spirit of the Evans gambit. The cleanest solution to that is well known since game 5 of the 2018 match between Caruana and Carlsen. 6...Nxb4! 7.Bb2 a6 8.a3! A clever move counterattacking the knight. 8...axb5 9.axb4 Rxa1 10.Bxa1 d6 11.bxc5 Ne7! The key move to solve all of Black's problems.B2 6.Bxc6 is quite popular here, and we get a different kind of closed Rossolimo. 6...dxc6 7.d3 Qe7! We have to spare a tempo protecting the [e5]-pawn before developing our knight. This lets White play [Re1], but it's a fair deal for us, since this is not a particularly useful move.}) 4... dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 {[%csl Gg4] This is the main way for White to play after taking on [c6].} b6 $5 {[%cal Gb6c5]} ({I really like this, which is a useful half-waiting move, protecting c5 and waiting for White to show how they want to develop. I really do believe that this is a more clever move-order than} 6... Nf6 {, chosen by Magnus.}) 7. O-O (7. Nc3 e5 $1 {Now we can go for the aggressive set-up with ...[Ne7] and ...[f5] to follow as our pawn on [e5] won't be vulnerable. By playing 7.Nc3, White lost the option of playing [Nbd2]-[Nc4] putting pressure on the [e5]-pawn.}) 7... Nf6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf6d7,Ge7e5,Gd7f8,Gf8e6] Now we are getting back to the usual setup with ...[Nd7]/...[e5]. In the process, we have avoided the dangerous and aggressive setups with long castle for White.} 8. Nc3 Nd7 9. Be3 e5 10. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6]} Nf8 $1 {As I show in the theory section, [Bh6] is not really a worry for Black.} (10... h6 {is what Magnus played, but then it is very difficult for Black to castle as the [h6]-pawn is constantly hanging.}) 11. Bh6 Bf6 $1 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gf8e6,Gg6g5] Very concrete and very good for Black. In some lines, the bishop on [h6] might even be trapped.} *

