1. e4 {The first game of the 2018 match. Generally, the first games of WC matches come as a relief for the players and their teams. You have been preparing for months, not sure what to expect, and at some point, you just want the whole thing to start.} c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 {We did expect this to happen on the board.} Nf6 {The main move. In my course, I suggest a much trickier move order.} (6... b6 {is our repertoire.}) 7. Nc3 Nd7 8. Be3 e5 9. O-O b6 {We have nevertheless transposed to our repertoire.} 10. Nh2 {[%cal Gf2f4] That's the standard and most logical plan.} Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6]} 11. f4 exf4 12. Rxf4 Be6 $1 {[%cal Ge6f7,Gh7h6,Gg6g5,Gf8g6] A clever and solid move which protects [f7]. The bishop on [e6] is not easy to attack as the knights are very far, and we will very soon control the [g5]-square with ...[h6].} 13. Rf2 h6 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gf8g6]} 14. Qd2 (14. a4 $5 {Always an interesting option. Here,} a5 $6 {wouldn't be a good reply as it weakens the [b6]-pawn. 15.Nf3 and White will open the centre with [d4], exposing the [b6]-pawn. Therefore, 14...Nd7! bolstering the [c5]-pawn 15.a5 b5 and well, of course, the [c5]-pawn looks weak, but it is really not simple to attack it a second time.}) 14... g5 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gf8g6]} 15. Raf1 Qd6 $1 {[%cal Gf8g6,Gf8d7,Ge8c8,Gd6e5] A brilliant move which prepares long castle and keeps flexibility for the black knight. It also controls the very important [e5]-square, thus preventing any [e4]-[e5].} 16. Ng4 O-O-O 17. Nf6 Nd7 $1 {Getting rid at once of that annoying knight on [f6].} 18. Nh5 Be5 {[%cal Gg5g4]} 19. g4 {A strange but efficient way to close the kingside for the moment.} f6 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Ge6f7] The verdict of the opening is pretty clear: White was outplayed! Black has all the fun on the kingside, and soon they will be able to open up the game on the kingside by exchanging on [h5].} 20. b3 Bf7 21. Nd1 Nf8 $6 {Looks nice but it is too subtle and based on a miscalculation.} (21... Bxh5 $1 {was simple and good.} 22. gxh5 Nf8 {Black's plan ...[Ne6]-...[Nf4] is quite hard to prevent.}) 22. Nxf6 Ne6 23. Nh5 (23. Nd7 $3 {clearing the f-file would have been the issue of the move order chosen by Magnus but was not spotted by his opponent either.} Bf4 24. Nf6 {and it seems that the best way to play for Black is to repeat the moves.} Be5) 23... Bxh5 24. gxh5 Nf4 {[%cal Gf4h3,Gf4h5] Black gave a pawn meaningless on [h5], actually but has a wonderful initiative while White is left without counterplay and only can try to defend themselves.} 25. Bxf4 gxf4 {[%cal Gh8g8]} 26. Rg2 (26. Rxf4 $1 {was by far the best chance, but I guess it is not an easy move to make, especially in the first game of a WC match.} Bxf4 27. Qxf4 Qd7 {winning a tempo with the attack on the [h3]-pawn.} 28. Kh2 Rhf8 29. Qxf8 Rxf8 30. Rxf8+ Kc7 {And it seems that White has very good chances of holding this despite their numerous weak pawns.}) 26... Rhg8 27. Qe2 Rxg2+ 28. Qxg2 Qe6 {[%cal Gd8g8]} 29. Nf2 {[%cal Gf2g4]} Rg8 30. Ng4 Qe8 $1 {[%cal Ge8h5] A logical sequence was just played, and Magnus now finds the winning idea: taking the pawn on [h5], as he will be able to push ...[h5] afterwards.} 31. Qf3 Qxh5 32. Kf2 {The king is trying to escape; hard to blame Fabi for that decision. This is the only chance.} Bc7 33. Ke2 $2 {White is missing a golden opportunity to get good drawing chances.} (33. e5 $1 {unveils an attack on [c6]. After} Kb7 34. Nf6 Qh4+ 35. Ke2 Rg7 36. Qxf4 Qxh3 {, White is just in time to stop some of Black's threats.} 37. Rf2 Re7 38. Ne4 Bxe5 39. Qf3 {. Of course, White lost a pawn but somehow regained some king safety as the knight on [e4] is a good cover to their king on [e2].}) 33... Qg5 {[%cal Gh6h5]} 34. Nh2 h5 35. Rf2 Qg1 (35... Qg7 $1 {planning to invade on the queenside was a pretty simple way to finish the game.}) 36. Nf1 h4 {[%cal Gg8g3]} (36... Qg7 {still wins! but Magnus wants his rook on [g3].}) 37. Kd2 Kb7 38. c3 Be5 ({Too slow, but it doesn't spoil anything yet! That was the moment for} 38... Rg3 $1 {but of course, it's move 38, and it's the first game of the match... I Guess Magnus didn't want to spoil a golden opportunity to start the match with a win as Black and thought that he would have time to decide after the time control.} 39. Nxg3 hxg3 40. Rg2 Qa1 41. d4 Qxa2+ 42. Kd3 Qxb3 {Black is collecting all the queenside, and the white king is in huge trouble.} 43. e5 cxd4 44. Kxd4 b5 {with multiple threats, such as ...[Bb6]+ and ...[Qc4]+.}) 39. Kc2 Qg7 40. Nh2 $1 Bxc3 $4 {Just nervosity.} ({Repeating the moves was the best:} 40... Qg1 41. Nf1 {to stop ...[Qa1].} b5 {Black will play ...[b4] and invade on the dark squares. White is helpless.}) 41. Qxf4 Bd4 42. Qf7+ Ka6 43. Qxg7 Rxg7 44. Re2 Rg3 {[%cal Ge4e8] Black wins a pawn, but the e-pawn is suddenly a nice source of counterplay for White.} 45. Ng4 Rxh3 46. e5 Rf3 47. e6 Rf8 48. e7 Re8 49. Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f5]} h3 50. Nf5 Bf6 {No other choice for White than entering a 4 vs 3 rook endgame, which is easily drawn.} 51. a3 b5 52. b4 cxb4 53. axb4 Bxe7 54. Nxe7 h2 55. Rxh2 Rxe7 {As always, Magnus will try everything till the end, but this is too easy to defend for White. Overall, a very well-played game by Magnus. His bad decisions in time trouble prevented him from getting the full point.} 56. Rh6 Kb6 57. Kc3 Rd7 58. Rg6 Kc7 59. Rh6 Rd6 60. Rh8 Rg6 61. Ra8 Kb7 62. Rh8 Rg5 63. Rh7+ Kb6 64. Rh6 Rg1 65. Kc2 Rf1 66. Rg6 Rh1 67. Rf6 Rh8 68. Kc3 Ra8 69. d4 Rd8 70. Rh6 Rd7 71. Rg6 Kc7 72. Rg5 Rd6 73. Rg8 Rh6 74. Ra8 Rh3+ 75. Kc2 Ra3 76. Kb2 Ra4 77. Kc3 a6 78. Rh8 Ra3+ 79. Kb2 Rg3 80. Kc2 Rg5 81. Rh6 Rd5 82. Kc3 Rd6 83. Rh8 Rg6 84. Kc2 Kb7 85. Kc3 Rg3+ 86. Kc2 Rg1 87. Rh5 Rg2+ 88. Kc3 Rg3+ 89. Kc2 Rg4 90. Kc3 Kb6 91. Rh6 Rg5 92. Rf6 Rh5 93. Rg6 Rh3+ 94. Kc2 Rh5 95. Kc3 Rd5 96. Rh6 Kc7 97. Rh7+ Rd7 98. Rh5 Rd6 99. Rh8 Rg6 100. Rf8 Rg3+ 101. Kc2 Ra3 102. Rf7+ Kd6 103. Ra7 Kd5 104. Kb2 Rd3 105. Rxa6 Rxd4 106. Kb3 Re4 107. Kc3 Rc4+ 108. Kb3 Kd4 109. Rb6 Kd3 110. Ra6 Rc2 111. Rb6 Rc3+ 112. Kb2 Rc4 113. Kb3 Kd4 114. Ra6 Kd5 115. Ra8 1/2-1/2

