1. e4 {This is is the fifth game of the match and already the third Rossolimo. Caruana didn't get anything was even outplayed in the first one in the first two, and we did expect a different line.} c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e5 6. b4 {Here comes the surprise. Luckily, we noticed during our prep that this was a dangerous line and checked it carefully.} Nxb4 $1 {The cleanest way, in my opinion.} (6... cxb4 7. a3 $1 {leads to good compensation for White.}) 7. Bb2 a6 8. a3 $1 {The critical line.} (8. Bf1 Nc6 {protecting the [e5]-pawn, and it is very hard to prove compensation for White.}) 8... axb5 9. axb4 Rxa1 10. Bxa1 d6 11. bxc5 Ne7 12. Qe2 (12. cxd6 {This is the main line and probably the best try, but Black is very solid.} Qxd6 13. d4 exd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 Qxd4 16. Nxd4 b4 17. c3 bxc3 18. Nxc3 O-O {White may claim the position is easier to play for them as the [b7]-pawn is isolated and potentially weak, but that's clearly not enough to get any winning chances.}) 12... b4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c3]} 13. Qc4 (13. Qb5+ {intending to grab the [b4]-pawn is the other option trying to open up the centre as soon as possible.} Nc6 14. d4 exd4 15. Bxd4 O-O $1 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Rd1 Bg4 {It is actually Black now who has the best development and can play for the initiative.} 18. Rxd6 Qe7 19. Nbd2 Ra8 {with great compensation for Black. White has some back-rank issues.}) 13... Qa5 {[%cal Ga5a1,Ga5c5]} 14. cxd6 Be6 $1 {A nice move that was still prep. Black is not worse at all and can hope to take over.} 15. Qc7 Qxc7 16. dxc7 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Ge5d4,Ge8d7,Gc6e5] Protecting [e5] and controlling the key break [d2]-[d4].} 17. c3 $6 (17. Rd1 {was best, as I explain in the course, but Black is completely fine.} Kd7 {and the [c7]-pawn will fall.} 18. d4 exd4 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Bxd4 21. Rxd4+ Kxc7 22. Rxb4 Ra8 {White is a pawn up, but all Black pieces are very active and fully compensate for that deficit.} 23. Nc3 Kc6 {Black's king is active, and ...[Ra3] is an annoying idea.}) 17... Kd7 18. cxb4 Ra8 $1 {A nice intermediate move that gives White a hard time.} 19. Bc3 (19. Nc3 Nxb4 $1 {with [d3] and [c2] as entry points for the knight.}) 19... Kxc7 20. d3 Kb6 $6 ({Magnus misses a great opportunity to put Caruana under quite some pressure after} 20... b5 $1 {fixing the pawn on [b4].} 21. Nbd2 Ra2 {Black is very active, and an even more important factor is that the [b4]-pawn is weak. ...[Rc2] is an immediate idea.}) 21. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gb1c3] Nice defensive move!} Rd8 22. Be3+ Kb5 23. Nc3+ {Entering a forced line which doesn't give any chances to Black} Kxb4 24. Nd5+ Bxd5 25. exd5 Rxd5 26. Rb1+ Kc3 27. Rxb7 Nd8 28. Rc7+ Kxd3 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc7h7] Black is a pawn up but lacks coordination, and the white rook is very active. Now the black king doesn't make any sense on [d3]. He would rather be on [g8] protecting his pawns.} 29. Kf1 {[%cal Gf1e2]} h5 30. h3 Ke4 {[%cal Ge4f5]} 31. Ng5+ Kf5 32. Nxf7 Nxf7 33. Rxf7+ Bf6 34. g4+ {Draw agreed. After this game, Caruana didn't repeat the Rossolimo during the match.} 1/2-1/2

