{This is actually a blitz game which was played in the 2024 French championship final. That was a tense match where I won the first classical and the first rapid, but in both cases, Jules managed to score in the second games, which led us to the blitz tie-break. I lost the first one as White and had to win on demand as Black. I felt using my course on the Sveshnikov would give me chances.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {I was happy to see the Rossolimo as the play, generally, remains complex for a long time.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e5 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Qe7 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gg8f6] Overprotecting [e5] in order to prepare ...[Nf6] is very typical. More on this here.} 8. a4 {A small surprise here, but I knew that [a4] is basically decent in any of these positions.} Nf6 9. a5 O-O 10. h3 Ne8 {[%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6]} 11. Bg5 f6 12. Be3 Nc7 13. Nbd2 {[%cal Gc8e6]} Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b6] Preparing ...[b6] but a bit slow.} (13... Be6 $1 {was the way to go, preparing ...[Rad8] and ...[Nb5]-...[Nd4]. Black is just doing well.}) 14. Nc4 (14. c3 $1 {preparing [d4] would have been unpleasant. The [a7]-pawn might be hanging in some cases as well, which shows another drawback of ...[Rb8].}) 14... Ne6 15. c3 (15. b4 $1 {highlighting the weakness on [a7] and making something happen on the queenside.}) 15... Rd8 16. Qc2 (16. b4 $1 {was still good.}) 16... b5 17. axb6 axb6 18. b4 {Less effective than a move earlier but still the way to go.} b5 19. Na5 Bd7 20. bxc5 f5 {Felt like a good try in a must-win blitz game. Black is getting a lot of counterplay. I felt that this was probably not correct, but who cares in blitz?} (20... Nxc5 {was objectively best and approximately equal.} 21. d4 Ne6 22. d5 cxd5 23. exd5 Nc7 24. c4 bxc4 25. Qxc4 Qd6 26. Rac1 $1 Rdc8 $1 {is OK for Black, who will capture the [d5]-pawn. ( Instead, 26...Nxd5? would be a blunder. 27.Bc5 Qe6 28.Nd4! and Black is losing an exchange due to the [Nc6] threat. )}) 21. exf5 gxf5 22. Bd2 (22. Nb3 $1 {protecting the [c5]-pawn and clearing the a-file for the rook was the way to go, keeping a healthy extra pawn.} Be8 {But I felt that many things could happen in a blitz game.}) 22... Qxc5 23. Nb3 Qd6 {[%csl Gd7,Ge5,Gf5,Rg1,Gg7][%cal Gg8g1] Black is suddenly doing very well with bishops, a strong centre, and potentially a strong attack.} 24. Re2 Be8 {[%cal Gd6d3]} 25. d4 e4 26. Ng5 Nc7 {[%cal Gh7h6]} 27. h4 $2 (27. Qc1 {was the right move threatening to play [Bf4].} h6 {would be met by} 28. Bf4 {while after 27...Nd5 28.Nc5 eyeing the [e6]-square. 28...Bd7 29.h4 leads to a complicated game. The white knight will be rerouted to [f4] via [h3].}) 27... h6 28. Nh3 Nd5 29. Ra7 Rd7 (29... Bh5 $1 {would have basically won the game.} 30. Re1 Bg4 {-+ Just taking on [h3] and opening up White's king.}) 30. Rxd7 Bxd7 31. Nc5 Ra8 ({Tempting but} 31... Be8 $1 {first, intending ...[Bh5], was strong. One wants to keep his bishops in an open position!}) 32. Re1 (32. Nxd7 Qxd7 33. c4 $1 {was a good chance to equalise the game.}) 32... Be8 33. f3 b4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb4c3]} 34. cxb4 Bxd4+ 35. Kh1 e3 36. Bc1 Qg3 37. Nd3 {Black is completely winning, but the time trouble is severe!} Bc3 (37... Be5 {with a mating threat on [h2] was simple and winning.} 38. Nxe5 Qxe1+ 39. Kh2 e2 {and ...[Qd1] next.}) 38. Rxe3 Nxe3 39. Bxe3 Ra1+ 40. Bg1 Bf6 41. Ndf4 Be5 {The rest of the game is played in full 'panic mode,' which we all had at the end of blitz games.} (41... Qxh4 {was the last chance to get winning chances.} 42. Qxf5 Bd4 43. Qe6+ Bf7 44. Qc8+ Kg7 45. Ne2 Bxg1 46. Nexg1 Qf6 {Protecting the [c6]-pawn. Black is definitely pressing, but there is still a long way before converting it to a full point.}) 42. Qxf5 Bxf4 43. Nxf4 Qxh4+ 44. Nh3 Qe7 45. Qf4 Kh7 46. Kh2 Ra2 47. Be3 Qe6 48. Qc7+ Bd7 49. Nf4 Qf7 50. Qd6 Be8 51. Nh3 Qg6 52. Qe7+ Qg7 53. Qe4+ Bg6 54. Qxc6 Rxg2+ $5 {I thought Jules had missed this, and he indeed missed it, but there is a nice defence for White.} 55. Kxg2 Be4+ 56. Ng5+ {And here, instead of taking on [g5] with the queen and then taking on [c6], I just resigned. A draw was not helping much in the match...} 1-0

