{Preparing a game for Magnus as Black vs Caruana was always a tough challenge, and this one was no exception. We decided to choose a somewhat surprising line, but as always, Fabiano was ready for it and chose the most challenging approach.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 e5 (5... Nf6 {is the most common.}) 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 8. Bf4 {That's the way to go if you want to ask Black serious questions. Both players are following our repertoire for very long.} a6 $1 9. Ba4 Nge7 10. Bd6 b5 11. Bb3 Bb7 12. Re1 Nc8 13. e5 Nxd6 14. exd6+ Kf8 {One of the critical positions discussed at length in the course.} 15. h4 {[%cal Gf3g5]} Bf6 16. Nbd2 Kg7 17. Bd5 Na5 $2 (17... Bxh4 $1 {is the right move and our repertoire!}) 18. Bxb7 Nxb7 19. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6,Ga1c1,Gh4h5] White has an easy play and a better position. The next few moves played by Fabi are very logical and good.} Re8 20. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6]} Rc8 21. Rc1 Rxc1 22. Qxc1 {[%cal Gh5h6]} h6 23. hxg6 $2 {Here comes the only mistake from White in this game. That will allow Magnus to save the game. That's how it works at the elite level: beautiful prep, great play, but one single mistake and your opponent saves himself.} (23. Qd2 $1 {That was the way to go: keeping the tension and especially the pawn on [f7] as it gives an escape square for the black king in a very concrete line.} d3 24. Qxd3 Re6 25. Qd5 Qb6 {looks very similar to the game, but there is a major difference.} 26. Nxf6 Rxe1+ 27. Nxe1 Kxf6 28. Nf3 $3 {with a mating threat with [Qe5] as the [f7]-pawn is still there and prevents the black king from going there after [Qe5]+. White is winning.}) {25...Qc8 is also very bad for Black. 26.hxg6 fxg6 27.Nxf6 Rxe1+ 28.Nxe1 Kxf6 29.Nd3 will full domination; the black knight is stuck on [b7].} 23... fxg6 24. Qd2 d3 25. b4 (25. Qxd3 {is precisely the line which illustrates why it was better not to take on [g6].} Re6 26. Qd5 Qb6 27. Nxf6 Rxe1+ 28. Nxe1 Kxf6 29. Nf3 Nxd6 30. Qe5+ {and the [f7]-square is available for the king.}) 25... Re6 26. Qxd3 Qb6 {[%cal Gb7d6,Ge6d6] Black still needs to be precise, but the worst is over. Magnus just defends perfectly and saves the day.} 27. Rd1 (27. Nxf6 Rxe1+ 28. Nxe1 Kxf6 {and [d6] will drop.}) (27. Qd5 Nxd6) 27... Qc6 {[%cal Gc6e4,Ge6e4]} 28. Nxf6 Rxf6 29. Ne5 Qc8 30. Qd5 Re6 {[%cal Gb7d6]} 31. Ng4 {[%cal Gd5d4]} Kh7 32. Qd4 Qf8 {[%cal Gf8f6,Ge6d6]} 33. Qa7 Rxd6 {[%cal Gd6d1] Nice little tactic, and Black eventually takes the very annoying [d6]-pawn. However, it is not enough to pretend for more than a draw as White is very active.} 34. Re1 ({The tactical justification is} 34. Rxd6 Qxd6 $1 {and Black can meet} 35. Qxb7 {with} Qd1+ 36. Kh2 Qxg4 {.}) 34... Nd8 35. Ne5 Qe7 36. Nf3 Re6 37. Rd1 Rd6 38. Re1 Re6 39. Rd1 Rd6 1/2-1/2

