1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the more popular 5...[Nf6] .} 6. d3 ({This is the alternative to} 6. d4 {, obviously much less direct and less critical.}) 6... Nge7 7. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5]} d6 8. d4 ({The only way to make sense for White.} 8. Nbd2 {is just way too slow. White won't be able to play [d4] anymore and the bishop on [e3] is misplaced, as ...[f5] will come quite soon.} O-O {Black is already better.}) 8... exd4 $1 9. cxd4 O-O {[%cal Gg7b2] Using the fact that White can't take on [c5], as [b2] is hanging.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gd4c5] A logical developing move threatening to take on [c5]. Now we have a choice.} Qb6 {[%cal Gc5d4] I like this move that asks White concrete questions.} 11. Bxc6 Nxc6 {And now neither knight jump is really dangerous for Black.} 12. Na4 ({This seems to win a pawn, but things are not that simple. Unfortunately, after} 12. Nd5 {, we have to play} Qxb2 {and let White force a perpetual with [Rb1]-[a1].} 13. Rb1 Qxa2 14. Ra1 Qb2) 12... Qb5 13. dxc5 dxc5 14. Bxc5 Rd8 {[%csl Gc8,Gg7][%cal Gd8d1] We have great counterplay, as the queen should be protecting the [a4]-knight.} 15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. axb3 b6 {[%csl Gc8,Gg7][%cal Gc8e6] Followed by ...[Be6]. We will get our pawn back and have a better endgame thanks to our bishops.} *

