1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the more popular 5...[Nf6] .} 6. d3 ({This is the alternative to} 6. d4 {, obviously much less direct and less critical.}) 6... Nge7 7. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5]} d6 8. d4 ({The only way to make sense for White.} 8. Nbd2 {is just way too slow. White won't be able to play [d4] anymore and the bishop on [e3] is misplaced, as ...[f5] will come quite soon.} O-O {Black is already better.}) 8... exd4 $1 9. cxd4 O-O {[%cal Gg7b2] Using the fact that White can't take on [c5], as [b2] is hanging.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gd4c5] A logical developing move threatening to take on [c5]. Now we have a choice.} Qb6 {[%cal Gc5d4] I like this move that asks White concrete questions.} 11. dxc5 dxc5 12. Qd6 {[%cal Ge3c5,Gd6c5] This looks like a very good move putting under heavy pressure the [c5]-pawn.} (12. Bxc6 {is met by a very simple and effective novelty!} Nxc6 13. Qc1 Be6 {and White has to be careful in order to keep the balance.}) 12... Nd4 $1 {Nice tactics, apparently blundering the knight on [e7].} 13. Qxe7 Bf6 {[%csl Re7] And the white queen has no square. Nevertheless, White can keep the balance.} 14. Nd5 {[%cal Gd5f6,Gd5b6]} Bxe7 15. Nxb6 Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 axb6 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3][%cal Gc8e6,Gf8d8] And Black is at least fine in this endgame.} *

