1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the more popular 5...[Nf6] .} 6. d3 ({This is the alternative to} 6. d4 {, obviously much less direct and less critical.}) 6... Nge7 7. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5]} d6 8. d4 ({The only way to make sense for White.} 8. Nbd2 {is just way too slow. White won't be able to play [d4] anymore and the bishop on [e3] is misplaced, as ...[f5] will come quite soon.} O-O {Black is already better.}) 8... exd4 $1 9. cxd4 O-O {[%cal Gg7b2] Using the fact that White can't take on [c5], as [b2] is hanging.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gd4c5] A logical developing move threatening to take on [c5]. Now we have a choice.} Qb6 {[%cal Gc5d4] I like this move that asks White concrete questions.} 11. dxc5 dxc5 12. Qd6 {[%cal Ge3c5,Gd6c5] This looks like a very good move putting under heavy pressure the [c5]-pawn.} (12. Bxc6 {is met by a very simple and effective novelty!} Nxc6 13. Qc1 Be6 {and White has to be careful in order to keep the balance.}) 12... Nd4 $1 {Nice tactics, apparently blundering the knight on [e7].} 13. Qxb6 {That is the other option but Black don't have any problems in the endgame.} axb6 $1 {[%csl Gd4] We could also take on [f3] with check first but why to get rid of our powerful knight on [d4].} 14. Bxd4 {White is getting rid of that knight but that costs the bishop pair!} cxd4 15. Ne2 Nc6 {[%cal Gf8d8] Offering White the exchange of the other bishop.} 16. Bxc6 (16. Nf4 {Activating the knight at once and trying to keep the position closed.} d3 $1 {Nice pawn sac activating our dark-squared bishop and opening up the position.} 17. Nxd3 Bg4 {I would be worried here as White considering the numerous threats they face: ...[Bxf3] followed by ...[Nd4] is a strong idea. ...[Rfd8] is also coming.}) 16... bxc6 17. Nfxd4 Re8 18. f3 Ba6 {[%cal Ga6f1,Gg7b2,Gc6c5] Black has more than enough compensation. The position is opened for our bishops, White's knights are under pressure, and the [b2]-pawn might also be hanging after ...[c5].} *

