1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the more popular 5...[Nf6] .} 6. d3 ({This is the alternative to} 6. d4 {, obviously much less direct and less critical.}) 6... Nge7 7. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5]} d6 8. d4 {That's the only way to make sense for white.} exd4 $1 9. cxd4 O-O {[%cal Gg7b2] Using the fact that White can't take on [c5], as [b2] is hanging.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gd4c5] A logical developing move threatening to take on [c5]. Now we have a choice.} d5 $5 {This is completely fine but will lead to massive liquidation in most of the lines. It could be a very good choice again a much higher rated player.} 11. exd5 {Harmless.} Nxd5 12. Nxd5 cxd4 $1 {A little intermezzo avoiding any kind of problems in all lines.} 13. Bxc6 (13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Qxd5 {is just completely equal.}) 13... bxc6 {[%cal Gc6d5,Gd4e3]} 14. Bxd4 Qxd5 $10 {The position is equal and a bunch of pieces have been exchanged. A draw is the most likely outcome.} *

