1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Bc4 $5 (9. Bc4 {It seems as if the bishop is better placed here than on a4, but the disadvantage of this move is that it allows us to continue with} d6 {.}) 9... Nge7 $6 {This is not great as it allows White to continue with their plan.} 10. Bd6 b5 ({We need to act energetically before getting under serious pressure.} 10... O-O {is too slow due to} 11. a4 {as White prevents ...[b5] and gets a very firm control on the queenside.}) 11. Bd5 ({This is the most annoying.} 11. Bb3 {would be good news for us, as after} Bb7 {with ...[Nc8] and ...[Na5] ideas the position transposes to our main line.}) 11... O-O 12. Re1 Bb7 13. Nbd2 {This is a good version for White.} *

