1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Bc4 $5 (9. Bc4 {It seems as if the bishop is better placed here than on a4, but the disadvantage of this move is that it allows us to continue with} d6 {.}) 9... d6 $1 {Taking advantage of White's last move. The bishop is no longer pinning our knight, making this move possible.} 10. Ng5 {Another way to put pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Nh6 11. Na3 (11. Nd2 O-O {followed by ...[Be5] with a pleasant position.}) 11... O-O {[%cal Yh6g4,Yg4e5]} 12. h3 $7 {[%csl Gg4] White prevents our ...[Ng4]-...[Ne5] manoeuvre.} Kh8 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gc6e5] With the idea of following up with ...[f6] and ...[Ne5] next.} *

