1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Ba4 {The most precise as it does not give us a chance to play ...[d6].} b5 $6 {Played numerous times, but I consider it slightly inaccurate.} 10. Bb3 Bb7 (10... Nge7 {also seems logical, but again after} 11. a4 {White will try to destabilize our queenside, and I think White's chances are preferable. 11.Bd6 is what we would like to see as after 11...Bb7! we transpose to our main line.}) 11. a4 {White is not in a hurry for [Bd6]. As we have weakened our queenside by pushing ...[b5], they can try to take advantage of it first.} Nf6 ({As White did not play Bd6, we have a possibility to develop our knight here.} 11... Nge7 {is now met by} 12. Na3 $1 {, putting additional pressure on the [b5]-pawn.}) 12. Nbd2 $1 {[%cal Gf4d6] Simple but effective, protecting the pawn and planning to go [Bd6] next. Our position is playable, but I believe that White is better and will continue to increase the pressure.} (12. axb5 {is another possibility that could lead to some concrete play that is not really necessary for White.} axb5 13. Rxa8 Bxa8 {(( 13...Qxa8 14.Bd6 and we have difficulty castling. 14.Ng5 is not scary as we have 14...Nd8! ∓ )) Now} 14. Bd6 {works less well due to} Nxe4 15. Re1 Ne7 $1 {with a complicated game. White's best try is 14.Ng5 leading to a very sharp and forced line. 14...O-O 15.Bd6 Ne7 and now White has an interesting try: 16.Bxf7+!? Rxf7 17.Qb3 Qf8 18.Nxf7 Qxf7 19.Qa3 here, unfortunately, we are losing a piece, and after 19...Bc6 20.Bxe7 Nxe4 , the position is very messy, but we surely have enough counterplay.}) *

