1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Ba4 {The most precise as it does not give us a chance to play ...[d6].} Nge7 $1 ({The correct move order, and you will soon see why. Not} 9... d6 $2 10. Nxd4 {and White is taking over.}) 10. e5 {This seems less logical than putting the bishop on [d6], but it has been played a dozen times and needs to be checked. The idea is actually the same as after [Bd6]: White prevents the [d7]-pawn from moving.} O-O 11. Nbd2 b5 {We continue in the same manner as in the main line.} 12. Bc2 Bb7 13. Re1 {Here we have a pleasant choice.} Qb6 ({I like to continue with this move.} 13... Nb4 {is also possible but looks too artificial to me.} 14. Be4 Nbd5 {Jumping around is also fine according to the computer, but it feels as an inhuman way to treat the position.} 15. Bg3 Qb6 {Finally protecting the extra pawn, which is an annoying pawn for White to get back.} 16. Qb3 {This is a sensible possibility, coordinating the rooks and putting some kind of pressure on the [b6]-queen. Pretty equal according to the engine, fully playable for both sides is my human evaluation.}) 14. Ne4 Na5 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga5c4] Simply activating the pieces.} 15. Nd6 {We are ready for this.} Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nec6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ga5c4] ...[Nc4] will follow next putting pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} *

