1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Ba4 {The most precise as it does not give us a chance to play ...[d6].} Nge7 $1 ({The correct move order, and you will soon see why. Not} 9... d6 $2 10. Nxd4 {and White is taking over.}) 10. Bd6 {The critical try.} b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7c8] Another important move. We prepare ...[Bb7] and ...[Nc8] to get rid of the annoying dark-squared bishop.} (10... O-O $6 {is not precise as after} 11. Nbd2 b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 13. Re1 {, White's bishop on [d6] is too powerful.}) 11. Bb3 Bb7 $1 {[%cal Ge7c8,Gc6a5]} (11... Bb7 {Preparing ...Nc8 and ...Na5 taking care of both bishops. Now} 12. a4 {is not an issue anymore as we have} Nc8 {kicking off the bishop from his comfortable throne.}) (11... O-O {is once again inaccurate, and after} 12. Nbd2 {it transposes to the 10...O-O?! line mentioned in the note to Black's 10th move.}) 12. Ng5 {[%csl Rf7] A tempting move creating serious threats on [f7].} O-O 13. Qf3 Qe8 {Obviously, the only move here not to lose [f7].} 14. Nd2 {This is very natural but a bit slow at the same time and gives us time to breathe.} h6 {We are eager to chase away this active knight, especially because its only available retreat square is [h3].} 15. Nh3 {Now we have several good options, but my suggestion would be to go for active play.} a5 16. Rfe1 Qd8 {Our queen was clearly misplaced on [e8] and deserved to have better prospects.} 17. a4 Qb6 18. axb5 Ne5 {Here I like this, forcing White's reply.} 19. Bxe5 Bxe5 {We finally managed to remove the annoying bishop from [d6].} 20. Bc4 {White can try to keep the [b5]-pawn, but now we are ready to take active measures on the kingside.} g5 $1 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Ge7g6] A multifunctional move. First of all, we are searching for a better life for our knight, activating it via [g6]. Secondly, the white knight on [h3] gets totally restricted.} 21. Bd3 Ng6 {[%cal Gg8g7,Ga8c8,Yc8e8] And it's White who needs to be careful here not to end up being worse. We have several ways to improve our position, for example, ...[Kg7], ...[Rae8], or ...[Rac8].} *

