1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Ba4 {The most precise as it does not give us a chance to play ...[d6].} Nge7 $1 ({The correct move order, and you will soon see why. Not} 9... d6 $2 10. Nxd4 {and White is taking over.}) 10. Bd6 {The critical try.} b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7c8] Another important move. We prepare ...[Bb7] and ...[Nc8] to get rid of the annoying dark-squared bishop.} (10... O-O $6 {is not precise as after} 11. Nbd2 b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 13. Re1 {, White's bishop on [d6] is too powerful.}) 11. Bb3 Bb7 $1 {[%cal Ge7c8,Gc6a5]} (11... Bb7 {Preparing ...Nc8 and ...Na5 taking care of both bishops. Now} 12. a4 {is not an issue anymore as we have} Nc8 {kicking off the bishop from his comfortable throne.}) (11... O-O {is once again inaccurate, and after} 12. Nbd2 {it transposes to the 10...O-O?! line mentioned in the note to Black's 10th move.}) 12. Ng5 {A tempting move creating serious threats on [f7].} O-O 13. Qf3 Qe8 {Obviously, the only move here not to lose [f7].} 14. Qg3 (14. Qg3 {White is ready to meet} h6 {with} 15. Nf3 {now.}) 14... Na5 {It's time to take care of the annoying bishops.} 15. Nd2 h6 {This has to be played sooner or later.} 16. Ngf3 {The knight is obviously better placed here than on [h3], but we still have decent play.} Rc8 17. Rfe1 Qd8 18. a3 ({The recommendation of Wesley So in his Chessable Lifetime Repertoire. Black is facing a tough challenge indeed, but we do have a solution! Instead,} 18. Rad1 {allows} Nc4 19. Bxc4 bxc4 {with a messy game. ...[c3] should be considered next.}) 18... Nc4 {We want to get one of the bishops. If White takes on [c4], then our pawn structure is improved.} 19. Nxc4 bxc4 20. Ba2 {A natural follow-up after playing [a3].} Re8 $1 {The thematic move of this line but, of course, very logical. We need to unpin the knight.} 21. Nd2 {White would be happy to get rid of the [c4]-pawn to bring the light-squared bishop back to life. Here, we have two good options.} Bxe4 $5 {A funny-looking move.} 22. Rxe4 (22. Nxe4 {looks dubious as now} Nf5 23. Qf4 Rc6 {gives Black an edge! One might ask why we gave a piece, but it looks like White is not having an easy life here. ...[Rxe4] is in the air, and if the dark-squared bishop moves, then we get a chance to push ...[d5].}) 22... Nf5 {By removing the [e4]-pawn, we finally get a chance to bring our knight into play. And it turns out it is worth sacrificing a piece!} 23. Qf4 c3 24. bxc3 dxc3 {Now, White needs to be precise.} 25. Nc4 ({The natural-looking} 25. Rxe8+ {is a serious mistake due to} Qxe8 26. Nb3 Qe2 {with a decisive advantage. White's pieces are too badly coordinated.}) 25... Re6 $5 {With a crazy position which computers obviously evaluate as zeros.} *

