1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Ba4 {The most precise as it does not give us a chance to play ...[d6].} Nge7 $1 ({The correct move order, and you will soon see why. Not} 9... d6 $2 10. Nxd4 {and White is taking over.}) 10. Bd6 {The critical try.} b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7c8] Another important move. We prepare ...[Bb7] and ...[Nc8] to get rid of the annoying dark-squared bishop.} (10... O-O $6 {is not precise as after} 11. Nbd2 b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 13. Re1 {, White's bishop on [d6] is too powerful.}) 11. Bb3 Bb7 $1 {[%cal Ge7c8,Gc6a5]} (11... Bb7 {Preparing ...Nc8 and ...Na5 taking care of both bishops. Now} 12. a4 {is not an issue anymore as we have} Nc8 {kicking off the bishop from his comfortable throne.}) (11... O-O {is once again inaccurate, and after} 12. Nbd2 {it transposes to the 10...O-O?! line mentioned in the note to Black's 10th move.}) 12. Ng5 {A tempting move creating serious threats on [f7].} O-O 13. Qf3 Qe8 {Obviously, the only move here not to lose [f7].} 14. Qg3 (14. Qg3 {White is ready to meet} h6 {with} 15. Nf3 {now.}) 14... Na5 {It's time to take care of the annoying bishops.} 15. Nd2 h6 {This has to be played sooner or later.} 16. Ngf3 {The knight is obviously better placed here than on [h3], but we still have decent play.} Rc8 17. Ne5 {Creating a serious threat on [g6], but we are just in time to solve our problems.} Nxb3 {Since [Ne5] prevents ...[Nc4], we should grab the light-squared bishop.} 18. Nxb3 Qd8 {[%cal Gf8e8] An important move in this line in order to untangle. We cannot waste time and need to bring the queen and the rook into action.} 19. Rae1 Re8 20. Nd3 {Here, everything is playable. For example:} a5 21. Nbc5 Bc6 22. h4 h5 {[%cal Gf7f5] It might visually look that White is much more active with his bishop on [d6], but in fact, the position is just extremely complicated for both sides and promises an interesting fight ahead.} *

