e doesn't seem to attack the right target! It is pretty clear to me than Black's king should be the target.} 15. a4 {looks very far from the action to me.}) 15... Bf6 {[%cal Gf8g7] Of course, now we have time to get our king to [g7].} 16. Nbd2 Kg7 17. Bd5 {[%cal Gd2e4] Preparing [Ne4] without allowing ...[Na5] hitting the knight on [e4] and the bishop on [b3] simultaneously.} ({The immediate} 17. Ne4 $2 {is simply not good due to} Na5 {and Black is much better.}) 17... bxa4 {The pawn on [b5] could become weak, so it makes sense to take first.} 18. Ne4 Re8 19. Qxa4 Rb8 {All black pieces are developed} 20. Nc5 {The only move for White to keep the game balanced. Now it becomes very concrete for both and as you know, with perfect play, the game generally ends in a draw. 😀} Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5c5]} 22. Qxa5 Nxa5 (22... Nxa5 {The draw seems inevitable by now:} 23. Nxd7 Rd8 24. Nxf6 Kxf6 25. Bxb7 Nxb7 26. Nxd4 Rxd6 {I could argue that Black is slightly better due our more active king, but it will definitely be a draw if White plays precisely.}) *

