nd preventing any [Ng5] business.} (15... h5 $6 {trying to stop the h-pawn is not a good idea as after} 16. Ng5 Ne5 17. Nd2 {± , White's knight on [g5] becomes too strong, and the pressure on [f7] is very unpleasant.}) (15... Rc8 {is too slow as after} 16. Nbd2 {, we cannot go} f5 {as in the previous line due to} 17. Ng5 {± .}) 16. Nbd2 Kg7 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5] It is absolutely necessary as the king needs to be taken care of.} 17. Bd5 {White needs to pin the knight as, otherwise, ...[Na5] might be unpleasant.} Na5 $6 {Played by Magnus himself, but is not the best due to the following sequence.} 18. Bxb7 Nxb7 19. Ne4 {And Black needs to be extremely careful here.} Re8 ({For example} 19... Rc8 {is already a serious mistake due to} 20. g4 $1 {, and our bishop is in serious trouble.}) 20. h5 $1 ({This is the best and was played by Caruana in the aforementioned game against Magnus.} 20. g4 {is not scary now, as we have} Kg8 {.}) 20... Rc8 21. Rc1 $1 Rxc1 {Forced,} 22. Qxc1 {[%cal Gh5h6]} h6 {To prevent White's [h6].} 23. hxg6 $6 (23. Qd2 {is an improvement over the Caruana-Carlsen game. It turns out it is better to keep the pawns on [h5] and [f7] due to a very concrete reason.} d3 24. Qxd3 Re6 25. Qd5 {+-} Qb6 26. Nxf6 Rxe1+ 27. Nxe1 Kxf6 28. Nf3 {threatening mate is a major difference compared to the game and shows why White should not have taken on [g6].}) 23... fxg6 24. Qd2 d3 (24... d3 {If} 25. Qxd3 {, and then we continue with the previously mentioned} Re6 26. Qd5 Qb6 27. Nxf6 Rxe1+ 28. Nxe1 Kxf6 29. Nf3 {and, as there is no threat of [Qe5] mate, we can simply play} Nxd6 {with an equal position.}) 25. b4 (25. b4 {The game finished} Re6 26. Qxd3 Qb6 27. Rd1 Qc6 28. Nxf6 Rxf6 29. Ne5 Qc8 30. Qd5 Re6 31. Ng4 Kh7 32. Qd4 Qf8 33. Qa7 Rxd6 34. Re1 Nd8 35. Ne5 Qe7 36. Nf3 Re6 37. Rd1 Rd6 {1/2-1/2 Caruana - Carlsen, Norway Chess 2020.}) *

