1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Ba4 {The most precise as it does not give us a chance to play ...[d6].} Nge7 $1 ({The correct move order, and you will soon see why. Not} 9... d6 $2 10. Nxd4 {and White is taking over.}) 10. Bd6 {The critical try.} b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7c8] Another important move. We prepare ...[Bb7] and ...[Nc8] to get rid of the annoying dark-squared bishop.} (10... O-O $6 {is not precise as after} 11. Nbd2 b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 13. Re1 {, White's bishop on [d6] is too powerful.}) 11. Bb3 Bb7 $1 {[%cal Ge7c8,Gc6a5]} (11... Bb7 {Preparing ...Nc8 and ...Na5 taking care of both bishops. Now} 12. a4 {is not an issue anymore as we have} Nc8 {kicking off the bishop from his comfortable throne.}) (11... O-O {is once again inaccurate, and after} 12. Nbd2 {it transposes to the 10...O-O?! line mentioned in the note to Black's 10th move.}) 12. Re1 {And now we should go for our idea.} Nc8 13. e5 {The most coherent to support the bishop.} Nxd6 14. exd6+ Kf8 (14... Kf8 {We have reached a very unconventional position. Black is a pawn up, but White obviously has enough compensation due to the awkward position of our king. The d6-pawn can be both White's strength and weakness. Here, to my mind, the most critical is} 15. h4 {.}) 15. h4 {To prepare [Ng5] ideas.} Bf6 $1 {The most precise, preparing ...[Kg7] and preventing any [Ng5] business.} (15... h5 $6 {trying to stop the h-pawn is not a good idea as after} 16. Ng5 Ne5 17. Nd2 {± , White's knight on [g5] becomes too strong, and the pressure on [f7] is very unpleasant.}) (15... Rc8 {is too slow as after} 16. Nbd2 {, we cannot go} f5 {as in the previous line due to} 17. Ng5 {± .}) 16. Nbd2 Kg7 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5] It is absolutely necessary as the king needs to be taken care of.} 17. Bd5 {White needs to pin the knight as, otherwise, ...[Na5] might be unpleasant.} Bxh4 $1 {This is necessary to get decent play. Now White has a few interesting options, and we will check a couple of them.} 18. Re4 {Very natural, attacking the bishop and bringing the rook into the attack.} Bg5 19. Rg4 {Here I recommend a calmer approach.} h6 {[%cal Gf7f5]} ({The rook is a bit awkwardly placed and can soon get under fire with ...f5. Thus, White needs to go for some simplifications.} 19... Bxd2 {also works, but the price of a mistake is very high in this line.} 20. Qxd2 {White has multiple threats at his disposal, like [Nxd4] or [Ng5], so we need to act fast.} f5 $1 21. Rh4 {and now} h5 {should be played if we do not want to get mated after [Qh6].} 22. Re1 {By bringing the last piece into play, White also creates a dreadful threat of [Bxc6] and [Re7].} Qf6 23. Bxc6 Bxc6 24. Re7+ Kg8 25. Ng5 {Now again, we have only one move to stay alive:} Qxd6 {□} 26. Rf7 Qd5 {□ Once again the only way to keep the balance in view of the threat [Rxd4].} 27. f3 Qe5 28. Rxd4 Re8 29. Rdxd7 Bxd7 30. Qxd7 Rh6 $1 {in order to protect [g6].} 31. Rg7+ Qxg7 32. Qxe8+ Qf8 33. Qe6+ {and the game will end in a draw by perpetual.}) 20. Ne4 {Who could say that in 4 moves, all of the light pieces, as well as one pair of rooks, will get off the board?} f5 21. Rxg5 {Necessary.} fxe4 (21... hxg5 22. Bxc6 fxe4 {is just a transposition.}) 22. Bxc6 hxg5 23. Bxb7 exf3 24. Bxa8 Qxa8 25. Qxd4+ Kf7 {Our king might look weak, but White does not have enough resources to create any kind of attack.} 26. Re1 Re8 27. Rxe8 Qxe8 28. gxf3 Qe6 $10 {With an equal endgame.} *

