[ECO "B31"]
[PlyCount "52"]
[GameId "2123892868751878"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 {This is White's main continuation.} e5 $5 ({An interesting alternative to the more popular} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d4 {As usual in the Rossolimo, once Black plays ...[e5], White should always consider the direct attack in the centre.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 $1 (7... Nxd4 {is less precise due to} 8. Nc3 $1) 8. Bf4 {White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development. It is clear that the bishop is heading to [d6], where it will have a firm grip on the d-pawn.} a6 (8... Nge7 {is less good.} 9. Bd6 O-O {Here, White can continue with} 10. a4 $1 a6 11. Bc4 {transposing to the 9.Bc4!? Nge7 line.}) 9. Ba4 {The most precise as it does not give us a chance to play ...[d6].} Nge7 $1 ({The correct move order, and you will soon see why. Not} 9... d6 $2 10. Nxd4 {and White is taking over.}) 10. Bd6 {The critical try.} b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7c8] Another important move. We prepare ...[Bb7] and ...[Nc8] to get rid of the annoying dark-squared bishop.} (10... O-O $6 {is not precise as after} 11. Nbd2 b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 13. Re1 {, White's bishop on [d6] is too powerful.}) 11. Bb3 Bb7 $1 {[%cal Ge7c8,Gc6a5]} (11... Bb7 {Preparing ...Nc8 and ...Na5 taking care of both bishops. Now} 12. a4 {is not an issue anymore as we have} Nc8 {kicking off the bishop from his comfortable throne.}) (11... O-O {is once again inaccurate, and after} 12. Nbd2 {it transposes to the 10...O-O?! line mentioned in the note to Black's 10th move.}) 12. Re1 {And now we should go for our idea.} Nc8 13. e5 {The most coherent to support the bishop.} Nxd6 14. exd6+ Kf8 (14... Kf8 {We have reached a very unconventional position. Black is a pawn up, but White obviously has enough compensation due to the awkward position of our king. The d6-pawn can be both White's strength and weakness. Here, to my mind, the most critical is} 15. h4 {.}) 15. h4 {To prepare [Ng5] ideas.} Bf6 $1 {The most precise, preparing ...[Kg7] and preventing any [Ng5] business.} (15... h5 $6 {trying to stop the h-pawn is not a good idea as after} 16. Ng5 Ne5 17. Nd2 {± , White's knight on [g5] becomes too strong, and the pressure on [f7] is very unpleasant.}) (15... Rc8 {is too slow as after} 16. Nbd2 {, we cannot go} f5 {as in the previous line due to} 17. Ng5 {± .}) 16. Nbd2 Kg7 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5] It is absolutely necessary as the king needs to be taken care of.} 17. Bd5 {White needs to pin the knight as, otherwise, ...[Na5] might be unpleasant.} Bxh4 $1 {This is necessary to get decent play. Now White has a few interesting options, and we will check a couple of them.} 18. Ne4 {A logical follow-up, restricting our dark-squared bishop and having some possibilities to jump on the queenside with [Nc5].} Bf6 19. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2f4] White's idea will probably be to activate his queen by going to [f4]. Here, besides the standard ...[Na5] plan, we can also try something different.} Rb8 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb8b7]} 20. Qf4 Nb4 {With the same idea of exchanging the bishops, but the knight is more actively placed on [b4] and can easily get back to the centre.} 21. Bxb7 Rxb7 22. Ne5 {[%cal Ge5g4]} Nd5 ({It is important to destabilize White's pieces, as the threat of Ng4 was very unpleasant. We have no time for} 22... Nc2 {as after} 23. Ng4 {, there are too many threats around the king.}) 23. Qg3 b4 {[%cal Gb7b5] Preparing for White's next move.} 24. Nc5 Rb5 25. Nexd7 Nb6 26. Nxf6 Rxc5 {With equality.} *

