nd preventing any [Ng5] business.} (15... h5 $6 {trying to stop the h-pawn is not a good idea as after} 16. Ng5 Ne5 17. Nd2 {± , White's knight on [g5] becomes too strong, and the pressure on [f7] is very unpleasant.}) (15... Rc8 {is too slow as after} 16. Nbd2 {, we cannot go} f5 {as in the previous line due to} 17. Ng5 {± .}) 16. Nbd2 Kg7 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5] It is absolutely necessary as the king needs to be taken care of.} 17. Bd5 {White needs to pin the knight as, otherwise, ...[Na5] might be unpleasant.} Bxh4 $1 {This is necessary to get decent play. Now White has a few interesting options, and we will check a couple of them.} 18. Ne4 {A logical follow-up, restricting our dark-squared bishop and having some possibilities to jump on the queenside with [Nc5].} Bf6 19. Rc1 {A natural developing move, but it gives us time to solve some problems.} Na5 {[%csl Gb7] We finally manage to play this move, opening up our passive bishop.} 20. Bxb7 Nxb7 21. Nxd4 Re8 {[%cal Ga8c8] Here, the play is not forced, of course, but the line could continue with White playing as follows:} 22. Nf3 Re6 {[%cal Ga8c8] As already mentioned in the note to White's 14th move, the [d6]-pawn is White's strength and weakness at the same time. Now it can become our target.} 23. Qd5 Qb6 (23... Qb6 {Putting additional pressure on the pawn. For example,} 24. Rc7 $4 {is a huge mistake due to} Nxd6 25. Nxd6 Qxc7 {and the game is over.}) 24. Nfg5 {This is playable.} Bxg5 25. Nxg5 Rf6 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Gb6f2]} 26. Ne4 Rf5 27. Qd3 Re8 28. Qc3+ Rfe5 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ge5e4] Creating a threat of ...[b4] and ...[Rxe4].} 29. b4 f6 {Now White has only one move to stay in the game.} 30. Qc7 Qxc7 31. dxc7 Rc8 {[%csl Gc8] White does not have a way to attack our [c8]-rook and promote. The position is equal, but the game is not over.} *

