[Black "Rossolimo 5.Re1 - 6.Bxc6, 7.d3 & 8.Nbd2 - Why not 8...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B31"]
[PlyCount "31"]
[GameId "2123892868829707"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. Bxc6 {Clearly the most popular choice and White's last chance to double our pawns; otherwise, we will continue with ...[Ne7]-...[Nxc6]. Now it is important how to recapture.} dxc6 (6... bxc6 $6 {is dubious as after} 7. c3 $1 {we are not in time to meet [d4].}) 7. d3 {Here, we have an interesting setup to finish our development.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg8f6] The idea is simple: we protect the [e5]-pawn to be able to develop the knight to [f6] or to [h6], depending on White's play.} (7... Ne7 {was tried by many players, myself included, but I believe our knight is not greatly placed here.} 8. a3 {and White will continue with their usual plan with [b4].}) 8. Nbd2 (8. Nbd2 {The most common reply, and here I believe the best is} Nh6 {.}) 8... Nf6 {The problem with this move is that we are not in time to get the setup we want, as White immediately puts pressure.} 9. Nc4 {[%csl Re5]} Nd7 {[%csl Rc8] Forced, but it is obviously not ideal as now the light-squared bishop is blocked.} 10. a4 {Typical space-gaining move.} O-O (10... O-O {We are ready to meet} 11. a5 {with} Re8 {and the useful regroup ...[Nf8]-...[Ne6].}) 11. Bg5 {We have no choice.} f6 (11... Qe6 {is leading to an even less harmonious position.} 12. a5 {, and we have difficulties in finding good moves.}) 12. Be3 Nb6 {It makes sense to try to exchange White's active knight.} 13. b3 Nxc4 14. bxc4 Bg4 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 $14 {White is slightly better.} *

