1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. Bxc6 {Clearly the most popular choice and White's last chance to double our pawns; otherwise, we will continue with ...[Ne7]-...[Nxc6]. Now it is important how to recapture.} dxc6 (6... bxc6 $6 {is dubious as after} 7. c3 $1 {we are not in time to meet [d4].}) 7. d3 {Here, we have an interesting setup to finish our development.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg8f6] The idea is simple: we protect the [e5]-pawn to be able to develop the knight to [f6] or to [h6], depending on White's play.} (7... Ne7 {was tried by many players, myself included, but I believe our knight is not greatly placed here.} 8. a3 {and White will continue with their usual plan with [b4].}) 8. Nbd2 (8. Nbd2 {The most common reply, and here I believe the best is} Nh6 {.}) 8... Nh6 $5 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gf7f6] As White's knight is heading to [c4], it makes sense for us to keep the possibility of ...[f6] to reinforce the defence of the [e5]-pawn.} 9. b4 {This always needs to be checked in this line.} cxb4 10. a3 O-O {The simplest.} 11. axb4 Rd8 {To avoid any possible future problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal.} 12. Nb3 Be6 {Provoking a seemingly good knight jump.} 13. Nc5 Bg4 14. Bd2 a5 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ga5b4] However, we can see that, in fact, White's knight is not stable on [c5], and we get enough counterplay.} *

