1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. Bxc6 {Clearly the most popular choice and White's last chance to double our pawns; otherwise, we will continue with ...[Ne7]-...[Nxc6]. Now it is important how to recapture.} dxc6 (6... bxc6 $6 {is dubious as after} 7. c3 $1 {we are not in time to meet [d4].}) 7. d3 {Here, we have an interesting setup to finish our development.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg8f6] The idea is simple: we protect the [e5]-pawn to be able to develop the knight to [f6] or to [h6], depending on White's play.} (7... Ne7 {was tried by many players, myself included, but I believe our knight is not greatly placed here.} 8. a3 {and White will continue with their usual plan with [b4].}) 8. a4 {Here White does not create any immediate threats, so we have time for ...[Nf6].} Nf6 9. Bg5 h6 {As usual, once the bishop gets to [g5], we want to see White's further intentions.} 10. Be3 O-O 11. h3 {[%csl Gg4] Prophylaxis against ...[Ng4] or ...[Bg4].} Rd8 {[%cal Gc5c4]} 12. Nbd2 {And now it's time for our knight improving manoeuvre.} Ne8 {[%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6,Ge6d4]} 13. Nc4 Nc7 14. a5 Kh7 {[%cal Gc7b5] White took some space on the queenside, but advancing the a-pawn that far left some squares available for our pieces. ...[Nb5] can be played next with an interesting position.} *

