1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. Bxc6 {Clearly the most popular choice and White's last chance to double our pawns; otherwise, we will continue with ...[Ne7]-...[Nxc6]. Now it is important how to recapture.} dxc6 (6... bxc6 $6 {is dubious as after} 7. c3 $1 {we are not in time to meet [d4].}) 7. d3 {Here, we have an interesting setup to finish our development.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg8f6] The idea is simple: we protect the [e5]-pawn to be able to develop the knight to [f6] or to [h6], depending on White's play.} (7... Ne7 {was tried by many players, myself included, but I believe our knight is not greatly placed here.} 8. a3 {and White will continue with their usual plan with [b4].}) 8. a3 {A preparation for [b4], but it gives us some time to regroup the pieces the way we want.} Nf6 ({If} 8... a5 {trying to stop [b4], after} 9. Nbd2 {, the knight will be even stronger on [c4] than with the pawn on [a7].}) 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Nc4 {[%csl Ge5] Delaying [Nbd2] by one move allows us to have a comfortable setup.} Ne8 {[%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6] The knight is better here than on [d7], as we have already seen in some lines. The reason is simple: our bishop is not blocked here, and the knight can be improved via the [c7] and [e6]-squares.} 11. Be3 Bg4 {When allowed, we are always happy to exchange this bishop.} 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 {And now it's time to improve our knight.} Nc7 {[%cal Gc7e6]} 14. b4 Ne6 {[%csl Gc5] Just in time to protect [c5].} 15. bxc5 Nxc5 16. a4 f5 {With a double-edged position.} *

