1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. Bxc6 {Clearly the most popular choice and White's last chance to double our pawns; otherwise, we will continue with ...[Ne7]-...[Nxc6]. Now it is important how to recapture.} dxc6 (6... bxc6 $6 {is dubious as after} 7. c3 $1 {we are not in time to meet [d4].}) 7. d3 {Here, we have an interesting setup to finish our development.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg8f6] The idea is simple: we protect the [e5]-pawn to be able to develop the knight to [f6] or to [h6], depending on White's play.} (7... Ne7 {was tried by many players, myself included, but I believe our knight is not greatly placed here.} 8. a3 {and White will continue with their usual plan with [b4].}) 8. a3 {A preparation for [b4], but it gives us some time to regroup the pieces the way we want.} Nf6 ({If} 8... a5 {trying to stop [b4], after} 9. Nbd2 {, the knight will be even stronger on [c4] than with the pawn on [a7].}) 9. b4 {Now we have a pleasant choice; all of the suggested moves are playable here.} O-O {Probably the most natural and the most frequent in practice.} 10. bxc5 Qxc5 11. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] As usual, White wants to get the bishop on this diagonal, but we are just in time to avoid any trouble.} Rd8 12. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4] Preventing ...[Bg4].} Qd6 13. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4]} Be6 {Developing the last piece and preventing [Nc4].} 14. Ng5 {This can simply be ignored, as we are not afraid to exchange our light-squared bishop.} b6 {Our plan could be ...[a6]-...[b5], but we need to make sure White does not fix our pawn structure with [a4]-[a5]. The position is equal, but the all the fight is still ahead.} *

