1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. Bxc6 {Clearly the most popular choice and White's last chance to double our pawns; otherwise, we will continue with ...[Ne7]-...[Nxc6]. Now it is important how to recapture.} dxc6 (6... bxc6 $6 {is dubious as after} 7. c3 $1 {we are not in time to meet [d4].}) 7. a4 {White can start with this, but it does not really have an independent value after some developing moves, as we'll see.} Qe7 {Just as in the 7.d3 line.} 8. Na3 {White's knight is going to [c4], so it makes sense to react in the same manner as after 7.d3 and 8.Nbd2.} Nh6 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gh6f7]} 9. d3 {It looks a bit weird to delay [Nc4], but one can't argue that [d3] is an useful move.} ({After} 9. Nc4 f6 {, it's difficult to find something better than} 10. d3 {and finally we transpose to this line.}) 9... b6 {I like to start with this, making sure that our [b7]-pawn won't get fixed with [a4]-[a5].} 10. a5 {This is always an option for White.} (10. Nc4 f6 {is again a transposition.}) 10... O-O $1 (10... b5 {feels a bit too early, as White has a nice regrouping.} 11. c3 O-O 12. Nc2 {followed by [b4] and [Be3]. Black has some issues with the [c5]-square.}) 11. Nc4 b5 {Now we can go for this, as White doesn't have time for their nice regrouping.} 12. Ncd2 Be6 {[%cal Gc5c4] With the threat of ...[c4], and Black enjoys a very easy game.} *

