1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. Bxc6 {Clearly the most popular choice and White's last chance to double our pawns; otherwise, we will continue with ...[Ne7]-...[Nxc6]. Now it is important how to recapture.} dxc6 (6... bxc6 $6 {is dubious as after} 7. c3 $1 {we are not in time to meet [d4].}) 7. a4 {White can start with this, but it does not really have an independent value after some developing moves, as we'll see.} Qe7 {Just as in the 7.d3 line.} 8. Na3 {White's knight is going to [c4], so it makes sense to react in the same manner as after 7.d3 and 8.Nbd2.} Nh6 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gh6f7]} 9. a5 b5 {[%csl Ra3]} (9... b5 {If} 10. d3 {pretending nothing happened, the problem is that the [a3]-knight is really stuck.} O-O {and ...[Rd8] followed by ...[c4] may come soon.} 11. c3 {Trying to reroute the knight via [c2], but that's too slow.} Rd8 {Black has pressure on the [d3]-pawn and an excellent game.}) 10. axb6 axb6 {[%cal Ga8a1] And now it will take a lot of time for White to develop normally, as the pin on the a-file is very annoying.} *

