1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. d3 {This is not the top choice but was played by some strong grandmasters, so we should briefly check how to react.} Nge7 7. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5] White basically abandons any ideas connected with [d4] and instead tries to play for the [d5]-square.} O-O 8. Bc4 d6 9. Bg5 ({The bishop should be questioned immediately. Alternatively, White can play} 9. a3 h6 {and we have an easy plan with ...[Kh7] and ...[f5].}) 9... h6 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 {And we still keep control over the [d5]-square.} 11. Nd5 Bd7 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 12. a4 {Preventing Black's expansion on the queenside.} Kh7 {It's always good to remove the king from the [a2]-[g8] diagonal once the white bishop gets to [c4]. We do not necessarily want to push ...[f5] next, but it's good to have it ready.} (12... Nxd5 {is a good alternative.} 13. Bxd5 Bc6 14. Bxc6 bxc6 {with equal chances. ...[Kh7], ...[Qd7], and ...[Rb8] are good ideas to continue.}) 13. a5 Bc6 {Inviting White to exchange on [e7].} 14. Nxe7 Qxe7 15. c3 h5 {[%cal Gg7h6] Followed by ...[Bh6] with mutual chances.} *

