1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. d3 {This is not the top choice but was played by some strong grandmasters, so we should briefly check how to react.} Nge7 7. Nc3 {White basically abandons any ideas connected with [d4] and instead tries to play for the [d5]-square.} O-O 8. Bc4 d6 9. Nd5 h6 {We can continue with the same plan as after 9.Bg5.} 10. c3 Kh7 11. a3 {Here we have several good options, but I recommend the simplest.} Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Ne7 13. Ba2 f5 {With an easy play.} *

