1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] Quite a popular setup preparing [d4] with a pawn sacrifice.} Nge7 7. d4 {Now we should accept the challenge.} cxd4 8. cxd4 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4d6] White's thematic idea is to try to put the bishop on [d6] to block the d-pawn and pin the [e7]-knight.} O-O 11. Bd6 Re8 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ge7c6] Unpinning the knight and preparing ...[Qb6] with a double attack.} 12. Na3 a6 {And here it's White who has to be careful.} 13. Rc1 {[%cal Gd6c7]} ({The only move to keep the balance.} 13. Ba4 {would be a serious mistake already, as after} b5 {, we get a nice square for our light-squared bishop, and the knight will jump to [c6] to protect the [d4]-pawn. White does not have enough compensation here.}) 13... Nc6 14. Bc4 {Once again, the only move not to be worse. Any other retreat would allow ...[Re6] or ...[b5].} b5 15. Bd5 {That's why it was important to play [Bc4]. White's bishops look quite powerful, but we are fine if we continue with the most logical play.} Bb7 16. e5 {And here I suggest a novelty.} Na5 {Abandoning the [d4]-pawn but exchanging one of the most active white pieces.} 17. Qxd4 Bxd5 18. Qxd5 Nc6 {[%cal Gd8g5,Gc6e7,Ge7f5] The knight has done its job and needs to come back closer to the centre. Moreover, we can continue improving the knight's position by regrouping it to [f5] via [e7].} *

