1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] Quite a popular setup preparing [d4] with a pawn sacrifice.} Nge7 7. d4 {Now we should accept the challenge.} cxd4 8. cxd4 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4d6] White's thematic idea is to try to put the bishop on [d6] to block the d-pawn and pin the [e7]-knight.} O-O 11. Bd6 Re8 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ge7c6] Unpinning the knight and preparing ...[Qb6] with a double attack.} 12. Qb3 {This has never appeared in practice, but it makes sense. The rook has just moved to [e8], and White might try to put some pressure on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal. Black has a choice here.} Nc6 {[%cal Gd8f6] I would go for this, improving the knight and opening up the way for our queen.} 13. Bc4 Qf6 {[%csl Gf7,Rd6] The queen is not only playing a defensive role but is also attacking the bishop.} 14. e5 {This seems natural but is, in fact, a mistake.} Qxd6 $1 15. Bxf7+ {Luckily for White, they still have this check and are not losing on the spot.} Kf8 16. Bxe8 Qe7 {[%csl Re8] The bishop is not going to escape. White managed to avoid the total disaster, but our position remains better.} *

