1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] Quite a popular setup preparing [d4] with a pawn sacrifice.} Nge7 7. d4 {Now we should accept the challenge.} cxd4 8. cxd4 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4d6] White's thematic idea is to try to put the bishop on [d6] to block the d-pawn and pin the [e7]-knight.} O-O 11. Bd6 Re8 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ge7c6] Unpinning the knight and preparing ...[Qb6] with a double attack.} 12. Qb3 {This has never appeared in practice, but it makes sense. The rook has just moved to [e8], and White might try to put some pressure on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal. Black has a choice here.} Nc6 {[%cal Gd8f6] I would go for this, improving the knight and opening up the way for our queen.} 13. Bc4 Qf6 {[%csl Gf7,Rd6] The queen is not only playing a defensive role but is also attacking the bishop.} 14. Na3 {[%cal Ga3b5] A better version of the bishop sacrifice.} Qxd6 15. Bxf7+ Kf8 16. Bxe8 Qe7 $1 {Just like in the 14.e5 line, only this time White still has some weapons at his disposal.} 17. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7] And it turns out that it is not that easy to win this bishop.} Rb8 18. Nc7 Be5 {[%cal Ge5c7] Anyway, now White's position looks very suspicious.} 19. Bxg6 Bxc7 ({With a very messy position.} 19... hxg6 {is not good as now} 20. Nd5 {gives White a big advantage due to our weakened king and uncompleted development.}) *

