1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. b4 {Not the most popular choice, but it is a critical try implemented in the World Championship match Caruana-Carlsen in 2018. As often in the Rossolimo, White sacrifices a pawn, hoping to get fast development and decent initiative.} Nxb4 $5 ({A less popular choice than} 6... cxb4 {, but I believe it's the best way to continue.}) 7. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] Obviously, a preparation for a fast blow in the centre.} Nc6 8. d4 exd4 {White has two interesting ways to continue here.} 9. Ba3 {Here we have various possibilities.} a6 {I would suggest this, forcing White to trade.} 10. Bxc6 dxc6 11. Bxc5 dxc3 {With a very sharp position. Being two pawns down, White should avoid the queen exchange.} 12. Qb3 Be6 {The advantage of having extra material is that we can give it back at any moment to win some time.} 13. Qxb7 c2 14. Nd4 {The only move, but a logical one.} Rb8 {White's attempt to play for more than a draw goes in our favour.} 15. Qxc6+ (15. Qa7 {is White's best, and after} Ra8 {draw should be reached by a move repetition.}) 15... Bd7 16. Qd6 Rc8 $1 ({This quiet move turns out to be very strong.} 16... cxb1=Q {is not that clear as after} 17. Raxb1 Rxb1 18. Rxb1 {, White gets a powerful initiative. The [b1]-knight is now under attack.}) 17. Na3 {This looks also logical, but here we have a nice way to maintain our advantage.} Qe7 $1 {White will lose material soon.} *

