1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. b4 {Not the most popular choice, but it is a critical try implemented in the World Championship match Caruana-Carlsen in 2018. As often in the Rossolimo, White sacrifices a pawn, hoping to get fast development and decent initiative.} Nxb4 $5 ({A less popular choice than} 6... cxb4 {, but I believe it's the best way to continue.}) 7. c3 {Obviously, a preparation for a fast blow in the centre.} Nc6 8. d4 exd4 {White has two interesting ways to continue here.} 9. e5 {[%csl Gf6,Rg7] White's main idea, to close our bishop and take control of the [f6]-square.} Nge7 {An obvious move; we need to finish our development as soon as possible.} 10. cxd4 {Here we have several interesting options.} Nxd4 {I would go for this.} 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Ba3 O-O 13. Bd6 {And here we can continue with a surprising sac.} Nf5 14. Bxf8 Bxf8 {[%cal Gd7d5] Being two pawns up for an exchange gives us enough compensation. Besides, we have two bishops, and we will follow with ...[d5] next to finish our development.} *

