1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {One of the main lines for White.} e5 $1 {We stick to the same ...[e5]-system we have already seen in other chapters after White's 5.c3 or 4.c3-5.Qe2.} 6. b4 {Not the most popular choice, but it is a critical try implemented in the World Championship match Caruana-Carlsen in 2018. As often in the Rossolimo, White sacrifices a pawn, hoping to get fast development and decent initiative.} Nxb4 $5 ({A less popular choice than} 6... cxb4 {, but I believe it's the best way to continue.}) 7. Bb2 $5 a6 $1 ({An important move forcing White's reply.} 7... Ne7 {is a possibility but allows White to regain the pawn too easily.} 8. Bxe5 Bxe5 9. Nxe5 {with a more pleasant position for White.}) ({Bringing back the knight is on our agenda, but here, once again,} 7... Nc6 {allows White to win back the pawn easily.} 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Nxe5 Nf6 10. Nf3 {with a slight advantage.}) 8. a3 ({This leads to forced exchanges. Instead,} 8. Bf1 {would give us an easy game after} Nc6 {bringing back the knight and defending the central pawn. White has some compensation, but I don't think it's enough.}) 8... axb5 9. axb4 Rxa1 10. Bxa1 d6 $1 ({The move I recommend. We simply defend the e5-pawn.} 10... cxb4 {is probably playable, but I am not a fan of our tripled pawns, and especially of giving away the central [e5]-pawn.} 11. Bxe5 Bxe5 12. Nxe5 {and White can put some pressure here.}) 11. bxc5 {The most natural-looking reply, but we continue as if nothing has happened.} Ne7 {Most importantly, our [e5]-pawn is still safe. Here, White has a choice: either exchanging on [d6] immediately or trying to keep the tension and put some pressure on the [b5]-pawn.} 12. Qe2 $5 {This was Caruana's choice in the World Championship match against Carlsen. Here, we have no choice.} b4 13. c3 {I like} Nc6 {I like this move. It might seem that we are protecting the [b4]-pawn, but we have some hidden agenda.} 14. cxb4 dxc5 {[%cal Gc6e5] The point of the previous move. This is possible now that the [e5]-pawn is protected by the knight.} 15. bxc5 Qa5 $10 {[%cal Ga5c5] And we will take back the pawn next.} *

