c6 {was played once, but White gets a dangerous initiative after} 15. d4 Qxa1 16. d5 {with an unpleasant position for Black.}) 15. Qc7 {Forcing us to exchange.} Qxc7 16. dxc7 {Before proceeding with our attack on the [c7]-pawn, we should first take care of our own important [e5]-pawn.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge8d7,Gc6e5]} 17. Rd1 $1 {[%cal Gd2d4] White's idea is clear: to follow with [d4] and open up the position.} Kd7 {The king is rushing to eliminate the [c7]-intruder.} 18. d4 {Here we have several possibilities. I'll show you my favourite.} b3 $1 {[%cal Gb3c2] Creating some mess.} 19. Nxe5+ Kxc7 $1 20. cxb3 Ra8 $1 {[%csl Ga8] Before taking back on [b3], we can improve our last passive piece.} 21. Nc3 {Now it's time to recapture on [b3].} Bxb3 {The moves are not forced here. Let's see a possible continuation for White:} 22. Nd5+ Bxd5 23. exd5 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d5] Threatening to simply win back the pawn. White has an interesting try.} 24. Rc1+ Kd6 25. Nc4+ Ke7 26. d6+ Kd8 27. Nb6 {And it might seem that Black is in danger here, but actually, we are fine after the final touch.} Nd3 $10 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Ga8a2,Ga8a6] And the rook has to abandon its active position. Depending on White's reply, we can continue with ...[Ra2] or ...[Ra6] with sufficient counterplay.} *

