1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O {White can, of course, start with this.} Bg7 5. Bxc6 {And then go for this.} dxc6 {Here, compared to the main line 4.Bxc6, White shows his intentions right away by castling short.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. Nc3 {Now it's time to take advantage of the fact that White hasn't included [h3].} Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 {Here we should follow with the most natural play.} O-O (9... Nd7 {is also playable with the thematic idea of ...[e5].}) 10. Be3 Qd6 $5 {[%cal Gf6e8,Ge8c7,Gc7e6] This is my suggestion, with an idea of regrouping the knight to [e6] via [e8]-[c7].} 11. Rad1 {[%cal Gd3d4] One of the possible ways to continue for White, preparing [d4].} ({If} 11. Qe2 {, intending [f4], we should go for} Nh5 $5 {followed by ...[Bd4].}) 11... Ne8 {Improving our knight and keeping an eye on [d4].} 12. Ne2 {[%cal Gd3d4] And now it's time for the thematic ...[e5].} e5 {[%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6] We prevent [d4] first and then we can finish our knight manoeuvre.} *

