1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O {White can, of course, start with this.} Bg7 5. Bxc6 {And then go for this.} dxc6 {Here, compared to the main line 4.Bxc6, White shows his intentions right away by castling short.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. Re1 $5 {Played by Magnus himself as White, so we should have a look even if it's not the main move.} Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 8. e5 {That's the idea! Preventing Black from going ...[e5].} Nf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8e6,Ge6d4,Gc8g4] The knight has nothing to do on [d7] anymore once White played [e5]. It is now heading to [e6] and [d4], and we're also threatening to pin the knight on [f3] with ...[Bg4].} 9. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4]} h6 $5 {[%cal Gg6g5] I really like this aggressive and rare approach only one game played. Black is simply going for ...[g5] while the centre is closed.} ({Alternatively, after} 9... Ne6 10. Nc3 {, we get back to some well-known lines.}) 10. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] In order to jump to [e4] and most likely to [f6], which is a typical theme in the Rossolimo lines where Black hasn't castled.} g5 {[%cal Gf8g6,Gg5g4] According to the plan.} 11. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4f6,Ge4c5]} Ng6 {[%cal Gg6e5] Putting pressure on the [e5]-pawn and forcing White to choose a direction with the knight on [e4].} 12. Nxc5 {Greedy!} g4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 {[%cal Gd8d5,Gg6e5,Gg6h4] And White has to face a lot of threats: ...[Qd5], ...[Nxe5], ...[Nh4]...} 14. d4 {[%cal Gd4e5]} Nh4 {[%cal Gd8c8,Gg4f3] Followed by ...[Qc8] threatening to take on [f3] and mate with ...[Qh3]. Black has a strong attack.} *

