1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O {White can, of course, start with this.} Bg7 5. Bxc6 {And then go for this.} dxc6 {Here, compared to the main line 4.Bxc6, White shows his intentions right away by castling short.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. h3 {Once again, this is almost an automatic reaction in the Rossolimo. Now, we will continue with a plan that will be constantly applied in this line.} Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 8. Nbd2 $5 ({This is way less popular than Nc3 but deserves attention.} 8. Nc3 e5 9. Be3 b6 {transposes to this line covered via 7.O-O.}) 8... O-O (8... O-O {Our plan is to meet} 9. Re1 {with} e5 {when our further play could develop with ...[Re8], ...[Qe7]/...[Qc7], ...[Nf8].}) 9. Nc4 {Jumping immediate allows our standard reaction.} b5 (9... e5 {is not that great here due to} 10. Nd6 {White takes back the bishop, and we still have our damaged pawn structure.}) ({However,} 9... Qc7 {is also decent. If White continues with} 10. a4 {we can simply play} b6 {to develop our bishop via [a6] after playing ...[a5].}) 10. Ne3 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] The simplest, intending to advance the pawn even further.} 11. Ng4 (11. a4 {is a natural reaction to stop the black pawns avalanche, but it is not impressive due to} Nb6 $1 {and White faces an unpleasant choice between taking on [b5] and improving our structure or sacrificing on [a4].}) 11... a4 {[%cal Ge7e5] Now, we'll play ...[e5].} 12. a3 e5 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gd7f8,Gf8e6,Ge6d4,Gf8e8] With a complex game. We will kick out the white knight once again! with ...[h5] and on a good day we will manage to land our knight on [d4] via [f8]-[e6]. We have a lot of space on the queenside, and it is pretty clear that nothing will happen to us therer. Very hard to suggest a plan for White.} *

