1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O {White can, of course, start with this.} Bg7 5. Bxc6 {And then go for this.} dxc6 {Here, compared to the main line 4.Bxc6, White shows his intentions right away by castling short.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. h3 {Once again, this is almost an automatic reaction in the Rossolimo. Now, we will continue with a plan that will be constantly applied in this line.} Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 8. Nbd2 $5 ({This is way less popular than Nc3 but deserves attention.} 8. Nc3 e5 9. Be3 b6 {transposes to this line covered via 7.O-O.}) 8... O-O (8... O-O {Our plan is to meet} 9. Re1 {with} e5 {when our further play could develop with ...[Re8], ...[Qe7]/...[Qc7], ...[Nf8].}) 9. Nc4 {Jumping immediate allows our standard reaction.} b5 (9... e5 {is not that great here due to} 10. Nd6 {White takes back the bishop, and we still have our damaged pawn structure.}) ({However,} 9... Qc7 {is also decent. If White continues with} 10. a4 {we can simply play} b6 {to develop our bishop via [a6] after playing ...[a5].}) 10. Ne3 Nb6 $5 {An interesting alternative.} 11. Rb1 Re8 12. b3 e5 {[%cal Ga7a5] With a complicated position. Black can continue taking space on the queenside with ...[a5] while White should start organising some play on the kingside} *

