1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O {White can, of course, start with this.} Bg7 5. Bxc6 {And then go for this.} dxc6 {Here, compared to the main line 4.Bxc6, White shows his intentions right away by castling short.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. h3 {Once again, this is almost an automatic reaction in the Rossolimo. Now, we will continue with a plan that will be constantly applied in this line.} Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 8. Nbd2 $5 ({This is way less popular than Nc3 but deserves attention.} 8. Nc3 e5 9. Be3 b6 {transposes to this line covered via 7.O-O.}) 8... O-O (8... O-O {Our plan is to meet} 9. Re1 {with} e5 {when our further play could develop with ...[Re8], ...[Qe7]/...[Qc7], ...[Nf8].}) 9. a4 {[%cal Gd2c4] As usual, White tries to grab space.} e5 $6 {This is the move we want to play, but here it is a bit imprecise as now White gets what he is aiming for.} 10. Nc4 {[%cal Gc4d6]} Qe7 {To avoid [Nd6].} 11. a5 {Taking space, and our position gets a bit unpleasant here as we struggle to achieve harmonious development.} Rd8 12. Be3 Nf8 13. Qd2 f6 {We are forced to play this to be able to bring the knight to [e6] without losing [e5].} 14. Rfb1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4] However, after this, White has an easy play.} *

