1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. O-O {White can, of course, start with this.} Bg7 5. Bxc6 {And then go for this.} dxc6 {Here, compared to the main line 4.Bxc6, White shows his intentions right away by castling short.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. h3 {Once again, this is almost an automatic reaction in the Rossolimo. Now, we will continue with a plan that will be constantly applied in this line.} Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 8. Nbd2 $5 ({This is way less popular than Nc3 but deserves attention.} 8. Nc3 e5 9. Be3 b6 {transposes to this line covered via 7.O-O.}) 8... O-O (8... O-O {Our plan is to meet} 9. Re1 {with} e5 {when our further play could develop with ...[Re8], ...[Qe7]/...[Qc7], ...[Nf8].}) 9. a4 {[%cal Gd2c4] As usual, White tries to grab space.} a5 $1 {An important move preventing White from advancing any further and keeping a possibility to develop the light-squared bishop by means of ...[b6]-...[Ba6].} 10. Re1 {A kind of waiting move, waiting for inaccurate play from Black, but we actually have some useful moves to improve our pieces.} ({The immediate} 10. Nc4 {is, of course, a call for} b5 11. Ne3 Nb6 $1 {and it's White who has to be careful here as none of the choices are pleasant: he has to either take on [b5] and improve our pawn structure or simply sacrifice the [a4]-pawn.}) 10... Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5]} ({The most precise, ready to meet Nc4. Once again, it's not the best timing for} 10... e5 $6 {, as now after} 11. Nc4 $1 {. the ...[b5] idea works less well due to [Nd6].}) 11. Nc4 b5 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6] As usual. We'll follow up with ...[Nb6].} *

