1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. Nc3 {I don't think this is a particularly dangerous move for Black.} e5 $1 {That's something you have to remember much more important than concrete lines, actually!: It is possible to play ...[e5] when the white knight is committed to [c3], as it won't be able to attack our [e5]-pawn from there. And we will generally be able to prepare ...[f5], gain some more space, and have great prospects.} 7. O-O (7. Be3 b6 8. h3 {transposes here.}) (7. h3 b6 {is also a transposition.}) 7... b6 {Our usual half-waiting move!} 8. Be3 (8. h3 {transposes here.}) 8... Ne7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf7f5,Ga2a4,Ga7a5]} 9. Qd2 {Trying to exchange dark-squared bishops while saving a tempo on [h3].} (9. h3 {again transposes here.}) 9... h6 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gg6g5,Ge7g6] Preventing [Bh6] and preparing something on the kingside, which could be ...[Bg4] and ...[f5] or even ...[g5] and ...[Ng6] with a very nice and easy game for Black.} 10. h3 f5 {We have transposed to this line covered via 6.h3.} *

