1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. a4 {A very rare move, but this AI-inspired idea could always come at any moment.} a5 $1 {This is the antidote I am recommending in this course: always stop White's queenside expansion as soon as possible!} 7. O-O (7. h3 b6 {transposes here.}) 7... Nf6 8. Be3 (8. Na3 {is the most logical heading to [c4].} O-O 9. Nc4 {transposes here.}) 8... b6 {[%cal Gf6g4]} 9. Qc1 {[%cal Ge3h6]} (9. h3 {transposes here.}) 9... O-O 10. Bh6 Nh5 {[%cal Gf7f6,Ge7e5,Gh5f4,Gg8g7] Fair enough! White managed to exchange our bishop on [g7]. So what? They lost a bunch of time doing so, and we will go ...[f6]-...[e5] with a nice structure and firm control over the central dark squares replacing our dark-squared bishop. And we are already dreaming of landing a knight on [f4] to launch an attack on the kingside.} *

