1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... Nf6 {This was Magnus' choice in the 2018 World Championship match vs Caruana.} 7. Nc3 Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] The idea behind this slightly unusual-looking move is to play ...[e5] next.} 8. Be3 $1 {This is the most precise, creating some concrete problems for Black.} e5 9. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1,Ge1g1] A multifunctional move, giving the king a possibility of long castling but also intending [Bh6] if allowed.} (9. Qd2 {Now,} h6 {is kind of forced to stop [Bh6].}) 9... b6 $2 {This is a try to transpose into our concept, but it's failing here.} 10. Bh6 Bf6 11. Nd1 $1 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Gd1e3,Ge3g4] The knight is heading to [g4], and Black is basically busted here.} *

