1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. O-O Nf6 {We have nothing better than to develop the knight to [f6]. On the other hand, White revealed his strategy by castling short.} (7... e5 {works less well here due to} 8. a3 $1 {Once our bishop gets blocked by the [e5]-pawn, White can prepare the thematic plan with [b4]. It is important to notice that with the knight still on [b1], this plan is more effective, as any attempt to stop it with, let's say} Qd6 {can be ignored:} 9. b4 {and after} cxb4 10. axb4 {, Black cannot really capture on [b4] due to [Ba3]. With the knight already on [c3], this would be a different story.}) 8. Nbd2 {This gives us an easy play.} O-O 9. a4 {Here, as usual, we need to stop White.} a5 10. Nc4 Qc7 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ge7e5] Preventing [Bf4] and keeping in mind our usual setup with ...[e5].} 11. Be3 Nd7 12. Qd2 Ba6 {[%cal Ga6c4,Ge7e5,Gf8e8,Gd7f8] Our problematic bishop finally gets out, and we have various possibilities here. Besides the intention to exchange on [c4], we can also consider ...[e5], followed by ...[Re8] and ...[Nf8]-...[Ne6], for example.} *

