1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. O-O Nf6 {We have nothing better than to develop the knight to [f6]. On the other hand, White revealed his strategy by castling short.} (7... e5 {works less well here due to} 8. a3 $1 {Once our bishop gets blocked by the [e5]-pawn, White can prepare the thematic plan with [b4]. It is important to notice that with the knight still on [b1], this plan is more effective, as any attempt to stop it with, let's say} Qd6 {can be ignored:} 9. b4 {and after} cxb4 10. axb4 {, Black cannot really capture on [b4] due to [Ba3]. With the knight already on [c3], this would be a different story.}) 8. Re1 $5 {[%cal Ge4e5] A very interesting and also very rare move suggested by Gajewski in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4. The point is very simple: supporting the [e5] push by protecting it with the rook. Pure prophylaxis.} Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] Already only a couple of games in my database. Black is threatening ...[e5]. If Black pushes ...[e5], then the rook on [e1] wouldn't make any sense, so we're forcing White's hand.} 9. e5 $1 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6]} 10. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2e4,Ge4h4] Without [a4]-[a5], we go for the same plan anyway. White wants a quick attack with [Qe4]-[Qh4] if we play some routine plan as ...[Ne6]-...[Nd4].} h6 $1 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gg6g5,Gf8g6] Stopping [Qe4]-[Qh4] at once as we get ...[g5]. You might be worried about your king in the centre, but there is no reason to do so as the centre is closed. We may choose later where to put the king. Also, White played [h3], creating a possibility to open up the g-file, later or much later with ...[g5]-...[g4], and creating a dangerous attack. White has to keep in mind that option, which is very annoying.} 11. b3 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gf8g6,Gc8e6]} g5 12. Bb2 Ng6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gd8d7] Followed by ...[Be6]-...[Qd7] and then deciding where the king should go. Both alternatives, short and long castle are definitely on the table, very much depending on how White will react.} *

