1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. O-O Nf6 {We have nothing better than to develop the knight to [f6]. On the other hand, White revealed his strategy by castling short.} (7... e5 {works less well here due to} 8. a3 $1 {Once our bishop gets blocked by the [e5]-pawn, White can prepare the thematic plan with [b4]. It is important to notice that with the knight still on [b1], this plan is more effective, as any attempt to stop it with, let's say} Qd6 {can be ignored:} 9. b4 {and after} cxb4 10. axb4 {, Black cannot really capture on [b4] due to [Ba3]. With the knight already on [c3], this would be a different story.}) 8. Re1 $5 {[%cal Ge4e5] A very interesting and also very rare move suggested by Gajewski in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4. The point is very simple: supporting the [e5] push by protecting it with the rook. Pure prophylaxis.} Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] Already only a couple of games in my database. Black is threatening ...[e5]. If Black pushes ...[e5], then the rook on [e1] wouldn't make any sense, so we're forcing White's hand.} 9. e5 $1 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6]} 10. a4 $5 {[%cal Ga4a5] The move recommended by Gajewski, assuming that the [a4]-...[a5] inclusion is favourable for White.} a5 {A novelty in practical play but not in Gajewski's course, who gives that option. As you will probably notice in this chapter, I really recommend not letting white continue with his a-pawn when they start with [a4].} 11. Na3 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga3c4,Gc4b6] Also an interesting option. White wants to put his knight on [c4] right away. Makes sense as the [b6]-pawn was weakened by the [a4]-...[a5] inclusion.} h6 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gf8g6,Gc8e6] Same plan!} 12. d4 {White may think that this move ...[h6] is too slow, and it would be a good time to open up the centre and punish Black. But things are not so simple!} cxd4 13. Nxd4 Ne6 $1 {Setting up a nice trap!} 14. Nxc6 Qd7 $1 {[%csl Rc6] And the [c6]-knight is trapped!} *

