1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. O-O Nf6 {We have nothing better than to develop the knight to [f6]. On the other hand, White revealed his strategy by castling short.} (7... e5 {works less well here due to} 8. a3 $1 {Once our bishop gets blocked by the [e5]-pawn, White can prepare the thematic plan with [b4]. It is important to notice that with the knight still on [b1], this plan is more effective, as any attempt to stop it with, let's say} Qd6 {can be ignored:} 9. b4 {and after} cxb4 10. axb4 {, Black cannot really capture on [b4] due to [Ba3]. With the knight already on [c3], this would be a different story.}) 8. Re1 $5 {[%cal Ge4e5] A very interesting and also very rare move suggested by Gajewski in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4. The point is very simple: supporting the [e5] push by protecting it with the rook. Pure prophylaxis.} Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] Already only a couple of games in my database. Black is threatening ...[e5]. If Black pushes ...[e5], then the rook on [e1] wouldn't make any sense, so we're forcing White's hand.} 9. e5 $1 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6]} 10. a4 $5 {[%cal Ga4a5] The move recommended by Gajewski, assuming that the [a4]-...[a5] inclusion is favourable for White.} a5 {A novelty in practical play but not in Gajewski's course, who gives that option. As you will probably notice in this chapter, I really recommend not letting white continue with his a-pawn when they start with [a4].} 11. Na3 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga3c4,Gc4b6] Also an interesting option. White wants to put his knight on [c4] right away. Makes sense as the [b6]-pawn was weakened by the [a4]-...[a5] inclusion.} h6 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gf8g6,Gc8e6] Same plan!} 12. Nc4 g5 {[%cal Gf8g6,Gg5g4]} (12... g5 {Now,} 13. Qe2 {is just transposing to our main line.}) 13. d4 $5 {Trying to punish Black's provocative play by opening the centre. Very logical. The position is very rich and unexplored; this position has never been reached in a practical game, for instance. So, it is quite hard to predict how White will react, but this makes sense!} b5 14. Ne3 Ng6 $1 {[%cal Gg6e5] Better not to take on [d4] as White will get too active. Counterattacking the [e5]-pawn is the key!} 15. dxc5 Qxd1 16. Rxd1 b4 $1 {[%cal Gg6e5,Gg7e5] Very important move preventing [axb5] and the subsequent invasion of the [d5]-square with the knight. We will get back the pawn anyway, as [e5] is a nice target.} 17. Nc4 Be6 18. Nb6 Rd8 {[%csl Ge6,Gg7][%cal Gg6e5] Black will regain the pawn and have very nice prospects in the endgame with the bishop pair.} *

