1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. O-O Nf6 {We have nothing better than to develop the knight to [f6]. On the other hand, White revealed his strategy by castling short.} (7... e5 {works less well here due to} 8. a3 $1 {Once our bishop gets blocked by the [e5]-pawn, White can prepare the thematic plan with [b4]. It is important to notice that with the knight still on [b1], this plan is more effective, as any attempt to stop it with, let's say} Qd6 {can be ignored:} 9. b4 {and after} cxb4 10. axb4 {, Black cannot really capture on [b4] due to [Ba3]. With the knight already on [c3], this would be a different story.}) 8. Nc3 Nd7 {We insist on pushing ...[e5].} 9. Be3 e5 $1 10. Nh2 {[%cal Gf2f4] This was Caruana's choice in the World Championship match.} Nf8 {The most precise continuation, ready to meet White's [f4].} 11. f4 exf4 12. Rxf4 Be6 {It might seem like a strange plan to leave the passive knight on [f8] and develop the bishop to [e6] occupying the knight's place, but we actually have another itinerary planned for our knight depending on White's play.} 13. Rf2 h6 {[%cal Gg6g5] A preparation of a future ...[g5].} 14. Nf3 {[%cal Gd3d4] White can try to open the position in the centre now.} Qc7 15. d4 Rd8 16. Rd2 {Now clearly the best choice is to take on [d4].} cxd4 17. Bxd4 {And now we should go for an ugly-looking move.} f6 {The thing is that our dark-squared bishop is an important defender, and to be able to castle, it is better to have the [h6]-pawn well protected.} 18. Bf2 Nd7 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 19. Qe1 {[%cal Gf2g3]} O-O 20. Bg3 Qc8 21. Bd6 Rf7 {[%cal Gd8e8,Gd7f8,Gg6g5] It might visually seem that Black is under pressure here, but the truth is we have a very rich position and enough resources. Our next steps could be ...[Re8]-...[Nf8]-...[g5].} *

