 but this time, it will lead to simplifications.} Bxg5 13. Qxg5 Qxg5 14. Nxg5 f6 15. Nf3 Ne6 {with a pleasant position. Our king remains in the centre and is in no danger after exchanging the queens. We also have a clear plan with ...[g5]-...[h5]-...[h4].}) 12. Ng5 {[%cal Gf2f4] This was tried a couple of times in practice. The idea is [f4].} Ne6 {We have nothing better.} 13. Nxe6 Bxe6 14. f4 exf4 15. Qxf4 Be7 {Here White has a choice. For example:} 16. Bg7 g5 {To make sure the queen does not get to [h6].} 17. Qe5 Rg8 18. Bf6 Bd6 $1 {The simplest, forcing exchanges.} 19. Bxd8 Bxe5 20. Bf6 Bxf6 21. Rxf6 Rg6 22. Rff1 (22. Rxg6 hxg6 {followed by ...[Ke7] is also a very comfortable endgame for Black. We'll get rid of our doubled pawns with ...[g4].}) 22... Ke7 $10 {[%csl Rc3] With a comfortable endgame.} *

