1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. O-O Nf6 {We have nothing better than to develop the knight to [f6]. On the other hand, White revealed his strategy by castling short.} (7... e5 {works less well here due to} 8. a3 $1 {Once our bishop gets blocked by the [e5]-pawn, White can prepare the thematic plan with [b4]. It is important to notice that with the knight still on [b1], this plan is more effective, as any attempt to stop it with, let's say} Qd6 {can be ignored:} 9. b4 {and after} cxb4 10. axb4 {, Black cannot really capture on [b4] due to [Ba3]. With the knight already on [c3], this would be a different story.}) 8. Nc3 Nd7 {We insist on pushing ...[e5].} 9. Be3 e5 $1 10. Qd2 {The most played.} Nf8 $1 {The best, in my opinion. With the closed centre, our king is in no danger, so we have time to improve our light pieces.} 11. Bh6 {The most principled.} Bf6 (11... Bf6 {Here, White has a wide choice. They can insist on exchanging the bishops with} 12. Bg5 {, but this time, it will lead to simplifications.} Bxg5 13. Qxg5 Qxg5 14. Nxg5 f6 15. Nf3 Ne6 {with a pleasant position. Our king remains in the centre and is in no danger after exchanging the queens. We also have a clear plan with ...[g5]-...[h5]-...[h4].}) 12. a4 {We know how to meet this.} a5 13. Ne2 Ne6 14. Nh2 {[%cal Gf2f4] White is obviously hoping to make [f4] work, so our next move is kind of forced.} g5 15. Ng4 Rg8 16. Ng3 {This was actually tried by Caruana in 2023. Here, I suggest a novelty:} Nd4 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gg8g6] Opening up our bishop and creating a threat of ...[Bxg4] and ...[Rg6].} 17. Rae1 {[%cal Ge1e8,Gg3f5]} Bxg4 18. hxg4 Rg6 {Luckily for White, the piece can still be saved by playing as follows.} 19. c3 Ne6 20. Nf5 Qd7 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Ge8c8] We will castle next, and White has no way to liberate that bishop.} *

