 but this time, it will lead to simplifications.} Bxg5 13. Qxg5 Qxg5 14. Nxg5 f6 15. Nf3 Ne6 {with a pleasant position. Our king remains in the centre and is in no danger after exchanging the queens. We also have a clear plan with ...[g5]-...[h5]-...[h4].}) 12. Nh2 {This seems very natural; White wants to increase the pressure on the kingside by pushing [f4].} Ne6 13. f4 {This leads to a forced line.} exf4 14. Bxf4 Nxf4 15. Qxf4 Bd4+ 16. Kh1 O-O 17. Nf3 (17. Ng4 {is not advisable for White as after} Bxg4 18. Qxg4 Be5 {, we get an excellent play on the dark squares.}) 17... Bg7 {It's important to keep this bishop.} 18. e5 {[%cal Gc3e4]} Bf5 {[%cal Gf5e4] The most logical, to be ready for [Ne4].} 19. g4 {Understandable, but this weakens White's king.} Be6 {[%cal Gf7f6]} 20. g5 {An interesting try. White prevents any attempts to go for ...[f6] or ...[f5] and hopes to bring his knight soon. But this is not meant to be!} Bd5 ({Now we control e4 from another side.} 20... Bxh3 {looks a bit over-optimistic to me. After} 21. Rf2 {, White gets an easy plan to attack on the h-file.}) 21. Rae1 {Here everything is good. For example:} Bxf3+ 22. Rxf3 Qe7 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gd8d4] Once again preventing [Ne4] as the [e5]-pawn is hanging.} 23. Rfe3 Rad8 24. b3 ({It may sound tempting to open the e-file, but} 24. e6 {is met by the simple} f6 $1 {and we only open the f-file and enjoy a very nice initiativethanks to it.}) 24... Rd4 25. Qg3 b5 {[%cal Gc5c4] With enough counterplay.} *

