1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. a4 {This is quite rarely played but is, of course, one of the thematic ideas in the Rossolimo, trying to take space on the queenside.} a5 {The best reaction to stop White's expansion.} 8. O-O Nf6 9. Na3 {Heading to [c4] when our pawn is still on [e7] is much less harmful to us.} O-O 10. Bd2 Qc7 11. Nc4 Be6 {[%cal Ge6c4] The simplest.} 12. Ne3 Nh5 {[%cal Gh5f4,Ga8d8] Black equalises comfortably.} *

