1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. a4 {This is quite rarely played but is, of course, one of the thematic ideas in the Rossolimo, trying to take space on the queenside.} a5 {The best reaction to stop White's expansion.} 8. O-O Nf6 9. Be3 Qc7 {[%cal Ge7e5]} ({This way to prepare ...e5 is less accurate than} 9... O-O {. The difference is not easy to spot at first glance.}) 10. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] White goes for his usual plan with [Bh6].} e5 11. Bh6 O-O 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Nc3 {And here, if we try to play in the same spirit as in the 9.O-O line, it works less well.} h6 14. Ne2 {This works for White.} c4 {This is not working well with the rook on [f8] and the queen on [c7].} 15. d4 $1 Nxe4 16. Qe3 {[%cal Gd4e5] With the rook on [e8], we could simply grab on [d4], as we'll see whereas here we need to retreat, and after [dxe5], White will get a serious advantage.} *

