1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. a4 {This is quite rarely played but is, of course, one of the thematic ideas in the Rossolimo, trying to take space on the queenside.} a5 {The best reaction to stop White's expansion.} 8. O-O Nf6 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 e5 {It turns out we don't even need to take any preparatory measures this time to play ...[e5].} 11. Bh6 (11. Nxe5 {gives White nothing as we have} Nxe4 {with an equal position.}) 11... Re8 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 {[%cal Gf6h5]} 13. Nc3 h6 {[%cal Ga8a7,Ga7e7,Gf6h5,Gg6g5,Gh5f4,Gd8f6] Preparing ...[g5] and ...[Nh5]-...[Nf4].} ({We can also start by} 13... Nh5 14. Ne2 {and now} Qf6 15. Kh2 h6 {followed by ...[g5] with good play on the kingside.}) 14. Ne2 {This is less impressive here in comparison to the line shown in the informational.} c4 $1 {This is very strong now.} 15. d4 {This does not work against our setup.} Nxe4 16. Qe3 exd4 {[%csl Ge8] Now we see why it was important to start by ...[Re8] and not ...[Qc7].} *

