1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. a3 {It might seem strange, but some very strong grandmasters have tried it. This is a waiting move, provoking Black to continue with ...[e5] in order to reply with [b4] immediately. But here, we can easily avoid White's little trap by continuing with another well-known plan.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ge7e5]} 8. Nc3 Nd7 9. Be3 e5 10. Qd2 h6 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6] Preventing [Bh6] and planning to continue with ...[Nf8]-...[Ne6] next.} 11. b4 {This has been played by some strong players, but it doesn't work out well for White.} f5 {With the obvious threat of winning the bishop. White will be forced to lose few tempi in order to avoid that.} 12. Qe2 O-O {And it is already not easy for White.} 13. bxc5 f4 {Even the big plan of creating a weakness on [c5] failed.} 14. Bd2 Nxc5 {[%cal Gc5e6] Black is much better.} *

