1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. Nc3 e5 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7] Once the knight has jumped to [c3], we can push ...[e5] without any worries. As mentioned here, with the knight still on [b1], the [a3]-[b4] plan is more effective.} (7... Nf6 {would be met by} 8. Be3 {and we have seen here that there is no time for ...[e5] and ...[b6].}) 8. O-O {White's decision to castle short will allow us to do the same without the risk of getting under attack.} Ne7 9. a3 Qd6 {[%cal Gd6c5]} ({We are not really preventing White from playing b4, but we want to be ready to recapture on c5 with our queen. We can start by} 9... O-O {and after} 10. b4 Qd6 {we reach the same position.}) 10. b4 O-O (10... cxb4 11. axb4 Qxb4 {is bad due to} 12. Na4 {and we are in big trouble there.}) 11. Na4 {[%csl Rc5] This forces us to take.} cxb4 12. axb4 Be6 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg6g5] We can go for our usual plan with ...[h6]-...[g5] here as well.} *

