1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. Nc3 e5 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7] Once the knight has jumped to [c3], we can push ...[e5] without any worries. As mentioned here, with the knight still on [b1], the [a3]-[b4] plan is more effective.} (7... Nf6 {would be met by} 8. Be3 {and we have seen here that there is no time for ...[e5] and ...[b6].}) 8. a3 {It is interesting to compare this line with the one we analysed without the inclusion of [Nc3].} a5 {Stopping [b4] but unfortunately not for a long time.} 9. Be3 Ne7 10. Na4 {[%cal Gb2b4,Re3b6] White continues to organise the [b4]-push.} Rb8 {[%csl Gb6] To make sure the [b6]-pawn is protected once White plays [b4].} 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gb2b4] And our usual response fails.} h6 12. b4 {White can finally go for this.} f5 13. Qc3 {[%csl Rb6,Ra5,Rc5] It starts to be difficult to withstand the pressure on our queenside pawns.} *

