1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Bxc6 {We can call this the main Rossolimo line against the ...[g6] setup. Basically, White's idea when playing [Bb5] is exactly this: to damage Black's pawn structure by taking on [c6].} dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 ({A useful prophylactic move. White is not showing his intentions yet, keeping all the options open, notably with his king, which can castle long later on.} 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes here.}) 6... b6 $5 {A very interesting and rare half-waiting move protecting [c5] in the process. The idea is to wait for White to show his intentions. If White plays [Nc3] right away, then we can play ...[e5] followed by ...[Ne7], and at some point, we will go for [f5] as our [e5]-pawn won't be that vulnerable. If White is going for castle, then we can transpose to the line Magnus Carlsen played in his match vs Caruana in 2018, but White lost the option of castling long. Overall, we are trying to play as Magnus did but avoiding the most dangerous lines.} 7. Nc3 e5 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7] Once the knight has jumped to [c3], we can push ...[e5] without any worries. As mentioned here, with the knight still on [b1], the [a3]-[b4] plan is more effective.} (7... Nf6 {would be met by} 8. Be3 {and we have seen here that there is no time for ...[e5] and ...[b6].}) 8. Be3 Ne7 ({We can also start by} 8... h6 $5 {when} 9. O-O Ne7 {transposes here and 9.Qd2 Ne7 transposes to our main line.}) (8... Nf6 $2 {was played by Magnus himself but is not recommended as after} 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 {White has a refutation:} 10. Qf3 $1 {, and Black's position will start collapsing soon.}) 9. Qd2 ({For} 9. O-O {see here.}) (9. a4 a5 {as usual.} 10. Qe2 h6 {preparing ...[Be6].}) 9... h6 {As usual, we need to avoid [Bh6].} 10. g4 {This is an aggressive way to continue, but here we have a good antidote.} h5 {Asking White some questions about their further intentions.} 11. g5 Be6 {[%cal Ge7d5] We have a funny idea of ...[Nd5] here.} 12. O-O-O O-O {[%cal Ge7d5]} (12... O-O {White successfully closed the kingside and now will have difficult times facing our attack on the queenside. ...Nd5 could come soon with the point} 13. Z0 Nd5 14. exd5 cxd5 {and ...[d4]. This is a recurring idea also seen here.}) *

