1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. Nc3 (4. Nc3 {Another interesting sideline. White gives up on the idea of going for d4 anytime soon and instead wants to harden the development of our knight, as on} Nf6 {, they are ready for} 5. e5 {, and the [Nc3] controls the [d5]-square.}) 4... Bg7 5. O-O {Here, we have several good options, but I like to stick to the same move as in our main line.} e5 {[%cal Gg8e7] Preparing ...[Ne7]. The clear drawback of this pawn push is that we give away the [d5]-square. However, White's bishop is not on the good diagonal yet, and it will take some extra time to regroup White's pieces.} 6. d3 (6. a3 Nge7 7. b4 d6 {is a standard plan for White in this structure, but it should transpose sooner or later to our 6.d3 line as it is hard to imagine White playing without [d3] and [Bc4].}) 6... Nge7 7. Bc4 {Seems more logical to have the bishop on this diagonal after we played ...[e5].} O-O 8. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] As mentioned above, this is a standard way of playing in this structure. White is preparing [b4].} d6 {[%cal Gc8g4]} 9. h3 {To avoid being pinned.} h6 $132 {[%cal Gg8h7,Gf7f5] We also prevent [Bg5] or [Ng5] business and will go for ...[Kh7] next preparing ...[f5].} *

