1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. d3 {This can be played if White wants to avoid any long theoretical battles.} Bg7 5. Nc3 Nd4 $5 {As the knight went to [c3], White lost the possibility of having [c2]-[c3] anytime soon, so we could activate our own knight.} (5... Nd4 {Note that} 6. Nxd4 $2 {is losing on the spot due to} cxd4 7. Ne2 Qa5+ {and the bishop drops.}) 6. O-O {After this, we are happy to take the bishop.} Nxb5 {Usually, in the Rossolimo, White gives this bishop for the knight on [c6] in exchange for a damaged black pawn structure. Here, we get the bishop and keep our pawn chain flexible.} 7. Nxb5 a6 8. Nc3 d6 {[%cal Gg8f6] We need this move before playing ...[Nf6] to avoid the unpleasant [e5].} 9. Be3 Nf6 10. a4 b6 {To stop White's expansion and avoid our pawns being fixed.} 11. Qd2 {A classical way to prepare the bishop exchange, but we do not mind it.} O-O 12. Bh6 e5 {[%cal Gc8e6,Rd3d4] The move we often see in this line, preventing [d4] and preparing ...[Be6].} *

