1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. d3 {This can be played if White wants to avoid any long theoretical battles.} Bg7 5. Nc3 Nd4 $5 {As the knight went to [c3], White lost the possibility of having [c2]-[c3] anytime soon, so we could activate our own knight.} (5... Nd4 {Note that} 6. Nxd4 $2 {is losing on the spot due to} cxd4 7. Ne2 Qa5+ {and the bishop drops.}) 6. Bc4 {The most logical continuation.} e6 {With the bishop on [c4], we should prepare ...[d5] to neutralise it.} 7. Bf4 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gc3b5,Gb5d6] With the idea of playing [Nxd4] and [Nb5]-[Nd6].} a6 {An obvious prophylaxis against [Nb5] ideas and also preparing ...[b5] at a convenient moment.} 8. Nxd4 ({White does not have time for} 8. Bd6 {as after} Qb6 {, they lose material.}) 8... cxd4 9. Ne2 {Here we have a choice; the knight can be developed both to [e7] or [f6], depending on our taste.} Ne7 {I like this.} 10. Bd6 {This should always be checked, but once again, we have the same antidote.} Qb6 {[%csl Gb2,Gd6] Not being afraid of losing castling rights.} 11. Bxe7 Kxe7 {[%cal Gb6c5,Gb7b6,Gc8b7] We get a preferable position for Black. Our king is in no danger on [e7], and we can continue with ...[Qc5], ...[b6] and ...[Bb7].} *

