1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. d3 {This can be played if White wants to avoid any long theoretical battles.} Bg7 5. Nc3 Nd4 $5 {As the knight went to [c3], White lost the possibility of having [c2]-[c3] anytime soon, so we could activate our own knight.} (5... Nd4 {Note that} 6. Nxd4 $2 {is losing on the spot due to} cxd4 7. Ne2 Qa5+ {and the bishop drops.}) 6. Bc4 {The most logical continuation.} e6 {With the bishop on [c4], we should prepare ...[d5] to neutralise it.} 7. Bf4 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gc3b5,Gb5d6] With the idea of playing [Nxd4] and [Nb5]-[Nd6].} a6 {An obvious prophylaxis against [Nb5] ideas and also preparing ...[b5] at a convenient moment.} 8. Nxd4 ({White does not have time for} 8. Bd6 {as after} Qb6 {, they lose material.}) 8... cxd4 9. Ne2 {Here we have a choice; the knight can be developed both to [e7] or [f6], depending on our taste.} Ne7 {I like this.} 10. Qd2 {[%cal Gf4h6] A standard procedure - White wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops.} d5 11. exd5 {Here we even have time for ...[b5].} b5 {A useful intermezzo, as we get the [b7]-square to develop the bishop.} 12. Bb3 Nxd5 13. Bh6 {The best line is a bit strange-looking, but it leads to an interesting play.} Bf6 14. Ng3 Rg8 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gf6e7,Gg7g5]} (14... Rg8 {We accept to leave our king in the centre, but the truth is that White doesn't really have a way to create any threats. ...Bb7, ...Be7 and ...g5 could be played next with an untypical but interesting position to play. Putting the king into safety defenitely looks very human to me, but after} 15. O-O-O Bb7 16. Ne4 Be7 {, the problem for White is that Black's king is very safe in the centre, as there are no pawn breaks and we have a very solid pawn structure. Meanwhile, we have a very clear plan of continuing with ...[a5]-...[a4] and start asking unpleasant questions.}) *

