1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. d3 {This can be played if White wants to avoid any long theoretical battles.} Bg7 5. Nc3 Nd4 $5 {As the knight went to [c3], White lost the possibility of having [c2]-[c3] anytime soon, so we could activate our own knight.} (5... Nd4 {Note that} 6. Nxd4 $2 {is losing on the spot due to} cxd4 7. Ne2 Qa5+ {and the bishop drops.}) 6. Bc4 {The most logical continuation.} e6 {With the bishop on [c4], we should prepare ...[d5] to neutralise it.} 7. Bf4 {[%cal Gf3d4] With the idea of playing [Nxd4] and [Nb5]-[Nd6].} d6 {A good alternative.} 8. Nxd4 {White can double our pawns, but it's not a problem as we will be able to organise ...[d5] at some point.} ({After} 8. O-O Ne7 {, White has to make a decision. Either taking} 9. Nxd4 {, which will most likely transpose to 8.Nxd4, or ignore the knight and allow us to go ...[Nec6] next when we will be able to recapture with the knight on [d4]. In any case, the position remains balanced.}) 8... cxd4 9. Ne2 (9. Nb5 {does not achieve anything as we can simply play} e5 {with already better chances as White's knight is misplaced.}) 9... Ne7 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 10. O-O {And here we have a choice, but it won't change the character of the position as at some point we will need to play.} d5 11. Bb3 O-O {[%cal Ga7a5,Ge6e5] With equal chances. Our next moves could be ...[a5] and ...[e5] opening up the light-squared bishop.} *

