1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. d3 {This can be played if White wants to avoid any long theoretical battles.} Bg7 5. Nc3 Nd4 $5 {As the knight went to [c3], White lost the possibility of having [c2]-[c3] anytime soon, so we could activate our own knight.} (5... Nd4 {Note that} 6. Nxd4 $2 {is losing on the spot due to} cxd4 7. Ne2 Qa5+ {and the bishop drops.}) 6. Bc4 {The most logical continuation.} e6 {With the bishop on [c4], we should prepare ...[d5] to neutralise it.} 7. Bf4 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gc3b5,Gb5d6] With the idea of playing [Nxd4] and [Nb5]-[Nd6].} d6 {A good alternative.} 8. a4 {Giving the bishop a retreat square and preventing ...[b5] for now.} a6 {[%csl Gb5] This is always a useful move in this lin,e as we prevent [Nb5] and still might go for ...[b5] later on.} 9. O-O Nf6 (9... Ne7 {is also perfectly playable. In general, I recommend ...[Ne7] setups in this line, but just to demonstrate that ...[Nf6] is also completely fine.}) 10. Be3 {White wants to get rid of the unpleasant knight.} Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 Bd7 {The advantage of having the knight on [f6] is that we can use the [c6]-square for our bishop.} 12. e5 {This might be tried, and it leads to an interesting position.} Bc6 13. exf6 Bxf3 14. fxg7 Rg8 15. gxf3 Rxg7 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Ge8f8,Gd8h4] We get a queen and a pawn for three pieces. Moreover, White's king is weakened, and with all our pawns still on the board, White's light pieces lack space and good squares.} *

