1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. d3 {This can be played if White wants to avoid any long theoretical battles.} Bg7 5. Nc3 Nd4 $5 {As the knight went to [c3], White lost the possibility of having [c2]-[c3] anytime soon, so we could activate our own knight.} (5... Nd4 {Note that} 6. Nxd4 $2 {is losing on the spot due to} cxd4 7. Ne2 Qa5+ {and the bishop drops.}) 6. Bc4 {The most logical continuation.} e6 {With the bishop on [c4], we should prepare ...[d5] to neutralise it.} 7. Bb3 {This has never been tried and indeed looks a bit strange, but it actually bears an interesting idea in mind. White is waiting for our next move.} Ne7 {The most logical, and here comes White's point.} 8. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Once the knight goes to [e7], White can try to push the h-pawn as it is well known nowadays that this pawn advance works often well.} h6 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gg6g5] Not the only way but probably the easiest. On [h5], we are ready for ...[g5].} 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Ne2 {And now comes the traditional central push.} d5 11. h5 g5 12. f4 {Quite an original approach by White, but here everything is good for us; for example:} a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Forcing White's next.} 13. a4 Nc6 {[%cal Gd8g5] Defending [g5].} 14. fxg5 hxg5 15. h6 Be5 {With a very strange-looking position, but it seems to me that only Black can be better here.} *

