1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. d3 {This can be played if White wants to avoid any long theoretical battles.} Bg7 5. Nc3 Nd4 $5 {As the knight went to [c3], White lost the possibility of having [c2]-[c3] anytime soon, so we could activate our own knight.} (5... Nd4 {Note that} 6. Nxd4 $2 {is losing on the spot due to} cxd4 7. Ne2 Qa5+ {and the bishop drops.}) 6. Bc4 {The most logical continuation.} e6 {With the bishop on [c4], we should prepare ...[d5] to neutralise it.} 7. O-O Ne7 ({Here, this is more logical than} 7... Nf6 {as we do not block our bishop, which defends [d4].}) 8. Bf4 a6 {We react the same way as against Bf4 before castling. White has plenty of options:} 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Ne2 d5 {As usual, striking the centre.} 11. Bb3 O-O 12. Qd2 a5 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ga8a6] This is often played when we want to completely block White's bishop and give our rook the [a6]-square, which can be exploited one day.} 13. a4 e5 {A good way to play for a win.} 14. Bg5 f6 15. Bh6 g5 {Giving our knight the [g6]-square.} 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Ng3 Ra6 {And here we go! Now we see why ...[a5] was a good idea.} 18. Nh5+ {This leads nowhere.} Kg6 19. Qe2 Rb6 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gd4d3] Creating a nasty threat of ...[dxe4] and ...[d3]. The position is a mess, but we have good chances to play for a win here.} *

