1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. c3 ({Rarely played compared to more popular} 4. O-O {or 4.Bxc6 , but it is a decent option, and we need to know how to react. White wants to comfortably take the centre by playing [d4] next. However, this move has a certain drawback: the pawn on [e4] can no longer be protected by [Nc3] and as White did not castle yet, [Re1] is not available either, so we should immediately hit the pawn.}) 4... Nf6 {Asking White to decide between protecting the pawn or pushing it. Both approaches are equally popular.} 5. e5 ({This is usually White's idea once the knight comes to f6 and is equally popular to the} 5. Qe2 {line.}) (5. d4 {is a third possibility, but we will most likely transpose to 5.e5.} Nxe4 {might be dangerous in practice as we need to be precise not to get into trouble.} 6. d5 {is White's idea. Our knight doesn't have many squares.} Nd6 7. Bd3 Na5 8. Bf4 {and White gets enough play for a pawn as our knights are too awkwardly placed.Better is 5...cxd4 and here, White has nothing better than 6.e5 Nd5 transposing to 5.e5. 6.cxd4 is a bad idea due to 6...Qa5+ 7.Nc3 Nxe4 ∓ , and compared to the immediate 5...Nxe4 line, White has a problem with his bishop, allowing us to win time.}) 5... Nd5 6. d4 cxd4 7. O-O Nc7 {Our knight is a bit shaky on [d5], so it's logical to bring it to a safe square and win time by attacking the bishop.} 8. Bxc6 {This only helps us develop, and we are not even getting our pawns doubled.} dxc6 9. cxd4 Bg7 10. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4] To avoid ...[Bg4].} O-O 11. Nc3 Be6 {[%csl Ge6,Gg7,Rd4][%cal Gd8d7] We have two bishops and a clear plan in mind: doubling on the d-file and putting pressure on White's weakness on [d4].} *

