1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. c3 ({Rarely played compared to more popular} 4. O-O {or 4.Bxc6 , but it is a decent option, and we need to know how to react. White wants to comfortably take the centre by playing [d4] next. However, this move has a certain drawback: the pawn on [e4] can no longer be protected by [Nc3] and as White did not castle yet, [Re1] is not available either, so we should immediately hit the pawn.}) 4... Nf6 {Asking White to decide between protecting the pawn or pushing it. Both approaches are equally popular.} 5. e5 ({This is usually White's idea once the knight comes to f6 and is equally popular to the} 5. Qe2 {line.}) (5. d4 {is a third possibility, but we will most likely transpose to 5.e5.} Nxe4 {might be dangerous in practice as we need to be precise not to get into trouble.} 6. d5 {is White's idea. Our knight doesn't have many squares.} Nd6 7. Bd3 Na5 8. Bf4 {and White gets enough play for a pawn as our knights are too awkwardly placed.Better is 5...cxd4 and here, White has nothing better than 6.e5 Nd5 transposing to 5.e5. 6.cxd4 is a bad idea due to 6...Qa5+ 7.Nc3 Nxe4 ∓ , and compared to the immediate 5...Nxe4 line, White has a problem with his bishop, allowing us to win time.}) 5... Nd5 6. O-O Bg7 7. d4 Nc7 8. Bxc6 {A dangerous try to win a pawn.} dxc6 9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bg4 {So, White won the desirable pawn, but they are behind in development, and the [e5] and [c5]-pawns are quite vulnerable.} 11. Re1 {An attempt to keep the pawn up, but also a dangerous decision.} Bxf3 {First, we damage White's pawn structure on the kingside.} 12. gxf3 Ne6 {[%cal Ge6c5] Forcing White to weaken the queenside.} 13. b4 {And now, a simple move.} O-O-O {[%csl Rc3,Re5,Rf2,Rf3][%cal Gd8d5,Gh8d8] White's position is simply collapsing: ...[Rd5] and ...[Rhd8] are coming whereas White still needs to develop.} *

