1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. c3 ({Rarely played compared to more popular} 4. O-O {or 4.Bxc6 , but it is a decent option, and we need to know how to react. White wants to comfortably take the centre by playing [d4] next. However, this move has a certain drawback: the pawn on [e4] can no longer be protected by [Nc3] and as White did not castle yet, [Re1] is not available either, so we should immediately hit the pawn.}) 4... Nf6 {Asking White to decide between protecting the pawn or pushing it. Both approaches are equally popular.} 5. e5 ({This is usually White's idea once the knight comes to f6 and is equally popular to the} 5. Qe2 {line.}) (5. d4 {is a third possibility, but we will most likely transpose to 5.e5.} Nxe4 {might be dangerous in practice as we need to be precise not to get into trouble.} 6. d5 {is White's idea. Our knight doesn't have many squares.} Nd6 7. Bd3 Na5 8. Bf4 {and White gets enough play for a pawn as our knights are too awkwardly placed.Better is 5...cxd4 and here, White has nothing better than 6.e5 Nd5 transposing to 5.e5. 6.cxd4 is a bad idea due to 6...Qa5+ 7.Nc3 Nxe4 ∓ , and compared to the immediate 5...Nxe4 line, White has a problem with his bishop, allowing us to win time.}) 5... Nd5 6. O-O Bg7 7. d4 Nc7 8. Ba4 cxd4 9. cxd4 O-O ({Another way of playing if we don't want to push ...b5. The ideas remain the same, though.} 9... b5 10. Bb3 {is just a transposition if we prefer.}) 10. Nc3 d6 {This is an important move as we need to challenge White's strong centre and also to finish development.} 11. exd6 Qxd6 {[%csl Rd4] Now we get a target.} 12. d5 Na5 13. Re1 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gc1g5] Of course, White needs to put pressure on the [e7]-pawn.} Rd8 14. Bg5 {And here we should simplify going to an equal endgame.} Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Rxe7 Qxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 18. Bxd1 Be6 {[%csl Ga2]} 19. b4 {White will win a pawn but not for a long time.} Nc4 20. Rxb7 Nd6 $10 {[%cal Ge6a2] And we will take on [a2] next.} *

