1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. c3 ({Rarely played compared to more popular} 4. O-O {or 4.Bxc6 , but it is a decent option, and we need to know how to react. White wants to comfortably take the centre by playing [d4] next. However, this move has a certain drawback: the pawn on [e4] can no longer be protected by [Nc3] and as White did not castle yet, [Re1] is not available either, so we should immediately hit the pawn.}) 4... Nf6 {Asking White to decide between protecting the pawn or pushing it. Both approaches are equally popular.} 5. Qe2 {Here I suggest a very rare but interesting option.} e5 $5 {The idea is, first of all, to prevent any [e5] and [d4] business, and to achieve this, we are even ready to go for a pawn sacrifice.} 6. O-O {Mostly played when White wants to accept the challenge and take the pawn.} Bg7 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. Nxe5 Nh5 {We offered a central pawn, so now it is important to play energetically. White's problem is that the knight does not have a comfortable retreat square.} 9. Nd3 {This gives us an easy game.} c4 10. Ne1 Nf4 11. Qe3 (11. Qxc4 {is losing a piece after} Be6 {.}) 11... g5 {[%csl Rb1,Rc1,Ra1][%cal Gc8e6] We are a pawn down, but our initiative is tremendous. ...[Be6] will follow next, and then we can consider ...[O-O] and ...[b5]. White still needs to solve numerous problems in this position.} *

