1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. c3 ({Rarely played compared to more popular} 4. O-O {or 4.Bxc6 , but it is a decent option, and we need to know how to react. White wants to comfortably take the centre by playing [d4] next. However, this move has a certain drawback: the pawn on [e4] can no longer be protected by [Nc3] and as White did not castle yet, [Re1] is not available either, so we should immediately hit the pawn.}) 4... Nf6 {Asking White to decide between protecting the pawn or pushing it. Both approaches are equally popular.} 5. Qe2 {Here I suggest a very rare but interesting option.} e5 $5 {The idea is, first of all, to prevent any [e5] and [d4] business, and to achieve this, we are even ready to go for a pawn sacrifice.} 6. O-O {Mostly played when White wants to accept the challenge and take the pawn.} Bg7 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. Nxe5 Nh5 {We offered a central pawn, so now it is important to play energetically. White's problem is that the knight does not have a comfortable retreat square.} 9. Nf3 {White can try to stick to a pawn, but life will not be easy at all.} Nf4 {[%cal Gf4d3]} 10. Qe3 {The only move.} Bh6 {We don't count the pawns in this line!} 11. Qxc5 Bg4 {White is already in a very dangerous situation and needs to be precise not to get into big trouble.} 12. Qe5+ {It is tempting to go for a queen exchange as the poor white queen cannot find a comfortable square.} Kd7 13. Qd4+ Kc7 14. Qxd8+ Raxd8 $36 {[%csl Rb1,Ra1,Rc1][%cal Gf4d3] But even after exchanging queens, White is struggling due to lack of development, and there is a big hole on [d3] where our knight will land shortly.} (14... Raxd8 {Note that the liberating} 15. d4 $4 {is not possible due to} Ne2+ {and ...[Nxc1].}) *

