1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. c3 ({Rarely played compared to more popular} 4. O-O {or 4.Bxc6 , but it is a decent option, and we need to know how to react. White wants to comfortably take the centre by playing [d4] next. However, this move has a certain drawback: the pawn on [e4] can no longer be protected by [Nc3] and as White did not castle yet, [Re1] is not available either, so we should immediately hit the pawn.}) 4... Nf6 {Asking White to decide between protecting the pawn or pushing it. Both approaches are equally popular.} 5. Qe2 {Here I suggest a very rare but interesting option.} e5 $5 {The idea is, first of all, to prevent any [e5] and [d4] business, and to achieve this, we are even ready to go for a pawn sacrifice.} 6. d4 {White is not only refusing our pawn sacrifice but is offering a pawn instead! The idea is to remove our [e5]-pawn and be able to push [e4]-[e5].} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 {Challenge accepted!} 8. e5 Nd5 9. O-O (9. Bc4 {White is not really threatening to win a piece, so we can continue to develop.} Bg7 {and now} 10. O-O Nde7 {transposes to our main line, while after 10.Bxd5 Qa5 , Black is much better.}) 9... Bg7 10. Bc4 Nde7 {[%cal Ge7f5] The best square to retreat as our knight can jump to [f5] later.} 11. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4e5,Gb1d2] This setup makes a lot of sense. White is developing the bishop, protecting the central pawn and preparing [Nd2].} O-O 12. Nbd2 Nf5 13. g4 {A critical try.} Nh4 $1 {We are a pawn up, so we don't mind exchanging some pieces!} 14. Nxh4 Qxh4 {This leads to some crazy lines.} 15. Bg3 d3 ({A nice intermezzo forcing the bishop to leave the most active square.} 15... Qh3 16. f3 d3 {is also possible. 16...Nxe5 , however, trying to make the same idea work without including ...[d3], would be severely punished by 17.Bxe5 Re8 18.Bxf7+! . Now we see why it was crucial to include ...[d3]. 18...Kxf7 19.Qc4+ and White is taking over.}) 16. Bxd3 Qh3 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gc8g4] Our idea is simple: we want to play ...[d6] next and attack the [g4]-pawn.} 17. f3 {A natural reaction to reinforce the [g4]-pawn. Now we have a bunch of interesting moves, but I like the direct approach.} Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Re8 {[%csl Re5] Black gets a serious advantage as the bishop will be lost soon.} *

