1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. c3 ({Rarely played compared to more popular} 4. O-O {or 4.Bxc6 , but it is a decent option, and we need to know how to react. White wants to comfortably take the centre by playing [d4] next. However, this move has a certain drawback: the pawn on [e4] can no longer be protected by [Nc3] and as White did not castle yet, [Re1] is not available either, so we should immediately hit the pawn.}) 4... Nf6 {Asking White to decide between protecting the pawn or pushing it. Both approaches are equally popular.} 5. Qe2 {Here I suggest a very rare but interesting option.} e5 $5 {The idea is, first of all, to prevent any [e5] and [d4] business, and to achieve this, we are even ready to go for a pawn sacrifice.} 6. d4 {White is not only refusing our pawn sacrifice but is offering a pawn instead! The idea is to remove our [e5]-pawn and be able to push [e4]-[e5].} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 {Challenge accepted!} 8. e5 Nd5 9. O-O (9. Bc4 {White is not really threatening to win a piece, so we can continue to develop.} Bg7 {and now} 10. O-O Nde7 {transposes to our main line, while after 10.Bxd5 Qa5 , Black is much better.}) 9... Bg7 10. Bc4 Nde7 {[%cal Ge7f5] The best square to retreat as our knight can jump to [f5] later.} 11. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4e5,Gb1d2] This setup makes a lot of sense. White is developing the bishop, protecting the central pawn and preparing [Nd2].} O-O 12. Nbd2 Nf5 13. g4 {A critical try.} Nh4 $1 {We are a pawn up, so we don't mind exchanging some pieces!} 14. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4] White needs to protect [g4] as otherwise, ...[d5] might come as a bad surprise.} Nxf3+ 15. Nxf3 d6 {We need this move sooner or later to open up our bishop.} 16. exd6 {And now we have a nice shot.} h5 {White weakened his king, and we want to take advantage of it.} 17. gxh5 Qf6 {[%csl Gf4,Gg6]} ({An important move to start with, both attacking the bishop and defending the pawn. The immediate} 17... Bxh3 {would run into} 18. hxg6 {and [Ng5] might come next.}) 18. Bg3 (18. Bg5 Qxd6 {remains complicated for both.}) 18... Bxh3 {Since our [g6]-pawn is protected, we can go for this.} 19. hxg6 Qxg6 20. Rfe1 Bf6 {[%cal Gg8g7,Gf8h8] With a simple but effective plan: ...[Kg7] and ...[Rh8] to increase pressure on the white monarch. The position remains double-edged.} *

