1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. c3 ({Rarely played compared to more popular} 4. O-O {or 4.Bxc6 , but it is a decent option, and we need to know how to react. White wants to comfortably take the centre by playing [d4] next. However, this move has a certain drawback: the pawn on [e4] can no longer be protected by [Nc3] and as White did not castle yet, [Re1] is not available either, so we should immediately hit the pawn.}) 4... Nf6 {Asking White to decide between protecting the pawn or pushing it. Both approaches are equally popular.} 5. Qe2 {Here I suggest a very rare but interesting option.} e5 $5 {The idea is, first of all, to prevent any [e5] and [d4] business, and to achieve this, we are even ready to go for a pawn sacrifice.} 6. d4 {White is not only refusing our pawn sacrifice but is offering a pawn instead! The idea is to remove our [e5]-pawn and be able to push [e4]-[e5].} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 {Challenge accepted!} 8. e5 Nd5 9. O-O (9. Bc4 {White is not really threatening to win a piece, so we can continue to develop.} Bg7 {and now} 10. O-O Nde7 {transposes to our main line, while after 10.Bxd5 Qa5 , Black is much better.}) 9... Bg7 10. Bc4 Nde7 {[%cal Ge7f5] The best square to retreat as our knight can jump to [f5] later.} 11. Bg5 {Strangely enough, this natural-looking move is already a serious inaccuracy.} O-O 12. Re1 h6 $1 {[%csl Rg5] And it is not clear where to put the bishop now as every retreat has a certain drawback.} 13. Bf6 ({For example,} 13. Bf4 {is met by} g5 14. Bg3 Nf5 {and White is in big trouble already, not having any compensation for a sacrificed pawn.}) 13... d6 {We will exchange our doubled pawns against the annoying [e5]-pawn and will be able to develop our bishop soon. White does not have compensation for the lost material.} *

