1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. c3 ({Rarely played compared to more popular} 4. O-O {or 4.Bxc6 , but it is a decent option, and we need to know how to react. White wants to comfortably take the centre by playing [d4] next. However, this move has a certain drawback: the pawn on [e4] can no longer be protected by [Nc3] and as White did not castle yet, [Re1] is not available either, so we should immediately hit the pawn.}) 4... Nf6 {Asking White to decide between protecting the pawn or pushing it. Both approaches are equally popular.} 5. Qe2 {Here I suggest a very rare but interesting option.} e5 $5 {The idea is, first of all, to prevent any [e5] and [d4] business, and to achieve this, we are even ready to go for a pawn sacrifice.} 6. d4 {White is not only refusing our pawn sacrifice but is offering a pawn instead! The idea is to remove our [e5]-pawn and be able to push [e4]-[e5].} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 {Challenge accepted!} 8. e5 Nd5 9. O-O (9. Bc4 {White is not really threatening to win a piece, so we can continue to develop.} Bg7 {and now} 10. O-O Nde7 {transposes to our main line, while after 10.Bxd5 Qa5 , Black is much better.}) 9... Bg7 10. Bc4 Nde7 {[%cal Ge7f5] The best square to retreat as our knight can jump to [f5] later.} 11. Na3 {Dreaming of getting to [d6] via [b5].} a6 $1 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gb7b5] Simple prophylaxis to restrict White's knight but also to prepare the future ...[b5].} (11... d5 {is a move on our agenda, but I find it premature here as White has the unpleasant [Nb5] jump:} 12. exd6 Qxd6 13. Nb5 Qd8 14. Bg5 {↑ with initiative.}) 12. Bb3 {White responds in the same prophylactic manner, moving away the bishop from the ...[d5] and ...[b5] threats.} d5 {Now we are ready!} 13. exd6 Qxd6 {Compared to the note to Black's 11th move, White's knight is not able to jump to [b5] and attack the queen and the [d4]-pawn} 14. Nc4 {Another way to get the knight into play, but now the light-squared bishop is blocked, and the [d4]-pawn is not under attack.} Qc7 ({The most natural square, controlling e5.} 14... Qd8 $5 {is also playable, but it allows an extra line:} 15. Nce5 {Here, some precision is needed. For example,} O-O {would be a huge mistake due to} 16. Nxf7 Rxf7 17. Ng5 {and White is winning.It is important to distract the knight as otherwise, the pressure on f7 is too unpleasant. 15...d3 16.Nxd3 O-O 17.Nde5 Now we are just in time to release the tension with 17...Nxe5 18.Nxe5 Nc6 19.Nxc6 bxc6 20.Be3 a5 White has a better pawn structure, but we will have enough counterplay, for example, with ...[Qf6] attacking [b2]. Our light-squared bishop will be nicely placed on [a6], offering a balanced position.}) 15. Ng5 {White does not have [Ne5], so they can try to put pressure from another side.} O-O 16. Qf3 {Now we have a pleasant choice.} Nf5 {This is my suggestion.} 17. g4 {This should be always checked once the knight goes to [f5]. Here, the best is to counterattack.} h6 {This leads to a strange structure.} 18. gxf5 hxg5 19. fxg6 {Our next move is important.} Be6 {[%csl Ge6] It is absolutely necessary to take care of the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 20. Bxg5 fxg6 {In the computer world, this position is just 0.00, but I believe that for human beings, it offers a rich and interesting game to play with mutual chances} *

