play, but now the light-squared bishop is blocked, and the [d4]-pawn is not under attack.} Qc7 ({The most natural square, controlling e5.} 14... Qd8 $5 {is also playable, but it allows an extra line:} 15. Nce5 {Here, some precision is needed. For example,} O-O {would be a huge mistake due to} 16. Nxf7 Rxf7 17. Ng5 {and White is winning.It is important to distract the knight as otherwise, the pressure on f7 is too unpleasant. 15...d3 16.Nxd3 O-O 17.Nde5 Now we are just in time to release the tension with 17...Nxe5 18.Nxe5 Nc6 19.Nxc6 bxc6 20.Be3 a5 White has a better pawn structure, but we will have enough counterplay, for example, with ...[Qf6] attacking [b2]. Our light-squared bishop will be nicely placed on [a6], offering a balanced position.}) 15. Ng5 {White does not have [Ne5], so they can try to put pressure from another side.} O-O 16. Qf3 {Now we have a pleasant choice.} Nf5 {This is my suggestion.} 17. Bf4 (17. Re1 {is very natural, and should be met by} d3 {just as in our main line. After} 18. Qxd3 {, we get a dream position.} Nfd4 {is just one of the ways to continue. White's position is collapsing slowly but surely. 18.Bf4 is the only way for White not to be worse, and now 18...Qd8 transposes to the main line.}) 17... Qd8 18. Rfe1 d3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc6d4] Liberating the [d4]-square for one of our knights and opening up the diagonal for our bishop.} 19. Nxf7 $5 {An interesting try leading to a forced line.} Rxf7 20. Nd6 Nxd6 21. Bxd6 {[%csl Rf7]} Bf5 22. Bxf7+ Kxf7 23. Qd5+ Kf6 {Until here, everything was forced, and now it seems that White has a bunch of options, but it turns out that only one move allows him to keep the balance.} 24. Rac1 {[%cal Gc1c6] Now we also have only one move to stay in the game, but it's a logical one.} Bf8 {[%cal Gf6g7] We vacate the [g7]-square for the king and want to exchange some pieces.} 25. Rxc6 {Removing the defender of the [e5]-square is a necessity.} bxc6 26. Be5+ Kg5 {And here White does not have a way to create dreadful threats on our king, but of course, we need to be extremely careful.} 27. Qf3 d2 {Forcing the rook to go into passive position.} 28. Rd1 Qe7 {It is important to keep the queen on this diagonal to avoid any [h4] & [Bf6] threats.} 29. Qf4+ Kh5 30. h3 {And now it's time to give back some material.} Bxh3 31. gxh3 Qg5+ (31... Qg5+ {Finally, we manage to exchange queens and get into equal endgame after} 32. Qxg5+ Kxg5 33. Rxd2 Kf5 {.}) *

