1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Rossolimo is the main weapon nowadays to avoid the Sveshnikov variation.} g6 4. c3 ({Rarely played compared to more popular} 4. O-O {or 4.Bxc6 , but it is a decent option, and we need to know how to react. White wants to comfortably take the centre by playing [d4] next. However, this move has a certain drawback: the pawn on [e4] can no longer be protected by [Nc3] and as White did not castle yet, [Re1] is not available either, so we should immediately hit the pawn.}) 4... Nf6 {Asking White to decide between protecting the pawn or pushing it. Both approaches are equally popular.} 5. Qe2 {Here I suggest a very rare but interesting option.} e5 $5 {The idea is, first of all, to prevent any [e5] and [d4] business, and to achieve this, we are even ready to go for a pawn sacrifice.} 6. d4 {White is not only refusing our pawn sacrifice but is offering a pawn instead! The idea is to remove our [e5]-pawn and be able to push [e4]-[e5].} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 {Challenge accepted!} 8. e5 Nd5 9. O-O (9. Bc4 {White is not really threatening to win a piece, so we can continue to develop.} Bg7 {and now} 10. O-O Nde7 {transposes to our main line, while after 10.Bxd5 Qa5 , Black is much better.}) 9... Bg7 10. Bc4 Nde7 {[%cal Ge7f5] The best square to retreat as our knight can jump to [f5] later.} 11. Na3 {[%cal Ga3b5,Gb5d6] Dreaming of getting to [d6] via [b5].} a6 $1 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gb7b5] Simple prophylaxis to restrict White's knight but also to prepare the future ...[b5].} (11... d5 {is a move on our agenda, but I find it premature here as White has the unpleasant [Nb5] jump:} 12. exd6 Qxd6 13. Nb5 Qd8 14. Bg5 {↑ with initiative.}) 12. Bb3 {White responds in the same prophylactic manner, moving away the bishop from the ...[d5] and ...[b5] threats.} d5 {Now we are ready!} 13. exd6 Qxd6 {Compared to the note to Black's 11th move, White's knight is not able to jump to [b5] and attack the queen and the [d4]-pawn} 14. Nc4 {Another way to get the knight into play, but now the light-squared bishop is blocked, and the [d4]-pawn is not under attack.} Qc7 ({The most natural square, controlling e5.} 14... Qd8 $5 {is also playable, but it allows an extra line:} 15. Nce5 {Here, some precision is needed. For example,} O-O {would be a huge mistake due to} 16. Nxf7 Rxf7 17. Ng5 {and White is winning.It is important to distract the knight as otherwise, the pressure on f7 is too unpleasant. 15...d3 16.Nxd3 O-O 17.Nde5 Now we are just in time to release the tension with 17...Nxe5 18.Nxe5 Nc6 19.Nxc6 bxc6 20.Be3 a5 White has a better pawn structure, but we will have enough counterplay, for example, with ...[Qf6] attacking [b2]. Our light-squared bishop will be nicely placed on [a6], offering a balanced position.}) 15. Ng5 {White does not have [Ne5], so they can try to put pressure from another side.} O-O 16. Qf3 {Now we have a pleasant choice.} Nf5 {This is my suggestion.} 17. Bf4 (17. Re1 {is very natural, and should be met by} d3 {just as in our main line. After} 18. Qxd3 {, we get a dream position.} Nfd4 {is just one of the ways to continue. White's position is collapsing slowly but surely. 18.Bf4 is the only way for White not to be worse, and now 18...Qd8 transposes to the main line.}) 17... Qd8 18. Rfe1 d3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc6d4] Liberating the [d4]-square for one of our knights and opening up the diagonal for our bishop.} 19. Rad1 {A very human way to increase the pressure on the pawn.} Nfd4 20. Qxd3 Bg4 {We comfortably finish our development.} 21. Rd2 h6 {Now it's time to get rid of the active white knight.} 22. Ne4 Be6 {The position is very interesting with all the pieces still on the board. I believe that Black does not have a single problem here and can fight for a win.} *

