1. e4 c5 2. c3 {A tricky system which, from White’s perspective, has the upside of sidestepping all the sharpest Sicilians Sveshnikov, Najdorf, Richter-Rauzer and to dictate the playing area from the very beginning.} (2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {simply doesn't make any difference and will transpose into 2.c3 after} Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 {. This is the move order I've used for the main lines.}) (2. d4 {The Morra gambit is also an option, and now I give you a pleasant choice between transposing into our line vs the Alapin or accepting the dubious gambit.} cxd4 3. c3 dxc3 {(( 3...Nf6 4.e5 Nd5 5.cxd4 is one of the numerous move order which transposes to our line vs the Alapin.))} 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Bc4 {By far, the main move. White has given up a central pawn in order to speed up the development. As Sasha Grischuk once told me, 'It is very rare to have enough compensation for a central pawn'.} a6 {An important prophylactic move preventing all kinds of jumps via [b5].} 7. O-O b5 {That's obviously not the only way to fight, but I thought that was a good and simple solution.} 8. Bd3 Nge7 {with a nice control of the central squares, or 8.Bb3 Na5 harassing the light-squared bishop and preparing ...[Bb7]. Black is more than fine.}) 2... Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 (4. d4 {This is another way leading to Rome!} cxd4 5. cxd4 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes.}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {Here is the first real choice for White. They have to decide if they want to start with} 5. d4 {or 5.Bc4 . As always, we are ready for all the move orders.}) 5. Bc4 {Not the most played, but definitely the most challenging, and covered in this chapter.} (5. d4 cxd4 {and here:A} 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 dxe5 $1 {An important finesse which allows us to have a very decent choice on the next move.} 8. dxe5 Ndb4 {That's the most solid, offering an endgame where it seems to me that White has to be more careful than Black in order to keep the balance. 8...Be6!? That's a more aggressive approach, which I offer as an alternative and would advise against a weaker opponent. 9.O-O g6 Black is simply trying to collect the [e5]-pawn, but things are not that simple. 10.Ng5 Bg7 11.Nxe6 fxe6 A weird and very concrete position which is fully playable for Black.B 6.Bc4 It is also possible to mix [d4] and [Bc4], an independent and very decent line. 6...Nb6 7.Bb3 d5 Closing the always dangerous [a2]-[g8] diagonal. 8.exd6 Qxd6 9.O-O Be6! Black has nothing to worry about if they study their lines.}) 5... Nb6 6. Bb3 c4 $1 {Kicking the bishop out of the dangerous diagonal.} 7. Bc2 d6 {[%csl Re5] Undermining White's centre as they can't keep their pawn on [e5]. Black's play makes perfect sense.} 8. exd6 Qxd6 {I must admit that I was very much impressed by the game Jones-Anand in Wijk 2018. Vishy showed excellent preparation and excellent play, and he completely outplayed Gawain, who is a great Alapin expert. I started checking the line, and the verdict was clear: sound and giving Black excellent chances to seize the initiative.} 9. O-O Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5] Pinning and, as we can see, Black has more space and better development. Things are not simple, though.} 10. h3 Bh5 11. Re1 O-O-O $1 {White has many different options, but overall, I would already definitely pick Black.} (11... Ne5 $6 {is a line we should avoid. It gives White a much simpler play.} 12. Rxe5 Bxf3 13. Qe1 $1) 12. Be4 (12. b3 Qf6 {and the pin becomes pretty annoying for White.}) 12... e6 {[%cal Gf7f5] That's Vishy's point, kicking out White's bishop and expanding on the centre.} 13. b3 f5 14. Bc2 g6 $1 {[%cal Gg6f5,Ge6e5] A very nice move protecting the [f5]-pawn and therefore preparing the ...[e5] push.} *

