{This is clearly the game which made me choose the recommended set-up in the course in order to face the Alapin. That’s just the kind of game we would all love to play: great and deep opening prep followed by a brilliant technique to score the full point.} 1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 {Gawain is going for the sharp Alapin.} c4 7. Bc2 d6 8. exd6 Qxd6 9. O-O Bg4 10. h3 {That's generally the sign that White knows what he is doing.} (10. Re1 Ne5 {is very simple for Black right away, as I show in the theory section.}) 10... Bh5 11. Re1 O-O-O 12. Be4 e6 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 13. b3 f5 14. Bc2 g6 {[%cal Gg6f5,Ge6e5] I was very impressed by this concept, which is hardly seen. Black is protecting [f5] in order to be able to push [e5].} 15. bxc4 e5 {Gawain is facing a tough challenge, and he is choosing the most active response, which actually fits his dynamic style. Unfortunately, it simply doesn't work.} 16. d4 $2 (16. d3 {is the best move.} e4 $1 {see our repertoire.}) 16... exd4 17. Bg5 Bg7 $1 {[%cal Gg7a1] A fantastic exchange sac. Black has full control of the dark squares after this and is already winning!} 18. Bxd8 Rxd8 19. Qd3 Qf4 {[%cal Gd4c3,Gg7a1]} 20. Qd2 {A sad necessity for White as the endgame is hopeless for him. I really like how Vishy converts this; he just doesn't give any counterplay chances.} Qxd2 21. Nbxd2 dxc3 22. Nb3 Bxf3 23. gxf3 Nb4 24. Re2 Nxc4 {[%csl Gb4,Gc3,Gc4,Gg7] It is pretty obvious that Black is doing extremely well with two pawns for the exchange, active knights, a powerful dark-squared bishop, and a passer on [c3].} 25. Rc1 b5 26. Na1 {[%cal Ga1c2] Not cute, but the knight was not doing much on [b3]. It now protects the bishop on [c2] and frees the rook from [c1]. Generally, it is difficult to offer White any good advice.} Bh6 27. Rb1 a5 28. Kg2 Nd2 29. Rbe1 Bf4 30. Re7 Rd7 $1 {Not allowing any kind of counterplay on the seventh rank.} 31. Re8+ Kc7 32. Ra8 a4 {[%csl Ra1]} 33. Re6 Kb7 34. Rae8 Bd6 {[%cal Gb4d5,Gd5f4]} 35. Bd1 Nd5 36. Re1 Nf4+ 37. Kh1 Bc5 {[%cal Gf4d3,Gf4h3,Gc5f2] Just improving the pieces. White's position will collapse by itself.} 38. Be2 Nxe2 39. R1xe2 b4 {[%cal Gb4b3] And ...[b3] is unstoppable. Feels too easy for Vishy.} 40. R2e5 Rc7 {I wish I could play such games. Don't you?} 0-1

