1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. Bc4 {Quite a rare move order but should transpose to one of our lines later on.} Nb6 5. Be2 {Not a typical retreat for the Alapin, but I tried it myself a long time ago against MVL with the inclusion of [Nf3] and [Nc6].} Nc6 6. Nf3 g6 (6... d6 {right away is definitely possible. We can also start by the text preparing ...[Bg7] and keeping ...[d6] for later on.}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 d6 {Breaking White's centre.} 9. exd6 {This is not that great for White.} Qxd6 10. Nc3 Be6 11. Ne4 Qc7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf8g7,Ge6d5] We get a comfortable position where our play will turn around the [d4]-pawn.} *

