1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. Bc4 {Quite a rare move order but should transpose to one of our lines later on.} Nb6 5. Be2 {Not a typical retreat for the Alapin, but I tried it myself a long time ago against MVL with the inclusion of [Nf3] and [Nc6].} Nc6 6. Nf3 g6 (6... d6 {right away is definitely possible. We can also start by the text preparing ...[Bg7] and keeping ...[d6] for later on.}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 d6 {Breaking White's centre.} 9. Nc3 Bg7 {Forcing White to take.} 10. exd6 Qxd6 {Now White has a wide choice of options, but their best try is to enter some concrete lines.} 11. Nb5 Qd7 12. d5 {Pushing the isolated pawn and hoping to exchange it soon.} Nb4 13. d6 {[%cal Gb5c7]} O-O {Of course, we do not want to take on [d6] and we need to avoid the [Nc7] fork.} 14. O-O exd6 15. Nxd6 {White achieved their goal of getting rid of their weakness, but it cost quite some time, and our pieces got good activity.} N4d5 {Forcing White to make a decision about their knight.} 16. Nxc8 {The most logical, but we can be happy as now one more piece is entering the game.} Raxc8 {[%cal Gg7b2,Gb6c4,Gb6a4] Even though the computer claims this position is about equal, I think in practice it is much easier to play for us. We have a target on [b2], and White is, as usual, struggling with the dark-squared bishop's development.} 17. Qb3 Qa4 {[%csl Gd5,Rb2,Gc8] With a nice activity.} *

