1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. Bc4 {Quite a rare move order but should transpose to one of our lines later on.} Nb6 5. Bb3 c4 {We play the same plan as in our main line.} 6. Bc2 Nc6 (6... Nc6 {Attacking the e5-pawn. After the most logical} 7. Nf3 {, play transposes to our main line.}) 7. Qe2 {This is playable, but it gives us some extra options.} d6 8. exd6 (8. Nf3 {still transposes to the 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.c3 lines with [Bc4] we'll see in the next chapter..}) 8... e5 {A good way to play, taking the centre and ready to develop fast.} 9. Na3 Be6 10. Nf3 Bxd6 {Now, White has only one way not to be worse.} 11. b3 {Otherwise, ...[Bxa3] could be annoying.} cxb3 12. axb3 O-O {Here, only Black can be better as we are clearly ahead in development.} 13. O-O Re8 {Preparing for White's knight jump.} 14. Nc4 Bc7 {White may go for the pawn.} 15. Ncxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Qxe5 Bxb3 {We win back the pawn instantly and get a slightly more pleasant position. The following line is forced:} 18. Qf5 {[%cal Gf5h7]} g6 19. Qd3 Qxd3 (19... Bxc2 {(is also an option but I wouldn't recommend it even if the engine says it's equal as, in the long run, the dark squares around our king might become weak.)} 20. Qxc2 Re2 {temporarily preventing the development of White's bishop.}) 20. Bxd3 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gb6c4] With some pressure. Our passed pawn will be White's headache, and our knight can always jump to [c4].} *

