1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. Bc4 {Quite a rare move order but should transpose to one of our lines later on.} Nb6 5. Bb3 c4 {We play the same plan as in our main line.} 6. Bc2 Nc6 (6... Nc6 {Attacking the e5-pawn. After the most logical} 7. Nf3 {, play transposes to our main line.}) 7. Qe2 {This is playable, but it gives us some extra options.} d6 8. exd6 (8. Nf3 {still transposes to the 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.c3 lines with [Bc4] we'll see in the next chapter..}) 8... e5 {A good way to play, taking the centre and ready to develop fast.} 9. Na3 Be6 10. Nf3 Bxd6 {Now, White has only one way not to be worse.} 11. b3 {Otherwise, ...[Bxa3] could be annoying.} cxb3 12. axb3 O-O {Here, only Black can be better as we are clearly ahead in development.} 13. Nc4 {We can simply trade knights.} Nxc4 14. bxc4 Re8 15. O-O h6 {[%csl Gg5] A good prophylactic move against any White's future attempts of [Ng5], [Bg5] or [Bxh7].} *

