1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. g3 {This is quite rare as usually, White wants to develop the bishop to [c4] and have some attacking ideas.} d6 {We can continue with our standard approach to this line.} 5. exd6 Nc6 {The same idea as in the line with 4. d4. We are offering a pawn for quick development.} 6. Bg2 {White should ignore the pawn sacrifice and concentrate on their development.} Qxd6 7. Na3 {[%cal Ga3b5] Always an option in the Alapin, especially with the queen on [d6], but it does not bother us.} Bf5 (7... Bf5 {A simple response. The point is that} 8. Nb5 {directly is dubious due to} Qe6+ {not giving White time for [Bxd5] and [Nc7].} 9. Qe2 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 O-O-O {and we have a nice advantage as the knight on [b5] will soon have to return to [a3] losing time again.}) (7... Bf5 {Another point is that, although} 8. Nc4 {hitting the queen looks logical, that's an unfortunate square for the knight as it will get hit back by ...[Bd3].} Qd7 {followed by ...[Bd3] and long castle. Black has a very nice initiative.}) 8. d4 {This is smarter, opening up the bishop and taking the centre.} cxd4 9. Nb5 Qc5 {[%csl Rb5] Preparing some surprises for White.} 10. Nxd4 Nxc3 {Forcing the following line:} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. bxc3 Qxc3+ {[%cal Gc3e1,Gc3a1] And White cannot avoid material losses.} 13. Qd2 (13. Kf1 {is a very bad idea due to} Bd3+ {and the [d4]-knight drops.}) 13... Qxa1 14. Nxf5 Qb1 {[%csl Rf5,Gb1][%cal Rd2c2] Not the only move, but the queen is well placed on the light squares as White has exchanged one of their bishops. We also want to prevent [Qc2] for now because we can make more threats with our bishop when the queen remains on the dark squares.} 15. Ne3 e5 {[%cal Gf8b4,Gb4a3,Ga8d8] Our play seems easier as we have more active pieces. ...[Bb4] is a threat as well as ...[Ba3], and ...[Rd8] will be coming soon.} *

