1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. g3 {This is quite rare as usually, White wants to develop the bishop to [c4] and have some attacking ideas.} d6 {We can continue with our standard approach to this line.} 5. exd6 Nc6 {The same idea as in the line with 4. d4. We are offering a pawn for quick development.} 6. Bg2 {White should ignore the pawn sacrifice and concentrate on their development.} Qxd6 7. Nf3 {A natural-looking move planning to castle next, but there's a problem.} Bf5 {[%cal Gf5d3] White still cannot bring their king into safety due to ...[Bd3].} 8. d4 {To prevent ...[Bd3].} Qe6+ 9. Qe2 ({Or} 9. Kf1 Qd7 {with a very pleasant position. Our next moves will be ...[e6] and ...[Rd8] or even ...[O-O-O]. White's king is not ideally placed on [f1].}) 9... Qxe2+ {The queen exchange favours Black because White remains with an isolated [d4]-pawn, and any endgame will be strategically worse for the first player.} 10. Kxe2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4+ 12. cxd4 O-O-O {[%csl Rd4] Black has a comfortable game against an isolated pawn.} *

