1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. g3 {This is quite rare as usually, White wants to develop the bishop to [c4] and have some attacking ideas.} d6 {We can continue with our standard approach to this line.} 5. exd6 Nc6 {The same idea as in the line with 4. d4. We are offering a pawn for quick development.} 6. Bg2 {White should ignore the pawn sacrifice and concentrate on their development.} Qxd6 7. Ne2 {Not an ideal square for the knight, but at least ...[Qe6]+ is no longer a headache for White.} e5 $1 {Taking the centre whenever we can!} 8. O-O (8. d4 {is not such a good idea because of} cxd4 9. cxd4 Bg4 {and suddenly, all the black pieces are coming into play, making White's life quite difficult.}) 8... Bg4 {Even with the knight on [e2] this move is a good way to play.} 9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 ({Getting rid of the unpleasant pin, but now White's king is weakened.} 10. d4 {is possible, but after} O-O-O {, we get a nice position with active pieces.}) 10... Bg6 11. d4 O-O-O {[%cal Gh7h5] Bringing our king into safety and planning to proceed with ...[h5] next.} 12. f4 {This can be met by a cold-blooded response.} f6 {[%csl Rb1,Rc1] The position remains complicated, but the activity of our pieces and White's weakened kingside give us good chances to play for a win.} *

