1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. g3 {This is quite rare as usually, White wants to develop the bishop to [c4] and have some attacking ideas.} d6 {We can continue with our standard approach to this line.} 5. exd6 Nc6 {The same idea as in the line with 4. d4. We are offering a pawn for quick development.} 6. dxe7 {Being greedy is not a good idea for White.} Qxe7+ 7. Qe2 ({Probably the best try, but even here after} 7. Ne2 Ne5 {White has terrible holes around his king.}) (7. Be2 {does not make much sense after playing [g3]. We'll go} Bf5 {with a fantastic position. Next, we'll castle long.}) 7... Ne5 {[%cal Ge5d3]} (7... Ne5 {We create some unpleasant threats around the white king and get a good advantage. For instance,} 8. d4 {trying to untangle at once doesn't work due to} Nd3+ 9. Kd2 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 {Forced. The king has to protect [f2]; otherwise, the rook on [h1] is lost!} Nxc1+ 11. Kd2 {The knight on [c1] is trapped but Black is well ahead in development.} cxd4 12. cxd4 Bf5 {Problems are only starting for White. Our rook is coming to [c8].}) *

