1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. d4 {By far, the most played.} cxd4 5. cxd4 (5. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the main line covered via 2.Nf3.}) 5... d6 {We need to challenge White's centre.} 6. Bc4 ({The standard approach.} 6. f4 {is a bit too optimistic as after} Nc6 7. Nc3 dxe5 8. fxe5 Bf5 {, Black is already slightly better, creating the unpleasant threat of ...[Nb4] and just planning to continue with [e6] to ...finish development.}) 6... Nb6 7. Bb3 dxe5 8. Qh5 {[%csl Rf7] It makes sense to provoke ...[e6].} e6 {We have to block our light-squared bishop, but we still get a comfortable game.} 9. dxe5 Nc6 10. Nf3 ({If} 10. Nc3 {, we continue the same way with} Qd3 $1 {with an eye on the [g6]-square.}) 10... Qd3 {[%csl Re1,Gd3,Rh5] White's queen has run too far away, and now we can perfectly place ours here to disturb the white king. Moreover, our queen can always come back to defence by switching to [g6] if needed.} 11. Nc3 Bd7 12. Bd2 {This has been tried several times in practice.} Na5 {[%cal Ga5b3] We are always happy to grab the light-squared bishop in the Alapin.} 13. Ng5 Qg6 {And here we go! As mentioned above, our queen is not only restricting White's movements but can come back to defend the king at any moment.} 14. Qxg6 hxg6 {[%cal Ga5b3,Gd7c6] Our chances are preferable. First of all, we will grab the bishop if White allows, and secondly, we want to go ...[Bc6], where our bishop will be nicely placed targeting the [g2]-pawn.} *

