1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. d4 {By far, the most played.} cxd4 5. cxd4 (5. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the main line covered via 2.Nf3.}) 5... d6 {We need to challenge White's centre.} 6. Bc4 ({The standard approach.} 6. f4 {is a bit too optimistic as after} Nc6 7. Nc3 dxe5 8. fxe5 Bf5 {, Black is already slightly better, creating the unpleasant threat of ...[Nb4] and just planning to continue with [e6] to ...finish development.}) 6... Nb6 7. Bb3 dxe5 8. Qh5 {[%csl Rf7] It makes sense to provoke ...[e6].} e6 {We have to block our light-squared bishop, but we still get a comfortable game.} 9. dxe5 Nc6 10. Nf3 ({If} 10. Nc3 {, we continue the same way with} Qd3 $1 {with an eye on the [g6]-square.}) 10... Qd3 {[%csl Re1,Gd3,Rh5] White's queen has run too far away, and now we can perfectly place ours here to disturb the white king. Moreover, our queen can always come back to defence by switching to [g6] if needed.} 11. Nc3 Bd7 12. Be3 {[%cal Ga1d1] Never played, but it makes sense to try to get rid of our queen on [d3] by preparing [Rd1]. However, now we get a chance to develop and create some threats.} Bb4 13. Rd1 {Giving away a pawn and hoping for some compensation in exchange.} Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Qxc3+ 15. Bd2 Qd3 {Coming back to annoy White's king. Of course, White can make a discovered attack by moving the bishop, but we always have ...[Qe4]+ if necessary. There is some compensation for the lost material, but a pawn is a pawn, and it is not sure whether White will manage to prove anything.} *

