1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. d4 {By far, the most played.} cxd4 5. cxd4 (5. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the main line covered via 2.Nf3.}) 5... d6 {We need to challenge White's centre.} 6. exd6 ({Again,} 6. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the main line.}) 6... Nc6 $5 ({A very rare move offering a pawn, but actually not for a long time.} 6... Qxd6 {is the usual answer and not a bad choice either. After} 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Nf3 Bg4 {, it will transpose here.}) 7. Nf3 Bg4 $1 (7... Bg4 {As usual. Since our bishop is already on g4, after} 8. Nc3 {we have the additional option of} e6 {planning to recapture the pawn with ...[Bxd6], while 8...Qxd6 transposes here, as mentioned above.}) 8. Bb5 ({This is harmless. After} 8. Be2 {, once again, if our bishop is already developed on [g4], we can always consider} e6 {since it is no longer blocking the bishop. After the ...[Bxd6] recapture, we will have a comfortable position where White's isolated [d4]-pawn will always be a target.}) 8... Qxd6 9. O-O a6 10. Bxc6+ Qxc6 11. h3 {Here, everything is good but trading is probably the simplest.} Bxf3 {Removing any future ideas of [Ne5].} 12. Qxf3 e6 {[%cal Gf8d6] With a balanced position.} *

