1. e4 c5 2. c3 {This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. d4 {By far, the most played.} cxd4 5. cxd4 (5. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the main line covered via 2.Nf3.}) 5... d6 {We need to challenge White's centre.} 6. exd6 ({Again,} 6. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the main line.}) 6... Nc6 $5 ({A very rare move offering a pawn, but actually not for a long time.} 6... Qxd6 {is the usual answer and not a bad choice either. After} 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Nf3 Bg4 {, it will transpose here.}) 7. Nc3 {White does not accept the challenge and decides to develop quietly.} Qxd6 8. Nf3 Bg4 {The advantage of our line is that we always develop similarly: if our bishop can get to [g4], we are happy to go there before playing ...[e6].} 9. Be2 e6 10. O-O Be7 {[%csl Rd4] White is playing with an isolated pawn and needs to find some concrete play, as otherwise, they will be strategically worse} 11. h3 Bh5 12. Qb3 O-O 13. Nxd5 {Simplification is probably the best chance for White not to be worse.} Qxd5 14. Qxd5 exd5 {The pawn structure becomes symmetric, giving a balanced position.} *

