1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is a standard approach to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is simple: to take the centre quickly by pushing [d4] and planning to recapture with [cxd4].} Nf6 {Of course, we keep the same strategy here as in the main lines after 2.Nf3 Nc6.} 3. e5 Nd5 (3... Nd5 {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 {just transposes to the main lines.}) 4. d4 {By far, the most played.} cxd4 5. cxd4 (5. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the main line covered via 2.Nf3.}) 5... d6 {We need to challenge White's centre.} 6. exd6 ({Again,} 6. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the main line.}) 6... Nc6 $5 ({A very rare move offering a pawn, but actually not for a long time.} 6... Qxd6 {is the usual answer and not a bad choice either. After} 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Nf3 Bg4 {, it will transpose here.}) 7. dxe7 {The most principled, but now we get an easy game.} Qxe7+ {If we compare the activity of White's and Black's pieces, we can easily understand that sacrificing a pawn here is not a big deal.} 8. Be2 Qb4+ {Here, White has a choice, and I am not sure that the best move is easy to play over the board as it sacrifices two pawns.} 9. Nc3 ({This might look strange at first glance, but it's actually the best as in other continuations, White gets a worse position. White's idea is to give away two pawns but develop fast.} 9. Nd2 {allows} Nf4 {with great activity. The [d4]-pawn will fall soon.}) 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qxc3+ 11. Bd2 Qxd4 12. Nf3 Qd6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Now it's us who emerge a pawn up. We should develop fast with ...[Be7] and ...[O-O], and White will still have to prove if they have enough compensation} *

