1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. Bc4 ({This is less popular than the natural} 6. cxd4 {but still widely played. By including [d4] first, White removes Black's possibility of pushing the [c4]-pawn and attacking the bishop as in our main line. However, Black has now other options.}) 6... Nb6 {We continue in the same manner as in our main line, asking the bishop to choose a square.} 7. Bb3 d5 ({A very natural move taking the centre and opening up our light-squared bishop.} 7... dxc3 $6 {would be a mistake as it allows White to get a very comfortable play and an excellent compensation for a pawn. After} 8. Nxc3 {, Black struggles to complete development.}) 8. exd6 {The best choice, as otherwise, Black would simply play ...[Bg4] followed by ...[e6] and get a nice French structure with the light-squared bishop already developed.} Qxd6 9. Nxd4 (9. cxd4 {allows us to equalise easily with} Be6 {. Black enjoys a comfortable position and will try to put pressure on the isolated [d4]-pawn soon.}) 9... Nxd4 {By exchanging the knights, we force White to play with an isolated pawn.} 10. cxd4 Be6 {[%cal Ge6b3,Gb3e6] Neutralizing White's best piece.} 11. Nc3 {This is possible, but Black has absolutely no problems after the following operation.} Bxb3 12. Qxb3 e6 {[%csl Gf8] Time to think about our dark-squared bishop!} 13. Be3 Qb4 {[%csl Rd4] We do not mind exchanging as many pieces as possible as at the end of the day, White will be left with their isolated pawn, which can become a serious weakness in the endgame.} 14. Ke2 {This might look weird, but White is already preparing for the endgame and improving the position of their king.} Qxb3 15. axb3 {[%csl Rd4,Rb3,Rb2] Besides their isolated central pawn, White now gets doubled pawns.} a6 {[%csl Ga8] We will need to play this move sooner or later, as otherwise our rook will be stuck for a long time on [a8] protecting the pawn.} 16. d5 {The right approach for White as exchanging the isolated pawn before it’s too late is always a good idea!} Nxd5 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Rhd1 O-O-O 19. Bb6 Rd7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ga1a5,Gh8e8,Gf8e7] Unfortunately, we will not be able to keep our extra pawn for long as the white rook will come to [a5] soon. Nevertheless, there is absolutely no danger here for us; we simply need to finish our development by playing ...[Be7] next and bringing up the [h8]-rook into the centre.} *

