1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. Bc4 ({This is less popular than the natural} 6. cxd4 {but still widely played. By including [d4] first, White removes Black's possibility of pushing the [c4]-pawn and attacking the bishop as in our main line. However, Black has now other options.}) 6... Nb6 {We continue in the same manner as in our main line, asking the bishop to choose a square.} 7. Bb3 d5 ({A very natural move taking the centre and opening up our light-squared bishop.} 7... dxc3 $6 {would be a mistake as it allows White to get a very comfortable play and an excellent compensation for a pawn. After} 8. Nxc3 {, Black struggles to complete development.}) 8. exd6 {The best choice, as otherwise, Black would simply play ...[Bg4] followed by ...[e6] and get a nice French structure with the light-squared bishop already developed.} Qxd6 9. Nxd4 (9. cxd4 {allows us to equalise easily with} Be6 {. Black enjoys a comfortable position and will try to put pressure on the isolated [d4]-pawn soon.}) 9... Nxd4 {By exchanging the knights, we force White to play with an isolated pawn.} 10. cxd4 Be6 {[%cal Ge6b3,Gb3e6] Neutralizing White's best piece.} 11. O-O Bxb3 12. Qxb3 e6 {Of course, we do not take on [d4] as it would give a tremendous initiative for White. Our development is more important than a pawn!} 13. Nc3 {We have several good options here, but I like going for the queen trade.} Qb4 {[%csl Rd4] As usual, when playing against an isolated pawn, we are happy to exchange as many pieces as possible.} 14. Qd1 Be7 15. a3 Qc4 {[%csl Gc4] White weakened their light squares, so our queen feels very comfortable on [c4] attacking [d4].} (15... Qa5 {is also playable with the option of bringing the queen to the kingside fast if necessary.} 16. Qg4 {is not dangerous as we can simply go} O-O 17. Bh6 Bf6 {protecting [g7] and targeting [d4]. ...[Qf5] will be played next with a balanced position.}) 16. Qg4 {We can meet this with short castle.} O-O 17. Bh6 Bf6 {[%cal Gc4d4]} 18. Ne4 {This is not great as we can simply take on [d4].} Bxd4 {[%cal Gf7f5] White has no way to create threats against our king.} *

