1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. Bc4 ({This is less popular than the natural} 6. cxd4 {but still widely played. By including [d4] first, White removes Black's possibility of pushing the [c4]-pawn and attacking the bishop as in our main line. However, Black has now other options.}) 6... Nb6 {We continue in the same manner as in our main line, asking the bishop to choose a square.} 7. Bb3 d5 ({A very natural move taking the centre and opening up our light-squared bishop.} 7... dxc3 $6 {would be a mistake as it allows White to get a very comfortable play and an excellent compensation for a pawn. After} 8. Nxc3 {, Black struggles to complete development.}) 8. exd6 {The best choice, as otherwise, Black would simply play ...[Bg4] followed by ...[e6] and get a nice French structure with the light-squared bishop already developed.} Qxd6 9. O-O {White can try to continue playing a pawn down, as it is not a good idea for Black to try to keep the extra pawn by taking on [c3] now. We should try to finish our development as soon as possible.} Be6 {[%cal Ge6b3,Gb3e6]} ({Our standard reaction in this line and easy to remember: we need to neutralise White's strong b3-bishop.} 9... Bg4 {would be nice if not for} 10. Bxf7+ $1) 10. Na3 {White might continue to play for the initiative, but here we are well enough developed to finally take on [c3].} (10. Bxe6 Qxe6 {brings our queen to an awkward place, but we still have time to improve her position. After} 11. cxd4 Qd7 {, the queen gets on a safe square, and we will proceed with ...[e6] next developing our dark-squared bishop.}) 10... dxc3 11. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gb5c7] This is not dangerous as we are just in time to protect the [c7]-square.} Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Rc8 {And now White needs to be precise not to fall into a worse position.} 13. Bf4 {For example, this tempting move is losing.} cxb2 {[%csl Ra1] And Black has three extra pawns!} *

