1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Nc3 ({This is way less popular than} 7. Bc4 {as it leads to simplifications.}) 7... dxe5 8. dxe5 Nxc3 9. Qxd8+ Nxd8 {[%cal Ge8g8] We take back with the knight to keep the possibility of castling.} 10. bxc3 Bd7 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Preventing [Bb5]+ and ready to continue with ...[g6]-...[Bg7] completing development. Black enjoys a comfortable position.} *

