1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} dxe5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the most common ...[Nb6].} 8. dxe5 {Getting rid of the isolated pawn is the most popular choice.} Ndb4 {This might look a bit shaky, but in fact, White has no way to get rid of this knight any time soon.} 9. Qb3 {[%csl Rf7] This is most frequently played and makes sense as it attacks [f7] and forces our hand.} e6 {Blocking our light-squared bishop, but it is not a big deal as we will manage to exchange it soon by concrete play.} 10. O-O {[%cal Gf1d1] The most logical, planning [Rd1].} Na5 11. Bb5+ {This looks critical.} Bd7 {And White cannot avoid the trade.} 12. Qa4 Bxb5 13. Qxb5+ Nac6 {[%cal Ga7a6] Bring back the [a5]-knight is more logical. We managed to exchange White's active bishop for our passive one, and now we can play on the light squares.} 14. Nc3 a6 15. Qc4 Qd3 {[%csl Gd3] It is not the first time in this opening that we see the queen landing on [d3]!} 16. Qg4 {[%csl Rg7] Trying to bother our bishop's development.} h5 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e7,Gb4d3] Depending on the queen's retreat square, we can play ...[Qf5] or ...[Qc4] liberating the [d3]-square for our knight. ...[Rd8] and ...[Be7] will also be played soon.} *

