1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} dxe5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the most common ...[Nb6].} 8. dxe5 {Getting rid of the isolated pawn is the most popular choice.} Ndb4 {This might look a bit shaky, but in fact, White has no way to get rid of this knight any time soon.} 9. Qxd8+ {By playing this, White wants to put our knight into some passive position.} Nxd8 10. Na3 {In fact, having the knight on [d8] enables this continuation:} Be6 {[%csl Gd8][%cal Ge6c4,Gc4e6] As usual, we would be happy to exchange White's active [c4]-bishop.} 11. Bb5+ Nbc6 12. O-O g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] The only way for our dark-squared bishop to develop.} 13. Nd4 {This is not dangerous.} Bd7 {Simple chess. Our [Nc6] is extremely solid.} 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Be3 {A bit tricky, offering the [e5]-pawn.} (15. f4 {is the most probable answer to protect the pawn. We'll continue with} Bg7 16. Be3 f6 {trying to break White's centre and open up our bishop.}) 15... Bg7 (15... Bg7 {The most logical, and play would likely continue} 16. f4 f6 {, as mentioned above.}) ({Note that} 15... Nxe5 {would be a mistake due to} 16. Bxd7+ Nxd7 17. Nb5 {eyeing [a7] and [c7]. White gets some initiative as we are still behind in development.}) *

