1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} dxe5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the most common ...[Nb6].} 8. dxe5 {Getting rid of the isolated pawn is the most popular choice.} Ndb4 {This might look a bit shaky, but in fact, White has no way to get rid of this knight any time soon.} 9. Qxd8+ {By playing this, White wants to put our knight into some passive position.} Nxd8 10. Na3 a6 {[%csl Gb5] This is a good alternative preventing both the unpleasant threats [Bb5] and [Nb5].} 11. O-O ({Played as often as} 11. Bd2 {.}) 11... Bg4 {As usual!} 12. Nd4 Nbc6 {Our knight has done its job and now can retreat offering simplifications.} 13. Nxc6 Nxc6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7e6,Ga8c8] Bringing our passive knight back into play. White should take care of their [e5]-pawn, and we, in the meantime, we can finish our development with ...[e6].} *

