1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} dxe5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the most common ...[Nb6].} 8. dxe5 {Getting rid of the isolated pawn is the most popular choice.} Ndb4 {This might look a bit shaky, but in fact, White has no way to get rid of this knight any time soon.} 9. O-O {This is another try, and here we can take advantage of one detail.} Qxd1 10. Rxd1 {The rook gets to [d1]. It looks well placed, but this move has one significant drawback.} Bg4 {The knight gets pinned, and we are happy to develop the bishop before playing ...[e6].} 11. Nc3 e6 12. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3] To break the pin and avoid doubling pawns.} h6 {This might look strange, but our idea is to restrict White's dark-squared bishop. If we check its possibilities now, we can see that [Bf4] looks the most logical, as on [e3], ...[Nc2] might always come. So, if the bishop gets to [f4], we can continue with our plan.} 13. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gb5c7] A thematic jump in our line.} Rc8 14. Nd6+ {This is not such a good idea:} Bxd6 15. exd6 Kd7 $5 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gb4d5] We block the pawn and can continue with ...[Nd5] with a more pleasant position.} *

