1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} dxe5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the most common ...[Nb6].} 8. dxe5 {Getting rid of the isolated pawn is the most popular choice.} Be6 $5 {A good alternative to 8...Ndb4.} 9. O-O {Decent, but it gives us time to improve our pieces.} g6 (9... Nc7 {offering a piece exchange is a solid choice.} 10. Bxe6 Nxe6 {and now:} 11. Qe2 g6 {Once again, we proceed with the fianchetto in this structure.} 12. Rd1 Qb8 {targeting the e5-pawn.} 13. Nc3 Bg7 14. Nd5 O-O 15. Qe4 $5 Re8 {protecting [e7] and threatening [Nxe5].} 16. Re1 Rd8 {and ...[Nc7] could be considered next, trying to exchange the unpleasant knight on [d5].If 11.Qb3 , we do not mind exchanging queens as it would open up the a-file for our rook. 11...Qb6 12.Qc2 g6 with easy play: ...[Bg7] and castle, with ...[Rc8] ideas and the [e5]-pawn as a target.}) 10. Ng5 {It is true that this time our trick with ...[Nc3] is not working, but here we can simply ignore the knight and finish our development.} Bg7 11. Nxe6 fxe6 {We got the doubled pawns, but White cannot really find a way to attack them as the e-file is closed by their own pawn.} 12. f4 {As in the previous line, protecting the [e5]-pawn but weakening the dark squares.} Qb6+ 13. Kh1 Rd8 ({Bringing one more piece into the centre and creating some threats of a discovered attack.} 13... O-O {would be imprecise due to} 14. Nc3 {, and unfortunately, we cannot capture} Nxc3 {because of the intermediate} 15. Bxe6+ {.}) 14. Qg4 {A logical attempt to attack the [e6]-pawn, but we can easily defend it here.} (14. Qe2 Qc5 {transposes here.}) (14. Qe1 {gives us a chance to activate the queen with} Qd4 {winning a tempo on the unprotected bishop.} 15. Bb3 O-O {and White needs to solve their development problems as well as take care of the [f4]-pawn.}) 14... Nd4 15. Nc3 {There are several good options here, but I like the following:} Qc6 {Forcing White to give away their bishop and improve our pawn structure.} 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Bd2 O-O 18. Rac1 {Seeing a rook in front of our queen should ring a bell to stay alert.} Qa6 ({Avoiding any possible trouble with discovered attacks. For example,} 18... e6 $4 {would be a huge blunder as White has} 19. Ne2 {and our knight is lost in one way or another.}) 19. Rfd1 Qe6 {This might look a bit weird as the queen just went to [a6], but it actually makes sense as now if White exchanges on [e6], their [f4]-pawn will be under attack. White can, of course, keep the queens on the board, but in either case, our position is solid enough, and White is struggling to find a clear plan to improve.} (19... h5 {is a good alternative with an idea of} 20. Qh3 Ne6 {attacking the [f4]-pawn, which was left without its defender after the white rook went to [d1].}) *

