1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} dxe5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the most common ...[Nb6].} 8. dxe5 {Getting rid of the isolated pawn is the most popular choice.} Be6 $5 {A good alternative to 8...Ndb4.} 9. O-O {Decent, but it gives us time to improve our pieces.} g6 (9... Nc7 {offering a piece exchange is a solid choice.} 10. Bxe6 Nxe6 {and now:} 11. Qe2 g6 {Once again, we proceed with the fianchetto in this structure.} 12. Rd1 Qb8 {targeting the e5-pawn.} 13. Nc3 Bg7 14. Nd5 O-O 15. Qe4 $5 Re8 {protecting [e7] and threatening [Nxe5].} 16. Re1 Rd8 {and ...[Nc7] could be considered next, trying to exchange the unpleasant knight on [d5].If 11.Qb3 , we do not mind exchanging queens as it would open up the a-file for our rook. 11...Qb6 12.Qc2 g6 with easy play: ...[Bg7] and castle, with ...[Rc8] ideas and the [e5]-pawn as a target.}) 10. Qe2 {[%cal Gf1d1] Preparing [Rd1] to put pressure along the d-file.} Bg7 11. Rd1 Qa5 {It is important to get rid of the X-ray right away.} 12. Ng5 {An idea we have already seen and learnt by now that we can simply ignore it. Now we have a pleasant choice between castling long and short.} O-O-O ({This can be our choice if we like to play the positions with opposite-side castling.} 12... O-O {is a more solid way to continue.} 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Nc3 Rad8 {bringing the last piece into play. ...[Qc7] and ...[Rf5] could be our next moves, putting heavy pressure on the [e5]-pawn.}) *

