1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} dxe5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the most common ...[Nb6].} 8. Nxe5 {This is not dangerous.} e6 {We can simply play this.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Ge7d6] Even though White succeeded in weakening our pawn structure, this does not give them anything as our knight is perfectly placed on [d5] and we will easily defend our [c6]-pawn if needed.} 10. O-O Bd6 ({I prefer to develop the bishop here as sometimes we can have tricky ideas with ...Bxh2, as you will soon see, but} 10... Be7 {is also perfectly playable.}) 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Re1 ({Here we can go for simplifications.} 12. Ne4 {allows the trick} Bxh2+ 13. Kxh2 Qh4+ 14. Kg1 Qxe4 {winning a pawn. Unfortunately, our light-squared bishop is quite passive so White has enough compensation but in any case, our position is solid.}) 12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 c5 {And if White is careless...} 14. d5 Bxh2+ $1 {[%cal Gd8h4,Gh4c4] This comes as an unpleasant surprise!} *

