1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 dxe5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the most common ...[Nb6].} 8. Nxe5 {This is not dangerous.} e6 {We can simply play this.} 9. Nxc6 ({White can start with} 9. O-O {, but it will just transpose quickly to our main line after} Bd6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 {.}) 9... bxc6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Ge7d6] Even though White succeeded in weakening our pawn structure, this does not give them anything as our knight is perfectly placed on [d5] and we will easily defend our [c6]-pawn if needed.} 10. O-O Bd6 ({I prefer to develop the bishop here as sometimes we can have tricky ideas with ...Bxh2, as you will soon see, but} 10... Be7 {is also perfectly playable.}) 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Qh5 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1d3,Gd3h3] A very aggressive idea planning to mate us! However, there are simply not enough pieces in the attack, and we have time to organize in order to meet the plan [Rd1]-[d3]-[h3].} a5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] Planning to exchange one potential attacker: the light-squared bishop.} 13. Rd1 Ba6 14. Bxa6 Rxa6 15. Rd3 {[%cal Gd3h3] White managed to get their rook on the third rank and are really threatening [Rh3].} Bf4 $1 {[%cal Gh7h6] A nice defensive move, Black will be able to play ...[h6] to meet the battery on the h-line.} 16. Rh3 (16. Nxd5 Bxc1 {As in the main line, no nasty jumps for White, and Black is more than fine.}) 16... h6 17. Nxd5 Bxc1 {Tactics are working for us; there is no nasty jump for the white knight.} 18. Rxc1 Qxd5 {[%csl Rh3,Rh5] And now White's heavy pieces are misplaced on the h-file. They have to be careful in order to keep the balance.} *

