1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} dxe5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the most common ...[Nb6].} 8. Bxd5 {Played numerous times by the former Women's World Champion Alexandra Kosteniuk. This looks like a good practical try, but with correct play, Black should not have any kind of trouble.} Qxd5 9. Nc3 Qd6 {[%csl Ge5] The best square as we need to keep the [e5]-pawn well protected. Otherwise, after [d5], we might simply lose it.} 10. d5 {And here, we have a nice idea to play for the initiative.} Nd4 (10... Nb4 {is less good as after} 11. a3 Na6 {, our knight is not that well placed.} 12. O-O {offers White a more pleasant position.}) 11. O-O {If White doesn't accept the challenge, we can simply continue with the most natural-looking move.} Bg4 12. Be3 Nxf3+ {Of course, we are always happy to weaken our opponent's king this way.} 13. gxf3 Bh3 14. Qa4+ {Here, both moves are good.} Qd7 $5 15. Nb5 {Only move to keep the balance.} Bxf1 16. Nc7+ Kd8 17. Qxd7+ Kxd7 18. Nxa8 Be2 ({Also possible is} 18... e6 {. It might look strange to leave the bishop hanging but the point is to finish our development and grab the [a8]-knight soon. If} 19. Kxf1 Bd6 {followed by ...[Rxa8], we have a slightly better endgame due to White's bad pawn structure on the kingside. 19.Bxa7 is a better try but we can keep the two bishops now. 19...Be2 transposes to the text.}) 19. Bxa7 e6 20. Nb6+ Kd6 21. Bb8+ Kc5 (21... Kc5 {It might look tempting for White to force the black monarch to take a walk towards his enemy's territory, but our king is actually feeling very comfortable there! I'll show you a sample continuation just for fun:} 22. Na4+ {This is already inaccurate.} Kb4 {White has three problems to solve: the knight on [a4] and the pawns on [f3] and [d5]. One of them will be lost.} 23. Nc3 Bxf3 24. a3+ {White's last try to threaten the king, but not a very good one.} Kb3 {The position is already close to winning for Black!}) *

