1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} dxe5 $5 {An interesting alternative to the most common ...[Nb6].} 8. Bxd5 {Played numerous times by the former Women's World Champion Alexandra Kosteniuk. This looks like a good practical try, but with correct play, Black should not have any kind of trouble.} Qxd5 9. Nc3 Qd6 {[%csl Ge5] The best square as we need to keep the [e5]-pawn well protected. Otherwise, after [d5], we might simply lose it.} 10. d5 {And here, we have a nice idea to play for the initiative.} Nd4 (10... Nb4 {is less good as after} 11. a3 Na6 {, our knight is not that well placed.} 12. O-O {offers White a more pleasant position.}) 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Qxd4 e5 {We gave a pawn to be able to develop fast and enjoy our two bishops' advantage.} 13. Qe4 {This is an invitation for an ...[f5] push.} f5 14. Qe2 Kf7 {Avoiding any threats of [Nb5] and [Nc7].} 15. Nb5 {Trying to complicate matters.} Qd7 {[%cal Ga7a6] The simplest, planning to get rid of the annoying knight with ...[a6] next. The queen is targeting the knight so [Qxe5] is not possible here.} 16. O-O a6 17. Nc3 Bd6 {[%cal Gh8e8,Gf7g8,Gb7b5,Gc8b7] We need to protect our [e5]-pawn and let out the [h8]-rook. Castling by hand with ...[Re8], ...[Kg8], followed by ...[b5] and ...[Bb7], are next.} *

