1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} Nb6 {The main move, but here, as we have already committed to ...[d6], White has an extra option of playing [Bb5], trying to take advantage of our pinned knight. Nevertheless, this line is perfectly playable for Black.} 8. Bb5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Bd7 10. Nxd7 {White might get two bishops but not for a long time.} Qxd7 11. Nc3 e6 12. O-O a6 {If White wants to save the central pawn, they need to give up their light-squared bishop.} 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Re1 {Here, we have several good options.} Bb4 {I like this idea, pinning the knight and threatening to win a pawn one day.} 15. Qg4 {This can be tried, but it's not really dangerous as we can simply protect the pawn.} Kf8 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gb4c3]} (15... Kf8 {Followed by ...h5 and the threat of} 16. Z0 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Qxc3 {is always there.}) *

