1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3d4,Rb1c3] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. d4 ({Lines with} 5. Bc4 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {We need to challenge White's strong centre and also try to develop our bishop soon.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5]} Nb6 {The main move, but here, as we have already committed to ...[d6], White has an extra option of playing [Bb5], trying to take advantage of our pinned knight. Nevertheless, this line is perfectly playable for Black.} 8. Bb5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Bd7 10. Bxc6 {With the idea of damaging Black's pawn structure.} Bxc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%csl Rc6,Rd4] It is true that our [c6]-pawn is a bit weak, but the same can be said about White's isolated [d4]-pawn.} 12. O-O g6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf8g7] Planning to put the bishop on [g7], from where it will be targeting White's weak pawn.} 13. Re1 Bg7 14. Bg5 {[%csl Ge7]} (14. Be3 O-O {gives us a comfortable position. We can improve our knight by playing ...[Nd5], and the rook can come to the semi-open file with ...[Rb8].}) 14... O-O {Offering an exchange of pawns.} 15. Bxe7 Qxd4 16. Qxd4 Bxd4 (16... Bxd4 {White does not have time to win an exchange as after} 17. Bxf8 {, we can reply with} Bxb2 {, and the rook is trapped. The position remains balanced.}) *

