1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. Qe2 {This is rarely seen in practice but makes sense.} Nxe5 ({Not often played but is, in fact, very interesting as it offers Black a rich, dynamic play.} 8... Bg4 {is unfortunately not working very well as after} 9. exd6 Qxd6 10. Na3 {, our [c4]-pawn becomes an easy target.} e6 11. Nxc4 {with a good advantage.}) 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qxe5 f6 $5 ({This is not obvious but very interesting.} 10... Be6 {is perfectly playable if we want a more solid approach to the position.} 11. O-O Qd5 12. Qe2 g6 {with an interesting position. Our next moves are obvious: ...[Bg7], ...[O-O], and ...[Rd8].}) 11. Qe2 {The most solid retreat.} e5 {Of course, by playing ...[f6], we prepared this move.} 12. b3 {White needs to find a way to get their pieces out.} Be6 13. O-O Qc7 {Not the only way to play, but it looks decent to me as we might need a fast escape with the king by playing …O-[O-O].} 14. bxc4 {White finally gets rid of this annoying [c4]-pawn which blocked their development for quite some time.} Bxc4 15. d3 Bf7 16. Be3 {A more solid choice related to a different plan.} Be7 17. c4 {[%cal Gb1c3] White has this possibility also, offering a square for the poor [b1]-knight.} Bb4 ({This can be annoying for White as now the knight can't develop to the desirable c3-square.} 17... O-O {is also playable.} 18. Nc3 Bc5 19. a4 {is a sample continuation.}) 18. Nd2 ({If} 18. a3 {, of course, we keep the bishop on the same diagonal with} Ba5 {to prevent [Nc3].} 19. Nd2 O-O 20. Nb3 Bc3 21. Rab1 f5 {offers nice counterplay on the kingside.}) 18... O-O {With equal chances.} *

