1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. Qe2 {This is rarely seen in practice but makes sense.} Nxe5 ({Not often played but is, in fact, very interesting as it offers Black a rich, dynamic play.} 8... Bg4 {is unfortunately not working very well as after} 9. exd6 Qxd6 10. Na3 {, our [c4]-pawn becomes an easy target.} e6 11. Nxc4 {with a good advantage.}) 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qxe5 f6 $5 ({This is not obvious but very interesting.} 10... Be6 {is perfectly playable if we want a more solid approach to the position.} 11. O-O Qd5 12. Qe2 g6 {with an interesting position. Our next moves are obvious: ...[Bg7], ...[O-O], and ...[Rd8].}) 11. Qb5+ {This only helps us as we want to play our next move anyway.} Kf7 {The king feels comfortable here.} 12. Na3 e5 {Once again, we are ready to give some material in exchange for the initiative.} 13. Nxc4 {And now the line is forced.} Bd7 14. Qb3 Be6 15. d3 {Here we have at least two possibilities. One of them is very solid with a good chance to make an immediate draw; the other one is messy, so it's a good choice if we wish to play for a win.} e4 {The ambitious and messy option. This looks very natural, trying to remove one of the defenders of the [c4]-knight.} ({We can play} 15... Qd5 {if we are happy with a move repetition:} 16. Ne3 Qa5 17. Nc4 Qd5 {.}) 16. Qb5 {A tricky move.} exd3 17. Bxd3 {[%cal Rd8d3,Rc4e5] The point is that we cannot really win the bishop due to the discovered attack.} Rc8 ({Of course,} 17... Qxd3 $4 18. Ne5+ {would be terrible.}) 18. Nxb6 {This looks very natural but is losing directly.} Rc5 $19 {With the idea of grabbing the bishop on [d3] if the queen moves away.} *

