10. Qxe5 f6 $5 ({This is not obvious but very interesting.} 10... Be6 {is perfectly playable if we want a more solid approach to the position.} 11. O-O Qd5 12. Qe2 g6 {with an interesting position. Our next moves are obvious: ...[Bg7], ...[O-O], and ...[Rd8].}) 11. Qb5+ {This only helps us as we want to play our next move anyway.} Kf7 {The king feels comfortable here.} 12. Na3 e5 {Once again, we are ready to give some material in exchange for the initiative.} 13. Nxc4 {And now the line is forced.} Bd7 14. Qb3 Be6 15. d3 {Here we have at least two possibilities. One of them is very solid with a good chance to make an immediate draw; the other one is messy, so it's a good choice if we wish to play for a win.} e4 {The ambitious and messy option. This looks very natural, trying to remove one of the defenders of the [c4]-knight.} ({We can play} 15... Qd5 {if we are happy with a move repetition:} 16. Ne3 Qa5 17. Nc4 Qd5 {.}) 16. Qb5 {A tricky move.} exd3 17. Bxd3 {[%cal Rd8d3,Rc4e5] The point is that we cannot really win the bishop due to the discovered attack.} Rc8 ({Of course,} 17... Qxd3 $4 18. Ne5+ {would be terrible.}) 18. Na5 a6 {[%csl Rb5,Rd3] Luckily for White, there's still a way to avoid material losses.} 19. Qh5+ g6 20. Bxg6+ {There's a similar line when White starts with 11.Qh5.} hxg6 21. Qxh8 Qd3 {And we continue exactly in the same way as in the line with 11.Qh5. It is true that White has clearly improved their position in comparison to the aforementioned line: their [c1]-bishop is not blocked, and the knight is already developed. However, one of the main problems remains: the white king's position. White is unable to castle, and thus, we have enough compensation for the material disbalance. Moreover, White needs to be precise not to lose immediately.} 22. Qh7+ {The only way to stay in the game.} Ke8 {[%cal Gc8c5,Gb6c4] The position is very messy, but one thing is for sure: we have more than enough counterplay, and White needs to stay alert.} *

