1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. Qe2 {This is rarely seen in practice but makes sense.} Nxe5 ({Not often played but is, in fact, very interesting as it offers Black a rich, dynamic play.} 8... Bg4 {is unfortunately not working very well as after} 9. exd6 Qxd6 10. Na3 {, our [c4]-pawn becomes an easy target.} e6 11. Nxc4 {with a good advantage.}) 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qxe5 f6 $5 ({This is not obvious but very interesting.} 10... Be6 {is perfectly playable if we want a more solid approach to the position.} 11. O-O Qd5 12. Qe2 g6 {with an interesting position. Our next moves are obvious: ...[Bg7], ...[O-O], and ...[Rd8].}) 11. Qh5+ {This is tempting because ...[g6] might seem a mistake.} g6 {But it's not!} 12. Bxg6+ (12. Qe2 {is the best choice, but we have easy play here. One of the lines could be} Qd5 13. O-O Bf5 14. Bxf5 Qxf5 {with a decent position. ...[O-O-O] will come next, and White is still struggling with their development.}) 12... hxg6 13. Qxh8 Qd3 $1 {[%csl Gd3,Re1,Rc1,Rh8] The truth is that we get an excellent compensation as the white king gets stuck in the centre, the bishop is blocked, and the queen is all alone in the corner.} 14. Qh4 {[%cal Gh4d4] An attempt to go to [d4].} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Opening up our dark-squared bishop but also taking control over [d4]-square to avoid the queen exchange.} 15. b3 ({This makes sense as White desperately needs to get more pieces into play.} 15. Qxf6 {is simply a suicide as after} Bf5 {, White is paralysed. ...[Nd5]-...[Nf4] is one of the possible continuations for us.}) 15... Bf5 {[%cal Ge8f7,Ye8c8,Gf8g7] We get a fantastic initiative in exchange for our material loss. White is still struggling to finish his development, whereas our play is easy. The king might find a shelter either on [f7] or on [c8] after ...[O-O-O]. The bishop will probably get to [g7] to protect [f6] and avoid exchanges on [a3].} *

