1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. Na3 {This has been tried by several strong grandmasters.} Ne5 $1 {White faces a dilemma: whether to simplify the position by exchanging on [e5] and the queens on [e2] later on or letting Black pin the [f3] knight with ...[Bg4].} 10. O-O {Allowing the pin.} Bg4 {With easy play.} 11. Be4 {As we successfully developed our queenside, it is logical to continue with long castle.} O-O-O 12. d4 {White is ready to give material in order to complete development.} cxd3 13. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gb5a7]} Qf6 {We should keep the pressure on the [f3]-knight.} 14. Nbd4 {This is more logical, to protect the [f3]-knight, block the [d8]-rook, and hope to win back the [d3]-pawn some time soon.} Nxf3+ 15. Nxf3 Rd7 {This might look bizarre at first glance but is, in fact, very tricky. The idea is to protect the [b7]-pawn and try to make ...[d2] work.} (15... e6 {is logical but a bit slow, and after} 16. a4 {White gets a good play on the queenside.}) ({The immediate} 15... d2 {is unfortunately not working well as White has enough resources for counterplay.} 16. Bxd2 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nc4 18. Qb3 $1 {+- and the threat on [b7] means we do not have time to take the bishop.}) 16. a4 {This would be a huge mistake as now we can push the d-pawn.} d2 17. Bxd2 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Nc4 19. Bxb7+ (19. Qb3 {is just useless here, as our [b7]-pawn is now protected!} Nxd2 {, and the game will be over soon.}) 19... Rxb7 {With a piece up and no compensation for White.} *

