plify the position by exchanging on [e5] and the queens on [e2] later on or letting Black pin the [f3] knight with ...[Bg4].} 10. O-O {Allowing the pin.} Bg4 {With easy play.} 11. Be4 {As we successfully developed our queenside, it is logical to continue with long castle.} O-O-O 12. d4 {White is ready to give material in order to complete development.} cxd3 13. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gb5a7]} Qf6 {We should keep the pressure on the [f3]-knight.} 14. Nbd4 {This is more logical, to protect the [f3]-knight, block the [d8]-rook, and hope to win back the [d3]-pawn some time soon.} Nxf3+ 15. Nxf3 Rd7 {This might look bizarre at first glance but is, in fact, very tricky. The idea is to protect the [b7]-pawn and try to make ...[d2] work.} (15... e6 {is logical but a bit slow, and after} 16. a4 {White gets a good play on the queenside.}) ({The immediate} 15... d2 {is unfortunately not working well as White has enough resources for counterplay.} 16. Bxd2 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nc4 18. Qb3 $1 {+- and the threat on [b7] means we do not have time to take the bishop.}) 16. Be3 {It is important for White to get the bishop out to avoid any unpleasant surprises with ...[d2].} Qe6 {We take advantage of White's last move, which slightly breaks their coordination.} 17. Bxd3 Bxf3 {[%csl Re3,Rd3] And now we see the drawback of [Be3] - White cannot recapture on [f3] with the queen as the bishop on [d3] would be lost.} 18. gxf3 Nd5 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3] With a complicated position. White has two bishops and better development, but we have a better pawn structure and can try to create some threats on the kingside.} *

