1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. Na3 {This has been tried by several strong grandmasters.} g6 {An alternative for those who prefer playing with a short castle.} 10. O-O Bg7 11. b3 {The thematic move for White in this line as the [c4]-pawn is simply too annoying.} Be6 12. Qe2 {Forcing Black to release the tension.} cxb3 13. axb3 O-O {We have successfully completed our development, whereas White's pieces are not on their ideal squares yet.} 14. d4 Bd5 {A good square for the bishop as [c4] is never a threat due to ...[Bxf3].} 15. Nc4 Qc7 16. Be4 {It totally makes sense for White to exchange one of Black’s most active pieces.} Rfd8 17. Nxb6 Qxb6 18. Bxd5 Rxd5 {[%cal Ge7e6,Ga8c8] We do not face any problems here. ...[e6] will probably be played next, and the rook could come to [c8].} *

