1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. b3 {Tried several times, but now we can continue with our plan.} Ne5 11. Be4 {[%cal Ge4f3,Ge4b7] Kind of forced.} O-O-O {Protecting [b7] and entering with one more piece into the game.} 12. bxc4 {This run into a surprising idea.} f5 {[%csl Re4,Rf3] Entering into some crazy position.} 13. c5 {The only way for White to stay in the game as moving the bishop would allow ...[Nxf3] leaving White's king terribly weakened.} Qf6 {Now, White absolutely needs to unpin as once again moving the bishop away would be bad, due to ...[Nd5] this time, keeping the threat of ...[Nxf3] in the air.} (13... Qxc5 {is not good due to} 14. d4 {.}) 14. Qb3 {Here, we need to be precise, but the line is not so difficult.} Bxf3 {With a forced sequence.} 15. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 Qg6+ 17. Kh1 Qc6 {[%cal Gc6f3]} (17... Qc6 {And the game is very likely to finish with a perpetual check if White plays} 18. cxb6 {, for example:} Qxf3+ 19. Kg1 Qg4+ {.}) *

