1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. Re1 {The most popular choice, trying to prevent ...[Ne5] ideas, but it turns out that we can still play it!} Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5d3] A very interesting continuation tried by some well-known players, such as Gelfand and Bacrot.} 11. Rxe5 {This is more or less forced as otherwise, the knight could jump to [d3].} Bxf3 12. Qe1 Bc6 $1 ({The most harmonious square for the bishop.} 12... Bd5 {is somehow less logical as it blocks the queen and takes the square we could use for our knight.} 13. b3 g6 14. Ba3 Qd7 {The best as, on any other square, Black faces some concrete problems.} 15. Bc5 {The computer claims that this position is playable for Black, but I believe that in practice, it might be more challenging than after ...[Bc6].}) 13. Na3 {[%cal Ga3b5,Gb5d4] With the idea of transferring the knight to [d4] via [b5].} g6 14. Nb5 Qd7 15. Nd4 Bd5 {[%csl Gd5] Forced because our bishop is too good to be exchanged for the knight.} 16. a4 a5 {An important move to stop any White's attempts to take space on the queenside.} 17. d3 Bg7 18. Re2 {This leads to a forced draw if we want to.} Bxd4 19. cxd4 cxd3 20. Bxd3 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Qg4+ {And White cannot avoid the perpetual check.} *

