1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. Re1 {The most popular choice, trying to prevent ...[Ne5] ideas, but it turns out that we can still play it!} O-O-O {The most common way to play in this position.} 11. Qe2 ({This might look like a smart way to improve the b3 idea, as the immediate} 11. b3 {is met by the standard plan} Qf6 {putting pressure on the pinned knight.} 12. bxc4 Bxf3 13. gxf3 {.}) (11. a4 {does not achieve anything as we can simply block the pawn by} Na5 {White will struggle with their usual plan [b3] here as the pawn is already on [a4], and the knight would be happy to grab the bishop in case White decides to go for it.}) (11. h3 Bh5 {transposes to the main line.}) 11... e6 {The most logical, but White's point is that our queen can no longer get to [f6].} 12. b3 {But here we still have one square to play the same idea.} Qf4 $1 13. Be4 {To avoid the king's weakening and to threaten [bxc4].} Bd6 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gg4f3] Now, White has no time to win a pawn due to the ...[Bxf3] threat.} 14. g3 {White succeeds in driving the queen away but weakens the light squares around the king.} Qf6 15. bxc4 {This is winning a pawn but not for long.} Ne5 {[%csl Gf3]} 16. Kg2 Nbxc4 {[%csl Gc4,Ge5,Gg4,Rb1,Rc1,Ra1] We win back the pawn and have very active pieces.} *

