..[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. Re1 {The most popular choice, trying to prevent ...[Ne5] ideas, but it turns out that we can still play it!} O-O-O {The most common way to play in this position.} 11. Qe2 ({This might look like a smart way to improve the b3 idea, as the immediate} 11. b3 {is met by the standard plan} Qf6 {putting pressure on the pinned knight.} 12. bxc4 Bxf3 13. gxf3 {.}) (11. a4 {does not achieve anything as we can simply block the pawn by} Na5 {White will struggle with their usual plan [b3] here as the pawn is already on [a4], and the knight would be happy to grab the bishop in case White decides to go for it.}) (11. h3 Bh5 {transposes to the main line.}) 11... e6 {The most logical, but White's point is that our queen can no longer get to [f6].} 12. b3 {But here we still have one square to play the same idea.} Qf4 $1 13. Be4 {To avoid the king's weakening and to threaten [bxc4].} Bd6 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gg4f3] Now, White has no time to win a pawn due to the ...[Bxf3] threat.} 14. d4 {[%cal Gc1f4] It is not stupid at all for White to take advantage that our queen gets under attack and we don't have time for ...[cxd3].} Bxf3 15. Qxf3 {I am not sure this move can be played without home preparation as White is allowing us to invade [h2].} Qxh2+ 16. Kf1 {White argues that our queen alone cannot put the king in danger and as we took her quite far away from the centre, they want to try to organise some threats against our own monarch.} Nd5 {This is necessary but requires good calculation or knowledge.} 17. bxc4 {This looks winning at first glance, but we have a fantastic line to stay in the game.} Nxc3 18. Nxc3 (18. Qxc3 {is not good due to} Bb4 {.}) 18... Qh1+ 19. Ke2 Nxd4+ 20. Kd1 Qxe1+ 21. Kxe1 Nxf3+ 22. Bxf3 {White gets two pieces against a rook and two pawns, and it is always difficult to evaluate such unbalanced positions.} Be5 {[%csl Rc3] A good continuation.} 23. Bb2 h5 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gg5g4,Gh5h4] We should try to push our kingside pawns as fast as possible to create a passed pawn.} *

