1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. a4 {Trying to take more space on the queenside, but this costs White quite some time.} Nd7 {As White's plan is slow, we have enough time to improve our passive knight.} 12. a5 Nde5 13. g4 {As mentioned before, this is one of the additional options for White when [h3] [Bh5] is included. The drawback of this move is, of course, the weakened position of the king.} Bg6 14. Nxe5 Bxc2 ({The best if we want to recapture on e5 with the knight.} 14... Nxe5 {right away allows} 15. Ba4+ {and White gets an advantage.}) 15. Qxc2 Nxe5 {[%cal Ge5d3]} 16. Qe4 {Centralising the queen before it's too late.} Nd3 {Our knight is incredibly annoying for White as it looks like the pawn will stay on [d2] forever.} 17. Qxb7 {Probably White's best option, trying to get at least some material to compensate for a poor development.} Rd8 {[%cal Gh7h5] Activating one more piece and planning ...[h5] next.} 18. Na3 h5 {Of course, we want to take advantage of White's weak king.} 19. Nxc4 Qc5 20. Ne3 {White managed to grab one more pawn and bring his knight to the centre, but things are not that easy.} hxg4 21. hxg4 e6 {I don't know anyone except the computer who would like to play this position with White. The computer still finds some way to hold here, but in practice, this is extremely dangerous for White.} *

