 h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. a4 {Trying to take more space on the queenside, but this costs White quite some time.} Nd7 {As White's plan is slow, we have enough time to improve our passive knight.} 12. a5 Nde5 13. g4 {As mentioned before, this is one of the additional options for White when [h3] [Bh5] is included. The drawback of this move is, of course, the weakened position of the king.} Bg6 14. Nxe5 Bxc2 ({The best if we want to recapture on e5 with the knight.} 14... Nxe5 {right away allows} 15. Ba4+ {and White gets an advantage.}) 15. Qxc2 Nxe5 {[%cal Ge5d3]} 16. Qe4 {Centralising the queen before it's too late.} Nd3 {Our knight is incredibly annoying for White as it looks like the pawn will stay on [d2] forever.} 17. Qxb7 {Probably White's best option, trying to get at least some material to compensate for a poor development.} Rd8 {[%cal Gh7h5] Activating one more piece and planning ...[h5] next.} 18. Qb5+ Rd7 {[%cal Gh7h5] If allowed, we'll go ...[h5] next.} 19. Ra4 {[%cal Ga4c4,Gc4c8]} ({Threatening to take on c4 in good conditions. Grabbing pawns right away is way too risky:} 19. Qxc4 h5 20. g5 Qg6 21. h4 e5 {and Black initiative is way too strong. White will get mated, as simple as that.}) 19... a6 (19... Ne5 {threatening ...[Nf3]+ is a way to almost force a draw but there is every reason to be more ambitious.} 20. f4 Qd3 21. fxe5 Qg3+ {That's just a perpetual.}) 20. Qb6 $1 (20. Qxc4 h5 21. g5 e5 {and once again, Black's initiative is obvious and very strong.}) 20... Qd5 {[%cal Gd5f3]} 21. Qxa6 {[%cal Ga6a8,Ga6c4] White has to take in order to create some counterplay.} Nc5 {Black wins the exchange but White has a couple of pawns in return.} 22. Qxc4 Nxa4 23. Qxa4 h5 {[%cal Gh5g4,Gd5f3] I like Black and our numerous threats on White's king.} *

