1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Na3 Qd5 {[%csl Rf3] Another way to put pressure on the pinned knight. The advantage of this move over ...[Ne5] is that [Be4] is not possible now, and also [Nb5] is coming without attacking our queen.} 12. d3 {White needs to complete development somehow, but now our play is easy.} Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qxf3 14. gxf3 cxd3 15. Bxd3 O-O-O 16. Be2 e6 {If White plays carelessly and ignores the ...[Bxa3] idea, they can be simply worse, so the best is to run.} 17. Nc4 Nxc4 18. Bxc4 Bd6 {[%cal Gg7g5] White has two bishops, but we have a better pawn structure and not a single weakness. ...[g5] can be played if White allows us, fixing White's poor structure and limiting their dark-squared bishop.} *

