[GameId "2123892871152337"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. Na3 {An alternative for White if they don't want to allow the plan with ...[f5] as in the main line.} Qf6 {[%cal Gh5f3,Gf6f3] As usual, putting the pressure on the pinned knight.} 13. Be4 {White avoids ...[f5], but now...} Ne5 {[%csl Rf3] We have enough pieces attacking the [f3]-knight!} 14. g4 {A logical continuation if White wants to avoid doubling pawns on [f3].} Nxf3+ {Forced.} 15. Qxf3 Qxf3 16. Bxf3 Bg6 {[%cal Gg6d3] Now our bishop is taking control of the [b1]-[h7] diagonal.} 17. b3 {As usual, White tries to get rid of the [c4]-pawn.} e6 {[%cal Gf8a3]} 18. Nxc4 (18. bxc4 {doesn’t make sense as the knight on a3 is misplaced.} Bd3 $1) 18... Nxc4 19. bxc4 Bd3 {[%csl Rd2]} 20. Be2 Be7 {[%csl Rc1,Rg4][%cal Gh7h5] With a nice compensation due to the bad bishop on [c1] and weakened White's pawn structure on the kingside. ...[h5] could be our idea.} *

