1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. a4 {Trying to take space on the queenside.} Na5 {A thematic way of blocking the a-pawn.} 13. Na3 (13. Qe2 {prepares a tricky idea, and now:A} e6 {is the most natural, but White has something in mind here.} 14. Na3 a6 {Necessary to prevent [Nb5] and here} 15. Nxc4 {Quite a surprising idea! Any recapture will be followed by the attack of the defending knight, and White will take back the material.} Naxc4 16. a5 {and the black knights are loose.} Bxf3 17. gxf3 {Obviously, White can't recapture with the queen or they won't be able to recapture the knight on [c4].} Nxa5 18. Rxa5 Qc7 {A nice regrouping move, as we will play ...[Nd5] and develop our bishop to [d6]. The position is a mess.}) (13. Na3 {B} Qc7 {is probably the safest and would be my recommendation, not allowing any tricks, and after Na3 a6 preventing [Nb5], it transposes to the text.}) 13... a6 {[%csl Gb5] We need to control [b5].} 14. Qe2 Qc7 $1 15. Qe5 ({This attempt to force the exchanges only helps us.} 15. d3 cxd3 16. Bxd3 e6 {and the opposite side castles promise us an interesting game where our chances are not inferior.}) ({If} 15. d4 {, we have a choice: either we transpose to 15.d3 by playing} cxd3 {, or we play 15...e6 with an interesting position to play. White's knight looks useless on [a3] and will need to go back to [b1] to find a better square.}) 15... Bxf3 16. Qf5+ e6 17. Qxf3 h5 ({Now we have a clear plan: to roll the pawns on the kingside.} 17... Bc5 {is less clear due to} 18. Rb1 {and White will try to organise [d4] and/or [b4].}) 18. Rb1 g5 $1 {It looks like our attack is going much faster.} *

