..[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. a4 {Trying to take space on the queenside.} Na5 {A thematic way of blocking the a-pawn.} 13. Na3 (13. Qe2 {prepares a tricky idea, and now:A} e6 {is the most natural, but White has something in mind here.} 14. Na3 a6 {Necessary to prevent [Nb5] and here} 15. Nxc4 {Quite a surprising idea! Any recapture will be followed by the attack of the defending knight, and White will take back the material.} Naxc4 16. a5 {and the black knights are loose.} Bxf3 17. gxf3 {Obviously, White can't recapture with the queen or they won't be able to recapture the knight on [c4].} Nxa5 18. Rxa5 Qc7 {A nice regrouping move, as we will play ...[Nd5] and develop our bishop to [d6]. The position is a mess.}) (13. Na3 {B} Qc7 {is probably the safest and would be my recommendation, not allowing any tricks, and after Na3 a6 preventing [Nb5], it transposes to the text.}) 13... a6 {[%csl Gb5] We need to control [b5].} 14. Qe2 Qc6 {This is playable but gives some extra options for White. For example:} 15. g4 Bg6 16. Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c6,Ge5g6] With the queen on [c6], this idea makes sense.} Qd5 {[%csl Gf7] We need to protect [f7].} 17. Nxg6 ({Another possibility. After} 17. Bxg6 hxg6 {, White has helped us open the h-file but we still need to finish our development to be able to make some pressure.}) 17... hxg6 {[%csl Rh3]} 18. Be4 {White activates the bishop and hopes to use it in the king's defence if necessary.} Qd7 (18... Qd6 {allows} 19. Nxc4 {We have already seen this idea, and it works here as well. The position remains complicated, but White must be relieved to get rid of our powerful [c4]-pawn. If 19.Bg2 then 19...Qc7 removing any [Nxc4] tricks.}) 19. Nxc4 {[%cal Gc4b6,Gc4a5] A good option for White leading to a forced line:} Nbxc4 20. b4 {[%csl Ra5,Rc4]} Nd6 21. bxa5 Nxe4 22. Qc4+ {[%cal Ge1e4,Gc4c8]} Kb8 23. Rxe4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Ge4d4]} e5 ({We still need to finish our development. We can go for} 23... Rxh3 {, but after} 24. Rd4 {and exchanges on [d8] will cause us to lose the [f7]-pawn.}) 24. Kg2 {[%csl Gh3]} Bd6 {[%cal Gf7f5] With ...[f5] coming next with an easy play. White's king is more vulnerable than ours.} *

