1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] White is not only willing to exchange the [c4]-pawn but also might consider [Ba3] attacking our queen.} Qf6 {[%cal Gh5f3,Gf6f3] Therefore, moving the queen is logical.} 13. Be4 {Recommended as an alternative by Norwegian GM Christiansen in his course "The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian" and also quite popular in correspondence games. Christiansen calls it a 'quiet choice', and it is indeed much less tactical than his other recommendation. The quiet choice doesn't pose Black any serious problems, and we will equalise easily.} Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5f3,Gh5d1] The next few moves are logical and best. The sequence leads to a harmless ending.} 14. g4 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 Qxf3 16. Bxf3 Bg6 17. Na3 {[%csl Rc4] White is trying to lure Black into taking on [b3] in order to get a nice centre. We don't do that, obviously.} e6 $1 18. Nxc4 (18. bxc4 {doesn’t make sense as the knight on a3 is misplaced.} Bd3 $1) 18... Nxc4 19. bxc4 Bd3 $1 {[%csl Rd2] Preventing the liberating [d4].} 20. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gc1a3]} Rd7 {[%cal Gd7b7,Gd7c7] A nice novelty which gives Black harmony. The rook is very useful here, protecting [b7] and planning to take back the [c4]-pawn with the rook via [c7].} 21. a5 a6 22. Ba3 Bxa3 23. Rxa3 Rc7 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gh8d8,Gd3b1,Gd3c4,Gc7c4] The other rook will come to [d8] and only then will we take back the pawn on [c4]. Black is by no means worse here; our play is even slightly easier as we know our next few moves.} *

