[GameId "2123892871230166"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] White is not only willing to exchange the [c4]-pawn but also might consider [Ba3] attacking our queen.} Qf6 {[%cal Gh5f3,Gf6f3] Therefore, moving the queen is logical.} 13. Na3 $5 {Suggested by Norwegian GM Christiansen in his course 'High-Pressure Alapin Sicilian' and also quite popular in my database. White attacks the pawn on [c4] while not really caring about taking twice on [f3] and getting an endgame where White will get bet the bishop pair.} Nd5 $1 {I like this one attacking the [c3]-pawn and centralising the knight. Also, we may jump to [f4] at some point...} 14. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2c3] Defending the [c3]-pawn is way too slow.} g5 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gh8g8,Gd5f4] Here we go for the king. White's minor pieces are far from the king, and we get a nice attack by playing natural moves.} 15. Nxc4 Rg8 $1 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gg5g4,Gd5f4] Here we go for the king. Honestly, I would be panicking as White; they are just a pawn up, and Black has a tremendous attack.} 16. Ne3 {[%cal Ge3d5,Ge3g4] Trying to exchange at least one piece.} Nxe3 {Simple and good!} 17. Rxe3 g4 {[%cal Gg8g1,Gf8h6] White will need a lot of imagination in order not to get mated or avoid an immediate disaster as Black's position plays by itself: the g-line will be opened, and also ...[Bh6] will come with a tempo.} *

