..[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] White is not only willing to exchange the [c4]-pawn but also might consider [Ba3] attacking our queen.} Qf6 {[%cal Gh5f3,Gf6f3] Therefore, moving the queen is logical.} 13. Na3 $5 {Suggested by Norwegian GM Christiansen in his course 'High-Pressure Alapin Sicilian' and also quite popular in my database. White attacks the pawn on [c4] while not really caring about taking twice on [f3] and getting an endgame where White will get bet the bishop pair.} Nd5 $1 {I like this one attacking the [c3]-pawn and centralising the knight. Also, we may jump to [f4] at some point...} 14. Nxc4 $1 {That's GM Christiansen's point. White doesn't care about sacrificing their queen and just grabs a pawn.} e6 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh8g8,Gd5f4] A strong novelty in terms of objective merits and practical value. Black just ignores the Greek Gift on [c3] and just develops. We will continue with a strong attack on the kingside with ...[g5]-...[Rg8]-...[Nf4]. Yes, White is a pawn up, but what's next?} ({This novelty is not considered in GM Christiansen's course. He is showing nice ideas after} 14... Nxc3 {and 14...b5 . Basically, it's a sharp mess ending in draws where Black has to find a lot of only moves. Not the case at all after 14...[e6]!N where there is more high pressure on White!After 14...Nxc3 15.dxc3 Rxd1 16.Bxd1 , indeed, White has full compensation for the queen, and the position is not easy to play for Black, who lacks kingside development.}) 15. Qe2 {Very reasonable, preventing ...[Nxc3] and planning to unpin.} Nf4 16. Qe3 ({The only move!} 16. Qe4 $4 Bg6 {is simply losing a piece.}) 16... Nd5 (16... Nd5 {And now White's best is already to repeat moves with} 17. Qe2 {.}) 17. Qg5 {This just leads to an ending where Black has more than full compensation for the pawn.} Bxf3 18. Qxf6 gxf6 19. gxf3 Rg8+ 20. Kf1 f5 {[%csl Rd2,Rf1,Gf4,Gh4][%cal Gf8h6,Gc6e7,Ge7g6] Black has an excellent control on the dark squares. It is also very difficult for White to push [d4] as the [c3]-pawn is hanging. Black has different plans, but the plan ...[Nc6]-[e7]-[g6]-[f4], while keeping the powerful knight on [d5], is very likely to happen and cause White some headaches.} *

