te has full compensation for the queen, and the position is not easy to play for Black, who lacks kingside development.}) 15. Bb2 {Developing and protecting [c3]. This looks like the most logical to me. On the other hand, it is very far from the main action, which will happen on the kingside!} g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gd5f4,Gh8g8] And immediately it looks tough for White to defend.} 16. d4 {That was the purpose of 15.Bb2.} Rg8 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gd5f4] Bringing one more attacker into the action!} 17. Be4 Nf4 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gf4g2] After the rook, it is time for the knight to jump into the attack.} 18. Ne3 {[%cal Ge3g4] It makes sense to stop Black's ...[g4].} Bd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6h2,Gg5g4] Now the [d6]-square is free, why not to bring another piece into the attack before pushing ...[g4]?} 19. Ng4 {This doesn't really help.} Bxg4 20. hxg4 h5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4] And the kingside will eventually open up with a very strong attack for Black.} *

