te has full compensation for the queen, and the position is not easy to play for Black, who lacks kingside development.}) 15. Bb2 {Developing and protecting [c3]. This looks like the most logical to me. On the other hand, it is very far from the main action, which will happen on the kingside!} g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gd5f4,Gh8g8] And immediately it looks tough for White to defend.} 16. d4 {That was the purpose of 15.Bb2.} Rg8 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gd5f4] Bringing one more attacker into the action!} 17. Be4 Nf4 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gf4g2] After the rook, it is time for the knight to jump into the attack.} 18. Bc1 {[%cal Gc1f4]} ({This looks like a panic move, but one has to try to defend.} 18. Bxc6 $6 {looks weakening for the black king, but the truth is that the light-squared bishop was doing a good job defending the knight on [f3].} bxc6 {and now ...[Nxh3] is a threat.}) 18... Nxg2 $1 {The fun begins!} 19. Kxg2 g4 20. hxg4 Rxg4+ 21. Kf1 {That's strictly the only move not to resign immediately. The following sequence is actually forced.} Rxe4 22. Rxe4 Bxf3 23. Rf4 $3 {A brilliant move and the only one.} Qxf4 24. Bxf4 Bxd1 25. Rxd1 b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] The number of pawns is now even. The endgame is equal.} *

