..[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. Be4 {By including [h3] [Bh5], White made sure this move won't be met by ...[f5].} e6 {[%cal Gf7f5] We still want to play ...[f5] because the bishop is too well placed on [e4].} 13. a4 {Never tried in practice but it is quite logical, as our king castled long and White would like to organise something on the queenside.} f5 $5 (13... Na5 {We have already seen this method of blocking the a-pawn, but here, we need to be careful as after} 14. d4 cxd3 {is not good due to} 15. b4 {, and White develops a dangerous attack.}) 14. Bxc6 (14. a5 {seems to give White some fun, but that's only for a few moves. After} fxe4 15. axb6 a6 $1 {, fun is over!} 16. Rxe4 Qd5 {Black's great compensation, thanks to our lead in development, is pretty obvious.} 17. Qe1 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Bd6 {This is just fantastic compensations. ...[Rhf8] or ...[Ne5] will come next! Note that we can meet 17.Qe2 with 17...Bg6 Hello from there! Black's bishop will land on [d3], where it will immobilize White's whole army.}) 14... Qxc6 ({A human choice.} 14... bxc6 {is computer chess! It looks somehow superficial.} 15. Qe2 Qd5 16. b3 {Here, we have a couple of good options.} e5 {forcing} 17. a5 Nd7 18. bxc4 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Qd6 {with a double-edged position.We can also play 16...Bxf3 directly, but we need to be precise. 17.gxf3 cxb3 18.d4 here, we need to go for 18...Qc4! with a complicated game.}) 15. a5 {The most consistent.} Nd5 16. Ne5 {This leads to a forced line:} Bxd1 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Rxd1 e5 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gd5f4]} ({Now, we want to play ...Nf4. It would be nice to get the knight to d3 but against the immediate} 18... Nf4 {, White has} 19. d4 {and gets a good advantage.}) 19. Ra4 Nf4 20. d4 {Still White's best chance, but here our knight is protected, so we can take en passant.} cxd3 21. Bxf4 exf4 22. Rxf4 Rd5 23. Rf3 {Unfortunately, we are not in time to save the [d3]-pawn, but...} Be7 24. Rfxd3 Rxd3 25. Rxd3 Rd8 26. Rxd8+ Bxd8 {We get into an equal-looking endgame.} *

