1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. Be4 {By including [h3] [Bh5], White made sure this move won't be met by ...[f5].} e6 {[%cal Gf7f5] We still want to play ...[f5] because the bishop is too well placed on [e4].} 13. a4 {Never tried in practice but it is quite logical, as our king castled long and White would like to organise something on the queenside.} f5 $5 (13... Na5 {We have already seen this method of blocking the a-pawn, but here, we need to be careful as after} 14. d4 cxd3 {is not good due to} 15. b4 {, and White develops a dangerous attack.}) 14. Bxc6 (14. a5 {seems to give White some fun, but that's only for a few moves. After} fxe4 15. axb6 a6 $1 {, fun is over!} 16. Rxe4 Qd5 {Black's great compensation, thanks to our lead in development, is pretty obvious.} 17. Qe1 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Bd6 {This is just fantastic compensations. ...[Rhf8] or ...[Ne5] will come next! Note that we can meet 17.Qe2 with 17...Bg6 Hello from there! Black's bishop will land on [d3], where it will immobilize White's whole army.}) 14... Qxc6 ({A human choice.} 14... bxc6 {is computer chess! It looks somehow superficial.} 15. Qe2 Qd5 16. b3 {Here, we have a couple of good options.} e5 {forcing} 17. a5 Nd7 18. bxc4 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Qd6 {with a double-edged position.We can also play 16...Bxf3 directly, but we need to be precise. 17.gxf3 cxb3 18.d4 here, we need to go for 18...Qc4! with a complicated game.}) 15. a5 {The most consistent.} Nd7 ({This looks more passive than} 15... Nd5 {, but now we control the [e5]-square.}) 16. d4 {White must finish development and thus, [d4] has to be played at some point.} cxd3 17. a6 (17. Qxd3 {would be a mistake due to} Nc5 {∓ .}) 17... Bxf3 ({Not the only move but a logical one to damage White's pawn structure.} 17... b6 {looks natural but is actually a blunder.} 18. Nd4 $1 {As the pawn is no longer protecting the queen, White gets material advantage.}) 18. axb7+ Kxb7 19. gxf3 {The position looks very complicated. The play is not forced, but here is an illustrative line of how we could develop.} Bc5 20. b4 Bb6 {[%csl Gb6] The bishop is useful on this diagonal.} 21. Be3 {[%csl Ga7] Our [a7]-pawn is not attacked, and we can go for our kingside play.} f4 22. Bxf4 {This is dubious.} Rhf8 {[%csl Rf4,Rf3,Rf2,Gb6][%cal Gf8f2] We get a nice play along the f-file.} *

