{29...a6 would be inaccurate as White could expand further with 30.a5 taking more space and fixing the [b7]-pawn, and if, let's say, 30...Ne5 31.Be4 , White manages to solve his problems. [Ra2]-[Rb2] will put pressure on [b7] and allow the knight's development via [d2]. B 26...Ne5! Now ...[Rg5] becomes a threat. 27.h4 is one way to avoid ...[Rg5]. 27...Nd3 and White still struggles to develop. Their best option is to continue with 28.Nd2 giving away a pawn. 28...Nxf2 We still are a pawn down, but the activity of our pieces fully compensates the material inequality.The other way to stop ...[Rg5] is 27.f4 , but now after 27...Nd3 , our knight becomes a real headache for White. If they decide to eliminate it by playing 28.Bxd3 , then after 28...Rxd3 , we have great initiative. White has two extra pawns but is playing without the knight and rook, so we have more than enough compensation.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. Be4 {By including [h3] [Bh5], White made sure this move won't be met by ...[f5].} e6 {[%cal Gf7f5] We still want to play ...[f5] because the bishop is too well placed on [e4].} 13. b3 f5 {We continue with our plan to get rid of the active bishop.} 14. Bc2 g6 $1 {[%cal Gg6f5,Ge6e5] The idea is simple: to protect [f5] and to push ...[e5] next.} 15. bxc4 {White finally manages to remove the [c4]-pawn and would like to play [d4] next, so we need to act fast.} e5 {Obviously, we follow our plan.} 16. d3 {[%csl Rc2,Ge4,Gc1] Protecting the [e4]-square and hoping to develop the bishop next. However, now the [Bc2] looks a bit sad.} e4 {Still! We are ready to open up the position.} 17. dxe4 Qc7 {Here, White has two options.} 18. Qe2 Ne5 {As usual, we want to double White's pawns on [f3].} 19. Bf4 ({This leads to simplifications.} 19. Nbd2 {transposes to 18.Nbd2.}) 19... Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 Bxf3 21. Bxc7 Kxc7 22. gxf3 {Now we have several good-looking moves, but I like the following:} Bc5 23. exf5 Nxc4 {[%csl Rb1,Gc4] We can ignore the [g6]-pawn for now and activate our knight, whereas White's knight seems stuck for some time on [b1].} 24. fxg6 hxg6 {[%cal Gh8h3]} (24... hxg6 {Obviously, White does not want to give away the h3-pawn and will play} 25. Kg2 {. Once again, the game is not forced here, and we have several good options. The following line could be an example of how the game might continue:} Rh5 26. Re4 {and now:A} Rg5+ {directly is met by} 27. Rg4 Rxg4+ 28. hxg4 {and White improves his pawn structure.} g5 {is a logical way to fix White's pawns and put our pawn on a dark square where the white bishop will be no longer able to attack it. Here,} 29. Bb3 Ne5 {only improves the position of our knight. A good way for White to play is 29.a4 , planning to continue with [Bb3] and [Na3]. We should block the pawn with 29...a5 30.Bb3 Ne5 31.Na3 and White finally completes their development.}) *

