..[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. Be4 {By including [h3] [Bh5], White made sure this move won't be met by ...[f5].} e6 {[%cal Gf7f5] We still want to play ...[f5] because the bishop is too well placed on [e4].} 13. b3 f5 {We continue with our plan to get rid of the active bishop.} 14. Bc2 g6 $1 {[%cal Gg6f5,Ge6e5] The idea is simple: to protect [f5] and to push ...[e5] next.} 15. bxc4 {White finally manages to remove the [c4]-pawn and would like to play [d4] next, so we need to act fast.} e5 {Obviously, we follow our plan.} 16. d3 {[%csl Rc2,Ge4,Gc1] Protecting the [e4]-square and hoping to develop the bishop next. However, now the [Bc2] looks a bit sad.} e4 {Still! We are ready to open up the position.} 17. dxe4 Qc7 {Here, White has two options.} 18. Nbd2 Ne5 19. Qe2 {Only move to unpin the [Nd2] and avoid problems on [f3].} Bc5 {Being two pawns down, we need to play actively and put pressure. Here, White has several options:} 20. Nf1 {It looks logical to unblock the bishop, but it abandons the [c4]-pawn.} Nbxc4 {Bringing one more piece into play. White needs to be extremely precise not to fall into a lost position.} 21. exf5 Nxf3+ {The most tempting, opening up White's king.} 22. gxf3 gxf5 {As you have probably understood by now, in this line we are not counting the pawns but playing for a powerful initiative instead.} 23. Bxf5+ Kb8 {Here, White has only one move to stay in the game.} 24. Kg2 {This might look strange, but we'll see the point soon.} Rhg8+ $132 25. Ng3 {This is the idea.} Bd6 {[%cal Gd6g3,Gg8g3]} 26. Bg4 Bf7 {[%cal Gh7h5] Being two pawns down and playing against the weakened white king, we prefer to keep as many pieces as possible on the board. Besides, now ...[h5] is a threat.} 27. Bh6 {Blocking the h-pawn.} Qc6 {[%cal Gd6g3,Gc6h6] Here, White is under heavy pressure, but there is still one way to save the game, though it is far from obvious.} 28. Rad1 $1 Bxg3 {[%cal Gc6h6]} 29. Rxd8+ Rxd8 30. Qe7 {The point! Not an easy one to see from far away.} Re8 {[%cal Ge8e1]} (30... Re8 {And the following is forced:} 31. Qxf7 Rxe1 32. Kxg3 Qxh6 33. Qg8+ Kc7 34. Qxc4+ Qc6 {White managed to survive the pressure and has some chances for a draw here, thanks to the extra pawns.}) *

