1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gd2d4,Gc3d4] This is another move order to get the Alapin Sicilian. White's idea is very simple: to push the [d4]-pawn and take the centre. However, this move has certain drawbacks, as it is taking the natural developing square of the [b1]-knight.} Nf6 {As we already saw in the 2.c3 lines, since White decided to put a pawn on [c3] and not their knight, which would be protecting the [e4]-pawn, this move makes a lot of sense.} 4. e5 {Of course, the most logical reply taking some space and attacking our knight. However, by pushing this pawn, White gives up the [d5]-square.} Nd5 {Here, White has two options: either developing their bishop and kicking the knight off [d5] or taking the centre with [d4]. Both moves have their advantages and disadvantages, and both of them are equally popular.} 5. Bc4 ({Lines with} 5. d4 {were covered in the previous chapter.}) 5... Nb6 {The most logical retreat, asking White to choose a square for the bishop.} 6. Bb3 {This is natural, but it invites our c-pawn to advance.} c4 {[%csl Gc4] Here, we can make use of White's decision to develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn. The [c4]-pawn is quite a headache for White in this line as they often struggle to finish their development because of it.} 7. Bc2 d6 ({Time to challenge White's centre and continue our development.} 7... Qc7 {is the most popular continuation, but after} 8. O-O {, White offers the [e5]-pawn and gets excellent compensation for it. If we do not accept the challenge and make some quiet move instead, then there is not much sense in playing ...[Qc7].} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 {with a dangerous initiative.}) 8. exd6 Qxd6 (8... Qxd6 {Now, trying to get rid of the c4-pawn immediately does not promise anything for White:} 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 e5 {and we can continue with ...[Be6] and ...[f6] consolidating the centre.}) 9. O-O {Now we continue with the most obvious.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Pinning the knight and preparing ...[O-O-O] and/or ...[Ne5] next.} 10. h3 {An important improvement for White, especially if they want to play with [Re1] next, but not only. By including [h3] [Bh5], White has [g4] at his disposal, and even though this is not necessarily the move they want to play, it can be a good way to deal with the ...[Ne5] threat in some lines. Moreover, as you will soon see, in the main line, White's bishop can land on [e4] now without fearing ...[f5], which is working well with our bishop on [g4], but not on [h5].} Bh5 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] The most played, and it looks like a good square for the rook as ...[Ne5] is now not working that well.} O-O-O 12. Be4 {By including [h3] [Bh5], White made sure this move won't be met by ...[f5].} e6 {[%cal Gf7f5] We still want to play ...[f5] because the bishop is too well placed on [e4].} 13. b3 f5 {We continue with our plan to get rid of the active bishop.} 14. Bc2 g6 $1 {[%cal Gg6f5,Ge6e5] The idea is simple: to protect [f5] and to push ...[e5] next.} 15. bxc4 {White finally manages to remove the [c4]-pawn and would like to play [d4] next, so we need to act fast.} e5 {Obviously, we follow our plan.} 16. d3 {[%csl Rc2,Ge4,Gc1] Protecting the [e4]-square and hoping to develop the bishop next. However, now the [Bc2] looks a bit sad.} e4 {Still! We are ready to open up the position.} 17. dxe4 Qc7 {Here, White has two options.} 18. Nbd2 Ne5 19. Qe2 {Only move to unpin the [Nd2] and avoid problems on [f3].} Bc5 {Being two pawns down, we need to play actively and put pressure. Here, White has several options:} 20. Kh1 {Logical, to avoid any possible ...[Qg3] or ...[Bxf2] checks as we have seen in the 20.exf5 or the 20.Nf1 lines.} f4 {Blocking the position and leaving White with awfully placed pieces.} 21. Qf1 {It is difficult to suggest anything better as the pin is very annoying. However, it allows doubling pawns on [f3].} Bxf3 22. Nxf3 Nxf3 23. gxf3 {White's king is once again weakened.} Qe5 {[%csl Ge5] The perfect square for the queen, blocking the e-pawn and keeping everything under control.} 24. Rb1 g5 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gg5g4] This is a decent alternative.} 25. Rb5 ({An attempt to put pressure on the pinned bishop, but it is not working.} 25. a4 {can be tried but is not dangerous.} h5 26. a5 Na8 27. a6 bxa6 {White is so poorly coordinated that there is no way to get their pieces closer to our king. ...[Nb6] will come next, and ...[g4] will always be an option.}) 25... a6 26. Ra5 {The rook is very awkwardly placed.} Nd7 {[%cal Ge5c3]} 27. Ba3 Qxc3 {[%csl Ra5,Rc2,Ra3] And White does not have time to win material. In fact, they're losing an exchange!} *

