[Black "2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 & 3.Bc4: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B30"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2123892871611114"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 (2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 {is obviously another way to get the 3.Nc3 line, while after 2...d6 3.f4!? , White gets a good version of the Grand Prix Attack as ...[d5] won't be played in one go.}) 2... Nc6 3. Nc3 {A very decent way to avoid the Sveshnikov used regularly by Kasparov back in the days and the third most popular move in this position after 3.d4 and 3.Bb5.} (3. Bc4 {A very recent line at the top level, probably inspired by the resurgence of the Italian opening.} Nf6 $1 {We immediately attack the [e4]-pawn.} 4. e5 {Logical and critical. After all, we didn't play 1...e5, so White has the option of going forward.} Ng4 $1 {Falling for a 'trap'.A} 5. Bxf7+ {The obvious reply, which seems to weaken Black king and win a pawn. But this is not so simple.} Kxf7 6. Ng5+ Kg8 7. Qxg4 Nxe5 8. Qe4 Nc6 9. Qf5 {Winning a pawn, but Black has two bishops, and we all know that fishing for pawns with our queen on the very first moves might backfire quite badly.} Qe8 10. Qxc5 b6 $1 11. Qc4+ e6 {we will go ...[d5] next, and it is Black who has the best development and a nice initiative coming up.B 5.Qe2 is objectively best. 5...f6! making sure to regain some space in the centre. 6.exf6 Nxf6 7.O-O e6 You will get the best version of the French Defence you could ever dream of! 8.c3 d5 Winning a tempo and occupying the centre. 9.Bb3 Be7 I like the following line, which shows Black's potential. 10.d4 O-O 11.dxc5 a5 (getting backward pawns is sometimes overrated!) 12.Be3 e5 We get a nice center and easy play in exchange for the [c5]-pawn. 13.h3 a4 14.Bc2 Qe8 I really like this move, which White will probably not see coming. We simply have a nice initiative as Black. 15.Nbd2 Bd8! Followed by ...[Bc7], ...[e4] and ...[Qe5] is a very unusual way to attack but also a very dangerous one.}) 3... e5 {We just play in the spirit of the Sveshnikov. We take firm control of the central dark squares. Obviously, we gave away the central square [d5]. You can't get it all!} 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 $1 {Be aware of the move order! Otherwise, it may lead to an opening disaster.} (5... Nf6 $6 {looks very natural but is incredibly dangerous.} 6. Ng5 $1 {is forcing Black to castle} O-O 7. h4 $1 {found by Dubov just gives White a powerful attack.} h6 8. Nd5 $1 {is the point. The knight on [g5] is taboo as the h file would open and Black would get mated.}) 6. O-O {There are two major plans : castling followed by [Ng5] and [f4] is the sharp and complicated option, while [Nd2] heading to [d5] via [f1]-[e3] is much more positional in nature.} (6. Nd2 Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 $1 {Not the most popular, but we want to activate and exchange our 'bad bishop' on [e7] via [g5] while keeping control of the [d5]-square with ...[Nb6]. There is also a tactical justification for starting with ...[Nd7] instead of castling:A} 8. Nd5 Nb6 9. Nxb6 axb6 10. Ne3 b5 $1 {This is the tactical justification, which does not work if both sides castle first.} 11. Bxb5 $4 Qa5+ {Hello! After 11.Bb3 Bg5 , we have taken some space on the queenside and activated our dark-squared bishop. We are doing well!B 8.Ne3 Nb6 9.Ned5 I actually played this way as White in a very important event for me: the World Cup. The Slovenian GM Lenic showed a nice way to deal with it. I still haven't found anything better for White! 9...Nxd5 10.Nxd5 O-O 11.O-O Be6 12.f4 That's the point of White's play, and indeed it looks quite pleasant for White. 12...exf4 13.Bxf4 Nb4! Black forces some exchanges and has nothing to fear.}) 6... Nf6 7. Ng5 O-O 8. f4 Bg4 9. Qe1 exf4 10. Bxf4 {All good and logical from both sides.} Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2]} 11. Qd2 Qd7 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga8e8]} 12. a4 {The most popular. Also, preventing Black’s expansion on the queenside makes a lot of sense to me.} a6 13. a5 {A bit weird for Black to provoke [a4]-[a5] as Black is now a bit cramped on the queenside, but the white pawn on [a5] might be weak at some point.} Rae8 $1 {[%cal Ge7d8,Gh7h6] Good centralization and also preparing a possible ...[Bd8] trying to activate our 'bad bishop'.} 14. Be3 h6 15. Nf3 Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 Bh3 {A very sharp and concrete position; if we know our way, there is nothing to worry about.} 17. Rf2 Nh5 $1 {[%cal Ge7h4] With the idea of activating our passive bishop. We explore this in great detail in the theory section.} *

