[ECO "B30"]
[PlyCount "72"]
[GameId "2123892871623403"]

{This game was played in the first round of the 2017 World Cup. The strong Slovenian GM Luka Lenic had prepared the Sveshnikov for the tournament. He did a good job, and I couldn't pose any problems to him. I eventually got annoyed by that and took too many risks in one of my White games and lost the match.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 6. Nd2 Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 {I already knew this was a good line, and, to this day, I couldn't find any antidote for White. That's why I decided to include it in my course!} 8. Ne3 Nb6 9. Ncd5 O-O 10. O-O Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Be6 12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d5] I wasn't aware of that move, which is a clean equaliser. It came as a nasty surprise.} 14. Nxb4 cxb4 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Qg4 Qd7 17. e5 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Ga8c8] I was still hoping I could create something by taking some space on the kingside, but this is actually compensated by the weakness of the white pawn on [c2].} d5 18. Bh6 Bc5+ {[%cal Gd7g7]} 19. d4 Bb6 20. Bd2 a5 {Simple and good.} ({Also interesting was} 20... h5 $5 {trying to lure the queen away from the defense of the [d4]-pawn.} 21. Qh4 Qa4 {hitting [c2].} 22. b3 Qb5 {threatening an invasion on [e2].} 23. Rae1 Rac8 {and I would definitely pick Black.}) 21. c3 bxc3 22. bxc3 Rxf1+ 23. Rxf1 Rf8 24. Rf6 {[%cal Gf6e6,Gg4e6] I was still hoping that I could put some pressure on Black, but Luka defended very calmly.} Re8 {[%cal Gb6d8]} 25. h4 Bd8 26. Rf3 Rf8 27. Rxf8+ Kxf8 28. h5 Qf7 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge8d7]} 29. Bg5 $1 {It is time for White to exchange their bishop and just make a draw.} Bxg5 30. Qxg5 Ke8 31. h6 gxh6 32. Qxh6 Kd7 33. Qc1 Qh5 34. Qa3 Qd1+ 35. Kf2 Qd2+ 36. Kg3 Qe3+ 1/2-1/2

