1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 {A very solid and sound setup which is very similar to our Sveshnikov's pawn structure. Solid doesn't mean that you won't get any winning chances as we will see in the game!; it just means that winning chances come later in the game!} 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 6. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3] The positional setup with the obvious plan of rerouting the knight to [d5].} Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6,Ge7g5] The finesse I am recommending in my repertoire. I think this is just a clever move order.} 8. Nd5 Nb6 9. Nxb6 axb6 {[%cal Gb6b5]} 10. c3 {White is forced to do this if they want to prevent ...[b5], as ...[Qa5]+ is not available anymore.} (10. Ne3 b5 $1 {and} 11. Bxb5 {runs into} Qa5+ {-+}) 10... O-O 11. Ne3 Bg5 12. O-O Kh8 ({I recommend} 12... Bd7 $1 {which makes more sense to me as it prepares ...[Ne7] and ...[b5]. More on this here. Black has zero problems.}) 13. a3 (13. Nd5 {looked more natural to me, but I guess Peter didn't want to give [f5] that easily.} Bxc1 14. Rxc1 f5 15. f4 fxe4 16. dxe4 exf4 17. Nxf4 Ne5 18. Bd5 c4 {and ...[b5] with a complex battle ahead.}) 13... f5 {Anyway!} 14. Nxf5 Bxc1 15. Rxc1 Bxf5 16. exf5 d5 17. Ba2 Rxf5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5,Ge5] That's the position Magnus wanted to reach when playing 12...Kh8. He gave up his bishop but has a powerful centre.} 18. Qg4 Rf6 19. f4 {I can imagine Peter was already worried here seeing this strong centre in front of him, and that's why he decided to simplify matters right away.} (19. Rce1 Qd6 {and Black will double up on the f-file.}) 19... exf4 20. Qg5 {[%cal Gg5d5,Gf1f4]} (20. Rxf4 $2 Ne5 {attacking the queen and the [d3]-pawn is just a bad idea for White.}) 20... Qf8 $1 {Giving up the central pawn, but now Black has the initiative on the kingside as we have more pawns there.} 21. Qxd5 Rd8 22. Qf3 {The most obvious but basically losing for White.} (22. Qh5 $1 {was the right but non-obvious way to play the position.} Rxd3 {and now not} 23. Bb1 g6 $1 {but 23.Rce1! Eyeing the [e8]-square. White has enough counterplay to keep the position balanced. 23...g6 24.Qh4 Re8 still a threat! The [f6]-rook is loose. 24...Kg7 25.Re6 Rd6 26.Re4 f3 27.Rxf3 Rxf3 28.gxf3 Rf6! The game goes on, but this is objectively equal. (28...Qxf3 29.Re7+! is suddenly losing for Black. )}) 22... Ne5 23. Qe4 Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e3] The knight on [e3] will be a monster, and Black is getting a devastating attack.} 24. Rce1 Ne3 25. Rf2 Re8 26. Qxb7 g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gf8h6,Gg4g3] A great move that gives Black a decisive attack. Not that difficult to play now for Black, as White has zero counterplay. The most difficult part was to get this position!} 27. Rfe2 g4 28. Rf2 {Easy to blame Peter for that sequence, but White is just helpless.} Qh6 {[%cal Gg4g3]} 29. Qc7 Ref8 30. h3 {A desperate attempt to confuse Magnus.} gxh3 31. g3 fxg3 32. Rxf6 h2+ 33. Kh1 g2# {Allowing a beautiful mate on the board!} 0-1

