1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. h3 {To prevent ...[Bg4]. This is the second most played move, which gives a completely different type of position where White wants to play slowly with an idea to prepare [a3]-[b4] or take space with [a4] and fight for a positional advantage.} (7. Bd2 O-O 8. h3 {transposes.}) 7... O-O {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 8. Bd2 {White can choose to play slowly.} Be6 9. Nd5 Bxd5 ({We should trade. I don't think} 9... Nd4 {is the best option as after} 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Qg4 Qd7 14. c4 dxc3 15. bxc3 {, White has a slightly more pleasant position. We need to protect our e6-pawn, and White can organise some play on the b-file.}) 10. exd5 (10. Bxd5 {has never been tried because after} Nxd5 11. exd5 Nb8 {we have easy play: ...[Nd7], ...[f5], ...[Bf6] are coming.}) 10... Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4] We have several good-looking options but this is my favourite, asking White some questions about that bishop.} 11. b3 {[%cal Gb3c4] The best as, otherwise, we would take ...[Nxc4] forcing [dxc4], which favours us. However, the bishop is extremely bad now.} ({If White ignores our last move and continues quietly, after for example} 11. Qe2 Nxc4 12. dxc4 Nd7 {, we get a very pleasant position with an easy plan: ...[f5].}) 11... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 12. a4 Nd7 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gf7f5] Preventing the [Ng5]-[Ne4] manoeuvre and preparing ...[f5].} 13. Qe1 b6 {[%cal Gf7f5] Both sides have one bad piece each, but somehow our play looks easier as we have an obvious plan with ...[f5].} *

