1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. h3 {To prevent ...[Bg4]. This is the second most played move, which gives a completely different type of position where White wants to play slowly with an idea to prepare [a3]-[b4] or take space with [a4] and fight for a positional advantage.} (7. Bd2 O-O 8. h3 {transposes.}) 7... O-O {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 8. Bd2 {White can choose to play slowly.} Be6 9. Re1 (9. Re1 {Here, we have a choice.} Nd4 {is a possibility, but I don't like it as after} 10. a4 h6 {controlling the [g5]-square, White plays} 11. Nh2 a6 12. a5 {and my feeling is that White has easy play here with [Nf1]-[Ne3]-[Nd5], whereas we struggle to find a good plan. Therefore, I recommend a different plan.}) 9... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Preparing ...[b5].} 10. a4 ({The standard reaction to ...a6.} 10. Ng5 {can be met by} Qd7 {. We should just remember that with this pawn structure we should never take on [c4].} 11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. exd5 Nb4 {and White needs to be careful here as we simply want to take [d5].}) 10... Rc8 11. b3 {[%cal Gb3c4] White wants to be able to take back with the b-pawn in case Black takes on [c4].} Qd7 {[%cal Ge7d8,Gd8a5] Preparing the activation of our dark-squared bishop.} 12. Nd5 Bxd5 13. exd5 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d5]} 14. d4 {A nice tactical idea trying to make Black's centre explode.} exd4 15. Bxb4 cxb4 16. Nxd4 {This looks good for White at first sight.} Bd8 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gd8b6] And suddenly our bishop will get active via [b6]. We will also be able to challenge white on the e-file by putting a rook on [e8].} *

