1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. h3 {To prevent ...[Bg4]. This is the second most played move, which gives a completely different type of position where White wants to play slowly with an idea to prepare [a3]-[b4] or take space with [a4] and fight for a positional advantage.} (7. Bd2 O-O 8. h3 {transposes.}) 7... O-O {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 8. Bd2 {White can choose to play slowly.} Be6 9. Re1 (9. Re1 {Here, we have a choice.} Nd4 {is a possibility, but I don't like it as after} 10. a4 h6 {controlling the [g5]-square, White plays} 11. Nh2 a6 12. a5 {and my feeling is that White has easy play here with [Nf1]-[Ne3]-[Nd5], whereas we struggle to find a good plan. Therefore, I recommend a different plan.}) 9... Qd7 {This is a good alternative.} 10. Nd5 Bd8 {[%cal Gc6e7,Ge6d5] An interesting piece regrouping. The [e7]-square can be used for our knight now.} 11. Ne3 {White wants to avoid the exchanges on [d5].} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 12. a4 Bc7 {[%cal Gc7e5,Gd6d5] The idea behind this manoeuvre is to try to organise ...[d5] at some point. The bishop on [c7] will be nicely defending [e5].} 13. b3 Rae8 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6d5] Moreover, now we can comfortably bring the rook over to reinforce the [e5]-defence and go for ...[d5] next.} *

