1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. h3 {To prevent ...[Bg4]. This is the second most played move, which gives a completely different type of position where White wants to play slowly with an idea to prepare [a3]-[b4] or take space with [a4] and fight for a positional advantage.} (7. Bd2 O-O 8. h3 {transposes.}) 7... O-O {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 8. a4 {The usual queenside expansion.} Be6 {We don't need to control the [g5]-square first.} 9. Ng5 Qd7 ({As we don't want to take on c4, this is the only sensible way to continue. Exchanging on c4 is almost never a good idea as after} 9... Bxc4 10. dxc4 {, White takes full control over [d5] and can put pressure on the d-file.}) 10. f4 exf4 11. Bxf4 {And now we can exchange on [c4].} Bxc4 12. dxc4 {The situation has changed. White played [f4] and allowed us to open the e-file. So now ...[Bxc4] is not putting us in danger as we have enough counterplay on the aforementioned e-file.} Rfe8 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge7f8] The bishop needs to move to allow us to put pressure on [e4]. At the same time, this bishop will continue defending the [d6]-pawn.} *

