1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. h3 {To prevent ...[Bg4]. This is the second most played move, which gives a completely different type of position where White wants to play slowly with an idea to prepare [a3]-[b4] or take space with [a4] and fight for a positional advantage.} (7. Bd2 O-O 8. h3 {transposes.}) 7... O-O {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 8. a4 {The usual queenside expansion.} h6 {Another decent choice preparing ...[Be6] and preventing [Ng5] ideas.} 9. Bd2 Be6 ({We can also go for} 9... Rb8 {, which is a useful half-waiting move, asking White how they want to proceed. And who knows, we might be able to go ...[a6]-...[b5] at some point and expand on the queenside.} 10. Kh1 {Returning the question to Black!} Be6 11. Nd5 Qd7 12. c3 Bd8 $1 {Our typical plan: activating the bishop and freeing the [e7]-square for the knight in view of an exchange on [d5].} 13. b4 cxb4 14. cxb4 {(( 14.Nxf6+ avoids the exchange on d5 but White doesn't get any edge. 14...Bxf6 15.Bxe6 Qxe6 16.cxb4 b5! and the move ...Rb8 proved to be useful!))} Bxd5 $1 {According to the plan!} 15. exd5 Ne7 16. Qb3 {The only way to protect the [d5]-pawn.} a6 {Once again the rook on [b8] makes sense!} 17. a5 b5 18. axb6 Bxb6 {and suddenly, our dark-square bishop is very much in the game.} 19. Rxa6 Qb7 {and we will get back our pawn by collecting [d5]. Black has the centre and a good game.}) 10. Bxe6 {With this exchange, White loses control of the important [d5]-square.} fxe6 11. Ne2 {It makes sense to regroup as the knight can no longer jump to [d5]. Moreover, White can prepare the [c3]-[b4] advance.} Nh5 $5 {I like this manoeuvre. As the f-file is open, we can comfortably install our knight on [f4].} (11... d5 $5 {is quite a standard reaction once we get this pawn structure.} 12. Ng3 Qc7 {To make sure the [e5]-pawn is well protected.} 13. c3 Rad8 14. Qe2 Rf7 {with a complex position. ...[a5] could be played next. ...[Nd7] is a good defensive resource if White tries to put pressure along the e-file.}) 12. Ng3 {White continues their plan.} Nf4 $5 {The knight is quite unpleasant for White, so we can expect a trade.} 13. Bxf4 exf4 14. Ne2 {The [f4]-square was taken by our pawn, but now we get another one available for our knight} Ne5 {[%cal Ge7f6] Our position is easier to play.} *

