1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. h3 {To prevent ...[Bg4]. This is the second most played move, which gives a completely different type of position where White wants to play slowly with an idea to prepare [a3]-[b4] or take space with [a4] and fight for a positional advantage.} (7. Bd2 O-O 8. h3 {transposes.}) 7... O-O {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 8. a4 {The usual queenside expansion.} h6 {Another decent choice preparing ...[Be6] and preventing [Ng5] ideas.} 9. Bd2 Be6 ({We can also go for} 9... Rb8 {, which is a useful half-waiting move, asking White how they want to proceed. And who knows, we might be able to go ...[a6]-...[b5] at some point and expand on the queenside.} 10. Kh1 {Returning the question to Black!} Be6 11. Nd5 Qd7 12. c3 Bd8 $1 {Our typical plan: activating the bishop and freeing the [e7]-square for the knight in view of an exchange on [d5].} 13. b4 cxb4 14. cxb4 {(( 14.Nxf6+ avoids the exchange on d5 but White doesn't get any edge. 14...Bxf6 15.Bxe6 Qxe6 16.cxb4 b5! and the move ...Rb8 proved to be useful!))} Bxd5 $1 {According to the plan!} 15. exd5 Ne7 16. Qb3 {The only way to protect the [d5]-pawn.} a6 {Once again the rook on [b8] makes sense!} 17. a5 b5 18. axb6 Bxb6 {and suddenly, our dark-square bishop is very much in the game.} 19. Rxa6 Qb7 {and we will get back our pawn by collecting [d5]. Black has the centre and a good game.}) 10. Nd5 (10. Re1 Qd7 11. a5 {and now} Bd8 {would be met by} 12. a6 $1 {, so instead, I suggest 11...Nd4!? 12.Nd5 and here we can go for 12...Nxd5 and after 13.exd5 , there is no fork as our knight already jumped to [d4] so we can simply move 13...[Bf5] .}) 10... Qd7 {[%cal Ge7d8] With an idea also seen here without the inclusion of [a4].} 11. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} ({If} 11. Bb3 {we continue the same way.} Bd8 12. Re1 {and now we are ready for} Bxd5 13. exd5 Ne7 {with a similar type of position as in 11.c3.}) ({Against} 11. Re1 {we still go for} Bd8 {and now} 12. Ne3 {is an attempt to avoid ...[Bxd5] and ...[Ne7], but after} Bxc4 13. Nxc4 Re8 {we have another clear plan: ...[Bc7] and ...[d5].}) 11... Bd8 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gc6e7] Liberating the [e7]-square for the knight.} 12. b4 ({The most consistent but even here we can make our idea work.} 12. Re1 {changes nothing in our plans.} Bxd5 13. exd5 Ne7 {and [d5] is a target.} 14. Qb3 Ba5 {and we can prepare the ...[a6] ...[b5] push.}) ({Simplifications are always welcome.} 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bxe6 Qxe6 14. b4 {White finally succeeds in pushing [b4] but after} cxb4 15. cxb4 {, we have our standard approach} d5 {When your opponent plays on the side, strike in the centre!}) 12... cxb4 {This should be included.} 13. cxb4 Bxd5 {And now, the usual operation.} 14. exd5 Ne7 {[%csl Gd5]} 15. Qb3 {We could probably say that White has improved their position by pushing [b4] and taking some space on the queenside. However, we still have comfortable play, and will continue by maneuvering our forces toward the white king.} Ng6 16. Rfe1 Qf5 $132 {With an interesting play on opposite flanks.} *

