1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. h3 {To prevent ...[Bg4]. This is the second most played move, which gives a completely different type of position where White wants to play slowly with an idea to prepare [a3]-[b4] or take space with [a4] and fight for a positional advantage.} (7. Bd2 O-O 8. h3 {transposes.}) 7... O-O {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 8. a3 {White is preparing [b4] and taking away any ...[Nb4] ideas which we have already seen in some lines.} h6 {Always useful to prevent any [Ng5] or [Bg5] ideas.} 9. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} a6 $1 (9... Be6 $5 {is another interesting way to continue bearing a tactical idea in mind. After} 10. b4 {, we can go} Nxe4 {and strangely, this move has never been met in practice.} 11. Nxe4 {is forced.} d5 12. b5 Nd4 13. Nxe5 dxc4 14. Nxc4 Qc7 {This is the most comfortable square for our queen for now. We prevent [Bf4] and plan to bring the rook next.}) 10. b4 {We are ready to meet this.} b5 11. Ba2 Be6 12. Nd5 ({The most principled.} 12. Bxe6 {only helps us.} fxe6 {White lost control over [d5] and now after} 13. bxc5 {we simply go for} d5 {and the [c5]-pawn will be lost anyway.}) 12... Nd4 {This has never been played in practice, but I don't see why not.} 13. c4 ({White is going for complicated play.} 13. c3 {also looks logical.} Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Bxd5 {, as a rule, we need to play this move at some point.} 15. exd5 Nd7 {bolstering [c5], and ...[Bg5] can be played next.}) 13... Bxd5 {We don't mind giving a bishop for this annoying knight.} 14. exd5 Nd7 {Defending both [e5] and [c5] and planning to recapture ...[Nxc5] if White takes on [c5]. The position remains complicated, but our chances are not inferior.} *

