[White "18) Anti-Sveshnikov 2.Nf3 - 3.Nc3 & 6.O-O"]
[Black "3.Nc3 e5 4.Bc4 - 6.O-O, 7.h3 & 8.a3 - Alternative 8...a6 #6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B30"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2123892871881469"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. h3 {To prevent ...[Bg4]. This is the second most played move, which gives a completely different type of position where White wants to play slowly with an idea to prepare [a3]-[b4] or take space with [a4] and fight for a positional advantage.} (7. Bd2 O-O 8. h3 {transposes.}) 7... O-O {Here, White has a bunch of possibilities.} 8. a3 {White is preparing [b4] and taking away any ...[Nb4] ideas which we have already seen in some lines.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Also very playable, especially because White has already committed to the [b4] plan by playing [a3].} 9. Ba2 {White decides not to wait for ...[b5] and retreats immediately.} Be6 10. Nd5 {The [b4]-square is not available. So, we go to [d4].} Nd4 11. Nxd4 {Here, we should take with the c-pawn.} cxd4 {Opening up the c-file for our pieces.} 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. c4 {We should take en passant.} dxc3 15. bxc3 {As usual with this pawn structure, we push.} d5 16. Qg4 (16. Qb3 Qd7 {.}) 16... Qe8 17. Be3 Rc8 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gh7h5,Ge8g6,Yb7b5] Asking White some questions about that weakened [c3]-pawn. We have various possibilities here. ...[h5] and ...[Qg6] putting pressure on the [e4]-pawn could be one of them. ...[b5] also looks decent, not allowing White to put any pressure on the b-file.} *

