1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. a4 {A thematic move which we often see in this line. White is not only taking some space but prevents ...[b5] ideas and gives a retreat square for the [c4]-bishop.} O-O (7... O-O {Now,} 8. h3 {transposes to 7.h3.}) 8. Re1 {As usual, here we have a choice.} Be6 $5 (8... Be6 {Directly. The point is that, as White hasn't played h3, we can meet} 9. Ng5 {with} Bg4 {.}) (8... h6 $5 {is the alternative approach, taking control of the [g5]-square first to then continue with ...[Be6]. Both options are fine.} 9. Ne2 {doesn't look great, as now White loses control of the important [d5]-square.} Be6 10. Ng3 Rb8 {and we will try to expand on the queenside.If White goes 9.Bd2 , the ideas are similar to those in our main line. Move orders are not that important: 9...Be6 10.Nd5 Qd7 preparing the thematic regroup. 11.c3 Bd8 with the point of exchanging on [d5] and retreating to [e7] with the knight. After 12.Bb3 Bxd5 13.exd5 Ne7 , White has difficulties saving the pawn.}) 9. Bd2 Qd7 {[%cal Ge7d8]} 10. Nd5 Bd8 (10... Bd8 {Now,} 11. c3 h6 {transposes to the note to Black's 8th move.}) 11. Ng5 {Now we are ready to take.} Bxd5 12. exd5 Nb4 {[%csl Gd5]} ({Creating the same threat.} 12... Ne7 {is, of course, possible.}) 13. c3 Nbxd5 14. d4 {White gave a pawn and needs to play energetically.} cxd4 15. cxd4 h6 16. Nf3 {Here, we have a choice.} e4 {I prefer this, forcing White's hand.} 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. Rxe4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf8e8] With a solid game.} *

