1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. a4 {A thematic move which we often see in this line. White is not only taking some space but prevents ...[b5] ideas and gives a retreat square for the [c4]-bishop.} O-O (7... O-O {Now,} 8. h3 {transposes to 7.h3.}) 8. Re1 {As usual, here we have a choice.} Be6 $5 (8... Be6 {Directly. The point is that, as White hasn't played h3, we can meet} 9. Ng5 {with} Bg4 {.}) (8... h6 $5 {is the alternative approach, taking control of the [g5]-square first to then continue with ...[Be6]. Both options are fine.} 9. Ne2 {doesn't look great, as now White loses control of the important [d5]-square.} Be6 10. Ng3 Rb8 {and we will try to expand on the queenside.If White goes 9.Bd2 , the ideas are similar to those in our main line. Move orders are not that important: 9...Be6 10.Nd5 Qd7 preparing the thematic regroup. 11.c3 Bd8 with the point of exchanging on [d5] and retreating to [e7] with the knight. After 12.Bb3 Bxd5 13.exd5 Ne7 , White has difficulties saving the pawn.}) 9. Bd2 Qd7 {[%cal Ge7d8]} 10. Ng5 {White can try to exploit the absence of ...[h6].} Bd8 {[%cal Gd8a5] As the white knight is not on [d5], one might ask why we play this move, as the typical idea was to free the [e7]-square for the knight. Actually, now our plan is to activate the bishop via [a5].} 11. Nxe6 {Of course, the most consistent, but by exchanging on [e6], White loses control of [d5].} fxe6 12. Ne2 Ba5 {Here we go. Our dark-squared bishop is probably the most problematic piece in our position, so we would be more than happy to exchange it.} 13. Ng3 (13. c3 {avoiding the bishop trade makes sense for White.} a6 {Just making sure that White won't be able to exchange their light-squared bishop. Next is ...[d5]!} 14. Ba2 d5 {And we got a massive center. We will follow with ...[Kh8] and ...[Rad8] and we are getting a very comfortable game.}) (13. Bb5 {Pinning and forcing a decision.} Bxd2 {That's why we came here!} 14. Qxd2 a6 15. Bxc6 Qxc6 {Followed by doubling on the f-file. In such closed positions, the doubled pawns don't really matter as White can't really attack them.}) 13... Bxd2 14. Qxd2 Rab8 $5 {With the obvious idea of ...[a6] and ...[b5].} 15. a5 h6 {[%cal Gf8f7] We can slowly improve our position.} *

