es 9.Bd2 , the ideas are similar to those in our main line. Move orders are not that important: 9...Be6 10.Nd5 Qd7 preparing the thematic regroup. 11.c3 Bd8 with the point of exchanging on [d5] and retreating to [e7] with the knight. After 12.Bb3 Bxd5 13.exd5 Ne7 , White has difficulties saving the pawn.}) 9. Nd5 (9. Bxe6 fxe6 {Once again, after this exchange, White can no longer dream of [Nd5].} 10. Ne2 d5 11. Ng3 Qc7 {protecting [e5]. [Rad8], ...[h6] and ...[Rf7] could be the follow-up.}) {Alternatively, 10...Nh5!? is an idea that we have already seen in this structure. 11.c3 d5 is also a typical way to react. 12.Ng3 Nxg3 13.fxg3 c4 with a complicated game.} 9... Bxd5 10. exd5 Nb4 {[%csl Gb4] When we have the [b4]-square for the knight, there is nothing to worry about.} 11. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5]} Qd7 {[%csl Gf5]} 12. c3 Nbxd5 13. Qf3 {White is hoping to have sufficient compensation for a pawn.} g6 $5 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Ge7h4] Taking full control of the [f5]-square.} 14. Bh6 (14. Bg5 {is dubious due to} Nh5 {.}) 14... Rfe8 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Nxg6 ({A way to win back the pawn.} 16. Qxd5 Bxh4 {and White's compensation is dubious.}) 16... hxg6 17. Qxd5 Qc6 {With equal chances.} *

