1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. a4 {A thematic move which we often see in this line. White is not only taking some space but prevents ...[b5] ideas and gives a retreat square for the [c4]-bishop.} O-O (7... O-O {Now,} 8. h3 {transposes to 7.h3.}) 8. Bd2 $5 h6 $5 {[%cal Gc8e6]} (8... h6 {Preparing ...Be6. Now,} 9. h3 {transposes here.}) 9. Nd5 {We have a standard response.} Nxd5 10. Bxd5 Be6 11. c3 ({Or} 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. c3 d5 {with a nice centre. ...[Qe8] and ...[Rd8] could be played next.}) 11... Bxd5 12. exd5 Nb8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf7f5] Now, our plan is obvious: to push ...[f5] and regroup the knight via [d7].} *

