1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. Bg5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gg5f6] With the idea of taking on [f6] and occupying the [d5]-square comfortably.} O-O 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Nd5 g6 {[%cal Gf6g7,Gf7f5] My suggestion, which is not the most played, but I like it because it offers a clear plan: we want to put our bishop on [g7] and push ...[f5].} 10. c3 Bg7 11. a4 {White's play will obviously be on the queenside.} Kh8 {Some prophylaxis is needed before proceeding with ...[f5].} 12. Qd2 Bd7 13. b4 f5 {This brings us to an interesting position where White is trying to put pressure on the queenside while we play on the kingside.} 14. b5 {This is possible, but there's a problem.} Na5 {White will hardly have any play on the queenside now.} 15. Ba2 fxe4 16. dxe4 Rxf3 {Removing one of the few defenders of the king.} 17. gxf3 Bh3 {[%csl Rf1,Rg1]} 18. Rfd1 (18. Kh1 Bxf1 19. Rxf1 Qh4 {with a very pleasant position. White's king is weakened, and we have easy play with ...[Bh6] and ...[Rf8] putting further pressure.}) 18... Qh4 {[%cal Ga8f8,Gg7h6] With great compensation for an exchange. Our knight is holding the queenside so the rest of our pieces can be brought to the kingside. ...[Bf6] and ...[Rf8] will follow next.} *

