1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. Ng5 {The most popular by far. White's idea is to attack [f7] to win time for [f4].} O-O 8. f4 Bg4 {We are following a well-known theoretical line.} 9. Qe1 exf4 10. Bxf4 Nd4 11. Qd2 Qd7 {[%cal Gb7b5] Connecting the rooks and threatening ...[b5] at some point.} 12. Be3 {A try to get rid of our strong [Nd4].} (12. h3 {gives nothing as after} Be6 13. Nxe6 fxe6 {, we have comfortable play. The light-squared bishop will be neutralized by means of ...[d5], and ...[Nh5] is always unpleasant for White, forcing them to make a decision with the dark-squared bishop.}) 12... Be6 $5 {The [g4]-square can be used for our knight, especially with the bishop on [e3]. Besides, it is a good idea to retreat on this diagonal and offer an exchange of bishops.} 13. h3 ({Preventing ...Ng4 but losing time.} 13. Rae1 Ng4 {⇆ and White needs to make a decision about that bishop.}) 13... d5 {We are fully ready to strike in the centre.} 14. exd5 Bxd5 15. Qf2 {[%csl Gd4]} Bc6 16. a4 b6 {Our pieces are nicely placed, and we have nothing to worry about.} *

