1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. Ng5 {The most popular by far. White's idea is to attack [f7] to win time for [f4].} O-O 8. f4 Bg4 {We are following a well-known theoretical line.} 9. Qe1 exf4 10. Bxf4 Nd4 11. Qd2 Qd7 {[%cal Gb7b5] Connecting the rooks and threatening ...[b5] at some point.} 12. Be3 {A try to get rid of our strong [Nd4].} (12. h3 {gives nothing as after} Be6 13. Nxe6 fxe6 {, we have comfortable play. The light-squared bishop will be neutralized by means of ...[d5], and ...[Nh5] is always unpleasant for White, forcing them to make a decision with the dark-squared bishop.}) 12... Be6 $5 {The [g4]-square can be used for our knight, especially with the bishop on [e3]. Besides, it is a good idea to retreat on this diagonal and offer an exchange of bishops.} 13. Nxe6 ({Taking the bishop is always an option, but here we have a very concrete way how to deal with it.} 13. Bxd4 {is not an independent idea as after} cxd4 14. Nxe6 fxe6 {, it transposes.}) 13... fxe6 {[%cal Gf6g4]} 14. Bxd4 {White's idea, combined with their next move.} cxd4 15. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2d4] Posing the question of how we will protect our pawn.} Kh8 $1 {Removing our king from the unpleasant diagonal is strong. The question is what happens if White goes through with their threat.} 16. Nf4 {This is a better try.} d5 17. exd5 exd5 18. Bb3 {It is true that our pawn structure is not ideal, but at the same time, it allows us to control many squares and gives interesting dynamic possibilities. Meanwhile, White has a very passive bishop now and no clear way how to attack our doubled pawns.} a5 {Forcing White's a-pawn to move.} 19. a4 {[%csl Rb3] Now, the bishop is completely blocked by its own pawns.} Bb4 20. Qf2 {Here we have plenty of interesting continuations, but I really like one.} g5 $5 {Forcing the white knight to go to a passive square.} 21. Ne2 {[%csl Re2]} Bd6 {[%cal Gd6h2,Gf6g4] The bishop did its job on [b4] and is now coming back to target [h2].} 22. Qxd4 (22. Nxd4 {is a huge mistake due to} Bxh2+ {+ -+ .}) 22... Qe7 23. Kh1 Bc5 {With excellent play on the dark squares. For example:} 24. Qc3 {Here, we can already force a draw if we want to.} Bb4 $10 {[%cal Gc3d4,Gb4c5]} (24... Bb4 {And} 25. Qd4 Bc5 {with a repetition. White has had to find a bunch of very good moves in the line to make a draw.}) *

