1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. Ng5 {The most popular by far. White's idea is to attack [f7] to win time for [f4].} O-O 8. f4 Bg4 {We are following a well-known theoretical line.} 9. Qe1 exf4 10. Bxf4 Nd4 11. Qd2 Qd7 {[%cal Gb7b5] Connecting the rooks and threatening ...[b5] at some point.} 12. a4 $5 {A thematic move in this opening. The main goal is to prevent Black's possible expansion with ...[b5].} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] This is quite rare in this position. We still want to organise ...[b5], and we delay the most tempting ...[h6] for now.} 13. a5 {Preventing our idea.} Rae8 $1 {The last piece enters the game.} 14. h3 {This has never been met in practice, but we should know how to react.} Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gh7h6]} ({...h6 is a threat now.} 14... Be6 15. e5 {leads to unnecessary complications.}) 15. Kh2 (15. e5 {here is less effective due to} dxe5 16. Bxe5 Qd8 $1 {preventing any sacrifices on [f6].}) 15... h6 16. Nf3 Bxf3 17. gxf3 {And here we can continue with a typical manoeuvre.} Nh5 {[%csl Rf4]} 18. Be3 Bh4 {Once again, our passive bishop can comfortably come to [h4].} 19. f4 Kh7 $1 {Removing the king from [a2]-[g8] diagonal and preparing ...[f5]. The king plays an important role here as, in some lines, we will need him to protect the [h6]-pawn.} (19... Kh8 {is playable but less precise.} 20. Nd5 {is not the best reaction from White due to} f5 {⇆ 20.f5 Qe7 21.Bxd4 cxd4 22.Nd5 Qe5+ 23.Kg1 and now we don't have ...[g6] as in our line. After 23...[Rg8] 24. [Rf3] [Rc8] , the position is still complicated, but I prefer to have the king on [h7].}) 20. f5 {To prevent any ...[f5] business from us.} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7e5] White has just given the [e5]-square so we can nicely activate our queen.} 21. Bxd4 cxd4 22. Nd5 Qe5+ 23. Kg1 g6 $132 {[%csl Gh6] We see why it was important to have the king on [h7]!} *

