ise our knight. For example,} Bd8 {is now met by} 15. b4 $1 {, and White gets play on the queenside.}) 14... h6 $1 {[%csl Rg5] After improving all our pieces, we are finally ready to chase White's unpleasant knight and force some pawn structure changes.} 15. Nf3 Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 Bh3 {[%csl Rf1,Rg2] Our bishop stands very nicely here controlling the [f1]- and [g2]-squares, making it difficult for White to consolidate pieces for an attack.} 17. Rfd1 {This allows a nice resource that forces a draw.} Ng4 (17... Ng4 {This allows us to make a draw if we want to. After} 18. fxg4 Qxg4+ 19. Kh1 Qf3+ {, White cannot avoid the perpetual check.}) 18. Kh1 {A way to avoid immediate draw.} Ne5 {[%csl Gc4,Gf3]} 19. Bxh6 {Tempting, but we keep everything under control after a cold-blooded reply.} Kh7 (19... gxh6 {is a very bad idea as after} 20. Qxh6 {, we cannot defend our open king.}) 20. Bf4 Nxf3 {[%cal Gd7g4] Winning back the pawn and planning to bring more pieces towards the white king next.} *

