1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. O-O ({Again,} 6. Nd5 {is pure transposition to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 6... Nf6 {Here, White has tried many moves.} 7. Ng5 {The most popular by far. White's idea is to attack [f7] to win time for [f4].} O-O 8. f4 Bg4 {We are following a well-known theoretical line.} 9. Qe1 exf4 10. Bxf4 Nd4 11. Qd2 Qd7 {[%cal Gb7b5] Connecting the rooks and threatening ...[b5] at some point.} 12. a4 $5 {A thematic move in this opening. The main goal is to prevent Black's possible expansion with ...[b5].} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] This is quite rare in this position. We still want to organise ...[b5], and we delay the most tempting ...[h6] for now.} 13. a5 {Preventing our idea.} Rae8 $1 {The last piece enters the game.} 14. Be3 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} (14. Be3 {White is trying to organise b4 to destabilise our knight. For example,} Bd8 {is now met by} 15. b4 $1 {, and White gets play on the queenside.}) 14... h6 $1 {[%csl Rg5] After improving all our pieces, we are finally ready to chase White's unpleasant knight and force some pawn structure changes.} 15. Nf3 Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 Bh3 {[%csl Rf1,Rg2] Our bishop stands very nicely here controlling the [f1]- and [g2]-squares, making it difficult for White to consolidate pieces for an attack.} 17. Rfd1 {This allows a nice resource.} Ng4 (17... Ng4 {This allows us to make a draw if we want to. After} 18. fxg4 Qxg4+ 19. Kh1 Qf3+ {, White cannot avoid the perpetual check.}) 18. Kh1 {A way to avoid immediate draw.} Ne5 {[%csl Gc4,Gf3]} 19. Qf2 Bg5 {[%cal Gg5e3,Ge3g5] A thematic move in this opening. If we have a chance, it is always good to exchange our passive dark-squared bishop.} 20. f4 {This demands some precision.} Nxc4 {The right way to continue!} 21. fxg5 Nxe3 22. Qxe3 hxg5 23. Qxg5 Re5 {[%csl Gh3] With a comfortable game.} *

