1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6,Gf3e5] This doesn't make much sense to me as the bishop doesn't belong on [b5], in my opinion. But it does pose a threat that is easy to parry.} d6 {[%cal Gd6e5]} 5. O-O Nf6 6. d3 Be7 {Very unclear what the bishop is doing on [b5]. A very logical move would be [Bc4]! Obviously, that would just lose a tempo compared to the main line.} 7. Bg5 {Actually, there is a blitz game, Caruana-Carlsen, which was played here in 2013!} a6 $1 {I like this move. White has two options: taking on [c6], which would reinforce Black's centre, or retreating with the bishop, which would allow Black to expand on the queenside. Either way, it sounds like a good deal for Black.} (7... O-O 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Nd5 Be6 10. Bc4 g6 {is how the game continued, and it is perfectly playable for Black.}) 8. Bc4 ({After} 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 {followed by castle, it's hard to come up with a constructive plan for White while Black will slowly but surely prepare the ...[f5] push.}) 8... b5 9. Bb3 O-O 10. Bxf6 {What else? That was the main idea of [Bg5], taking on [f6] and getting even more control over the light squares in the centre. Looks pretty artificial to me, as White already had firm control of those squares, just giving away the dark-square bishop for no particular reason.} Bxf6 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5 Rb8 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gg7g6] Avoiding any business with [Nxf6] followed by [Bd5], which would pin the [c6]-knight.} *

