1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Nd5 {It is always a bit dubious to move the same piece twice in the opening, and this is no exception.} Nf6 5. Bc4 Be7 {[%cal Gf6e4] Pretty standard development from our side and nothing to worry about. Now we threaten to take the pawn on [e4].} (5... Nxe4 $6 {would give White too much play.} 6. d4 $1 {Opening the position and giving White a great initiative.}) 6. Nxf6+ (6. d3 d6 7. c3 Nxd5 8. Bxd5 O-O {and ...[Be6] will come next challenging the strong bishop on [d5]. Black is OK.}) 6... Bxf6 {The knight on [b1] has moved three times to exchange itself for the [g8] knight, which only moved once. This cannot be a good deal for White!} 7. d3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. O-O Be6 $1 {[%cal Ge6c4,Gc4e6] Challenging the light-squared bishop is very often a good idea in such a position.} 10. Bxe6 fxe6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ge5d4] Those doubled central pawns may look a bit weak, but they actually control crucial squares in the centre and are easy to defend.} 11. b4 {Trying something on the queenside makes a lot of sense as the centre is locked down.} cxb4 12. cxb4 b5 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gc6b4] I like this move stopping White's action on the queenside and gaining space.} 13. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3e6]} Qd7 {[%cal Ga7a5]} 14. a4 a5 {A very nice and typical trick solving Black's issues on the queenside.} 15. axb5 (15. bxa5 Rxa5 {pinning the pawn on [a4] and making sure we can liquidate it on the very next move.}) 15... Nxb4 {[%cal Gd7b5]} 16. Bd2 Qxb5 {Trading [b5] for [e6] is certainly not a bad deal. Black is completely fine.} *

