1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. Nd2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3d5] A very interesting positional idea reinforcing the control of the [d5]-square and making sure that this square will be occupied by a white piece. It was very popular in the early 2000s and played by the likes of Kasparov, Ivanchuk, Kramnik, Anand, Leko...} Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Ge7g5] Not the most popular but my favourite. The knight is heading to [b6], but the main point is to clear the diagonal [d8]-[h4] for our bad bishop on [e7] and exchange it via [g5].} 8. Nd5 {It feels a bit too early to occupy that square, but Black still has to be precise.} Nb6 9. Nxb6 axb6 10. c3 O-O 11. Ne3 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5]} Bg5 {As planned.} 12. O-O Bd7 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gb6b5]} 13. Bd2 (13. a4 Ne7 {and we can prepare ...[b5] by the means of ...[Qe8].}) (13. Qh5 {is a move suggested by the engine but it fails to impress.} g6 14. Qe2 Ne7 {and we will just continue with the plan we started with 12...Bd7.}) 13... Ne7 {[%cal Gb6b5] I really like starting the expansion on the queenside, as it will create some early headaches for White.} 14. a4 Qe8 $1 {[%cal Gd7a4,Gb6b5] Attacking [a4] and insisting on playing ...[b5].} 15. Bb3 b5 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Bxg5 Nc7 {[%cal Gc7e6] Bishops are not helping White in such closed positions. Black is fine in this strategically complex battle.} *

