1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. Nd2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3d5] A very interesting positional idea reinforcing the control of the [d5]-square and making sure that this square will be occupied by a white piece. It was very popular in the early 2000s and played by the likes of Kasparov, Ivanchuk, Kramnik, Anand, Leko...} Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Ge7g5] Not the most popular but my favourite. The knight is heading to [b6], but the main point is to clear the diagonal [d8]-[h4] for our bad bishop on [e7] and exchange it via [g5].} 8. a4 {This is rarely played in practice, but it makes sense. White takes space on the queenside and gives the bishop a retreat square. Moreover, as one of our ideas is to go ...[Nb6], the [a5] push can be annoying.} O-O 9. h4 {White's idea is to prevent our ...[Bg5] plan for now and probably try to organise some attack later on. The drawback of this move is that it is not clear where White's king is planning to go now.} Nb6 10. Ne3 (10. Ba2 {saves the bishop but loses time.} Kh8 {and if White allows, we will happily go for ...[f5] next.} 11. Ne3 a5 {preventing White's [a5] once and for all and liberating our [c6]-knight for some ...[Nb4] jumps.}) 10... Be6 ({The Bc4 is quite annoying, and as exchanging it for our knight is not the best, we still try to neutralise it by other means.} 10... Nxc4 {grabbing the bishop is not great due to} 11. dxc4 {and White takes full control of the [d5]-square and can get good play along the d-file.}) 11. Ncd5 {White's best try to take control over the [d5]-square.} Nb4 {A typical jump in this line once the white knight gets to [d5]. We will see this idea in some other lines as well. The fact that the white pawn is already on [a4] and there is no [a3] makes this move quite effective.} 12. Nxb4 cxb4 13. Bxe6 fxe6 {It might look like White achieved something by damaging our pawn structure, but in fact, we can easily protect our [b4] and [e6]-pawns, and in exchange, we have some play on the f and c-files.} 14. Qg4 {[%csl Re6] This can be simply met.} Rf6 15. h5 h6 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ga8f8] To stop the h-pawn. Our next moves should be ...[Qc7] and ...[Raf8] with an interesting position.} *

