lan for now and probably try to organise some attack later on. The drawback of this move is that it is not clear where White's king is planning to go now.} Nb6 10. Ne3 (10. Ba2 {saves the bishop but loses time.} Kh8 {and if White allows, we will happily go for ...[f5] next.} 11. Ne3 a5 {preventing White's [a5] once and for all and liberating our [c6]-knight for some ...[Nb4] jumps.}) 10... Be6 ({The Bc4 is quite annoying, and as exchanging it for our knight is not the best, we still try to neutralise it by other means.} 10... Nxc4 {grabbing the bishop is not great due to} 11. dxc4 {and White takes full control of the [d5]-square and can get good play along the d-file.}) 11. Ncd5 {White's best try to take control over the [d5]-square.} Nb4 {A typical jump in this line once the white knight gets to [d5]. We will see this idea in some other lines as well. The fact that the white pawn is already on [a4] and there is no [a3] makes this move quite effective.} 12. Nxb4 cxb4 13. Bxe6 fxe6 {It might look like White achieved something by damaging our pawn structure, but in fact, we can easily protect our [b4] and [e6]-pawns, and in exchange, we have some play on the f and c-files.} 14. a5 {A nice way to win a tempo on the knight and then attack the [b4]-pawn.} Nd7 15. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6]} (15. Bd2 Bxh4 $1 {hitting [f2]. White should not forget about that pawn! It is hanging at times.}) 15... h6 16. Bd2 {Right now we can't really protect the [b4]-pawn, but we have a way to get nice counterplay.} b3 17. cxb3 Bg5 {[%cal Gd7c5] ...[Nc5] is coming next if White doesn't castle.} 18. O-O Qe8 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gd7f6] Threatening to get back the [h5]-pawn with ...[Nf6]. Black has nice compensation.} *

