1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. Nd2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3d5] A very interesting positional idea reinforcing the control of the [d5]-square and making sure that this square will be occupied by a white piece. It was very popular in the early 2000s and played by the likes of Kasparov, Ivanchuk, Kramnik, Anand, Leko...} Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Ge7g5] Not the most popular but my favourite. The knight is heading to [b6], but the main point is to clear the diagonal [d8]-[h4] for our bad bishop on [e7] and exchange it via [g5].} 8. Ne3 {By far, the most played.} Nb6 9. O-O {The most popular continuation.} O-O 10. Ncd5 Nxd5 {As usual, we exchange one knight on [d5].} 11. Bxd5 Bg5 {Activating our passive bishop. Here, White has several possibilities, for example:} 12. c3 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5]} 13. Bb3 h6 {[%cal Gh6g5]} ({Not obligatory but always useful, as it protects the bishop on g5 and White won't have an unpleasant Qg4 or Qh5 with tempo on the bishop at any moment. For example,} 13... Be6 $2 {would just win a pawn for White.} 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Qg4 {hitting the bishop and the [e6]-pawn, and now we understand why ...[h6] is useful.}) 14. a4 Be6 $132 {With mutual chances.} *

