1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. Nd2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3d5] A very interesting positional idea reinforcing the control of the [d5]-square and making sure that this square will be occupied by a white piece. It was very popular in the early 2000s and played by the likes of Kasparov, Ivanchuk, Kramnik, Anand, Leko...} Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Ge7g5] Not the most popular but my favourite. The knight is heading to [b6], but the main point is to clear the diagonal [d8]-[h4] for our bad bishop on [e7] and exchange it via [g5].} 8. Ne3 {By far, the most played.} Nb6 9. Ned5 Nxd5 $1 {The most precise; we usually always exchange one knight immediately after the [Nd5] jump.} (9... O-O {I like less because after} 10. Nxb6 axb6 11. O-O Bg5 12. a4 {, White can apply some pressure.}) 10. Nxd5 O-O 11. O-O Be6 $1 {The best and the most logical. We need to finish our development.} 12. c3 {[%cal Rc6b4]} ({To avoid any ...Nb4 business. For example,} 12. a4 {can be traditionally met by} Nb4 {.}) 12... Na5 (12... Bg5 {works less well here due to} 13. Bxg5 Qxg5 14. Nc7 Bg4 15. Qc1 {⩲ and White can try to put some pressure in the endgame, consolidating with [f3] and preparing [b4].}) 13. f4 {Often seen in this line but not dangerous.} exf4 14. Bxf4 Bg5 15. Qd2 ({This leads to massive simplifications, but after} 15. Bg3 Bh4 {, the only way White can avoid the bishop exchange is by accepting draw by repetition.}) 15... Nxc4 16. dxc4 Bxf4 17. Rxf4 Bxd5 18. Qxd5 Qe7 {[%csl Rd6,Re4] Both sides have weaknesses} *

