[White "19) Anti-Sveshnikov 2.Nf3 - 3.Nc3 & 6.Nd2"]
[Black "3.Nc3 e5 4.Bc4 - 6.Nd2 & 8.Ne3 Nb6 9.Ned5 #2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B30"]
[PlyCount "38"]
[GameId "2123892872450859"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {A natural developing move that is popular at the highest level and must be taken very seriously. The main idea of this move order is to avoid the Sveshnikov.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4] Preventing [d4] at once and in the spirit of the Sveshnikov defence! We take firm control over the dark squares in the centre, but in compensation, White has excellent play on the light squares.} 4. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] By far the most popular, logical and obvious move, which takes control over the light squares in the centre and puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Be7 5. d3 (5. Nd5 {just transposes to 4.Nd5 after} Nf6 {.}) 5... d6 $1 {That's a very important move order trick preventing an early [Ng5].} (5... Nf6 $6 {is just incredibly dangerous for Black because of the idea found by my colleague from Team Magnus, the very creative Daniil Dubov.} 6. Ng5 $1 {hitting [f7]. Now} O-O {is forced, and now White has the very strong} 7. h4 $1 {launching a very strong attack on the kingside with [f4] ideas. You can't really get rid of that knight on [g5] as if you play ...[h6], White will just ignore it, and if you take the knight, it will open up the h-file, and Black will most likely be mated.}) 6. Nd2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3d5] A very interesting positional idea reinforcing the control of the [d5]-square and making sure that this square will be occupied by a white piece. It was very popular in the early 2000s and played by the likes of Kasparov, Ivanchuk, Kramnik, Anand, Leko...} Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Ge7g5] Not the most popular but my favourite. The knight is heading to [b6], but the main point is to clear the diagonal [d8]-[h4] for our bad bishop on [e7] and exchange it via [g5].} 8. Ne3 {By far, the most played.} Nb6 9. Ned5 Nxd5 $1 {The most precise; we usually always exchange one knight immediately after the [Nd5] jump.} (9... O-O {I like less because after} 10. Nxb6 axb6 11. O-O Bg5 12. a4 {, White can apply some pressure.}) 10. Nxd5 O-O 11. O-O Be6 $1 {The best and the most logical. We need to finish our development.} 12. f4 ({The most ambitious try.} 12. Be3 {is a slow developing move which can be met by our usual} Bg5 13. a4 Bxe3 14. Nxe3 {and now} Rb8 {is not a necessity, but it's a kind of useful move. Sometimes, we can try to prepare ...[a6]-...[b5] or go ...[Qg5] and avoid the [Nd5]-[Nc7] fork.} 15. Nd5 {Now, everything is playable. 15...[Ne7] seems to be the easiest, with a very solid position.Alternatively, White can go 15.c3 h6 . In this kind of position, we have time for slow improvements. 16.Qf3 Kh7 17.Nf5 Ne7 and of course, once the white knight jumps forward we should always try to exchange it.}) 12... exf4 13. Bxf4 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gd5] White's knight on [d5] is quite annoying, and we don't want to take it with the bishop, so this is a natural choice to force some exchanges} 14. Nxe7+ {We are not afraid to give away our dark-squared bishop, which was quite passive on [e7] anyway.} Qxe7 15. c3 Nc6 16. Bb5 {White wants to keep the two bishops.} Rad8 17. Qd2 f6 {After exchanging our dark-squared bishop, we do not mind placing our pawns on the dark-squares to consolidate the position and limit the possibilities of White's bishop.} 18. d4 cxd4 ({We can keep the tension and continue with} 18... Bf7 {attacking [e4], followed by} 19. Rfe1 a6 20. Bf1 Qd7 {with a solid position. If White pushes [d5], we will happily jump ...[Ne5], and otherwise, our idea is to go for ...[cxd4] and ...[d5].}) 19. cxd4 Bf7 $1 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gf8e8] Our only weakness is [d6], but White has no way to put pressure on it. Their central pawns are targeted by our pieces, and that gives us enough play.} *

