 O-O Be6 $1 {The best and the most logical. We need to finish our development.} 12. f4 ({The most ambitious try.} 12. Be3 {is a slow developing move which can be met by our usual} Bg5 13. a4 Bxe3 14. Nxe3 {and now} Rb8 {is not a necessity, but it's a kind of useful move. Sometimes, we can try to prepare ...[a6]-...[b5] or go ...[Qg5] and avoid the [Nd5]-[Nc7] fork.} 15. Nd5 {Now, everything is playable. 15...[Ne7] seems to be the easiest, with a very solid position.Alternatively, White can go 15.c3 h6 . In this kind of position, we have time for slow improvements. 16.Qf3 Kh7 17.Nf5 Ne7 and of course, once the white knight jumps forward we should always try to exchange it.}) 12... exf4 13. Bxf4 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gd5] White's knight on [d5] is quite annoying, and we don't want to take it with the bishop, so this is a natural choice to force some exchanges} 14. Nxe7+ {We are not afraid to give away our dark-squared bishop, which was quite passive on [e7] anyway.} Qxe7 15. c3 Nc6 16. Bb5 {White wants to keep the two bishops.} Ne5 {This alternative is also good. For example:} 17. d4 ({Or} 17. h3 Rac8 {with a possibility to continue with ...[c4] next.}) 17... cxd4 18. cxd4 ({White gets a nice centre, but we have a concrete way to deal with it.} 18. Qxd4 {is also playable, planning to put pressure on the [d6]-pawn, but the drawback of this move is that it allows our knight to stay on [e5].} a6 19. Be2 Rac8 {is an interesting way to simplify matters.} 20. Bxe5 {looks the most logical.} dxe5 21. Qxe5 Rc5 22. Qf4 Bc4 {and White is a pawn up, but we will soon put heavy pressure on it, and White will hardly be able to make any progress.}) 18... Ng6 19. Bg3 d5 {Asking White to make a decision.} 20. e5 {Probably the most natural.} Qb4 {However, White doesn't have any advantage as now the dark-squared bishop is limited by the pawns and our knight.} *

