1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. d3 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf1g2] A very unambitious try clearly indicating that White wants a King's Indian setup with reversed colours.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gd7d6,Gg8e7,Gf8g7] Obviously not the only move to have a good game as 3. d3 is not really threatening anything but the setups with the pawn on [e5] fit perfectly our Sveshnikov repertoire. We create a hole on [d5], which is incredibly difficult for White to take advantage of, but in the meantime, we have firm control over the dark squares in the centre. And last but not least, we are taking space, which will help us get a harmonious development.} 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 7. c3 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b4,Gc1e3] This is how the best players, including the strong Egyptian GM Amin Bassem, who has reached this position many times, are dealing with the line as White.} O-O 8. Be3 {[%csl Rc5] A very logical developing move attacking the [c5]-pawn.} b6 {[%cal Gd7d5] Keeping the option to go ...[d5] in one go.} 9. d4 exd4 $1 {[%cal Gg7b2] It's very important to open the [a1]-[h8] diagonal as now the [b2]-pawn is hanging if White takes on [c5].} 10. cxd4 d5 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Re4] Putting immense pressure on White's centre at once!} 11. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5e3]} 12. Bg5 {Already the only move in order to avoid material loss.} Nde7 13. Nc3 h6 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 {[%csl Gc8,Gg7][%cal Ge7f5] Black has bishops in an open position, which is generally promising.} *

