1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. d3 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf1g2] A very unambitious try clearly indicating that White wants a King's Indian setup with reversed colours.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gd7d6,Gg8e7,Gf8g7] Obviously not the only move to have a good game as 3. d3 is not really threatening anything but the setups with the pawn on [e5] fit perfectly our Sveshnikov repertoire. We create a hole on [d5], which is incredibly difficult for White to take advantage of, but in the meantime, we have firm control over the dark squares in the centre. And last but not least, we are taking space, which will help us get a harmonious development.} 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 7. c3 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b4,Gc1e3] This is how the best players, including the strong Egyptian GM Amin Bassem, who has reached this position many times, are dealing with the line as White.} O-O 8. Nbd2 {This is just poor. White is not threatening anything, and Black can proceed with the plan: bishop to [e6] followed by ...[d5] or ...[f5]. Generally, it is better to start with ...[h6] in order to avoid an annoying [Ng5] hitting the bishop.} d6 9. a4 h6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gd6d5]} 10. Nc4 {I still can see many games in my database, which is a bit confusing as Black seems better to my eyes and more importantly! my engine.} Be6 11. Nfd2 f5 {[%cal Gf5f4]} 12. f4 {Not much choice for White. This is the best way to prevent Black's ...[f4].} exf4 13. gxf4 Qd7 {[%cal Gd6d5,Ga8d8] Very logical and simple. Black coordinates their rook and prepares an action in the centre with ...[d5].} 14. Ne3 {Ok, that's not an impressive move, but that's the best I could find.} d5 $1 15. e5 ({After} 15. exd5 Nxd5 {, the [d3]-pawn is basically lost, sooner or later.}) 15... d4 16. Nec4 Rad8 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gd4c3] Once again, it will be very difficult for White to defend their [d3]-pawn, while we have developed our pieces in a very harmonious way.} *

