1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. d3 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf1g2] A very unambitious try clearly indicating that White wants a King's Indian setup with reversed colours.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gd7d6,Gg8e7,Gf8g7] Obviously not the only move to have a good game as 3. d3 is not really threatening anything but the setups with the pawn on [e5] fit perfectly our Sveshnikov repertoire. We create a hole on [d5], which is incredibly difficult for White to take advantage of, but in the meantime, we have firm control over the dark squares in the centre. And last but not least, we are taking space, which will help us get a harmonious development.} 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 7. c3 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b4,Gc1e3] This is how the best players, including the strong Egyptian GM Amin Bassem, who has reached this position many times, are dealing with the line as White.} O-O 8. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] The most popular.} d6 9. b4 a6 {[%cal Rb4b5] Our setup is so harmonious that we don't want to allow [b5], which would kick away our [c6]-knight.} 10. Nbd2 h6 {[%cal Gc8e6]} 11. Rb1 Be6 (11... Be6 {Looks like we are blundering the b7-pawn, but when White takes, after} 12. bxc5 dxc5 {, we are attacking the [d3]-pawn.}) 12. Re1 ({The immediate} 12. Bb2 {is met by} b5 $1 {, which is almost automatic when the bishop lands on [b2] as it makes it much more difficult for White to push the c-pawn.}) 12... Qc7 {[%cal Gc7b7]} 13. Bb2 b5 {[%cal Gb5c4]} 14. d4 {A logical way to proceed for White, trying to gain space in the centre.} exd4 15. cxd4 cxd4 16. Nb3 {[%cal Gb3d4,Gf3d4]} Bxb3 {Giving away the bishop pair but making it more difficult for White to get the pawn back.} 17. Qxb3 a5 {[%cal Ga5b4,Ga8a4] Black has a very good game.} *

