1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. g3 ({This is very similar to} 3. d3 {and will more likely than not transpose.}) 3... e5 (3... Nf6 4. d3 {takes us out of our repertoire.}) 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. a3 (6. d3 {transposes to 3.d3.}) 6... Nge7 7. c3 d6 8. b4 a6 {Not taking on [b4] as it would open the a-line for White's rook, but we also don't want White to play [b5] and kick our knight. So, the solution is very often ...[a6].} 9. d3 {It is pretty clear that White has to do [d3] at some point.} O-O {And we just transposed here!} *

