1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. b4 {The Delayed Wing Gambit. Maybe I just invented an opening name, but you got the idea! Honestly, my first impression was not to be very impressed with that move, but it is not as dumb as it looks.} cxb4 {Such early and unexpected gifts have to be taken!} 4. d4 (4. a3 e5 {actually transposes into this line covered via 2.b4.}) 4... d5 {Most straightforward and asking concrete questions to White.} 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. c4 $1 {White has to be active and create threats; otherwise, it is just a clear pawn up for Black.} bxc3 7. Nxc3 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5e1]} 8. Rb1 {A nice move to make! White ignores the [c3]-knight, en prise with a check.} e6 ({After} 8... Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 Qa3 10. d5 {, White gets a great initiative. Actually, even if the computer thinks that Black is holding, I would rather avoid that line for practical reasons!}) 9. Bd2 Qd8 {Again, we are safe on [d8] and avoided an early [d5].} 10. Bd3 Nf6 11. O-O Be7 {Simple and good. Hard to find any compensation for the missing pawn as White.} 12. Ne4 O-O 13. Rb3 {[%cal Gb3h3] With some help, White could get their rook shifting to the kingside.} Nd5 14. Qb1 h6 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] We do have a clear plan, and are a clear pawn up!} *

