1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. b4 {The Delayed Wing Gambit. Maybe I just invented an opening name, but you got the idea! Honestly, my first impression was not to be very impressed with that move, but it is not as dumb as it looks.} cxb4 {Such early and unexpected gifts have to be taken!} 4. d4 (4. a3 e5 {actually transposes into this line covered via 2.b4.}) 4... d5 {Most straightforward and asking concrete questions to White.} 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. c4 $1 {White has to be active and create threats; otherwise, it is just a clear pawn up for Black.} bxc3 7. Nxc3 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5e1]} 8. Rb1 {A nice move to make! White ignores the [c3]-knight, en prise with a check.} e6 ({After} 8... Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 Qa3 10. d5 {, White gets a great initiative. Actually, even if the computer thinks that Black is holding, I would rather avoid that line for practical reasons!}) 9. Bd2 Qd8 {Again, we are safe on [d8] and avoided an early [d5].} 10. Bb5 {The best option. White has to play actively in order to get back the pawn sacrificed on move 3.} Bd6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7c6]} 11. Ne4 Bc7 12. O-O Nge7 13. Bb4 {[%cal Gb4f8]} O-O 14. Ba3 {[%cal Ra3f8] White definitely has some play as the knight on [e7] being pinned is uncomfortable for Black.} a5 {[%cal Gc6b4] A very nice solution. After all, we are a pawn up and ready to give it back to get a better position.} 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Ne5 {[%cal Ga3e7,Ge5c6]} f6 {Very direct and good.} 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Nxc6 Bxh2+ $1 {[%cal Ge7c7,Gc7c6]} (18... Bxh2+ {A nice cheapo! After} 19. Kxh2 Qc7+ 20. Kg1 Qxc6 21. Qf3 Qd5 {, White still have to work to prove they can make a draw.}) *

