1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. b4 {The Delayed Wing Gambit. Maybe I just invented an opening name, but you got the idea! Honestly, my first impression was not to be very impressed with that move, but it is not as dumb as it looks.} cxb4 {Such early and unexpected gifts have to be taken!} 4. d4 (4. a3 e5 {actually transposes into this line covered via 2.b4.}) 4... d5 {Most straightforward and asking concrete questions to White.} 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. c4 $1 {White has to be active and create threats; otherwise, it is just a clear pawn up for Black.} bxc3 7. Nxc3 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5e1]} 8. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2a5] The most popular move, which makes perfect sense.} e6 {[%cal Gf8b4,Gg8f6] As usual, we prevent the [d5] push and proceed with our standard development.} 9. Bc4 {[%cal Gd4d5]} (9. Rb1 Qd8 {transposes into 8. Rb1.}) 9... Bb4 {[%cal Gb4c3]} 10. Qb3 Nf6 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 {We have to give away our bishop pair, but we are still a healthy pawn up and our king is already safe.} Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Qc7 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc8c7,Gc8d7]} 14. d5 {Trying to create immediate play while Black is not fully developed yet.} Nxd5 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Qxd5 Ne7 {[%cal Gc7c3,Ge7d5]} 17. Qd4 f6 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ge7d5] White failed. Black still has a healthy extra pawn.} *

