1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. b3 {Such moves always fail to impress me. You can't really pretend to fight for an opening advantage with such an approach.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gd6e5] Sveshnikov style! We create a firm grip on the dark squares in the centre and make White regret choosing the diagonal [a1]-[h8] for their bishop.} 4. Bb5 {Playing a weird Rossolimo, but again, [e5] was more useful than [b3].} (4. Bc4 {is obviously possible, but it will just be a transposition to the line with 3.Nc3 e5.} d6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. d3 Nf6 {and we get the same kind of position as in 3.Nc3 e5, but White lost a tempo with [b3], and therefore, this is a very good version for Black.}) 4... Nge7 {[%cal Ge7c6]} 5. O-O a6 {Simple and good!} 6. Bxc6 ({If} 6. Bc4 b5 $1 7. Bd5 d6 {intending ...[Nxd5] and we will get the bishop pair while White was busy moving around with their light-squared bishop.}) 6... Nxc6 {[%csl Gc8,Gf8][%cal Gd7d6,Gf8e7,Gf7f5] Black is simply better thanks to their bishop pair and an active plan at their disposal. The dynamic ...[f5] will be surprisingly simple to achieve.} *

