1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. b3 {Such moves always fail to impress me. You can't really pretend to fight for an opening advantage with such an approach.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gd6e5] Sveshnikov style! We create a firm grip on the dark squares in the centre and make White regret choosing the diagonal [a1]-[h8] for their bishop.} 4. Bb2 d6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Bc4 Nf6 {As simple as that, it is pretty difficult for White to make sense of their setup.} 7. h3 O-O 8. d3 a6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb7b5]} 9. a4 Be6 {[%cal Gd8d7] A pretty obvious developing move but nevertheless a novelty.} 10. Ng5 {This is generally why Black prepares ...[Be6] with ...[h6] first.} Qd7 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf7e6] Here, we can allow [Nxe6] as the white bishop will be awkwardly placed on [c4].} 11. Nxe6 $4 fxe6 {[%csl Rd3,Rb3,Rc4][%cal Gd6d5] The bishop is stuck by his own pawns on [d3] and [b3].} *

