1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. b3 {Such moves always fail to impress me. You can't really pretend to fight for an opening advantage with such an approach.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gd6e5] Sveshnikov style! We create a firm grip on the dark squares in the centre and make White regret choosing the diagonal [a1]-[h8] for their bishop.} 4. Bb2 d6 5. Bb5 ({This seems to be the most challenging. Some strong players played different alternatives, such as 5.Nc3 or 5. Bc4, but Black is just doing more than fine by pretty simple means. Again, White's} 5. Bc4 {setup makes little sense to me.} Be7 6. O-O Nf6 7. d3 O-O {is a very comfortable position for Black with a misplaced bishop on [b2] for White.}) 5... Nge7 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5]} 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7,Gf3g5] Now that makes more sense than on the previous move, as [Ng5] is a real threat.} h6 7. O-O g5 $1 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg5g4] A nice active way of finishing our development and already starting an attack.} 8. Ne1 {[%cal Gd1h5]} h5 $1 ({Note that we can do such aggressive stuff as White is not able to counterattack in the centre. We will keep going in the same spirit.} 8... Bg7 9. Qh5 {unnecessarily gives the queen a good square.}) 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5 f5 {[%cal Gc6e7]} 12. exf5 Bxf5 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gc6e7,Ge8c8] Yes, Black is also allowed to castle long in the Sicilian!} *

