1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. b3 {Such moves always fail to impress me. You can't really pretend to fight for an opening advantage with such an approach.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gd6e5] Sveshnikov style! We create a firm grip on the dark squares in the centre and make White regret choosing the diagonal [a1]-[h8] for their bishop.} 4. Bb2 d6 5. Bb5 ({This seems to be the most challenging. Some strong players played different alternatives, such as 5.Nc3 or 5. Bc4, but Black is just doing more than fine by pretty simple means. Again, White's} 5. Bc4 {setup makes little sense to me.} Be7 6. O-O Nf6 7. d3 O-O {is a very comfortable position for Black with a misplaced bishop on [b2] for White.}) 5... Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] I really didn't know what to suggest as both alternatives seemed completely fine to me.} 6. d3 Be7 7. O-O O-O {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc6d4] It is time to get rid of their light-squared bishop for White as it is poorly placed on [b5].} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nbd2 Ne8 {[%cal Gf7f5] We have a solid control on the centre, so it is time to launch an attack on the kingside.} 10. Ne1 {[%cal Gf2f4]} Bg5 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gg5f4] We say no to counterplay with [f4]! Problems remain the same for White.} *

