1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. a3 {The idea is crystal-clear: White is ready to give up a pawn on the queenside in order to occupy the centre.} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] Immediately attacking the centre makes the most sense to me in order to punish White as soon as possible.} 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {[%cal Gc5b4,Gf8b4] Not the most popular, but again, we occupy the centre as soon as possible and play in the spirit of our beloved Sveshnikov. Last but not least, we are preventing [b4] as we can take twice and develop the bishop!} 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6,Gf3e5]} d6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8]} 6. b4 {White achieved the idea of playing [b4] in decent conditions, but that doesn't mean they gained an edge.} cxb4 7. axb4 Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 8. O-O O-O {[%cal Gc6b4] Now we are threatening to take on [b4], and the efficient way to prevent it is to take on [c6]. It also allows White to follow up with the central push [d4].} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. d4 Qc7 {[%csl Rc8,Re7][%cal Gc8g4,Ga7a5] We don't give away the centre that easily. We have bishops; you may argue that our [a7]-pawn is weak, but it will soon land on [a5] and be exchanged.} *

