1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. a3 {The idea is crystal-clear: White is ready to give up a pawn on the queenside in order to occupy the centre.} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] Immediately attacking the centre makes the most sense to me in order to punish White as soon as possible.} 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {[%cal Gc5b4,Gf8b4] Not the most popular, but again, we occupy the centre as soon as possible and play in the spirit of our beloved Sveshnikov. Last but not least, we are preventing [b4] as we can take twice and develop the bishop!} 5. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] The most played and most logical as White is trying to occupy the light squares in the centre.} Nxe4 $1 {This typical trick is working very well in this case.} 6. Bxf7+ $2 {That leads to an immediate disaster for White.} Kxf7 7. Nxe4 d5 {[%csl Gc5,Gc8,Gd5,Ge5,Gf8][%cal Ge5e4] We got the centre, the bishop pair and the initiative!} 8. Neg5+ Kg8 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gh7h6]} 9. d3 h6 10. Nh3 Bg4 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gd8f6,Gc6d4] Black is already winning!} *

