1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. a3 {The idea is crystal-clear: White is ready to give up a pawn on the queenside in order to occupy the centre.} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] Immediately attacking the centre makes the most sense to me in order to punish White as soon as possible.} 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {[%cal Gc5b4,Gf8b4] Not the most popular, but again, we occupy the centre as soon as possible and play in the spirit of our beloved Sveshnikov. Last but not least, we are preventing [b4] as we can take twice and develop the bishop!} 5. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] The most played and most logical as White is trying to occupy the light squares in the centre.} Nxe4 $1 {This typical trick is working very well in this case.} 6. Nxe4 d5 7. Bb5 (7. Bd3 c4 $1 {is a typical trick and a very good one for Black.}) 7... dxe4 8. Nxe5 Qd5 {[%cal Gd5e5]} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Be2 Bd6 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6][%cal Ge8g8,Gc8f5] We got more space and active pieces, which fully compensates for our damaged pawn structure.} *

