1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. c4 {[%cal Gd2d4] Intending to go 4.d4 and get a nice Maroczy as White.} e5 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gc5d4,Gg8e7,Ge5d4] Obviously, we prevent that, and compared to positions in the Closed Sicilian, White won't get [f4] easily. Meanwhile, we are more flexible, as our knight is not yet on [f6] and we will develop it on [e7].} 4. Nc3 g6 5. d3 Bg7 6. g3 {Both sides are developing in a logical way. It is a slow game without any early contacts, so the move orders don't really matter.} Nge7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O d6 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gc6d4] And now Black will have to make a decision on their plan.} 9. Be3 Nd4 {[%cal Gc8g4,Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Ga8b8] I like this somehow. We do put a piece in the centre, ...[Bg4] could be next, and more importantly, we will start expanding on the queenside before starting any kingside action.} (9... f5 {is very playable, but I think it gives away our intentions too early.}) (9... h6 {followed by ...[Kh7] if the [h6]-pawn is attacked twice, and preparing ...[Be6] and ...[f5], is a nice way to proceed on the kingside.}) 10. h3 Bd7 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Ge7c6] Black has a very comfortable game with a clear plan.} *

