1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. Bc4 {Looks like a beginner's move, but it became very popular recently as the very creative and Team Magnus colleague! Dutch GM Jorden Van Foreest tried it vs Praggnanandhaa in the Wijk Aan Zee super tournament in 2022.} (3. Be2 {is simply poor and very unambitious.} Nf6 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {The usual antidote. We still want the Sveshnikov structure.} 5. O-O Be7 {It's unclear what is next for White. It is similar to the 3.Nc3 e5 line, but White played it poorly with the bishop on [e2], which will probably be moved again to the more active square [c4], and therefore we will be tempo up compared to that line. Meanwhile, we'll continue with ...[d6] and castle.}) 3... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4]} ({Not the most popular choice by far, but that's my favourite, once again challenging White in the centre right away!} 3... e6 4. O-O d5 5. Bb5 {is how the game went in Wijk, and this is indeed very interesting.}) 4. Nc3 e6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({It is too early for} 4... Nxe4 $6 {as after} 5. Bxf7+ Kxf7 6. Nxe4 {threatening [Nxc5] and intending [d4], White has the initiative.}) 5. d4 {Trying to transpose into an Open Sicilian, but that doesn't fit our plans!} Nxe4 $1 6. Nxe4 d5 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qc4 {[%csl Gc8,Gf8][%cal Gc4f1] Black is doing very well as White has a hard time castling, and we do have the bishop pair.} *

