1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. Bc4 {Looks like a beginner's move, but it became very popular recently as the very creative and Team Magnus colleague! Dutch GM Jorden Van Foreest tried it vs Praggnanandhaa in the Wijk Aan Zee super tournament in 2022.} (3. Be2 {is simply poor and very unambitious.} Nf6 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {The usual antidote. We still want the Sveshnikov structure.} 5. O-O Be7 {It's unclear what is next for White. It is similar to the 3.Nc3 e5 line, but White played it poorly with the bishop on [e2], which will probably be moved again to the more active square [c4], and therefore we will be tempo up compared to that line. Meanwhile, we'll continue with ...[d6] and castle.}) 3... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4]} ({Not the most popular choice by far, but that's my favourite, once again challenging White in the centre right away!} 3... e6 4. O-O d5 5. Bb5 {is how the game went in Wijk, and this is indeed very interesting.}) 4. Nc3 e6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({It is too early for} 4... Nxe4 $6 {as after} 5. Bxf7+ Kxf7 6. Nxe4 {threatening [Nxc5] and intending [d4], White has the initiative.}) 5. d4 {Trying to transpose into an Open Sicilian, but that doesn't fit our plans!} Nxe4 $1 6. Nxe4 d5 7. dxc5 {Very natural but a novelty. I have to admit that the line is quite rare.} dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. Nd2 f5 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gf5e4] We do have a strong centre, and we are planning to keep it. In the long term, the [c5]-pawn could become a weakness.} 10. Nb3 e5 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Ge4,Ge5,Gf5][%cal Gc8e6] Now it all become obvious. Black has at least no problems.} *

