1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. Bc4 {Looks like a beginner's move, but it became very popular recently as the very creative and Team Magnus colleague! Dutch GM Jorden Van Foreest tried it vs Praggnanandhaa in the Wijk Aan Zee super tournament in 2022.} (3. Be2 {is simply poor and very unambitious.} Nf6 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {The usual antidote. We still want the Sveshnikov structure.} 5. O-O Be7 {It's unclear what is next for White. It is similar to the 3.Nc3 e5 line, but White played it poorly with the bishop on [e2], which will probably be moved again to the more active square [c4], and therefore we will be tempo up compared to that line. Meanwhile, we'll continue with ...[d6] and castle.}) 3... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4]} ({Not the most popular choice by far, but that's my favourite, once again challenging White in the centre right away!} 3... e6 4. O-O d5 5. Bb5 {is how the game went in Wijk, and this is indeed very interesting.}) 4. d3 e6 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5] Now this is the right timing. We managed to avoid Jorden's idea of playing without [d3].} 5. O-O d5 6. Bb5 Bd7 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gd7c6]} ({Simple and good!} 6... dxe4 {gives White too much play, in my opinion.} 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 {(and Black is facing practical and objective difficulties, as [Nxc6] is an annoying threat.)}) 7. Re1 Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8] We don't need to do anything special as White seems to threaten to push [e5] but actually they are not.} 8. c3 (8. e5 Nxe5 {just wins a pawn for Black.}) 8... O-O {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] Very playable and completely new territory. Black is definitely not worse and has a clear plan of expanding on the queenside.} *

