1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. Bc4 {Looks like a beginner's move, but it became very popular recently as the very creative and Team Magnus colleague! Dutch GM Jorden Van Foreest tried it vs Praggnanandhaa in the Wijk Aan Zee super tournament in 2022.} (3. Be2 {is simply poor and very unambitious.} Nf6 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {The usual antidote. We still want the Sveshnikov structure.} 5. O-O Be7 {It's unclear what is next for White. It is similar to the 3.Nc3 e5 line, but White played it poorly with the bishop on [e2], which will probably be moved again to the more active square [c4], and therefore we will be tempo up compared to that line. Meanwhile, we'll continue with ...[d6] and castle.}) 3... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4]} ({Not the most popular choice by far, but that's my favourite, once again challenging White in the centre right away!} 3... e6 4. O-O d5 5. Bb5 {is how the game went in Wijk, and this is indeed very interesting.}) 4. e5 {It might not be the most popular, but it definitely feels like the most challenging for Black.} Ng4 5. Bxf7+ {By far the most played according to my database, but Black is simply better, in my opinion, after the complications.} Kxf7 6. Ng5+ Kg8 7. Qxg4 Nxe5 {[%csl Gf8,Gc8,Gd7,Ge7] Obviously, it looks very dangerous for Black, but with more pawns in the centre and the bishop pair, we can definitely take over if our king becomes safe. Spoiler alert: he does become safe!} 8. Qe4 (8. Qf5 d6 {protecting the knight on [e5] and attacking the queen in one go!}) 8... Nc6 9. Qf5 {[%cal Gf5f7,Gf5c5] A double threat which looks quite annoying, but we just sacrifice a pawn for the initiative.} Qe8 10. Qxc5 b6 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1,Rc5,Rg5][%cal Gc8b7,Ge8g6] The compensation for the pawn is rather intuitive: Black is getting active play with ...[Bb7] and ...[Qg6] while White's army is disorganised the queen moving around and a knight on [g5] and underdeveloped.} 11. Qc4+ e6 12. O-O d5 13. Qe2 Nd4 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ge8g6] Black's position plays itself!} 14. Qd1 e5 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf5g4,Gh7h6] Now, this is just a very strong initiative for Black and an objectively much better position.} *

