1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. Bc4 {Looks like a beginner's move, but it became very popular recently as the very creative and Team Magnus colleague! Dutch GM Jorden Van Foreest tried it vs Praggnanandhaa in the Wijk Aan Zee super tournament in 2022.} (3. Be2 {is simply poor and very unambitious.} Nf6 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {The usual antidote. We still want the Sveshnikov structure.} 5. O-O Be7 {It's unclear what is next for White. It is similar to the 3.Nc3 e5 line, but White played it poorly with the bishop on [e2], which will probably be moved again to the more active square [c4], and therefore we will be tempo up compared to that line. Meanwhile, we'll continue with ...[d6] and castle.}) 3... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4]} ({Not the most popular choice by far, but that's my favourite, once again challenging White in the centre right away!} 3... e6 4. O-O d5 5. Bb5 {is how the game went in Wijk, and this is indeed very interesting.}) 4. e5 {It might not be the most popular, but it definitely feels like the most challenging for Black.} Ng4 5. Qe2 f6 {A fresh approach immediately challenging the White's pawn on [e5].} 6. d4 {Trying to open up the game while Black doesn't seem ready yet.} cxd4 {[%cal Gf6e5]} 7. exf6 Nxf6 8. O-O {[%cal Gf1d1]} e6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 9. Rd1 {It's time for White to get the pawn back.} d5 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Rxd4 Bc5 {[%cal Ge8g8] An important tempo. We just want to castle next, and we will do very well.} 12. Bb5+ $5 Bd7 {Play becomes tactical, but we are in control!} 13. Qxe6+ ({After} 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. Rd3 O-O {, all our pieces are developed while White still have some work to achieve the same. We are clearly doing well here. ...[Ne4] would unleash all kinds of hell on [f2].}) 13... Kf8 $1 {[%cal Gc5d4,Gd7e6,Gd7b5]} 14. Bxd7 Bxd4 15. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4d6]} Bc5 {[%cal Gd8b6] Black has won the exchange for a pawn and has better chances.} *

