1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. Bc4 {Looks like a beginner's move, but it became very popular recently as the very creative and Team Magnus colleague! Dutch GM Jorden Van Foreest tried it vs Praggnanandhaa in the Wijk Aan Zee super tournament in 2022.} (3. Be2 {is simply poor and very unambitious.} Nf6 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {The usual antidote. We still want the Sveshnikov structure.} 5. O-O Be7 {It's unclear what is next for White. It is similar to the 3.Nc3 e5 line, but White played it poorly with the bishop on [e2], which will probably be moved again to the more active square [c4], and therefore we will be tempo up compared to that line. Meanwhile, we'll continue with ...[d6] and castle.}) 3... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4]} ({Not the most popular choice by far, but that's my favourite, once again challenging White in the centre right away!} 3... e6 4. O-O d5 5. Bb5 {is how the game went in Wijk, and this is indeed very interesting.}) 4. e5 {It might not be the most popular, but it definitely feels like the most challenging for Black.} Ng4 5. Qe2 f6 {A fresh approach immediately challenging the White's pawn on [e5].} 6. exf6 Nxf6 7. O-O e6 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gf8d6] It looks like a weird French, but White still has to put a pawn on [d4] to achieve that.} 8. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] Very logical, trying to get back some space in the centre.} d5 9. Bb5 {Makes sense, but Black is OK by playing very natural moves.} Bd6 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 10. d4 O-O 11. Re1 Qc7 {[%cal Gf6g4]} 12. h3 Bd7 {[%cal Gd7e8,Ga8e8]} 13. Be3 (13. Nbd2 {forgets about the [c1]-bishop. After} Rae8 {, planning to go ...[e5] if allowed, White probably have to take on [c6] and give up the bishop pair if they want to prevent it.}) 13... cxd4 14. cxd4 Be8 {[%cal Ge8h5] The plan of activating the bishop via [e8]-[h5] is very typical in the pawn structures arising from the French defence.} *

