[White "20) Anti-Sveshnikov 2.Nf3 - 3.Bc4 & others"]
[Black "3.Bc4 Nf6 4.e5 Ng4 5.Qe2 f6 6.exf6 #5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B30"]
[PlyCount "28"]
[GameId "2123892872749901"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. Bc4 {Looks like a beginner's move, but it became very popular recently as the very creative and Team Magnus colleague! Dutch GM Jorden Van Foreest tried it vs Praggnanandhaa in the Wijk Aan Zee super tournament in 2022.} (3. Be2 {is simply poor and very unambitious.} Nf6 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {The usual antidote. We still want the Sveshnikov structure.} 5. O-O Be7 {It's unclear what is next for White. It is similar to the 3.Nc3 e5 line, but White played it poorly with the bishop on [e2], which will probably be moved again to the more active square [c4], and therefore we will be tempo up compared to that line. Meanwhile, we'll continue with ...[d6] and castle.}) 3... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4]} ({Not the most popular choice by far, but that's my favourite, once again challenging White in the centre right away!} 3... e6 4. O-O d5 5. Bb5 {is how the game went in Wijk, and this is indeed very interesting.}) 4. e5 {It might not be the most popular, but it definitely feels like the most challenging for Black.} Ng4 5. Qe2 f6 {A fresh approach immediately challenging the White's pawn on [e5].} 6. exf6 Nxf6 7. O-O e6 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gf8d6] It looks like a weird French, but White still has to put a pawn on [d4] to achieve that.} 8. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] Very logical, trying to get back some space in the centre.} d5 9. Bb3 Be7 (9... Bd6 {is also possible and will most likely transpose. This is one of the cases where I am not sure which move I should recommend, or I would choose in a practical game!} 10. d4 O-O 11. dxc5 Bxc5 {just transposes.}) 10. d4 O-O 11. Bg5 {Just a way to develop for White, but it clearly lacks punch.} Bd7 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Nbd2 Kh8 {Always a useful prophylaxis as we no longer have a pawn on [f7] protecting our king.} 14. Rae1 Qb6 {[%cal Ga8e8,Ge6e5] We have a good game; in the long run, it will be a headache for White to prevent the ...[e5] push.} *

