1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {White still has numerous ways to avoid the main lines. Nothing to worry about if you read this chapter and know the antidotes!} 3. Bc4 {Looks like a beginner's move, but it became very popular recently as the very creative and Team Magnus colleague! Dutch GM Jorden Van Foreest tried it vs Praggnanandhaa in the Wijk Aan Zee super tournament in 2022.} (3. Be2 {is simply poor and very unambitious.} Nf6 4. Nc3 e5 $1 {The usual antidote. We still want the Sveshnikov structure.} 5. O-O Be7 {It's unclear what is next for White. It is similar to the 3.Nc3 e5 line, but White played it poorly with the bishop on [e2], which will probably be moved again to the more active square [c4], and therefore we will be tempo up compared to that line. Meanwhile, we'll continue with ...[d6] and castle.}) 3... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4]} ({Not the most popular choice by far, but that's my favourite, once again challenging White in the centre right away!} 3... e6 4. O-O d5 5. Bb5 {is how the game went in Wijk, and this is indeed very interesting.}) 4. e5 {It might not be the most popular, but it definitely feels like the most challenging for Black.} Ng4 5. Qe2 f6 {A fresh approach immediately challenging the White's pawn on [e5].} 6. exf6 Nxf6 7. O-O e6 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gf8d6] It looks like a weird French, but White still has to put a pawn on [d4] to achieve that.} 8. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] Very logical, trying to get back some space in the centre.} d5 9. Bb3 Be7 (9... Bd6 {is also possible and will most likely transpose. This is one of the cases where I am not sure which move I should recommend, or I would choose in a practical game!} 10. d4 O-O 11. dxc5 Bxc5 {just transposes.}) 10. d4 O-O 11. dxc5 a5 $1 {Much more ambitious than getting back the pawn immediately.} 12. Be3 {Keeping the pawn gives Black a very dangerous initiative.} e5 {[%cal Gc8g4,Ga5a4]} 13. h3 a4 14. Bc2 Qe8 {[%cal Ge8h5,Ge7d8,Gd8c7]} 15. Nbd2 Bd8 $1 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ge5e4,Ge8e5] ...[Bc7] followed by ...[e4] and ...[Qe5] is a very strong and very hard to stop! plan. White will have to make some ugly defensive moves in order to stop it.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Fressinet’s Sveshnikov Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview & Model Games: 2.Nc3 & Others"]
[Black "2.Nc3 & Other 2nd Moves: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B23"]
[PlyCount "26"]
[GameId "2123892872782672"]

1. e4 c5 {I checked a pretty big number of second possible White moves almost all of them!, and it is pretty hard to pick a few of them when doing an overview. Black generally welcomes such moves as we immediately get a nice position and are not under the impression that White actually started the game!} 2. Nc3 {White may start with this move if they want to play the Grand Prix Attack or Closed Sicilian or even the 'Fake Rossolimo'.} (2. f4 {This was played by no less than Hikaru Nakamura in the 2024 Grand Chess Tour rapid and blitz, so it makes a lot of sense to include it in the overview.} d5 $1 {Immediately fighting back in the centre, that was the chosen response by its prestigious opponents.} 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. d3 Nc6 6. Nf3 e6 {That was not played against Nakamura, but it makes a lot of sense to me: we just strengthen our centre and prepare to develop our kingside minor pieces and keep the option of long castling. See more here.}) (2. b4 {I also very much like my suggestion for the Wing's Gambit, mainly for aesthetic reasons.} cxb4 {Always take presents!} 3. a3 e5 $1 {that one is very much in the Sveshnikov spirit but also reminds me of a 1.e4 e5 position except that the White's queenside just exploded.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bb5 Nf6 $1 {Berlin is a good opening, but that's the best version you will ever see!}) 2... Nc6 ({We stick to our guns and play} 2... Nc6 {, as usual.}) 3. Bb5 {Not sure how this is called, but I decided to call it the 'Fake Rossolimo' as it is very similar to the normal Rossolimo except that...} (3. g3 {The Closed Sicilian. Not really dangerous as we have a harmonious setup against that.} g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 {It's kind of too early for} 5. f4 {as after} e6 {, we will be able to counter strike in the centre with ...[Nge7] and ...[d5].}) ({5.d3 e6 Again, our setup involves ...[Nge7]. 6.Be3 White is forcing Black to waste a tempo on playing ...[d6] in order to protect the [c5]-pawn, but that also weakens the [b2]-pawn. 6...d6 7.Qd2 Rb8! No hurries in developing the [g8]-knight as the centre is closed, which would allow [Bh6]. We will first expand on the queenside and harass the knight on [c3].} 3. f4 {Once again, a dangerous weapon if Black doesn't know their way.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 {and now:A} 5. Bc4 e6 $1 {Immediately killing White's perspective on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal and preparing to take over with ...[Nge7] and ...[d5].} 6. d3 Nge7 7. O-O O-O {with two main branches:A1} 8. Qe1 {That's the main move and clearly preparing an attack.} d5 9. Bb3 Nd4 $1 {exchanging a potentially dangerous attacker as the knight on [f3] is a nice cooler to White's attack.} 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Ne2 dxe4 12. dxe4 b5 $1 {A nice move clearly showing that, unfortunately for White, the action is taking place on the queenside. 13...a5 is next asking unpleasant questions to White's light-squared bishop.A2 8.f5 This is the true spirit of the Grand Prix attack, but it simply doesn't work. 8...d5 9.Bb3 dxe4! Going for an endgame pawn up and breaking all White's dream of a quick mate. 10.dxe4 Qxd1 11.Rxd1 exf5 White will have a tough time proving any kind of compensation for the missing pawn.B 5.Bb5 The modern way to play it. Threatening to take on [c6] and get a very good version of the Rossolimo. 5...Nd4! 6.O-O a6 7.Bd3 b5 A nice move expanding on the queenside and making the White's light-squared bishop feel uncomfortable. 8.Nxd4 cxd4 9.Ne2 Bb7 And both Black bishops are doing an excellent job controlling the centre. We will finish the development with ...[Nf6] and get an excellent game.}) 3... Nd4 $1 {the knight can jump on [d4] without being taken!} 4. Nf3 {This seems the most critical to me. White is banking their hopes on a speedy development.} (4. Bc4 e6 {the usual: we close the [a2]-[g8] diagonal before it becomes a problem.} 5. Nf3 a6 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Ne2 Bc5 {White hasn't managed to create anything, and we will finish our development comfortably.}) 4... a6 5. Bd3 g6 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Ne2 d5 $1 ({A strong move which could come as a surprise to your opponent. The routine move} 7... Bg7 {is much more popular.}) 8. e5 {Not the best but most natural.} Bg7 9. f4 f6 $1 {The situation in the centre is already critical for White. It is very easy to go wrong by being greedy as White.} 10. exf6 Nxf6 11. Nxd4 Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gg7d4,Gh5f4] The key move. Black is already winning!} 12. Ne2 e5 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4]} 13. fxe5 O-O {[%csl Re1][%cal Gd8h4,Gc8g4] White's king is stuck in the centre while the position is completely opened. That's terrible news...} *

