[Black "Nepomniachtchi, Ian vs. Vachier Lagrave"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "B26"]
[PlyCount "116"]
[GameId "2123892872799057"]

{This game was played in the first-ever top tournament organised online during the pandemic. These players were both leaders of the interrupted 2020 Candidates.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 d6 {A small inaccuracy, in my opinion, as we are losing the option of going ...[e6]-...[d5] in one go. Obviously, that's not a disaster.} (5... e6 {and ...[Nge7] is our repertoire.}) 6. O-O e6 7. d3 Nge7 8. Be3 Nd4 9. Qd2 O-O {But we just transposed into our repertoire!} 10. h3 {The start of a very slow plan, which shows that even for a top player like Ian, White's prospects are not that obvious!} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] Developing the last piece. Black already comfortably equalised.} 11. Kh2 Bc6 12. a4 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd4e2,Gd5d4] Very logical and asking White tough questions.} 13. Bg5 Nxe2 (13... dxe4 14. dxe4 a6 {was another very decent way to play.}) 14. Qxe2 d4 15. Nb1 (15. Nd5 {was a better try.} f6 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Bd2 e5 {But Black has more space and is still doing very well. The [a8]-rook will come to [e8] and ...[f5] is coming.}) 15... Qd7 (15... e5 $1 {White doesn't have any active play, and Black will proceed with their plan: ...[Qd7], ...[h6] and ...[f5].}) 16. a5 ({White misses a golden opportunity to suddenly get a very nice position:} 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. e5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 {followed by [Nd2]-[Nc4].}) 16... e5 17. Na3 Nc8 18. Nc4 Nd6 19. Nxd6 Qxd6 {[%cal Gf7f5] And we are back to the 'normal' scenario of move 15 where Black has all the active options and White just has to sit and wait.} 20. Qd2 f5 21. exf5 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 gxf5 23. Rae1 Rae8 24. Qd1 Qg6 25. Bd2 e4 {Maxime proceeds with all the most natural moves and gets a very pleasant position.} 26. Bf4 Re6 27. Qd2 Rfe8 28. b4 {Naturally looking for counterplay, and this will work like a charm!} Rc6 29. bxc5 Rxc5 30. Qb4 Qc6 {[%cal Ge4d3]} 31. Kg1 Rxc2 (31... Rb5 $1 {was the way to go stopping all counterplay.} 32. Qa4 Rb2 $1 {targeting the [c2]-pawn.}) 32. Rc1 Rc3 33. Rxc3 dxc3 34. d4 $1 {[%csl Rg8] Suddenly, it is not clear at all. Black is a pawn up, but the position is open, and Black's king is weak. The [c3]-pawn might become weak as well.} Qd5 (34... Rd8 35. Be3 Kh8 36. Rc1 Rc8 37. Qb3 {threatening an invasion on [f7]. White definitely has counterplay.}) 35. Qxc3 Bxd4 36. Qd2 Rd8 37. Be3 Bf6 38. Qb4 a6 39. Rb1 Rd7 40. Rc1 {the position is simply very difficult to play for Black as the extra pawn on the queenside doesn't really matter, and the black king is very weak. Nevertheless, Maxime does a great job keeping the position together for a while.} Kf7 41. Kh2 Qb5 42. Qa3 Be7 43. Qc3 Bf6 44. Qc8 Qd5 45. Rc5 Qe6 46. Qb8 Be7 47. Rc1 Kg7 48. Rb1 Bd6 49. Qc8 Qf7 ({Tactic alert!} 49... Bxg3+ $3 {was a pretty way to save the game.} 50. fxg3 Rd2+ {or 50.Kxg3 f4+ 51.Kh2 fxe3 and both 52.Rxb7= and 52.Rg1+ lead to a draw: 52...Kh6 53.Qf8+ Kh5= No more checks!}) 50. Rb6 f4 51. Bd4+ Kh6 52. g4 {[%cal Gb6h6]} Kg5 {Brave and good practical decision.} 53. Qh8 (53. h4+ $3 {would have been winning for White.} Kxh4 54. Bf6+ Qxf6 55. Qxd7 {+-}) 53... f3+ {Now it's a draw.} 54. Rxd6 Qf4+ 55. Kg1 Qc1+ 56. Kh2 Qf4+ 57. Kg1 Qc1+ 58. Kh2 Qf4+ {A very lively game, but it is pretty clear that the outcome of the opening was in Black's favour.} 1/2-1/2

