1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Bc4 {Most people don't want to give up their bishop pair that easily, but the bishop is misplaced here.} e6 $1 {[%cal Gc4e6] As simple as that, we just want to close the [c4]-bishop's diagonal and also prepare ...[d7]-[d5], making the life of White's light-square bishop as uncomfortable as possible. Now White has to challenge the annoying knight on [d4] and has a couple of options in order to achieve that.} 5. Nge2 {The most popular.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ({Of course,} 5... Nf6 {is also a perfectly logical and playable move, but the concept is to harass the light-squared bishop and make White regret having developed their bishop that early.}) (5... a6 {Now,} 6. Nxd4 {transposes here.}) 6. Bb3 b5 7. Nxd4 {White has to take on [d4] in order to save their bishop.} cxd4 8. Ne2 Bc5 {[%csl Gd4] Very simple play. We maintain the pawn on [d4] and the space advantage we achieved. Black has many ways to play and is at least! completely fine.} 9. c3 {A quite rare but very logical way to challenge the [d4]-pawn.} d3 {Feels like the most natural in order to prevent White from developing normally.} 10. Nf4 {[%cal Gf4d3] But now the pawn is lost.} Bb6 {A strong novelty which will allow Black to gain back the pawn.} 11. Nxd3 {[%csl Gb6] The bishop on [c5] is no longer hanging. and we have time to counterattack the [e4]-pawn.} Qh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4e4]} 12. Qe2 Bb7 {[%cal Gb7e4] It is impossible for White to defend the [e4]-pawn.} 13. e5 {[%cal Gb7g2] This is a disaster due to Black's reply.} Bxg2 {And Black is even winning.} *

