1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Bc4 {Most people don't want to give up their bishop pair that easily, but the bishop is misplaced here.} e6 $1 {[%cal Gc4e6] As simple as that, we just want to close the [c4]-bishop's diagonal and also prepare ...[d7]-[d5], making the life of White's light-square bishop as uncomfortable as possible. Now White has to challenge the annoying knight on [d4] and has a couple of options in order to achieve that.} 5. Nge2 {The most popular.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ({Of course,} 5... Nf6 {is also a perfectly logical and playable move, but the concept is to harass the light-squared bishop and make White regret having developed their bishop that early.}) (5... a6 {Now,} 6. Nxd4 {transposes here.}) 6. a4 Nf6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 7. O-O (7. e5 d5 {anyway works like a charm for Black!}) 7... d5 8. exd5 exd5 9. Ba2 Bd6 {[%cal Gd6h2,Ge8g8] Finishing the development and keeping an eye on White's kingside.} 10. Nxd5 {The kind of novelties you want to see!} Bxh2+ {Hello!} 11. Kxh2 Ng4+ 12. Kg3 ({After} 12. Kg1 Qh4 {, Black is giving mate in 5 moves against the best defense!}) 12... Qg5 {[%cal Gg4e3]} 13. f4 Qg6 {[%cal Gg4e3] Game over! ...[Ne3] check is too big of a threat.} *

