1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Bc4 {Most people don't want to give up their bishop pair that easily, but the bishop is misplaced here.} e6 $1 {[%cal Gc4e6] As simple as that, we just want to close the [c4]-bishop's diagonal and also prepare ...[d7]-[d5], making the life of White's light-square bishop as uncomfortable as possible. Now White has to challenge the annoying knight on [d4] and has a couple of options in order to achieve that.} 5. Nf3 a6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb7b5]} 6. O-O {This is careless from White as the bishop will have to retreat on an unpleasant square.} b5 7. Bd3 (7. Be2 Ne7 {and the knight is coming to [c6], while White definitely lacks space for their pieces.}) 7... Bb7 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Ne2 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] Logical play targeting White's pawn on [e4]. White already needs to be careful in order to keep the balance.} 10. e5 $2 {if White gets ambitious, they can be immediately punished. A sample and beautiful line which shows Black's potential in that position.} Ng4 {[%cal Gd8h4,Gg4e5]} 11. f4 d6 12. h3 {Seems like White is able to repel Black's initiative.} dxe5 $1 13. hxg4 h5 $3 {[%cal Gh5g4,Ge5e4]} ({Just planning to mate.} 13... e4 {regaining the piece is also good for Black, but the main line is more fun and even better.}) 14. g5 h4 {[%cal Gh4h3,Ge5e4] White is completely busted.} *

