1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Nge2 a6 (4... Nxb5 5. Nxb5 {is always a decent option, but this is exactly what White wants: speeding up the development in exchange for the bishop pair.}) ({I generally don't want to give my opponents what they want! And that's why I prefer} 4... a6 {as a matter of principle.}) 5. Bc4 b5 6. Bd5 Rb8 {[%cal Ge7e6] With ...[e6] coming up, we are threatening to box in the light-squared bishop.} 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2d4]} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gf6e4,Ge7e6] A nice little tactic which allows Black to get back his pawn.} 9. Nxd4 e6 10. Bb3 Nxe4 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge4c5] Black has a very nice position. Once again, the bishop on [b3] is misplaced.} *

