1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Nf3 a6 (4... Nxb5 {is the most played, but again, it just speeds up White's development and gives them some initiative. I much prefer 4...a6 , which doesn't give White what they want.}) 5. Bc4 b5 {Taking space and gaining time! What's not to like?} 6. Bd5 Rb8 7. d3 (7. Nxd4 {transposes here after} cxd4 8. Ne2 Nf6 9. Nxd4 e6 10. Bb3 Nxe4 {or 9.Bb3 Nxe4 10.Nxd4 e6 .}) 7... e6 8. Bb3 Nxb3 9. axb3 Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gf8] We got the bishops; we just need to be careful by finishing the development in a harmonious way.} 10. O-O Ne7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Ge7c6]} (10... Nf6 $6 11. e5 {helps White get some play.}) 11. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5]} ({After} 11. e5 Ng6 {, the pawn is just weak, and we can attack it right away and continue our development with ...[Be7].}) 11... d6 12. d4 {Could be a bit scary as White is opening the center while Black hasn't finished its development.} cxd4 13. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Kicking the queen away and ensuring we can finish our development.} *

