1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Nf3 a6 (4... Nxb5 {is the most played, but again, it just speeds up White's development and gives them some initiative. I much prefer 4...a6 , which doesn't give White what they want.}) 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gf3d4] By far, the main move. 6.Be2 is a very unambitious way to deal with the line. The bishop is retreating to a passive square and also taking away the square from the [c3]-knight in case White wants to take on [d4]. After 6...e6 (, followed by ...[Ne7]-[c6], Black is at least! completely fine.)} g6 {Now that the light-squared bishop is no longer on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, we don't need to block it anymore with ...[e7]-[e6]. Therefore, developing the bishop via [g7] is a more ambitious way to play.} 6. O-O Bg7 (6... Bg7 {Now,} 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 d5 {transposes here.}) 7. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4] A typical idea to activate the rook and find a way for the [c1]-bishop to develop.} Nc6 $1 {Preventing [b4] and making White's life more difficult.} 8. a3 d6 9. b4 Nf6 {Ignoring White's gestures on the queenside and simply developing.} 10. bxc5 dxc5 11. Re1 O-O {[%cal Gc8g4,Ga8b8] Black has a very harmonious position. White spent a lot of time opening up the b-file. We will just protect the [b7]-pawn with ...[Rb8] and finish our development.} 12. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] An interesting move grabbing some space on the queenside and preparing [Ba3].} Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b7,Gc8g4] We stick to the plan!} 13. Bb2 (13. Ba3 {is always met by} Qa5 {and it is hard to see how White will proceed, while our plan is very clear: ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7].}) (13. h3 e6 {followed by ...[Nd7], and we have a very nice control over the central dark squares.}) (13. e5 Ng4 {is simply losing a pawn.}) 13... Bg4 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 e6 {[%csl Gd6,Ge5][%cal Gf6d7,Gd7e5,Ge6d5] With our usual and excellent grip on the central dark squares. I would definitely pick Black.} *

