1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Nf3 a6 (4... Nxb5 {is the most played, but again, it just speeds up White's development and gives them some initiative. I much prefer 4...a6 , which doesn't give White what they want.}) 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gf3d4] By far, the main move. 6.Be2 is a very unambitious way to deal with the line. The bishop is retreating to a passive square and also taking away the square from the [c3]-knight in case White wants to take on [d4]. After 6...e6 (, followed by ...[Ne7]-[c6], Black is at least! completely fine.)} g6 {Now that the light-squared bishop is no longer on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, we don't need to block it anymore with ...[e7]-[e6]. Therefore, developing the bishop via [g7] is a more ambitious way to play.} 6. O-O Bg7 (6... Bg7 {Now,} 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 d5 {transposes here.}) 7. Re1 Nf6 $1 (7... e6 8. e5 $1 {feels tricky for Black as the dark squares around the black king are weakened. [Ne4]-[d6] is the obvious threat.} Qc7 9. b3 Ne7 10. Bb2 Nec6 {.}) 8. e5 {The obvious approach, trying to punish Black at once.} Nh5 {[%csl Gf4] The knight on [h5] looks weird, but it is actually good as the [f4]-square is available. The [c1]-bishop is not close to controlling the [f4]-square as the bishop on [d3] is creating congestion in White's camp.} 9. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4] The first line of the engine on high depth, so it should be checked!} d5 {[%cal Gc8g4] Taking the chance that your opponent doesn't know the en passant rule!} 10. exd6 {[%cal Ge1e7] They will probably do, and so open up the line for their rook.} Qxd6 11. Ne4 Qc7 12. b4 {White has to act dynamically.} Bg4 13. bxc5 Bxf3 14. gxf3 {We have weakened White’s kingside for only one pawn.} O-O {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gd4e6,Ge6c5,Gh5f4] Objectively speaking, the position is equal according to the machine, but with such a weak white king, I'd take Black anytime!} *

