1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Nf3 a6 (4... Nxb5 {is the most played, but again, it just speeds up White's development and gives them some initiative. I much prefer 4...a6 , which doesn't give White what they want.}) 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gf3d4] By far, the main move. 6.Be2 is a very unambitious way to deal with the line. The bishop is retreating to a passive square and also taking away the square from the [c3]-knight in case White wants to take on [d4]. After 6...e6 (, followed by ...[Ne7]-[c6], Black is at least! completely fine.)} g6 {Now that the light-squared bishop is no longer on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, we don't need to block it anymore with ...[e7]-[e6]. Therefore, developing the bishop via [g7] is a more ambitious way to play.} 6. b4 {This is recommended in The GothamChess 1. [e4] Repertoire and this is indeed interesting, especially if Black is clueless about the line.} cxb4 $1 {Always accept the gambit!} 7. Nd5 (7. Nxd4 bxc3 8. dxc3 Bg7 {is simply better for Black due to White's very bad pawn structure.}) 7... Nxf3+ ({Much less provocative than} 7... Nc6 {, which I offer as an alternative.}) 8. Qxf3 Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1]} 9. Rb1 e6 $1 10. Ne3 ({Not} 10. Nxb4 a5 {The knight is lost!}) 10... Ne7 ({Time to develop. If} 10... a5 {, the typical} 11. a3 {gives White good play.}) 11. Rxb4 {White got the pawn back but they are somewhat disorganized.} d5 $1 {We put a pawn in the centre and there is some kind of harmony in Black's position.} 12. exd5 exd5 13. Ba3 O-O 14. O-O b5 $1 {Another good move freeing the bishop on [c8] that was forced to defend the [b7]-pawn.} 15. Rbb1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ga3e7] White puts pressure on our central pawn.} Be6 $1 {Simple and effective.} 16. Ng4 {[%cal Gg4f6]} ({The best move.} 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxd5 Qd6 {would simply be better for Black, as [a2] is hanging and our bishops are really powerful.}) 16... Bxg4 17. Qxg4 Re8 {[%cal Ge7c6,Gc6e5] I think White should take on [e7] and try to equalize before our knight gets to [c6] and [e5].} *

