1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Nf3 a6 (4... Nxb5 {is the most played, but again, it just speeds up White's development and gives them some initiative. I much prefer 4...a6 , which doesn't give White what they want.}) 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gf3d4] By far, the main move. 6.Be2 is a very unambitious way to deal with the line. The bishop is retreating to a passive square and also taking away the square from the [c3]-knight in case White wants to take on [d4]. After 6...e6 (, followed by ...[Ne7]-[c6], Black is at least! completely fine.)} g6 {Now that the light-squared bishop is no longer on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, we don't need to block it anymore with ...[e7]-[e6]. Therefore, developing the bishop via [g7] is a more ambitious way to play.} 6. b4 {This is recommended in The GothamChess 1. [e4] Repertoire and it is indeed interesting, especially if Black is clueless about the line.} cxb4 $1 {Always accept the gambit!} 7. Nd5 Nc6 $5 {A very interesting alternative protecting the pawn!} 8. Rb1 a5 9. Bb2 Nf6 {I think White has to play very energetically by now, as otherwise, they will be a pawn down for nothing.} 10. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} (10. O-O {is too slow.} Bg7 {and it is hard to see White's compensation for the missing pawn.}) 10... Bg7 11. h5 Nxh5 12. Rxh5 {It is getting wild!} Bxb2 13. Rxb2 e6 $1 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gg6h5]} ({A very nice cool-blooded move.} 13... gxh5 14. Ng5 {looks way too scary!}) 14. Rh4 {The only move to stay in the game.} exd5 15. exd5 Qf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6b2,Gc6e7] A key move winning an important tempo on the [b2]-rook. Black will be able to play ...[Ne7] without allowing [d6].} 16. Rb3 Ne7 {[%cal Gd7d6]} 17. d6 $1 {This has to be played anyway simply to prevent Black's ...[d6].} Qxd6 18. Qa1 {[%cal Ga1h8]} f6 {We are two pawns up, but White has a clear initiative. The position is a complete mess.} *

