1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Nf3 a6 (4... Nxb5 {is the most played, but again, it just speeds up White's development and gives them some initiative. I much prefer 4...a6 , which doesn't give White what they want.}) 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gf3d4] By far, the main move. 6.Be2 is a very unambitious way to deal with the line. The bishop is retreating to a passive square and also taking away the square from the [c3]-knight in case White wants to take on [d4]. After 6...e6 (, followed by ...[Ne7]-[c6], Black is at least! completely fine.)} g6 {Now that the light-squared bishop is no longer on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, we don't need to block it anymore with ...[e7]-[e6]. Therefore, developing the bishop via [g7] is a more ambitious way to play.} 6. Nxd4 {The most common and immediately challenging Black in the center. After all, Black has zero pieces developed once the knight on [d4] is exchanged!} cxd4 7. Ne2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ge2d4]} d5 $1 (7... d5 {The point is that} 8. Nxd4 $4 {is a blunder and obviously loses a piece after} dxe4 {, which is very important to understand, though, as it makes the 7...d5 push tactically justified!}) 8. e5 {Most ambitious as it takes space, but White cannot hold his center.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7e5]} 9. f4 f6 $1 {We don't give up the center that easily and put White's center under pressure.} 10. exf6 Nxf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] The natural recapture, but it seems to lose a pawn after White's reply.} 11. Nxd4 Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gg7d4,Gh5f4] But not quite! We can get it back with a very strong initiative. Therefore, White should not have taken the pawn on [d4], but Black would do extremely well either way.} 12. Ne2 {The only option not to see a black knight landing on [f4], but it only makes things worse...} e5 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4]} 13. fxe5 O-O {[%csl Re1][%cal Gc8g4,Gg7e5,Gd8h4] The white monarch is stuck in the center and will just get mated.} *

