1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Nf3 a6 (4... Nxb5 {is the most played, but again, it just speeds up White's development and gives them some initiative. I much prefer 4...a6 , which doesn't give White what they want.}) 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gf3d4] By far, the main move. 6.Be2 is a very unambitious way to deal with the line. The bishop is retreating to a passive square and also taking away the square from the [c3]-knight in case White wants to take on [d4]. After 6...e6 (, followed by ...[Ne7]-[c6], Black is at least! completely fine.)} g6 {Now that the light-squared bishop is no longer on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, we don't need to block it anymore with ...[e7]-[e6]. Therefore, developing the bishop via [g7] is a more ambitious way to play.} 6. Nxd4 {The most common and immediately challenging Black in the center. After all, Black has zero pieces developed once the knight on [d4] is exchanged!} cxd4 7. Ne2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ge2d4]} d5 $1 (7... d5 {The point is that} 8. Nxd4 $4 {is a blunder and obviously loses a piece after} dxe4 {, which is very important to understand, though, as it makes the 7...d5 push tactically justified!}) 8. c3 $1 {The best by quite some margin!} dxe4 (8... dxc3 9. Qa4+ Bd7 10. Qd4 dxe4 11. Bxe4 cxb2 {transposes here.}) 9. Bxe4 dxc3 10. bxc3 {Another novelty that fails to impress. White will remain with hanging pawns for no particular reason.} Nf6 11. Bf3 Bg7 12. O-O O-O 13. d4 {Both sides have played obvious and logical moves. Now there are two options for Black: quiet approach or chaos!} Bg4 $5 ({Giving up a couple of pawns for the initiative.} 13... Ra7 {followed by ...[b6] and ...[Bb7] is the calm way to play the position.}) 14. Bxb7 Rb8 15. Bxa6 Ne4 {Black's activity is enough for a draw but probably not more. White has a few options.} 16. Bd2 Rb2 17. Be1 Qa5 {[%csl Rc3,Rd4][%cal Ge4c3,Ga5a6,Gg4e2] And we will get back our pawns.} *

