1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Looks like a missed attempt to play the Rossolimo which is the most serious line in the non-open Sicilians, but it is actually a decent line that was played by none others than Carlsen, Caruana or Grischuk. White just wants to take on [c6] and play a closed position where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} Nd4 $1 {Of course, that's the main problem of not having played [Nf3]. The [d4]-square is now available and unchallenged.} 4. Nf3 a6 (4... Nxb5 {is the most played, but again, it just speeds up White's development and gives them some initiative. I much prefer 4...a6 , which doesn't give White what they want.}) 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gf3d4] By far, the main move. 6.Be2 is a very unambitious way to deal with the line. The bishop is retreating to a passive square and also taking away the square from the [c3]-knight in case White wants to take on [d4]. After 6...e6 (, followed by ...[Ne7]-[c6], Black is at least! completely fine.)} g6 {Now that the light-squared bishop is no longer on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, we don't need to block it anymore with ...[e7]-[e6]. Therefore, developing the bishop via [g7] is a more ambitious way to play.} 6. Nxd4 {The most common and immediately challenging Black in the center. After all, Black has zero pieces developed once the knight on [d4] is exchanged!} cxd4 7. Ne2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ge2d4]} d5 $1 (7... d5 {The point is that} 8. Nxd4 $4 {is a blunder and obviously loses a piece after} dxe4 {, which is very important to understand, though, as it makes the 7...d5 push tactically justified!}) 8. c3 $1 {The best by quite some margin!} dxe4 (8... dxc3 9. Qa4+ Bd7 10. Qd4 dxe4 11. Bxe4 cxb2 {transposes here.}) 9. Bxe4 dxc3 10. Qa4+ {Not an obvious move, but a very interesting one!} Bd7 11. Qd4 {If your opponent plays in such an artificial way, you can be sure they prepared with an engine, but if you know what you are doing, Black is completely fine.} cxb2 {The start of a forced sequence which will end in an equal endgame.} 12. Bxb2 Nf6 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bxa6 Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gb6a6] A good move that keeps the balance. White is a pawn up, but we are attacking both bishops, and they have to say goodbye to one of them.} 15. Qxb6 Rxb6 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gb6a6]} 16. Bxf6 {The only move which doesn't lose a piece !} Rxf6 17. Rb1 {[%cal Gb1b8,Gb8e8]} ({A nice little move which enlightens the weakness of Black's back rank.} 17. Bc4 Bg7 {followed by ...[Rd6] and castle. Hard to believe the bishop pair andthe weaknesses on [a2] and [d2] don't fully compensate for the missing pawn.}) 17... Rxa6 $1 18. Rb8+ Bc8 {Only legal move but enough to equalize the game!} 19. Rxc8+ Kd7 20. Rc2 Bg7 {[%csl Ga6,Gd7,Gg7][%cal Gh8a8] Black is way too active for White to have any hope in this endgame.} *

