1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] Most logical, I would say, as White attacks the weakness on [f7]. But this is basically an abandoned area at the highest level as the antidote is very simple for Black: just go ...[e6]-...[Nge7] and ...[d5]!} e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5]} 6. d3 Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 7. e5 {[%cal Gc3e4] The obvious try in order to stop ...[d5].} d5 $1 {Anyway!} 8. exd6 Qxd6 9. Ne4 Qc7 10. O-O (10. Nxc5 $4 {is just a blunder due to} Qa5+ {collecting the knight.}) 10... b6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1,Gg7b2] With both bishops on nice diagonals, Black is already doing very well.} *

