1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] Most logical, I would say, as White attacks the weakness on [f7]. But this is basically an abandoned area at the highest level as the antidote is very simple for Black: just go ...[e6]-...[Nge7] and ...[d5]!} e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5]} 6. d3 Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 7. O-O (7. Bb3 {will simply transpose to the next trainable after} O-O 8. O-O d5 9. Qe1 {.}) 7... O-O 8. f5 {It is White's dream to make an early [f5] work, but it actually never does!} d5 $1 {Again, the obvious reaction in the center just wins material!} 9. Bb3 dxe4 10. dxe4 Qxd1 {Without queens, there is no attack and, therefore, no compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} 11. Rxd1 exf5 {[%cal Gc8e6] With a healthy extra pawn. ...[Be6] is coming next.} *

