1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] Most logical, I would say, as White attacks the weakness on [f7]. But this is basically an abandoned area at the highest level as the antidote is very simple for Black: just go ...[e6]-...[Nge7] and ...[d5]!} e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5]} 6. d3 Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 7. O-O (7. Bb3 {will simply transpose after} O-O 8. O-O d5 9. Qe1) 7... O-O 8. Qe1 d5 (8... Nd4 $5 {is another very possible move order that will anyway transpose to our main line!} 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Ne2 d5 11. Bb3 dxe4 12. dxe4 b5 {.}) 9. Bb3 Nd4 {[%cal Gc5c4] White can't tolerate that knight very long.} 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Ne2 dxe4 12. dxe4 b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga7a5,Ga5a4] A multipurpose move preparing an expansion on the queenside with ...[a5] and soon occupying the long diagonal with ...[Bb7].} 13. Qf2 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge4e5,Gf1d1]} a5 14. a3 (14. a4 bxa4 15. Rxa4 Ba6 {just gives Black a lot of activity. Next is ...[d3] or ...[Bb5] followed by ...[a4].}) 14... Nc6 15. e5 {[%csl Rd4] The [d4]-pawn is quite weak, so we should act quickly!} a4 16. Ba2 Qc7 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc7c2]} 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Qxd4 Ba6 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gb5b4,Gf8d8,Ga6f1] We don't need to hurry up taking back the pawn as this unnatural but developing move is threatening ...[b4]!} 19. Bb1 {White may get greedy, but we get obvious compensation.} Rfb8 {[%csl Rb1,Rc1,Ra1][%cal Gb5b4,Gg7f8] Not only do we have threats, but the white pieces are awkward on the queenside!} *

