1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] Most logical, I would say, as White attacks the weakness on [f7]. But this is basically an abandoned area at the highest level as the antidote is very simple for Black: just go ...[e6]-...[Nge7] and ...[d5]!} e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5]} 6. d3 Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 7. O-O (7. Bb3 {will simply transpose after} O-O 8. O-O d5 9. Qe1) 7... O-O 8. Qe1 d5 (8... Nd4 $5 {is another very possible move order that will anyway transpose to our main line!} 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Ne2 d5 11. Bb3 dxe4 12. dxe4 b5 {.}) 9. Bb3 Nd4 {[%cal Gc5c4] White can't tolerate that knight very long.} 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Ne2 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Also giving excellent play to Black.} 12. a4 dxe4 13. dxe4 b6 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc8a6,Gd4d3] Very logical preparing ...[Ba6] followed by ...[d3]. Please note that the inclusion of ...[a5]-...[a4] weakens the bishop on [b3], as it is only protected by the [c2]-pawn and that one may get exchanged when we play ...[d3].} 14. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4d3]} Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 {[%cal Gd4d3] And ...[d3] is still looming. That would open up the long diagonal [h8]-[a1] and activate the black queen.} 16. e5 {[%csl Re5,Rf4][%cal Gg7e5]} d3 17. cxd3 Qxd3 18. Qd2 {White has to exchange this very active queen. We are ready to go for the endgame but on our terms!} Rd8 19. Rd1 Qxd2 20. Bxd2 Raa8 {[%cal Ge7d5,Gg6g5,Gg7f8] Bringing back the rook into the game. We have clear ideas on what to do on the next few moves. Black is definitely not worse.} *

