1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. a4 {Interesting prophylaxis proposed by GM Perelshteyn in his Chessable course Grand Prix Attack Reloaded, which avoids a future black expansion on the queenside by ...[a6]-...[b5] and basically ask Black how they want to develop before deciding where the light-squared bishop belongs c4 or [b5]. Quite a rare move, so it feels as a very good practical try for White.} b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7]} ({Just planning to develop the bishop on b7. A nice counter surprise of 5.a4, as there are only a couple of games after} 5... b6 {. And last but not least : a perfectly good and logical move. (5...e6 6.e5 is problematic. ) (5...d6 6.Bb5 does annoy actually, as we can't play ...[Nd4] anymore. )}) 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] This feels in the spirit of the Grand Prix Attack.} e6 {Here, White many logical options.} 7. e5 {[%cal Gc3e4,Ge4d6] Very agressive, trying to punish Black right away.} Nge7 8. Ne4 O-O $1 {Allowing the white knight on [d6] without check is no big deal, as we will be able to kick it away.} 9. Nd6 Nf5 $1 {[%cal Ge6f5,Gd7d6] White hasn't achieved anything with that jump.} *

