1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. a4 {Interesting prophylaxis proposed by GM Perelshteyn in his Chessable course Grand Prix Attack Reloaded, which avoids a future black expansion on the queenside by ...[a6]-...[b5] and basically ask Black how they want to develop before deciding where the light-squared bishop belongs c4 or [b5]. Quite a rare move, so it feels as a very good practical try for White.} b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7]} ({Just planning to develop the bishop on b7. A nice counter surprise of 5.a4, as there are only a couple of games after} 5... b6 {. And last but not least : a perfectly good and logical move. (5...e6 6.e5 is problematic. ) (5...d6 6.Bb5 does annoy actually, as we can't play ...[Nd4] anymore. )}) 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] This feels in the spirit of the Grand Prix Attack.} e6 {Here, White many logical options.} 7. f5 ({After} 7. O-O Nge7 {, we simply get a very good version of the line starting with 5.Bc4. Black gets the extra ...[b6], which will help the development of our light-squared bishop. The extra move [a4] White got is of little use to prevent Black's ...[d5] push...}) 7... gxf5 {[%cal Gg8e7] Not the only way, but certainly a very good one.} 8. d3 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5 Bb7 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gg8h8] We are not afraid. Our king will be very safe on [h8], and we are still a pawn up.} *

