1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. a4 {Interesting prophylaxis proposed by GM Perelshteyn in his Chessable course Grand Prix Attack Reloaded, which avoids a future black expansion on the queenside by ...[a6]-...[b5] and basically ask Black how they want to develop before deciding where the light-squared bishop belongs c4 or [b5]. Quite a rare move, so it feels as a very good practical try for White.} b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7]} ({Just planning to develop the bishop on b7. A nice counter surprise of 5.a4, as there are only a couple of games after} 5... b6 {. And last but not least : a perfectly good and logical move. (5...e6 6.e5 is problematic. ) (5...d6 6.Bb5 does annoy actually, as we can't play ...[Nd4] anymore. )}) 6. Be2 ({That's the big plan in the course I mentioned.} 6. Bb5 Nd4 {transposes here.}) 6... Bb7 7. O-O {This is White's idea, planning to go [f5] and attack in the spirit of the Grand Prix Attack.} (7. d3 {seems too tame. I don't really see any worries after} e6 {.}) 7... Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5] I really like this move preparing ...[f5] which would prevent a future [f5] for White, the main idea of the line and not touching our central pawns yet.} 8. f5 $1 ({Here starts the fun!} 8. d3 {is just harmless.} f5 9. e5 d6 {It is very unclear how White will get any play.}) 8... gxf5 9. d3 {A typical pawn sac preventing Black's short castle and trying to open up the f-file.} Ng4 10. Bf4 {[%cal Rd8c7] A clever developing move keeping the black queen off that diagonal.} Nd4 {[%cal Gb7g2,Gg7d4] A very logical move activating both bishops.} 11. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7]} Ne6 {[%cal Ge6f4] The position becomes out of control for both sides, but we know what we are doing.} 12. Ng5 $1 {A nice counterpush attacking [e6] and [g4] at the same time. Obviously, the position is full of life with a lot of options for us. My favorite is the following exchange sac.} h5 $1 13. Nxe6 dxe6 14. Nc7+ Kf8 15. Nxa8 Bd4+ 16. Kh1 Bxa8 {[%cal Ga8h1,Gd4g1,Gg4f2] After a sequence of forced moves, we have reached a very interesting position where we have the initiative.} 17. Bxg4 hxg4 {[%csl Ge6,Gf5,Gg4][%cal Ga8g2] Our pawn chain and our light-squared bishop on [a8] are very impressive. I like Black very much here.} *

