1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. a4 {Interesting prophylaxis proposed by GM Perelshteyn in his Chessable course Grand Prix Attack Reloaded, which avoids a future black expansion on the queenside by ...[a6]-...[b5] and basically ask Black how they want to develop before deciding where the light-squared bishop belongs c4 or [b5]. Quite a rare move, so it feels as a very good practical try for White.} b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] Just planning to develop the bishop on [b7]. A nice counter surprise of 5.a4 as there are only a couple of games after 5...[b6]. And last but not least : a perfectly good and logical move.} (5... e6 6. e5 {%cal Gc3e4,Ge4d6 (is problematic.)}) (5... d6 6. Bb5 {does annoy actually as we can't play [Nd4] anymore.}) 6. Be2 {That's the big plan in the course I mentioned.} (6. Bb5 Nd4 {tr. 5.Bb5 [Nd4] 6.a4}) 6... Bb7 7. O-O {This is White's idea, planning to go [f5] and attack in the spirit of the Grand Prix Attack.} (7. d3 {seems too tame. I don't really see any worries after} e6 {.}) 7... Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5] I really like this move preparing ...[f5] which would prevent a future [f5] for White, the main idea of the line and not touching our central pawns yet.} 8. f5 $1 ({Here starts the fun!} 8. d3 {is just harmless.} f5 9. e5 d6 {It is very unclear how White will get any play.}) 8... gxf5 9. d3 {A typical pawn sac preventing Black's short castle and trying to open up the f-file.} Ng4 10. Ng5 (10. exf5 {is just not in the spirit of the GP attack.} Qb8 $1 {Now, it is Black who is getting the threats and the fun!}) 10... h5 {[%cal Gh5g4] A must!} 11. Rxf5 {[%cal Gg5f7]} Bd4+ 12. Kh1 f6 {[%cal Gf6g5] Once again, play is becoming very sharp.} 13. Nh3 {White has to retreat in order not to be losing immediately. Sad but true.} (13. Nf3 $4 {is more natural, but we would end the game with} Nf2+ {.}) 13... e6 {[%cal Ge6f5]} 14. Bxg4 (14. Rf1 {is simply too slow.} Qe7 {followed by long castle, and we do have a great initiative on the kingside.}) 14... hxg4 15. Qxg4 {White had to do all that to avoid getting worse. We have a choice now.} Qe7 {Getting a very double-edged and playable position, so why should we stop the fun?} (15... exf5 {leads to a forced draw.} 16. Qg6+ Kf8 17. Bh6+ Rxh6 18. Qxh6+ Kg8 19. Qg6+ Kf8 {White has no better choice than taking the perpetual.}) 16. Rh5 O-O-O 17. Rxh8 Rxh8 {[%csl Gd4,Rh1,Rh3][%cal Gc6e5] It is pretty obvious that Black has full compensation for the pawn, as the white king is quite exposed and the knight is very misplaced on [h3].} 18. Bf4 c4 {[%cal Ge7b4] And the party continues!} *

