[GameId "2123892873417598"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. a4 {Interesting prophylaxis proposed by GM Perelshteyn in his Chessable course Grand Prix Attack Reloaded, which avoids a future black expansion on the queenside by ...[a6]-...[b5] and basically ask Black how they want to develop before deciding where the light-squared bishop belongs c4 or [b5]. Quite a rare move, so it feels as a very good practical try for White.} a6 {Honestly, my first intention was to recommend this move. Perelshteyn calls it 'a clever waiting move' and then gives some interesting lines which are by no means a refutation, but simply a way to get an interesting position with chances for both sides.} 6. Bc4 {That's the point. The bishop feels safer on [c4] with [a4]/...[a6] included.} e6 7. f5 $5 {[%cal Gc4f7] The sharpest option. White aims at a direct attack towards the black king.} gxf5 $1 {Challenge accepted! but not with the e-pawn, as that would open the [a2]-[g8] diagonal and the light-squared bishop would suddenly become a monster eyeing on [f7].} 8. d3 $1 {A typical way to play for White. Taking back on [f5] would allow Black to occupy the center with ...[d5].} Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5 {Again, an interesting concept, creating an annoying pin on the [e7]-knight. Nevertheless, Black is more than fine if we know what we are doing.} h6 {Controlling the very important [g5]-square and luring the bishop to [h4].} 11. Bh4 Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ge7g6] Two ideas in one move: unpinning and creating the idea of ...[Ng6] hitting the bishop on [h4].} 12. Qd2 f4 {[%cal Ge7g6] Closing down the position. ...[Ng6] is next!} 13. g3 {Trying to open up the position on the kingside, but we just refuse the offer.} Ng6 $1 14. Ne2 (14. gxf4 f5 $1 {and suddenly, it is Black who has play on the kingside, as the [f4]-pawn is weak.}) 14... Nxh4 15. Nxh4 fxg3 16. Nxg3 {[%cal Gg3h5,Gd2g2] Once again, if Black doesn't know the precise moves the initiative looks devastating in a practical game.} Qd8 $1 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gd8h4] A very strong defensive move. The queen gets back to the kingside winning a tempo by attacking the knight on [h4].} 17. Rf4 {'With an attack' says Perelshteyn. I think Black is better if we are precise.} Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5g6]} 18. Kh1 Ng6 19. Nxg6 fxg6 20. Raf1 b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] Black is a pawn up and has the pair of bishops. White has some compensation, as they are more active, but clearly not enough to get full compensation.} *

