1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. a4 {Interesting prophylaxis proposed by GM Perelshteyn in his Chessable course Grand Prix Attack Reloaded, which avoids a future black expansion on the queenside by ...[a6]-...[b5] and basically ask Black how they want to develop before deciding where the light-squared bishop belongs c4 or [b5]. Quite a rare move, so it feels as a very good practical try for White.} a6 {Honestly, my first intention was to recommend this move. Perelshteyn calls it 'a clever waiting move' and then gives some interesting lines which are by no means a refutation, but simply a way to get an interesting position with chances for both sides.} 6. Bc4 {That's the point. The bishop feels safer on [c4] with [a4]/...[a6] included.} e6 7. d3 {The quiet option.} Nge7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe1 {Clearly the main line.} d5 10. Bb3 Bd7 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gd7c6] I really like this very rare move only 3 games in my database and the plan behind it ...[Nd4]-...[Bc6] It also works tactically!} 11. exd5 {The obvious downside: the [d5]-pawn is hanging. But it is not over!} exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gb4d5]} 14. Bb3 Be6 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Ge6b3] A nice tactical shot exploiting the weakness of the [c2]-pawn.} 15. Bxe6 Nxc2 16. Qf2 Nxa1 17. Ba2 Qb6 $1 {[%cal Ga1b3] Making sure our knight gets out.} *

