1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. a4 {Interesting prophylaxis proposed by GM Perelshteyn in his Chessable course Grand Prix Attack Reloaded, which avoids a future black expansion on the queenside by ...[a6]-...[b5] and basically ask Black how they want to develop before deciding where the light-squared bishop belongs c4 or [b5]. Quite a rare move, so it feels as a very good practical try for White.} a6 {Honestly, my first intention was to recommend this move. Perelshteyn calls it 'a clever waiting move' and then gives some interesting lines which are by no means a refutation, but simply a way to get an interesting position with chances for both sides.} 6. Bc4 {That's the point. The bishop feels safer on [c4] with [a4]/...[a6] included.} e6 7. d3 {The quiet option.} Nge7 8. O-O O-O 9. Ne2 {A rare move recommended by Perelshteyn in his course. He clearly values surprise and rightly so!} d5 10. Ba2 {One of the points of having played that early [a4] is to get the [a2]-square for the bishop, but this is not without pluses for Black, as we can go ...[b5] and grab a lot of space.} b5 11. c3 Qb6 {[%cal Gc5c4] A novelty according to my database and also not covered in Perelshteyn course!} 12. Be3 (12. Kh1 b4 {followed by ...[a5] and ...[Ba6], and Black is very quickly getting play on the queenside.}) 12... a5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} (12... b4 $6 {is very natural but not precise, as White gets [a5] in, and it works for tactical reasons.} 13. a5 $1 Nxa5 14. cxb4 Qxb4 15. Bd2 {If Black protects the knight, White will just take on [a5] and [d5] winning material.}) 13. axb5 Qxb5 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc8a6]} 14. f5 {Black has already gotten a lot of play on the queenside, so it is time for White to generate some counterplay on the other side of the board.} dxe4 15. Bc4 Qb7 16. dxe4 exf5 {[%csl Rc5] A very sharp position, but it is clear that Black has at least equal chances.} *

