1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] A logical retreat attacking the weakest link on Black's camp: the [f7]-pawn.} Nh6 $5 {[%cal Ge7e6] I like this very rare move keeping an eye on the [f7]-pawn and preventing any White's [f5] push. On a good day, the knight may land on [f5] or [g4].} 7. O-O O-O 8. d3 e6 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gd7d5] As always, we want to push ...[d5] in one go.} 9. Be3 {This natural developing move is just terrible and can be punished right away.} d5 $1 {[%cal Gd4f3,Gd5d4]} 10. exd5 Ng4 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gg4e3]} 11. Bc1 exd5 {[%cal Gd4f3,Gg7d4]} 12. Bxd5 Nxf3+ {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gg7d4,Gd8d5] White has many ways to recapture on [f3] but all of them are losing material!} *

