1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] A logical retreat attacking the weakest link on Black's camp: the [f7]-pawn.} Nh6 $5 {[%cal Ge7e6] I like this very rare move keeping an eye on the [f7]-pawn and preventing any White's [f5] push. On a good day, the knight may land on [f5] or [g4].} 7. O-O O-O 8. d3 e6 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gd7d5] As always, we want to push ...[d5] in one go.} 9. Kh1 ({It always makes sense to start with hiding the king before starting any kingside actions for White. It's just too early for} 9. f5 d5 $1 10. exd5 {This is forced, as Black wanted to take on [e4], but after} Nhxf5 {, Black is already much better.}) 9... d5 {A very interesting pawn sac. Black is getting all the fun.} 10. exd5 exd5 11. Bxd5 Bg4 {[%csl Ra1,Rc1][%cal Gh6f5,Gf8e8,Gg4d1] It is pretty clear that White is under serious pressure and behind in development.} 12. Bxb7 {Greed also gives Black amazing compensation.} Rb8 13. Be4 Nhf5 {Black is fully active, and it won't be easy for White to finish their development. For instance, trying to exchange some pieces doesn't really help White, but it could be best anyway.} 14. Bxf5 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nxf5 {[%csl Rf3,Rf4,Rh1,Rh2][%cal Gd8h4,Gg7b2] White's kingside is in shambles. Our piece activity and pressure on both sides of the board give ample compensation.} *

