1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] A logical retreat attacking the weakest link on Black's camp: the [f7]-pawn.} Nh6 $5 {[%cal Ge7e6] I like this very rare move keeping an eye on the [f7]-pawn and preventing any White's [f5] push. On a good day, the knight may land on [f5] or [g4].} 7. O-O O-O 8. d3 e6 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gd7d5] As always, we want to push ...[d5] in one go.} 9. Kh1 ({It always makes sense to start with hiding the king before starting any kingside actions for White. It's just too early for} 9. f5 d5 $1 10. exd5 {This is forced, as Black wanted to take on [e4], but after} Nhxf5 {, Black is already much better.}) 9... d5 {A very interesting pawn sac. Black is getting all the fun.} 10. exd5 exd5 11. Bxd5 Bg4 {[%csl Ra1,Rc1][%cal Gh6f5,Gf8e8,Gg4d1] It is pretty clear that White is under serious pressure and behind in development.} 12. h3 ({This seems logical to get rid of the unpleasant pin as soon as possible. It's not possible to finish the development without losing material, e.g.:} 12. Be3 Ndf5 {and all the white pieces are attacked.}) 12... Ndf5 $1 {[%cal Gf5g3,Gg7c3,Gd8d5] Tactics are working in Black's favor!} 13. hxg4 Nxg4 {[%cal Gg7c3,Gf5g3] White is busted, and it is even possible to finish the game in style if White is not careful.} 14. Be4 Ng3+ 15. Kg1 Qd4+ $3 (15... Bd4+ {would be just as good, but giving up the queen in order to mate is definitely fancier!}) 16. Nxd4 Bxd4+ {[%cal Gd4g1] With mate to follow.} *

