1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. Nxd4 {The lazy way to deal with 5...Nd4 and not at all challenging for Black.} cxd4 $1 {Of course! winning a tempo on the knight on [c3], and the bishop on [b5] is loose as no longer has protection from the knight.} 7. Ne2 Nh6 $5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d5] I really like this concept: we're castling on the next move, and ...[d5] will come next. Once again, White has to be careful about the knight landing on [f5] or [g4] in the future.} 8. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] This natural retreat shows Black's position potential.} b5 9. Bb3 {That is just helping Black in getting an early initiative on the queenside.} a5 10. a4 bxa4 11. Bxa4 O-O {[%cal Gd8b6,Gd7d5] Feels like the white bishop was randomly moving around while Black just developed and gained space!} *

