[White "22) Grand Prix Attack"]
[Black "Grand Prix 5.Bb5 Nd4 6.Nxd4 #6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B23"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[GameId "2123892873515913"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. Nxd4 {The lazy way to deal with 5...Nd4 and not at all challenging for Black.} cxd4 $1 {Of course! winning a tempo on the knight on [c3], and the bishop on [b5] is loose as no longer has protection from the knight.} 7. Ne2 Nh6 $5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d5] I really like this concept: we're castling on the next move, and ...[d5] will come next. Once again, White has to be careful about the knight landing on [f5] or [g4] in the future.} 8. O-O O-O {[%cal Gd7d5]} 9. d3 {The most natural, but the bishop on [b5] is now very isolated.} d5 $1 {[%csl Rb5]} 10. e5 (10. exd5 {giving up the center way too early.} Qxd5 {and we will just follow up with ...[b6], ...[Bb7] while the knight has an ideal square on [f5].}) 10... Qa5 $1 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga7a6]} 11. c4 {The only move not to lose a piece!} dxc3 12. Nxc3 a6 (12... d4 $6 13. Qa4 {is surprisingly holding for White!}) 13. Ba4 Bg4 {[%cal Gd5d4]} 14. Qc2 Rfc8 {[%cal Gd5d4,Gb7b5,Gb5b4] White is having a hard time saving their light-squared bishop!} 15. h3 Bxh3 16. gxh3 b5 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gd5d4,Gb5a4] We are getting our piece back while the white king is now very exposed.} *

