1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. Bd3 Nf6 $5 {A very provocative move inviting White to push [e5].} 7. e5 Nh5 {[%cal Gh5f4] That was the plan; now that the light-squared bishop is on [d3], it is not possible to protect the [f4]-pawn in a natural way as [d2]-[d3] is illegal. Black is already better!} 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Ne2 d6 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gd6e5,Gc8g4] White's pawn centre is collapsing.} *

