1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. Bd3 Nf6 $5 {A very provocative move inviting White to push [e5].} 7. O-O O-O 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Ne2 d6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} (9... d6 {Finishing the development and preparing ...e7-e5 as the d4-pawn is taboo.} 10. Nxd4 $4 {is just a blunder, losing a piece because of the pin on the long diagonal.} Qb6 11. c3 e5 {-+ .}) 10. Qe1 Bd7 11. c3 e5 12. cxd4 exd4 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gf8e8]} 13. Nxd4 {The [d4]-pawn is still taboo.} Qb6 {[%csl Rc1,Ra1][%cal Gb6g1,Gf6g4] Winning material thanks to the pin on the [a7]-[g1] diagonal.} *

