1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. Bd3 Nf6 $5 {A very provocative move inviting White to push [e5].} 7. O-O O-O 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Ne2 d6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} (9... d6 {Finishing the development and preparing ...e7-e5 as the d4-pawn is taboo.} 10. Nxd4 $4 {is just a blunder, losing a piece because of the pin on the long diagonal.} Qb6 11. c3 e5 {-+ .}) 10. c3 e5 $1 {Taking on [c3] would only help White developing. We don't want that if possible!} 11. cxd4 exf4 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Rc1] Tactics are working in Black's favor, not a big surprise if we look at the massive underdevelopment of White’s queenside pieces.} 12. Rxf4 Nh5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gh5f4,Gc8g4]} 13. Rf1 Bg4 {[%cal Gg7d4]} 14. Qe1 d5 {Most precise and makes sense. White has the ugly choice of opening up the game or creating one more weakness...} 15. e5 Qb6 {[%csl Rd4,Re5][%cal Gg7e5,Gg4e2,Gb6d4]} 16. Qf2 f6 $1 {[%cal Gf8f1] White's position is falling apart!} *

