1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. O-O {By far, the most popular.} a6 7. Be2 {This is just too passive and allows Black to finish their development in a very harmonious way.} d6 8. d3 e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gb7b5,Ge8g8,Gc8b7]} 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Nb1 {The only possible retreat.} Ne7 11. Nd2 Bd7 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Ga8c8,Ge8g8] Black didn't need to be very creative in order to get a clear plan and a good position.} *

