1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. O-O {By far, the most popular.} a6 7. Bd3 (7. Bc4 {is simply wrong; the bishop will lack squares very soon.} b5 8. Bd5 Rb8 {followed by ...[e6], and the bishop will have to retreat once again.}) 7... b5 $1 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gc8b7]} (7... d6 {is a normal way to play and definitely not a disaster for Black, but much less incisive than the main line.} 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Ne2 Nf6 10. c3 {Now, White is in time to finish their development.} dxc3 11. dxc3 O-O {(That's an acceptable position for both sides engine showing zeros.... And in general, it is a pretty good outcome of the opening for Black, but against such dubious sidelines, I think Black should be more ambitious!)}) 8. e5 {[%cal Gd3e4] Creating space for the light-squared bishop but also creating a target.} d6 $1 {[%cal Gd6e5]} 9. Be4 Rb8 10. d3 (10. exd6 Qxd6 {giving away the center is rarely a good idea, and that is certainly not an exception. Our knight has the [f6]-square available now.}) 10... Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6] It is very unclear to me how White will proceed while we will just finish our development. The pawn on [e5] will become weak or will just be exchanged, and White's position will lose its main trump.} *

