1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix attack! Once again, this system is much more dangerous against Najdorf players as they are kind of forced to play 2...d6 if they don't want to end up in another Sicilian than the Najdorf, and therefore can't go ...[d5] in one go.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 (4... Bg7 {Note that now} 5. g3 {is actually just transposing to the Closed Sicilian chapter after} e6 6. Bg2 Nge7 {.}) 5. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $1 {We don't want to allow White to take on [c6] as it would give them an easy game and some nice prospects on the kingside.} 6. O-O {By far, the most popular.} a6 7. Bd3 (7. Bc4 {is simply wrong; the bishop will lack squares very soon.} b5 8. Bd5 Rb8 {followed by ...[e6], and the bishop will have to retreat once again.}) 7... b5 $1 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gc8b7]} (7... d6 {is a normal way to play and definitely not a disaster for Black, but much less incisive than the main line.} 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Ne2 Nf6 10. c3 {Now, White is in time to finish their development.} dxc3 11. dxc3 O-O {(That's an acceptable position for both sides engine showing zeros.... And in general, it is a pretty good outcome of the opening for Black, but against such dubious sidelines, I think Black should be more ambitious!)}) 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Ne2 Bb7 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd8b6,Gg8f6] Developing and immediately putting pressure on the white central pawn on [e4].} 10. a4 {A typical way to challenge the [b5]-pawn in Sicilians. It's the first line of the engine, but a novelty!} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] A typical way to play the Sicilian: ignoring White's threat and counterattacking in the center!} 11. e5 Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga4b5,Ge2d4] Black now has a beautiful and centralized knight. White can take one of the pawns; either way, Black is getting a lot of counterplay.} 12. axb5 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d3]} 13. bxa6 Nxd3 14. cxd3 Bxa6 {[%cal Ga6d3] Two bishops and activity guarantee Black enough compensation for the pawn.} 15. Nxd4 O-O {[%csl Rc1,Rd4][%cal Gd7d6] And ...[d6] on the next move will be hard for White to meet.} *

