1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. f4 {This feels too early to me.} e6 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5] I always like to start with ...[e6] before going ...[d6] as in some cases we can push ...[d5] in one go. I would say it is especially true in this particular line as 5.f4 gives us some time to organize that push.} 6. e5 $6 {[%cal Gc3e4] This could be a try to punish Black for starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6].} d5 $1 {[%cal Gg8h6,Gh6f5]} 7. exd6 Qxd6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8] White just lost time and they would rather have the pawn on [f2] instead of [f4]. Black already has better chances.} 8. Ne4 Qc7 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gg8e7] If White lets us finish our development with ...[b6], ...[Nge7], and ...[Bb7], we will have a very nice outpost on [d4] and we will do very well. Therefore, they can decide to grab a pawn.} 9. Nxc5 Nd4 {[%csl Rc5,Rc2][%cal Gd4c2,Gc7c5] Suddenly, White is in massive trouble, as the knight on [c5] is hanging and you can't really remove it, as [c2] would be lost.} 10. b4 {The only way to protect the knight.} a5 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Rc2][%cal Ga5b4,Gg7a1] And again, more problems, rather than solutions, are coming for White.} *

