1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. f4 {This feels too early to me.} e6 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5] I always like to start with ...[e6] before going ...[d6] as in some cases we can push ...[d5] in one go. I would say it is especially true in this particular line as 5.f4 gives us some time to organize that push.} 6. d3 Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 7. Be3 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5d4] This line illustrates perfectly why we started with 5...e6.} 8. exd5 {Opening up the position is simply wrong.} Nxd5 $1 9. Nxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gg7b2,Ge8g8] Black has a great initiative. The [c5]-pawn is untouchable:} 10. Bxc5 Qa5+ 11. b4 Nxb4 {[%cal Ga5e1,Gg7a1,Ga5c5] Black is just winning material.} *

