1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. f4 {This feels too early to me.} e6 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5] I always like to start with ...[e6] before going ...[d6] as in some cases we can push ...[d5] in one go. I would say it is especially true in this particular line as 5.f4 gives us some time to organize that push.} 6. Nf3 Nge7 7. d3 (7. O-O O-O 8. d3 {is another move order.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ({Again, we don't lose any time with} 8... d6 {before White goes [Be3]. Though it is the most played move, it doesn't make much sense to me.}) 9. a4 b6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 10. Qe2 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gc6d4] It's hard to see a constructive plan for White.} *

