1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In this chapter, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. d3 Nge7 7. Be3 Nd4 $5 {That's the simplest avoiding any breaks in the center.} 8. Qd2 ({Now} 8. O-O d6 9. Qd2 O-O {transposes here.}) 8... d6 {White has two attempts with independent value, but both fail to impress.} 9. O-O-O {This fails to scare Black.} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gd4e2]} (9... Qb6 {Preventing} 10. Bh6 {due to 9...Nxe2 and Black wins a piece.}) 10. Rhe1 {[%cal Ge1e2,Ge3h6]} ({Overprotecting e2 and threatening Bh6, as the immediate} 10. Bh6 {runs into} Nxe2+ {winning a piece.}) 10... h5 $1 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Ge8c8,Gc8d7] Preventing [Bh6] and preparing ...[Bd7] followed by long castle. Black is doing very well.} *

