1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In this chapter, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. d3 Nge7 7. Be3 Nd4 $5 {That's the simplest avoiding any breaks in the center.} 8. h4 {Keep in mind that something like that can always happen these days!} h5 {Stopping the action on the kingside but giving away the [g5]-square, which is not a big deal.} 9. Bg5 d6 10. O-O Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6]} 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Ne2 Qb6 {[%cal Ge7c6] A nice way to unpin. Having the king in the center for a while is not a big deal as the position is closed.} 13. Bxe7 (13. c3 Nc6 {supporting the [d4]-pawn.}) 13... Kxe7 {[%cal Gh8c8,Ge7f8] After ...[Rhc8], our king will be safe on [f8]. Black is very comfortable.} *

