1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In this chapter, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. d3 Nge7 7. Be3 d6 ({To be honest, I also looked at this, and the conclusion is that the sharp mess arising is very playable for Black. So my conclusion is that} 7... d6 {is for people who like unnecessary complications!}) 8. h4 {This always looks tempting, but it is unclear to me if the inclusion of [h4]/...[h5] favors White.} (8. Qd2 Nd4 {transposes to 7...Nd4.}) 8... h5 9. O-O Nd4 {[%csl Gh4,Gh5]} 10. Bg5 {The pin looks nice, but it doesn't really threaten anything.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] Black is finishing their development and has a very nice position.} *

