1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In this chapter, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. d3 Nge7 7. Be3 d6 ({To be honest, I also looked at this, and the conclusion is that the sharp mess arising is very playable for Black. So my conclusion is that} 7... d6 {is for people who like unnecessary complications!}) 8. d4 $5 {The other move with independent value. We can avoid all this by playing 7...Nd4 stopping any central breaks.} Qb6 $5 ({Quite rare.} 8... cxd4 {is by far the main move and transposes to some kind of weird Open Sicilian, which I assume we would preferably avoid.}) 9. Na4 Qa5+ 10. Nac3 {[%cal Ga5b6]} (10. Nac3 {Of course, we can repeat with} Qb6 {, but Black is objectively not worse, and we have no reason not to continue the game.}) 10... O-O 11. O-O Qb4 {[%cal Gc5d4]} 12. dxc5 dxc5 13. Rb1 {A sad necessity, but the position remains unclear.} Rd8 14. Qc1 e5 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc6d4]} 15. Nd5 ({This is simply not working. After} 15. f4 Be6 {, Black has zero problems.}) 15... Nxd5 16. exd5 Nd4 17. Nxd4 cxd4 {[%csl Rc2,Rd5] Black’s pawn structure is very compact while White has a couple of weaknesses on [c2] and [d5].} *

