1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In this chapter, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. d3 Nge7 7. Be3 d6 ({To be honest, I also looked at this, and the conclusion is that the sharp mess arising is very playable for Black. So my conclusion is that} 7... d6 {is for people who like unnecessary complications!}) 8. d4 $5 {The other move with independent value. We can avoid all this by playing 7...Nd4 stopping any central breaks.} Qb6 $5 ({Quite rare.} 8... cxd4 {is by far the main move and transposes to some kind of weird Open Sicilian, which I assume we would preferably avoid.}) 9. dxc5 dxc5 10. Rb1 ({A bit slow and not really posing any problems.} 10. f4 $6 {is met by} e5 {opening up the light-squared bishop.}) 10... O-O 11. Qd6 Bd4 $1 {Nice and important!} 12. Bh6 Rd8 13. Qf4 Bh8 {[%csl Gh8] Important to keep that bishop alive to avoid getting mated.} 14. O-O Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c2,Ge6e5] This leads to a sharp position where Black has very good counterplay. Be aware that the pin is not dangerous.} 15. Bg5 e5 $1 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gb6f6] A nice resource enabling ...[f6].} *

