1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In this chapter, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. d3 Nge7 7. Be3 d6 ({To be honest, I also looked at this, and the conclusion is that the sharp mess arising is very playable for Black. So my conclusion is that} 7... d6 {is for people who like unnecessary complications!}) 8. d4 $5 {The other move with independent value. We can avoid all this by playing 7...Nd4 stopping any central breaks.} Qb6 $5 ({Quite rare.} 8... cxd4 {is by far the main move and transposes to some kind of weird Open Sicilian, which I assume we would preferably avoid.}) 9. dxc5 dxc5 10. O-O O-O 11. Qd6 {[%cal Ge3c5,Gd6c5] The most aggressive and clearly asking serious questions to Black.} Qxb2 12. e5 $1 Bxe5 13. Qxc5 {[%csl Rb2] The queen on [b2] is a bit awkward, but we do have some very nice tactics working in our favor.} b6 14. Qc4 {[%csl Rc6]} Qa3 $3 {[%cal Gc8a6] Looks like we're blundering the knight on [c6] but Black is getting back the piece.} 15. Bxc6 Nxc6 16. Qxc6 Ba6 {[%csl Rc3,Re2][%cal Ga8c8] Both white knights are very loose, and we actually get one of them back!} 17. Nb5 Qa4 $1 18. Nec3 ({After} 18. c4 Rac8 19. Qf3 Rxc4 {, White can't save the knight, and Black is actually taking over.}) 18... Qa5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ga8c8,Gf8c8] Black is definitely not worse.} *

