1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In this chapter, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. f4 $6 d5 $1 (6... Nge7 {intending ...[d5] is also possible and good but really wanted to show how playing [f4] too early can be extremely dangerous for White.}) 7. exd5 exd5 8. Nxd5 Nge7 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc6d4]} 10. O-O ({Natural but basically losing. It makes sense to prevent ...Bg4 with} 10. h3 {, but it takes too much time. Black has a great initiative after} c4 11. O-O Be6 {as White's queenside is underdeveloped.}) 10... Bg4 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 11. Bf3 Bxf3 12. Rxf3 O-O {[%csl Ra1,Rc1][%cal Gf8e8] Black is much better developed in an open position. That's generally bad news for the other side, and this position is no exception.} *

