1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In this chapter, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. O-O Nge7 7. d3 O-O 8. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] An interesting way to play. White wants to provoke ...[h6] and retreat on [e3]; in that scenario, they would just win a tempo on the [h6]-pawn when they play [Qd2].} d6 (8... h6 {is not forced at all as the pin is not really threatening.} 9. Be3 Nd4 10. Qd2 {and the [h6]-pawn is a target.}) 9. Qd2 Nd4 $5 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7c6] If White don't react to ...[Nd4], Black will just keep developing with ...[Bd7]-[c6], for instance.} 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Ne2 e5 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gf7f6,Gc8e6,Ga8c8]} 12. c3 {Logical to get rid of the backward pawn on [c2].} f6 13. Bh6 Bxh6 14. Qxh6 dxc3 15. Nxc3 Be6 {[%cal Ge7c6,Gc6d4] White didn't achieve much on the kingside while Black has a beautiful square for their knight on [d4].} 16. h4 {A very agressive idea that could be a bit scary, but... no panic! There are clearly not enough pieces involved in White's attack for it to be successful.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 17. h5 g5 $1 {[%csl Rh6] This is a nice way to deal with the push. The white queen feels locked in Black's camp. We'll meet 18.f4!trying to lock out the queen with 18...gxf4 19.gxf4 Kh8 followed by ...[Rg8] and nice counterplay on the white king. It is pretty clear that it is Black who has benefited from the opening of the position.} *

