1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 e6 {In this chapter, I will always recommend starting with ...[e6] before ...[d6] as we keep hoping to get ...[d5] in one go.} (5... d6 6. d3 {is slightly more popular.}) 6. O-O Nge7 7. d3 O-O 8. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5,Gd3d4]} Nd4 {Stopping both threats at once!} 9. f4 d6 10. Qd2 (10. Qd2 {Hard to choose between} Rb8 {and 10...Bd7 , as both lead to similar good positions for Black.}) 10... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (10... Bd7 $5 {is a bit less sophisticated, though.} 11. Bf2 {intending to take on [d4].} Nxe2+ 12. Qxe2 Bc6 {supporting the ...[b5] push, and if White stops it with} 13. a4 {, then} Qc7 {keeping control of the [e5]-square. We'll continue with ...[b6].}) 11. a4 (11. Nd1 {is a very traditional way to get rid of the knight on [d4] without taking it. Here, [c3] will give Black an intermediate.} b5 12. c3 Nxe2+ 13. Qxe2 b4 {with ...[a5] and ...[Ba6] as our follow-up.}) 11... Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] And we have the same kind of positions/plans as in 10...Bd7, but I feel the addition [a4]/...[Rb8] can't harm Black.} *

