1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6 6. Be3 (6. f4 Nge7 {transposes here.}) (6. Nge2 Nge7 {transposes here.}) 6... d6 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6]} (7. Nge2 Nd4 {the standard way to stop White's [d4].} 8. Qd2 Ne7 {transposes here and 8.h4 h5 9.Bg5 Ne7 transposes here.}) 7... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] It makes sense not to develop the [g8]-knight yet, as it is still preventing [Bh6], and start the queenside expansion instead.} 8. a4 {[%cal Ga4b5] Stopping ...[b5].} Nd4 9. Nge2 Ne7 10. O-O O-O {[%cal Ge7c6,Gb7b6,Gc8b7]} (10... O-O {Once again Black will finish his development, and White is lacking a clear plan.} 11. f4 {transposes here.}) *

