1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6 6. Be3 (6. f4 Nge7 {transposes here.}) (6. Nge2 Nge7 {transposes here.}) 6... d6 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6]} (7. Nge2 Nd4 {the standard way to stop White's [d4].} 8. Qd2 Ne7 {transposes here and 8.h4 h5 9.Bg5 Ne7 transposes here.}) 7... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] It makes sense not to develop the [g8]-knight yet, as it is still preventing [Bh6], and start the queenside expansion instead.} 8. Nf3 {[%cal Ge4e5]} Nf6 $1 (8... b5 $6 {is surprisingly dubious.} 9. e5 $1 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. d4 $1 {, and White definitely gets a great initiative for the pawn.}) 9. Bh6 O-O 10. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} ({Not really a dangerous attack, as we can always take and kick out the queen of h6 easily. After} 10. O-O b5 {, Black has a free hand on the queenside. ...[b4] is the main idea.}) 10... Bxh6 11. Qxh6 Ng4 12. Qd2 b5 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ga7a5] It is hard to imagine White developing any kind of initiative on the kingside while Black is having fun on the queenside.} *

