1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nc3 {This can be a very subtle move order against Najdorf players as they are forced to play} d6 {or 2...a6 in order to be able to transpose to their stuff if White suddenly decides to transpose into an Open Sicilian.}) 2... Nc6 {That perfectly matches our repertoire and is the best setup vs the Closed Sicilian.} 3. g3 (3. Nge2 Nf6 $1 {transposes to 2.Ne2.}) (3. Nf3 e5 {transposes to 2.Nf3 [Nc6] 3.Nc3.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6 6. Be3 (6. f4 Nge7 {transposes here.}) (6. Nge2 Nge7 {transposes here.}) 6... d6 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6]} (7. Nge2 Nd4 {the standard way to stop White's [d4].} 8. Qd2 Ne7 {transposes here and 8.h4 h5 9.Bg5 Ne7 transposes here.}) 7... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] It makes sense not to develop the [g8]-knight yet, as it is still preventing [Bh6], and start the queenside expansion instead.} 8. Nge2 b5 9. a3 {Very understandable to slow down Black's play on the queenside.} Nd4 {The most played here and a very decent move. The position is about equal.} 10. O-O Ne7 11. Bh6 O-O 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1e3]} a5 14. Ne3 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge3g4]} h5 {[%cal Gh5g4] Taking space and preventing [Ng4].} 15. f4 d5 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Gb5,Gc5,Gd5][%cal Gd5e4] Black's phalanx on the fifth rank is quite impressive!} *

