1. e4 c5 2. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Generally a blitz weapon at the highest level and has been played by none others than Carlsen, Nepo or Mamedyarov!} g6 {[%cal Gg7a1] Exactly the same concept as against 2.b3. We don't want White to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8].} 3. Nc3 {White is changing their plans to play a Grand Prix Attack almost a tempo down as [a3] is not completely useless. The light-squared bishop will certainly be safe on [a2]!} Bg7 4. Bc4 (4. g3 {doesn’t make any sense; now, it is really a Closed Sicilian one tempo down for White after} Nc6 {.}) 4... Nc6 5. d3 e6 {[%cal Gc4e6]} 6. Ba2 {A useful waiting move asking Black where they want to develop the [g8]-knight.} d6 $1 ({And we don’t answer! We just play a useful move returning White the favour. Quite a rare move, but I think it is clever.} 6... Nge7 7. h4 $5 {is exactly what White wants.}) 7. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2]} (7. h4 Nf6 $1 {is the main point of not playing 7...Nge7. Now, it will be very difficult for White to justify the early [h4] push.} 8. Nge2 O-O {Even this is completely fine; Black will soon strike in the centre with ...[d5].}) 7... Nf6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf6h5,Gd6d5] The knight is doing a great job on [f6] defending against a possible [h4]-[h5]. Sometimes, ...[Ng4] can happen and, of course, the knight supports a possible central break such as ...[d5].} 8. Nf3 b6 {[%cal Gb6c5,Gd6d5] Protecting [c5] and therefore preparing ...[d5].} 9. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6]} h6 {Obviously, not the only option, but I think it setups a nice positional trap.} 10. O-O-O {[%cal Gd3d4] Very logical as Black can't castle due to the [h6]-pawn hanging.} e5 $1 {Closing down the centre and preparing an assault on the queenside while it seems impossible for White to generate any active play.} 11. h4 Rb8 {[%cal Gb6b5,Gb5b4] With a clear plan of pushing the b-pawn against White's king.} *

