1. e4 c5 2. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Generally a blitz weapon at the highest level and has been played by none others than Carlsen, Nepo or Mamedyarov!} g6 {[%cal Gg7a1] Exactly the same concept as against 2.b3. We don't want White to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8].} 3. h4 {That's the instinct of some people when they see a pawn on [g6]!} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6h5] Pure provocation! We want White to push their pawn forward and just collect it!} 4. Nc3 d6 {Slowing down a bit now that we prevented [h5].} (4... Bg7 {is the crazy option which gives an irrational position after a few moves. Not necessarily a bad try!} 5. e5 Nh5 6. g4 Nf4 7. d4 {White keeps going forward by chasing the knight.} cxd4 8. Qxd4 Ne6 9. Qe4 Nc6 {Very hard to say what's going on except that Black chances are definitely not worse.}) 5. Bc4 {Back to the Grand Prix Attack setup!} Bg7 6. d3 e6 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5] The usual closing down of the [a2]-[g8] diagonal. Ame time, we are preparing ...[d5].} 7. Bf4 {[%cal Gc3b5]} (7. Ba2 Nc6 {transposes here.}) ({As often, it is probably too early to get out with the queen.} 7. Qf3 Nc6 {intending to harass the queen from [d4].} 8. Nge2 a6 9. Ba2 h6 {, and it is really unclear what White has achieved and especially how they will continue, while we have a simple and concrete plan of expanding on the queenside.}) 7... a6 {[%cal Ga6b5,Gb7b5] Simple chess: preventing [Nb5] and supporting our queenside expansion by ...[b5].} 8. Ba2 b5 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 9. Qd2 h6 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ga8b8,Gb5b4] We just don't give anything to White, and we are preventing [Bh6] while we continue with our plan on the queenside.} *

