1. e4 c5 2. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Generally a blitz weapon at the highest level and has been played by none others than Carlsen, Nepo or Mamedyarov!} g6 {[%cal Gg7a1] Exactly the same concept as against 2.b3. We don't want White to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8].} 3. h4 {That's the instinct of some people when they see a pawn on [g6]!} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6h5] Pure provocation! We want White to push their pawn forward and just collect it!} 4. e5 Nh5 5. Be2 {That was played in Mamedyarov-Carlsen. Magnus missed a very strong move.} Nc6 {[%csl Re5] Simply ignoring White's threat!} 6. Bxh5 (6. Nf3 {Not only does it lack consistency, but it is quite a bad move.} d6 7. exd6 Qxd6 {and Black has achieved so much in so few moves! ...[Bg7] comes next, and the knights have lovely jumps to [d4] and [f4].}) 6... gxh5 7. Qxh5 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c2]} 8. Qd1 Qb6 {[%csl Rc2,Rg2][%cal Gc2c3,Gd4b3,Gb6g6] The queen is joining the party: the ...[Qg6] threat attacking [g2] and [c2] is quite a big deal.} 9. Nf3 {There is no better alternative than exchanging the powerful [d4] knight.} d6 {[%cal Gc8g4]} 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. exd6 Rg8 $1 {[%cal Gg8g2] Offering another pawn for the initiative. White is already busted!} *

