1. e4 c5 2. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Generally a blitz weapon at the highest level and has been played by none others than Carlsen, Nepo or Mamedyarov!} g6 {[%cal Gg7a1] Exactly the same concept as against 2.b3. We don't want White to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8].} 3. Bc4 Bg7 4. h4 {The delayed flank attack was actually tried by Nepo; it is not better than the immediate flank attack with 3.h4, to be honest.} Nf6 $1 5. e5 (5. Nc3 {will very likely transpose into something we've already seen. E.g.:} Nc6 6. d3 e6 7. Ba2 d6 {transposes here.}) 5... Ng8 $1 {[%csl Re5] We lost a couple of tempi but the [e5]-pawn is desperately weak.} 6. Nf3 (6. h5 Nc6 7. f4 Nh6 $1 {is just incredibly bad for White. It feels fair, nevertheless, as White was busy pushing pawns while we were developing!}) (6. f4 {covers the [e5]-pawn but weakens the kingside big time.} d6 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. d3 Nh6 {It is actually funny to notice that the engine already gives a decisive advantage for Black while we haven't done anything really active; we just waited for White to weaken themselves.}) 6... Nc6 7. Qe2 d5 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4] Natural, logical and good!} 8. exd6 Qxd6 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gc8g4,Gc6d4] We should just be careful of playing ...[Nf6] before pinning on [g4] with the bishop as after an immediate ...[Bg4], we could be tricked.} 9. d3 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4]} ({Black has a very nice position, but shouldn't fall for} 9... Bg4 $4 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Ng5+ {. A nasty and typical trick!}) *

