1. e4 c5 2. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Generally a blitz weapon at the highest level and has been played by none others than Carlsen, Nepo or Mamedyarov!} g6 {[%cal Gg7a1] Exactly the same concept as against 2.b3. We don't want White to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8].} 3. b4 {The logical follow-up of 2.a3!} Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c5] Simple and good, not giving any chance to White to get any active play.} 5. g3 ({If} 5. Rb1 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd7 {, we will finish our development with ...[Nf6] and castle, and it is very unclear what White achieved with this [a3]-[b4] operation.}) 5... Nc6 6. Rb1 {[%cal Gb1b4]} ({A sad necessity to protect the b4-pawn.} 6. bxc5 $6 dxc5 {is very awkward for White.}) 6... Nf6 7. Bg2 Bg4 $1 {Already asking an unpleasant question to White. They have to make a concession: getting pinned or making a non-desirable move as [f3].} 8. Nge2 (8. Nf3 cxb4 9. axb4 Nd4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Rc8 {Concrete play, which leads to a very unpleasant position for White as they are dominated on the central dark squares. ...[Nd7] and ...[e6] is a simple follow-up, and the [c2]-pawn is a headache for White.}) 8... Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4f3,Gg4f3]} 9. bxc5 dxc5 {[%cal Gd4e2,Gd4f3] Black has a nice pin, but White seems to be winning a pawn.} 10. Rxb7 Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Gh1b7]} 11. Bxe4 (11. Nxe4 Bxe2 {simply wins the queen.}) 11... Nf3+ {[%cal Ge1f1,Gg4h3]} 12. Bxf3 Bxf3 {[%cal Gf3h1,Gf3b7] Beautiful geometry, attacking both rooks and taking one of them for sure. Black is just completely winning.} *

