1. e4 c5 2. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Generally a blitz weapon at the highest level and has been played by none others than Carlsen, Nepo or Mamedyarov!} g6 {[%cal Gg7a1] Exactly the same concept as against 2.b3. We don't want White to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8].} 3. b4 {The logical follow-up of 2.a3!} Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c5] Simple and good, not giving any chance to White to get any active play.} 5. g3 ({If} 5. Rb1 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd7 {, we will finish our development with ...[Nf6] and castle, and it is very unclear what White achieved with this [a3]-[b4] operation.}) 5... Nc6 6. Rb1 {[%cal Gb1b4]} ({A sad necessity to protect the b4-pawn.} 6. bxc5 $6 dxc5 {is very awkward for White.}) 6... Nf6 7. Bg2 Bg4 $1 {Already asking an unpleasant question to White. They have to make a concession: getting pinned or making a non-desirable move as [f3].} 8. f3 {[%csl Rg2]} cxb4 $1 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb4c3] A nice intermediate move which prevents White from taking on [c5] and collecting the [b7]-pawn.} 9. axb4 Bd7 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 10. Nge2 {[%cal Gd2d4,Ge1g1]} b5 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga7a5] I like that idea fixing the [b4]-pawn and making sure ...[a5] happens next.} 11. d4 (11. Nxb5 Rb8 12. Na3 Rxb4 {What happened on the queenside looks very favourable to Black, who now has a passed pawn.}) 11... a5 12. bxa5 b4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c3]} 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nxa5 15. Rxb4 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd8c7] Black lost a pawn, but White's pieces are so poorly coordinated that they have more than enough compensation.} O-O 16. O-O Qc7 {[%cal Gf8b8]} 17. c3 Rfb8 18. Rxb8+ Rxb8 {[%cal Gc7c4,Gd7b5,Gb8b1,Ga5b3] Black is incredibly active on the queenside and is actually much better.} *

