1. e4 c5 2. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Generally a blitz weapon at the highest level and has been played by none others than Carlsen, Nepo or Mamedyarov!} g6 {[%cal Gg7a1] Exactly the same concept as against 2.b3. We don't want White to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8].} 3. b4 {The logical follow-up of 2.a3!} Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c5] Simple and good, not giving any chance to White to get any active play.} 5. g3 ({If} 5. Rb1 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd7 {, we will finish our development with ...[Nf6] and castle, and it is very unclear what White achieved with this [a3]-[b4] operation.}) 5... Nc6 6. Rb1 {[%cal Gb1b4]} ({A sad necessity to protect the b4-pawn.} 6. bxc5 $6 dxc5 {is very awkward for White.}) 6... Nf6 7. Bg2 Bg4 $1 {Already asking an unpleasant question to White. They have to make a concession: getting pinned or making a non-desirable move as [f3].} 8. f3 {[%csl Rg2]} cxb4 $1 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb4c3] A nice intermediate move which prevents White from taking on [c5] and collecting the [b7]-pawn.} 9. axb4 Bd7 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 10. b5 {The cleanest way to prevent Black from pushing ...[b5] themselves.} (10. d4 {is also very logical. White occupies the centre, which was abandoned by Black taking on [b4].} e5 $1 {and now} 11. d5 Nd4 {letting a protecting knight enter your position is always a risky business. That is no exception. ...[Rc8] is next. After 11.dxe5 dxe5 12.Nge2 O-O , Black has restored the equality in the centre and will happily benefit from the weakening the [b4] push has provoked in White's position.}) 10... Nd4 11. Nge2 {Getting rid of the annoying [d4]-knight immediately makes a lot of sense.} Nxe2 12. Qxe2 O-O 13. O-O a6 {Trying to create an outside passer with a rook behind it! is generally not a bad idea. It gives good scenarios for a potential endgame...} 14. bxa6 (14. f4 {White dreams of pushing e5.} axb5 {Opening up the a-line for the [a8]-rook was the other idea of Black's previous move.} 15. Nxb5 Ra5 16. Nc3 Qc7 {Black's pieces are very active while preventing White's play.}) 14... bxa6 {[%csl Ga8][%cal Ga6a1]} 15. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5] The most logical as the pawn on [f3] was misplaced anyway.} Rb8 {[%csl Gb8,Rg1] Moving the rook away from a potential [e5] push attacking the [a8]-rook. The [a6]-pawn is hanging, but that works tactically because the white king is on the open diagonal [g1]-[a7].} 16. Rxb8 Qxb8 17. Qxa6 $2 Ng4 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gg7d4,Gd7b5] Too many threats. White is busted.} *

