1. e4 c5 2. b4 {The Sicilian Wing Gambit. It's not really dangerous if we know what we are doing.} cxb4 {Accepting the gambits is generally the only way to refute them!} 3. d4 ({Trying to occupy the centre.} 3. Nf3 d5 {This reaction in the centre is natural and good.} 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 6. a3 {transposes. After 5.c4 Qd8 6.d4 e6 , Black is a healthy pawn up with ...[Nf6] and ...[Be7] coming.}) 3... d5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb4c3]} 4. exd5 (4. e5 {plays in the spirit of the Advance French, but Black is a pawn up, and the light-squared bishop on [c8] is not locked in by its own pawn on [e6].} Nc6 5. a3 Qa5 $1 6. Nf3 Bf5 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 e6 {We're a pawn up and the so-called 'bad bishop' exchanged. Black is doing well in this Advance French!} 9. O-O Rc8 10. Bb2 Qc7 {and if White takes on [b4], we'll recapture with the knight aiming at [c2].}) 4... Nf6 5. a3 Qxd5 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gb8c6] White is obviously lacking development.} 6. Nf3 (6. axb4 e5 {Black is winning a pawn.}) (6. c4 bxc3 7. Nxc3 Qa5 {luring the bishop on [d2] makes sense.} 8. Bd2 Qd8 {There is absolutely no compensation for the missing pawn. We will just complete our kingside development and castle.}) 6... e6 7. Be2 Nc6 8. O-O Qd8 $1 {Making sure that [c4] will not come with tempo on the queen.} 9. axb4 Bxb4 10. c3 Be7 11. c4 O-O 12. Nc3 a5 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4] Securing the [b4]-square for the knight. Hard to see White's compensation for the pawn.} *

