1. e4 c5 2. b4 {The Sicilian Wing Gambit. It's not really dangerous if we know what we are doing.} cxb4 {Accepting the gambits is generally the only way to refute them!} 3. Bb2 e6 {[%cal Gg8f6]} 4. Nf3 (4. a3 Nf6 $1 {hitting the central pawn, and} 5. e5 Nd5 {does not really help White.}) 4... Nf6 5. e5 Nd5 6. a3 Nc6 {We basically never take on [a3] as it would help White develop.} 7. axb4 Bxb4 8. c4 Nde7 9. Be2 d6 {A logical novelty, not being afraid of losing the [g7]-pawn as losing the [g2]-pawn is a much bigger deal for White.} 10. exd6 Qxd6 11. O-O ({If} 11. Bxg7 Rg8 {, the rook will land on [g2] and put pressure on the [f2]-pawn.}) 11... e5 {[%cal Gb2e5] Limiting the action of the bishop on [b2].} 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6] Winning a tempo on the queen is not enough to compensate for the missing pawn.} Qb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8e5]} 14. d4 exd4 15. Nfxd4 a5 {[%cal Ga8a6,Ge7f5,Ga5b4] Protecting the bishop on [b4] just in case and activating the [a8]-rook as the rook will come on [a6] and then navigate on the 6th rank.} *

