1. e4 c5 2. b4 {The Sicilian Wing Gambit. It's not really dangerous if we know what we are doing.} cxb4 {Accepting the gambits is generally the only way to refute them!} 3. a3 e5 $5 {[%cal Gf8b4] Not a popular move, but I like it and thought that having a pawn on [e5] will suit the Sveshnikov spirit well!} (3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nf3 e5 6. c4 {is the main line and also good for Black.}) 4. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2e5]} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] We immediately start our counterattack on the [e4]-pawn. There are no natural ways to defend it.} 5. Nf3 Nxe4 6. Nxe5 {Taking with the knight on [e5] does not help as the [b2]-bishop is a loose piece...} bxa3 $1 {Helping White develop has a tactical justification!} 7. Nxa3 Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6f2,Gb6b2]} 8. Nd3 d5 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ga3c4,Gd5c4,Gd5e4] Protecting the knight on [e4] and avoiding an unpleasant [Nc4] in one go!} 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gf2f3]} Be7 $1 {Happily restoring material equality for the initiative.} 10. Bxg7 Rg8 11. Rb1 (11. Bb2 Nc6 12. f3 Nc5 {is hopeless for White. Too many loose pieces.}) 11... Rxg7 $3 {A beautiful queen sac taking advantage of the weakened first rank.} 12. Rxb6 axb6 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Ga8a1] White is busted.} *

