1. e4 c5 2. b4 {The Sicilian Wing Gambit. It's not really dangerous if we know what we are doing.} cxb4 {Accepting the gambits is generally the only way to refute them!} 3. a3 e5 $5 {[%cal Gf8b4] Not a popular move, but I like it and thought that having a pawn on [e5] will suit the Sveshnikov spirit well!} (3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nf3 e5 6. c4 {is the main line and also good for Black.}) 4. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2e5]} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] We immediately start our counterattack on the [e4]-pawn. There are no natural ways to defend it.} 5. Bxe5 Nc6 $1 6. Bxf6 ({Giving up the dark-squared bishop is not White's dream, but probably the most reasonable option...} 6. Bb2 Nxe4 {is simply bad. Black just got back the pawn and developed! ...[d5], ...[Bc5] and ...[Qb6] is simple and scary development.} 7. Qe2 {is definitely not winning a piece due to} Qe7 $1 {and White's problems remain.}) 6... Qxf6 {[%cal Gf6a1,Gf8c5]} 7. c3 bxc3 8. Nxc3 Bc5 {[%cal Gf6f2,Gc5f2]} 9. Nf3 b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc6e5]} ({Setting up a devilish trap!} 9... O-O {is also fine, but there is no hurry in castling.} 10. Be2 Nd4 11. O-O d6 12. Nd5 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Qe5 {The bishop pair guarantees Black an edge, and there is absolutely no disaster for White.}) 10. Nd5 {[%cal Gd5f6,Gd5c7,Gc7e8,Gc7a8] The most natural as it attacks the queen and also threatens [Nc7]+.} (10. Bc4 Ne5 11. Qe2 Bb7 {and Black is slightly better thanks to the bishops.}) 10... Qg6 $1 {'Blundering' a roo!} 11. Nc7+ Kd8 12. Nxa8 Qxe4+ 13. Be2 ({After} 13. Qe2 Qa4 {, Black's initiative is too strong, and White is lost. ...[Re8] is coming.}) 13... Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4e2,Gd4c2,Gd4f3,Ge4a8] Black suddenly has many threats!} 14. Nxd4 {Exchanging the annoying enemy makes a lot of sense.} Qxg2 15. Rf1 (15. Bf3 $4 Re8+ {is the point of Black's rook sac.}) 15... Bxd4 {[%cal Gd4a1,Gg2a8]} 16. Rc1 Qxa8 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gh8e8,Gc8a6] Black has two pawns for the exchange, and our initiative is not yet over.} *

