1. e4 c5 2. b4 {The Sicilian Wing Gambit. It's not really dangerous if we know what we are doing.} cxb4 {Accepting the gambits is generally the only way to refute them!} 3. a3 e5 $5 {[%cal Gf8b4] Not a popular move, but I like it and thought that having a pawn on [e5] will suit the Sveshnikov spirit well!} (3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nf3 e5 6. c4 {is the main line and also good for Black.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gd6e5,Gg8f6]} (4. axb4 $6 Bxb4 5. Nf3 Nc6 {looks like an Evans gambit but without the bishop on [c4] for White, which obviously diminishes their attacking potential.} 6. Bb2 d6 {and once again, it is hard to imagine that White will get any kind of compensation for the pawn. If 6.Bb5 Nf6! , we got a Berlin with an extra pawn, and the dark-squared bishop developed. That's obviously a very good deal for Black.}) 4... Nc6 5. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2e5] This makes sense as it immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn.} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb4a3,Gf8c5] Eyeing the bishop on [b2] and threatening ...[Bc5].} 6. Nxe5 {Indeed, it looks like we didn't defend our central pawn!} bxa3 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gc6e5]} 7. Bc3 a2 $1 {Nice move, easy to miss.} 8. Rxa2 {The most obvious reply.} Nxe5 9. Bxe5 Qe6 {[%cal Ge6a2,Ge6e5]} 10. Ra5 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ga5e5] The only move to protect both the rook on [a2] and the bishop on [e5].} b6 11. Rd5 f6 {[%cal Ge6e4] Collecting the [e4]-pawn.} 12. Bb2 Qxe4+ 13. Qe2 Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2 Bb7 {[%cal Gb7g2] Black is already a pawn up and will collect another pawn on [g2]. The rest is a matter of technique, as they say!} *

