1. e4 c5 2. b4 {The Sicilian Wing Gambit. It's not really dangerous if we know what we are doing.} cxb4 {Accepting the gambits is generally the only way to refute them!} 3. a3 e5 $5 {[%cal Gf8b4] Not a popular move, but I like it and thought that having a pawn on [e5] will suit the Sveshnikov spirit well!} (3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nf3 e5 6. c4 {is the main line and also good for Black.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gd6e5,Gg8f6]} (4. axb4 $6 Bxb4 5. Nf3 Nc6 {looks like an Evans gambit but without the bishop on [c4] for White, which obviously diminishes their attacking potential.} 6. Bb2 d6 {and once again, it is hard to imagine that White will get any kind of compensation for the pawn. If 6.Bb5 Nf6! , we got a Berlin with an extra pawn, and the dark-squared bishop developed. That's obviously a very good deal for Black.}) 4... Nc6 5. Bb5 (5. axb4 Bxb4 {transposes here.}) (5. Bc4 {is in the Italian spirit but Black's pawn on b4 is very annoying. 5...Nf6 6.Ng5 d5 7.exd5 Nxd5 8.Nxf7 Kxf7 9.Qf3+ Ke6 White doesn't have [Nc3], which is obviously a major issue.}) 5... Nf6 {[%csl Gb4,Rb1] A weird Berlin which simply can't favour White, being a pawn down and unable to develop their knight on its natural square [c3].} 6. O-O Be7 {Simple chess!} 7. axb4 O-O {[%cal Gf6e4,Ge7b4] A logical novelty asking White to clarify how they are planning to protect their pawns. Not an easy task!} *

