1. e4 c5 2. d4 {Introducing the Morra gambit. We have two options: taking the pawn or transposing to the line I am recommending against the Alapin.} cxd4 3. c3 (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nxd4 {transposes into our repertoire after} Nf6 {. If 4.c3 , again we have the option to transpose into our Alapin or just grab the pawn. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 transposes into Morra territory.}) 3... dxc3 (3... Nf6 4. e5 {the only decent move which will transpose into our Alapin lines. 4.Bd3 is simply a free pawn for Black. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 d6 7.O-O g6 followed by ...[Bg7] and castle. The white bishop is misplaced.}) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 {There are many decent setups for Black; I favoured this one as it seems that the most dangerous ideas in this line are connected with [Bc4]. So, 5...e6 blunts the bishop if it lands on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 6. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4d6] This makes sense as Black has weakened the dark squares, especially [d6], by playing ...[e6].} Bb4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gb4e1,Gg8f6]} 7. Bc4 {Not the most logical follow-up.} Nf6 $1 8. e5 Ne4 {[%csl Rc3]} 9. O-O $1 {White shouldn't lose time in protecting [c3].} Bxc3 10. bxc3 b5 $1 {[%cal Ge4c3,Gc3d1,Gc3b5,Gc8b7] A nice way to finish our development and get some space for the [c8] bishop.} 11. Qd3 Nxc3 $1 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gb5c4] The cleanest way!} 12. Qxc3 bxc4 13. Qxc4 Bb7 {[%cal Gc6a5,Ge8g8] Black is a comfortable pawn up.} *

