1. e4 c5 2. d4 {Introducing the Morra gambit. We have two options: taking the pawn or transposing to the line I am recommending against the Alapin.} cxd4 3. c3 (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nxd4 {transposes into our repertoire after} Nf6 {. If 4.c3 , again we have the option to transpose into our Alapin or just grab the pawn. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 transposes into Morra territory.}) 3... dxc3 (3... Nf6 4. e5 {the only decent move which will transpose into our Alapin lines. 4.Bd3 is simply a free pawn for Black. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 d6 7.O-O g6 followed by ...[Bg7] and castle. The white bishop is misplaced.}) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 {There are many decent setups for Black; I favoured this one as it seems that the most dangerous ideas in this line are connected with [Bc4]. So, 5...e6 blunts the bishop if it lands on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 6. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4d6] This makes sense as Black has weakened the dark squares, especially [d6], by playing ...[e6].} Bb4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gb4e1,Gg8f6]} 7. Bd6 ({The most consistent.} 7. Bd3 {makes sense to protect the [e4]-pawn, but that's way too cautious. White must prove there's compensation for the pawn and play aggressively.} d6 8. Rc1 e5 9. Be3 Nf6 {and the [d6]-pawn is clearly extra for nothing! Or 9.Bg5 f6 followed by ...[Nge7] and ...[Be6].}) 7... Bxd6 8. Qxd6 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gd8e7] Not intuitive but good!} 9. e5 (9. Nb5 Qa5+ $1 {An important and basically winning trick! There is no good way for White to block the check.}) 9... Ng4 {[%cal Gd8e7]} 10. Nb5 Qa5+ $1 {Again, this check is more than saving Black.} 11. b4 ({After} 11. Nd2 Kd8 $1 {, Black is winning another pawn and repelling the attack.} 12. f4 {trying to protect the [e5]-pawn only makes things worse for White due to 12...[Ne3] threatening a fork on [c2]. ...[a6] is coming.}) 11... Nxb4 12. Nc7+ Kd8 13. Nxa8 Nd5+ 14. Nd2 ({If} 14. Ke2 Qc3 {, White is getting mated. ...[Qc2] and ...[b6] intending ...[Ba6] are threats, not to mention the hanging rook on [a1].}) 14... Nxf2 $3 {[%cal Gf2h1,Gf2e4] Very important and winning the game!} *

