[Result "*"]
[ECO "B21"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2123892874109906"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 {Introducing the Morra gambit. We have two options: taking the pawn or transposing to the line I am recommending against the Alapin.} cxd4 3. c3 (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nxd4 {transposes into our repertoire after} Nf6 {. If 4.c3 , again we have the option to transpose into our Alapin or just grab the pawn. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 transposes into Morra territory.}) 3... dxc3 (3... Nf6 4. e5 {the only decent move which will transpose into our Alapin lines. 4.Bd3 is simply a free pawn for Black. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 d6 7.O-O g6 followed by ...[Bg7] and castle. The white bishop is misplaced.}) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 {There are many decent setups for Black; I favoured this one as it seems that the most dangerous ideas in this line are connected with [Bc4]. So, 5...e6 blunts the bishop if it lands on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 6. Be2 {This too modest to create any serious issues for Black.} Nf6 (6... Bb4 {is not a bad move, but it gives White the opportunity to equalise the game.} 7. O-O Nge7 8. Nb5 d5 9. Bf4 {and Black can't avoid the move repetition.} O-O 10. Nc7 Rb8 11. exd5 exd5 12. Nb5 Ra8 {There is nothing better than repeating for both sides.}) 7. O-O d6 {[%cal Gd6e5,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Avoiding any ...[e5] push and preparing ...[Be7] followed by castle.} 8. Qb3 {[%cal Gf1d1]} Be7 9. Rd1 {[%cal Ge4e5]} e5 10. Be3 O-O 11. Rac1 {It is clear that White has some compensation.} h6 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Ga8b8,Gc8e6] However, it is still White who has to prove the full compensation.} *

