1. e4 c5 2. d4 {Introducing the Morra gambit. We have two options: taking the pawn or transposing to the line I am recommending against the Alapin.} cxd4 3. c3 (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nxd4 {transposes into our repertoire after} Nf6 {. If 4.c3 , again we have the option to transpose into our Alapin or just grab the pawn. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 transposes into Morra territory.}) 3... dxc3 (3... Nf6 4. e5 {the only decent move which will transpose into our Alapin lines. 4.Bd3 is simply a free pawn for Black. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 d6 7.O-O g6 followed by ...[Bg7] and castle. The white bishop is misplaced.}) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 {There are many decent setups for Black; I favoured this one as it seems that the most dangerous ideas in this line are connected with [Bc4]. So, 5...e6 blunts the bishop if it lands on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 6. Bc4 (6. Bb5 {is pretty dubious, as White is not really threatening to take on c6.} a6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. e5 {trying to infiltrate the knight, but it doesn't really matter as we will get a very strong knight on [d5], and we just take the knight if it lands on [d6].} Ne7 $1 {and ...[Nd5]. 8.O-O Nf6 Again, it's very hard to see White's compensation. We will finish our development with an extra pawn.}) 6... a6 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gb7b5,Gc8b7] I like this move which has a double purpose: it prevents all kinds of [Nb5] ideas and prepares the development of the [c8]-bishop on [b7].} 7. O-O b5 {We will study all possible retreats!} 8. Bd3 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Ge7d5] Very important to prevent the [Nd5] sacrifices, which are White's main idea to get some play.} 9. Be3 Bb7 $1 (9... Ng6 {is just too dangerous for Black. White will execute the [Nd5] sacrifice and get a powerful initiative after} 10. a4 b4 11. Nd5 {.}) 10. Rc1 Ng6 11. a4 $1 ({A good and logical attempt to disturb Black's development.} 11. Nd5 {is now much more different than without ...[Bb7], as the [b8]-square is now available for the black queen.} Bd6 12. Bb6 Qb8 {is simply good for Black.}) 11... Be7 ({Giving back the pawn and completing development.} 11... b4 12. Nd5 exd5 {Just want to illustrate how dangerous it can be to take that knight on [d5]. ((If 12...Bd6 13.Nb6 Rb8 , White getting the c4-square for the knight is a major difference brought by the a4/...b4 inclusion.))} 13. exd5 Nce5 14. Bxg6 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 hxg6 16. Rfe1 {Black is in a lot of trouble, but we may survive with very precise play.}) 12. axb5 axb5 13. Bxb5 O-O {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gd8b8] Seems to me that the [b2]-pawn is more a weakness rather than a trump. Objectively speaking, the position is equal, but I would still take Black.} *

