1. e4 c5 2. d4 {Introducing the Morra gambit. We have two options: taking the pawn or transposing to the line I am recommending against the Alapin.} cxd4 3. c3 (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nxd4 {transposes into our repertoire after} Nf6 {. If 4.c3 , again we have the option to transpose into our Alapin or just grab the pawn. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 transposes into Morra territory.}) 3... dxc3 (3... Nf6 4. e5 {the only decent move which will transpose into our Alapin lines. 4.Bd3 is simply a free pawn for Black. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 d6 7.O-O g6 followed by ...[Bg7] and castle. The white bishop is misplaced.}) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 {There are many decent setups for Black; I favoured this one as it seems that the most dangerous ideas in this line are connected with [Bc4]. So, 5...e6 blunts the bishop if it lands on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 6. Bc4 (6. Bb5 {is pretty dubious, as White is not really threatening to take on c6.} a6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. e5 {trying to infiltrate the knight, but it doesn't really matter as we will get a very strong knight on [d5], and we just take the knight if it lands on [d6].} Ne7 $1 {and ...[Nd5]. 8.O-O Nf6 Again, it's very hard to see White's compensation. We will finish our development with an extra pawn.}) 6... a6 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gb7b5,Gc8b7] I like this move which has a double purpose: it prevents all kinds of [Nb5] ideas and prepares the development of the [c8]-bishop on [b7].} 7. O-O b5 {We will study all possible retreats!} 8. Be2 {Honestly, it feels wrong to retreat to such a passive square being a pawn down.} Bb7 (8... Nge7 $6 {is now a mistake.} 9. a4 b4 10. Nd5 {This is the only asset of having the bishop on [e2] rather than on [d3]. The white queen is protecting the [d5]-square, thus making this particular sacrifice possible.}) 9. Bf4 Be7 10. e5 {[%cal Ge5f6] This makes a lot of sense, preventing Black from finishing their development with ...[Nf6], but that [e5]-pawn is actually falling!} g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gc6e5]} 11. Be3 (11. Bg3 h5 {is way too scary for White. ...[Nh6]-...[Nf5] is coming once White addresses...[h4].}) 11... g4 12. Nd2 Nxe5 13. Bd4 {[%cal Gd4h8] This looks a bit scary, but all is under control!} f6 14. Bxg4 Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6g4,Gh6f7]} 15. Bxe5 fxe5 16. Bh5+ Kf8 {[%csl Gb7,Gd7,Ge5,Ge6,Ge7][%cal Gh8g8,Gf8g7,Gg7h8] The king will actually be safe on [g7] or even later [h8] when the rook moves away from that square g8 attacking [g2] looks like a very decent square. Also, Black has many trumps as the centre and the bishop pair.} *

