1. e4 c5 2. d4 {Introducing the Morra gambit. We have two options: taking the pawn or transposing to the line I am recommending against the Alapin.} cxd4 3. c3 (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nxd4 {transposes into our repertoire after} Nf6 {. If 4.c3 , again we have the option to transpose into our Alapin or just grab the pawn. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 transposes into Morra territory.}) 3... dxc3 (3... Nf6 4. e5 {the only decent move which will transpose into our Alapin lines. 4.Bd3 is simply a free pawn for Black. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 d6 7.O-O g6 followed by ...[Bg7] and castle. The white bishop is misplaced.}) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 {There are many decent setups for Black; I favoured this one as it seems that the most dangerous ideas in this line are connected with [Bc4]. So, 5...e6 blunts the bishop if it lands on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 6. Bc4 (6. Bb5 {is pretty dubious, as White is not really threatening to take on c6.} a6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. e5 {trying to infiltrate the knight, but it doesn't really matter as we will get a very strong knight on [d5], and we just take the knight if it lands on [d6].} Ne7 $1 {and ...[Nd5]. 8.O-O Nf6 Again, it's very hard to see White's compensation. We will finish our development with an extra pawn.}) 6... a6 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gb7b5,Gc8b7] I like this move which has a double purpose: it prevents all kinds of [Nb5] ideas and prepares the development of the [c8]-bishop on [b7].} 7. O-O b5 {We will study all possible retreats!} 8. Be2 {Honestly, it feels wrong to retreat to such a passive square being a pawn down.} Bb7 (8... Nge7 $6 {is now a mistake.} 9. a4 b4 10. Nd5 {This is the only asset of having the bishop on [e2] rather than on [d3]. The white queen is protecting the [d5]-square, thus making this particular sacrifice possible.}) 9. Bf4 Be7 10. Rc1 Rc8 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gc8c6] Overprotecting the [c6]-knight in order to get ...[d6] without falling for the [Nxb5] trick.} (10... d6 {is premature because White has a nice trick.} 11. Nxb5 axb5 12. Bxb5 {and the pin is a huge problem for Black.}) 11. a4 (11. a3 {is an attempt to fix Black queenside, but this is too slow.} d6 12. b4 Nf6 {Black is better. Castle is next on the agenda.}) 11... b4 12. Nd5 {This is always in the air, and right now is probably the best time for White.} exd5 13. exd5 Na5 14. d6 Bf6 15. Rc7 $1 {White's point. The rook is very active and annoying but not threatening much at the moment.} Nh6 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 16. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gd3b1,Gd1d3]} O-O 17. Bb1 {[%cal Gd1d3] Creating a battery on the [b1]-[h7] diagonal and a mating threat on [h7].} Re8 18. Qc2 g6 {Giving back the piece is the most sensible option.} 19. Bxh6 b3 {[%cal Gf6b2] Fixing the weakness on [b2] while White's attack is over.} 20. Qc1 Bxf3 21. gxf3 Nc6 {[%csl Rb2,Gf2,Gf3,Gh2][%cal Gc8c7,Gc6d4] The position is balanced, but Black has clear targets. Meanwhile, this seems more difficult for White to navigate with their open king.} *

