1. e4 c5 2. d4 {Introducing the Morra gambit. We have two options: taking the pawn or transposing to the line I am recommending against the Alapin.} cxd4 3. c3 (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nxd4 {transposes into our repertoire after} Nf6 {. If 4.c3 , again we have the option to transpose into our Alapin or just grab the pawn. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 transposes into Morra territory.}) 3... dxc3 (3... Nf6 4. e5 {the only decent move which will transpose into our Alapin lines. 4.Bd3 is simply a free pawn for Black. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 d6 7.O-O g6 followed by ...[Bg7] and castle. The white bishop is misplaced.}) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 {There are many decent setups for Black; I favoured this one as it seems that the most dangerous ideas in this line are connected with [Bc4]. So, 5...e6 blunts the bishop if it lands on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 6. Bc4 (6. Bb5 {is pretty dubious, as White is not really threatening to take on c6.} a6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. e5 {trying to infiltrate the knight, but it doesn't really matter as we will get a very strong knight on [d5], and we just take the knight if it lands on [d6].} Ne7 $1 {and ...[Nd5]. 8.O-O Nf6 Again, it's very hard to see White's compensation. We will finish our development with an extra pawn.}) 6... a6 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gb7b5,Gc8b7] I like this move which has a double purpose: it prevents all kinds of [Nb5] ideas and prepares the development of the [c8]-bishop on [b7].} 7. O-O b5 {We will study all possible retreats!} 8. Bb3 {The most popular, but I would say the two other options are more dangerous and objectively better.} Na5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga5b3] Chasing once again the light-squared bishop and clearing the [a8]-[h1] diagonal for ours.} 9. Re1 {A natural centralisation of the rook. It fails to impress, though.} Nxb3 10. Qxb3 Bb7 {As usual in such gambits, immediate and concrete actions are needed in order to get some play.} 11. Bg5 Be7 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 {White's last couple of moves look a bit dumb exchanging dark-squared bishops and helping Black develop, but the point is to get back the pawn as Black can no longer meet [a4] with ...[b4].} 13. a4 {[%cal Gb3b7,Ga4b5]} Rb8 14. axb5 axb5 15. Nxb5 ({The pawn should be taken now; otherwise, Black will just defend it. E.g.:} 15. Red1 Bc6 $1) 15... O-O {[%cal Gb7c6,Gf7f5,Gb8b3] White got the pawn back, but Black now has a great initiative with the pin on the b-file and the ...[f5] idea opening up the long diagonal for the light-squared bishop.} *

