1. e4 c5 2. d4 {Introducing the Morra gambit. We have two options: taking the pawn or transposing to the line I am recommending against the Alapin.} cxd4 3. c3 (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nxd4 {transposes into our repertoire after} Nf6 {. If 4.c3 , again we have the option to transpose into our Alapin or just grab the pawn. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 transposes into Morra territory.}) 3... dxc3 (3... Nf6 4. e5 {the only decent move which will transpose into our Alapin lines. 4.Bd3 is simply a free pawn for Black. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 d6 7.O-O g6 followed by ...[Bg7] and castle. The white bishop is misplaced.}) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 {There are many decent setups for Black; I favoured this one as it seems that the most dangerous ideas in this line are connected with [Bc4]. So, 5...e6 blunts the bishop if it lands on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 6. Bc4 (6. Bb5 {is pretty dubious, as White is not really threatening to take on c6.} a6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. e5 {trying to infiltrate the knight, but it doesn't really matter as we will get a very strong knight on [d5], and we just take the knight if it lands on [d6].} Ne7 $1 {and ...[Nd5]. 8.O-O Nf6 Again, it's very hard to see White's compensation. We will finish our development with an extra pawn.}) 6... a6 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gb7b5,Gc8b7] I like this move which has a double purpose: it prevents all kinds of [Nb5] ideas and prepares the development of the [c8]-bishop on [b7].} 7. O-O b5 {We will study all possible retreats!} 8. Bb3 {The most popular, but I would say the two other options are more dangerous and objectively better.} Na5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga5b3] Chasing once again the light-squared bishop and clearing the [a8]-[h1] diagonal for ours.} 9. Re1 {A natural centralisation of the rook. It fails to impress, though.} Nxb3 10. Qxb3 Bb7 {As usual in such gambits, immediate and concrete actions are needed in order to get some play.} 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc1f4] Now we see the point of [Re1]: the knight can jump on [d5], but this is still insufficient to create serious counterplay for White.} Bd6 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7]} 13. Nxb4 Qb6 {[%cal Gb6b3]} 14. Bd2 a5 15. Qc3 {[%cal Gc3g7] Counterattacking on [g7] is the only way not to lose a piece.} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Ga5b4]} 16. Nd3 O-O {[%csl Gb6,Gb7,Gd6][%cal Gf6e4] And a small tactical idea makes castling possible. Black has two bishops and active pieces in an open position.} 17. e5 Nd5 {[%cal Gd6e7,Gd5c3] The point. Black is much better.} *

