1. e4 c5 2. d4 {Introducing the Morra gambit. We have two options: taking the pawn or transposing to the line I am recommending against the Alapin.} cxd4 3. c3 (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nxd4 {transposes into our repertoire after} Nf6 {. If 4.c3 , again we have the option to transpose into our Alapin or just grab the pawn. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 transposes into Morra territory.}) 3... dxc3 (3... Nf6 4. e5 {the only decent move which will transpose into our Alapin lines. 4.Bd3 is simply a free pawn for Black. 4...dxc3 5.Nxc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 d6 7.O-O g6 followed by ...[Bg7] and castle. The white bishop is misplaced.}) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 {There are many decent setups for Black; I favoured this one as it seems that the most dangerous ideas in this line are connected with [Bc4]. So, 5...e6 blunts the bishop if it lands on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 6. Bc4 (6. Bb5 {is pretty dubious, as White is not really threatening to take on c6.} a6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. e5 {trying to infiltrate the knight, but it doesn't really matter as we will get a very strong knight on [d5], and we just take the knight if it lands on [d6].} Ne7 $1 {and ...[Nd5]. 8.O-O Nf6 Again, it's very hard to see White's compensation. We will finish our development with an extra pawn.}) 6... a6 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gb7b5,Gc8b7] I like this move which has a double purpose: it prevents all kinds of [Nb5] ideas and prepares the development of the [c8]-bishop on [b7].} 7. O-O b5 {We will study all possible retreats!} 8. Bb3 {The most popular, but I would say the two other options are more dangerous and objectively better.} Na5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga5b3] Chasing once again the light-squared bishop and clearing the [a8]-[h1] diagonal for ours.} 9. Bc2 {Saving the bishop but losing a lot of time.} Bb7 10. Qe2 Rc8 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gb5b4] Another downside of [Bc2] is that the bishop is potentially hanging on [c2] now.} 11. Rd1 Bc5 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gc5f2] It is kind of nice to be able to develop on such an active square.} 12. e5 {[%cal Gc2e4,Gc3e4,Gc1g5]} (12. Bg5 Be7 $1 {We are losing a tempo but actually winning time as now White doesn't have any good scenario. Exchanging or retreating are not satisfactory.} 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 {and castle, or 13.Bf4 Nf6 and Black finished his development, will castle on the next move, and our extra pawn is very healthy.}) 12... f5 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gf5e4] A very nice move which kills White's main idea of getting a piece on [e4]. Also limits a lot the bishop on [c2]. Last but not least, taking en passant would just develop Black.} 13. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4e6] The ...[f5] push also created a new weakness on [e6]. White has to do something very concrete if they want to have hope of getting serious counterplay for the missing pawn.} Bxd4 14. Rxd4 Nc6 15. Rd6 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gd6d8]} Qh4 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gc6d4] A key move. The black queen leaves the d-file and the pin to reach an attractive square on [h4]. And it is almost impossible to harass the queen, actually. It's not an easy position for White.} ({Instead, after} 15... Nge7 $2 16. Bb3 {, the pin on the d-file is very annoying.}) 16. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4] A normal developing move controlling the [d4]-square, but it would lose another pawn.} Nxe5 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8] We'll quickly complete development with ...[Ne7] and ...[O-O].} *

