1. e4 c5 2. Qh5 $2 {Obviously, It is way too early for such actions with the queen. It can be played by a beginner, or also as a provocation from an experienced player.} e6 (2... Nf6 $5 {is also a very decent option.} 3. Qxc5 Nxe4 4. Qe3 d5 {already looks excellent for Black. We are occupying the centre and ready to develop.} 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Nc6 {intending ...[e5].} 7. f4 g6 {and Black has a very comfortable game. ...[Bg7] supporting ...[d4] is next.}) 3. Nf3 ({Neglecting development completely with} 3. f4 {is simply too much!} Nc6 {when} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {is an example of how natural developing moves may lose a pawn when you play such nonsense as [Qh5]+f4. After 4.d3 d5 5.c3 Nf6 , Black has only played natural moves and is already seizing the initiative. The queen must retreat, and ...[dxe4] and ...[e5] are strong ideas.}) 3... g6 {[%csl Rh5] A logical novelty asking the white queen what her plan is.} 4. Qh4 ({After} 4. Qe5 Nf6 {, Black will again win a tempo on the queen on the next move.}) (4. Qg5 Qxg5 5. Nxg5 Nc6 6. f4 d5 7. d3 Bg7 {is very similar to 4.Qh4, and yet again, the endgame is slightly better for Black. ...[Nge7] comes next to complete development.}) 4... Qxh4 5. Nxh4 {Black is getting a very comfortable endgame as White lost tempi moving around with their queen.} Nc6 6. d3 Bg7 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5]} ({Black is already slightly better and keeping the edge will be done by simple and natural means.} 6... Nd4 {would be too hasty due to} 7. Na3 {followed by [c3].}) *

