1. e4 c5 2. c4 {[%csl Rd4] A counterintuitive move, frankly, as it creates a hole on [d4]. Generally, it means that White is heading for a manoeuvring game, but that fails to pose Black any serious questions in the opening phase.} Nc6 (2... Nc6 {Now,} 3. Nf3 {is just transposing here.}) 3. Nc3 g6 {We are just playing the same setup as against the closed Sicilian. Making sure that White never gets to play [d4] and have a favourable Maroczy bind.} 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Already taking aggressive actions on the queenside asking White if they want to allow the expansion with ...[b5].} 6. a4 d6 7. Nge2 ({The natural setup for White.} 7. d3 {avoids our ...[Bg4] idea pinning the knight.} Nd4 $5 {and if} 8. h3 e6 {, White has lost a couple of tempi by preventing ...[Bg4] but now Black has time to gain control over the [d4]-square by playing ...[Ne7]-...[Nc6]. Alternatively, 8.Nge2 Bg4 is a very annoying pin.}) 7... Bg4 $5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gg4e2] This is a very rare move but makes a lot of sense to me as we just want to exchange one of the white knights to reinforce our control on the [d4]-square.} 8. O-O Bxe2 9. Nxe2 (9. Qxe2 $6 {White will lose a tempo due to ...[Nd4]. After} e6 10. d3 Nd4 11. Qd1 Ne7 {, Black has a very good game and a very clear plan with ...[Nc6] and ...[Rb8].}) 9... e6 10. d3 Nge7 11. Be3 {[%cal Gd3d4] White has to try to play [d4]. What else, really?} O-O 12. d4 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc6d4] Now we see the point of ...[Bg4xe2]. We do have an extra piece to control and occupy the weakened by 2.c4! [d4]-square.} 16. Qe3 e5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc6d4] Black has a comfortable game.} *

