1. e4 c5 2. c4 {[%csl Rd4] A counterintuitive move, frankly, as it creates a hole on [d4]. Generally, it means that White is heading for a manoeuvring game, but that fails to pose Black any serious questions in the opening phase.} Nc6 (2... Nc6 {Now,} 3. Nf3 {is just transposing here.}) 3. Nc3 g6 {We are just playing the same setup as against the closed Sicilian. Making sure that White never gets to play [d4] and have a favourable Maroczy bind.} 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Already taking aggressive actions on the queenside asking White if they want to allow the expansion with ...[b5].} 6. a4 d6 7. Nge2 ({The natural setup for White.} 7. d3 {avoids our ...[Bg4] idea pinning the knight.} Nd4 $5 {and if} 8. h3 e6 {, White has lost a couple of tempi by preventing ...[Bg4] but now Black has time to gain control over the [d4]-square by playing ...[Ne7]-...[Nc6]. Alternatively, 8.Nge2 Bg4 is a very annoying pin.}) 7... Bg4 $5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gg4e2] This is a very rare move but makes a lot of sense to me as we just want to exchange one of the white knights to reinforce our control on the [d4]-square.} 8. f3 {Not a move White likes to play, but that's probably the best one available.} Bd7 9. O-O e6 10. d3 Nge7 11. f4 O-O 12. Be3 {[%cal Gd3d4]} Nd4 {Of course, we should always prevent the [d4] push, which would gain too much space for White.} 13. Bf2 Nec6 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gb7b5,Gf7f5] All kind of natural ideas are available for Black while White will be busy trying to prevent them.} *

