1. e4 c5 2. c4 {[%csl Rd4] A counterintuitive move, frankly, as it creates a hole on [d4]. Generally, it means that White is heading for a manoeuvring game, but that fails to pose Black any serious questions in the opening phase.} Nc6 (2... Nc6 {Now,} 3. Nf3 {is just transposing here.}) 3. f4 {Trying to get as much space as possible with pawns but neglecting development. That should be punished by immediate action in the centre !} e6 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 4. Nf3 ({Letting Black achieve what they want without a fight.} 4. Nc3 Nge7 {Making sure the ...[d5] push will be available on the next move.} 5. Nf3 d5 6. d3 g6 {and Black gets a harmonious set-up and the better chances. ...[Bg7] and ...[b6] to develop the other bishop via [b7] or [a6] is our follow-up.}) 4... d5 5. exd5 exd5 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Bb5 Nh6 $5 {[%cal Gh6f5,Gf5d4] Not a very natural way to play, but making sure we will control the [d4]-square one more time.} 8. O-O Be7 9. Nc3 (9. Re1 {is met by} Qd6 {protecting [c6] and preparing to castle. Black is better due to the control of the [d4]-square and White's poor pawn structure.}) 9... Qd6 10. d4 O-O $1 {Ignoring White's push and putting the black king in a safe place is what we need to do before the centre gets opened!} 11. d5 Nd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Qxd4 Bf6 {[%csl Rf4,Rg1][%cal Gg1a7] Black has more than enough compensation due to the vulnerability of the white king on the diagonal [g1]-[a7].} 14. Qf2 Ng4 {[%cal Gd6c5]} 15. Qe2 Bf5 {[%cal Gf6d4,Ga7a6] Black is having all the fun!} 16. h3 Bd4+ 17. Kh1 a6 18. Ba4 ({That knight on g4 is obviously taboo:} 18. hxg4 Qh6#) 18... Rac8 {[%cal Gg4f6,Gb7b5,Gf8e8] Easier to play and considerably better for Black.} *

