1. e4 c5 2. c4 {[%csl Rd4] A counterintuitive move, frankly, as it creates a hole on [d4]. Generally, it means that White is heading for a manoeuvring game, but that fails to pose Black any serious questions in the opening phase.} Nc6 (2... Nc6 {Now,} 3. Nf3 {is just transposing here.}) 3. f4 {Trying to get as much space as possible with pawns but neglecting development. That should be punished by immediate action in the centre !} e6 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 4. Nf3 ({Letting Black achieve what they want without a fight.} 4. Nc3 Nge7 {Making sure the ...[d5] push will be available on the next move.} 5. Nf3 d5 6. d3 g6 {and Black gets a harmonious set-up and the better chances. ...[Bg7] and ...[b6] to develop the other bishop via [b7] or [a6] is our follow-up.}) 4... d5 5. exd5 exd5 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Nc3 {[%csl Rd4] Gaining a tempo on the queen, but it is all under control. In that centre liquidation, we gained the [d4]-square control forever.} Qe6+ 8. Be2 Nf6 9. O-O Bd6 10. d4 ({This looks very logical as Black didn't castle yet, but it fails tactically. Instead,} 10. Kh1 O-O {is very comfortable for Black.}) 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 {[%cal Gc5g1]} 12. Ncb5 O-O $1 {[%csl Rd4,Re2] White is already busted as too many pieces are hanging.} *

