1. e4 c5 2. c4 {[%csl Rd4] A counterintuitive move, frankly, as it creates a hole on [d4]. Generally, it means that White is heading for a manoeuvring game, but that fails to pose Black any serious questions in the opening phase.} Nc6 (2... Nc6 {Now,} 3. Nf3 {is just transposing here.}) 3. Ne2 Nf6 (3... e6 4. d4 $1 {is a playable line for Black but doesn't fit our repertoire.}) 4. Nbc3 ({After} 4. d4 $2 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nxe4 {, White gets no compensation whatsoever for the pawn deficit.}) 4... e6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 5. d4 d5 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 {would again enter a playable line of the Sicilian but not fitting our repertoire.}) 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg5 ({Trying to keep the tension in the centre.} 7. e5 {is way too ambitious.} Ng4 $1 {and White's centre will collapse.}) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Be7 $1 {A nice solution. Black has nothing to worry about.} 9. e5 Ne4 $1 (9... Nxe5 $6 {would be dangerous.} 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Qe2 {and Black is suddenly in trouble. Or 10...Kf8 11.O-O with obvious compensation due to the uncastled king.}) 10. Nxc6 (10. Bxe7 Qxe7 $1 {The [e5]-pawn is in a lot of trouble now.} 11. Nxe4 Qxe5 {Nice little trick winning a pawn. 11.Nxd5 Qxe5 is no less than winning for Black. The discovered check ...[Nc3] adds to the pile of threats.White can try 11.Nxc6 bxc6 12.Qd4 Nc5 followed by ...[Ne6], ...[O-O] and ...[f6].}) 10... bxc6 11. Nxe4 (11. Bxe7 Qxe7 {transposes to 10.Bxe7.}) 11... Bxg5 12. Nd6+ Kf8 {[%csl Gc6,Gc8,Gd5,Gg5] Looks a bit dangerous as the knight is very well placed on [d6] and the Black king is on [f8], but the pawn centre and the bishop pair give Black a good game.} 13. Qa4 Bd7 14. Ba6 Qb6 15. O-O h5 $1 {[%cal Gh8h6] Typical way of getting the rook into the game by 2022 standards!} *

