1. e4 c5 2. c4 {[%csl Rd4] A counterintuitive move, frankly, as it creates a hole on [d4]. Generally, it means that White is heading for a manoeuvring game, but that fails to pose Black any serious questions in the opening phase.} Nc6 (2... Nc6 {Now,} 3. Nf3 {is just transposing here.}) 3. Ne2 Nf6 (3... e6 4. d4 $1 {is a playable line for Black but doesn't fit our repertoire.}) 4. Nbc3 ({After} 4. d4 $2 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nxe4 {, White gets no compensation whatsoever for the pawn deficit.}) 4... e6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 5. d4 d5 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 {would again enter a playable line of the Sicilian but not fitting our repertoire.}) 6. exd5 exd5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. dxc5 {Massive liquidation leading to a better endgame for Black!} Ndb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c2]} 9. Qxd8+ Nxd8 10. Nd4 Ndc6 $1 {[%cal Gb4c2]} (10... Ndc6 {The point is to meet} 11. Bb5 Bxc5 12. a3 {with} O-O $1 {No time to lose!} 13. Bxc6 bxc6 {thanks to the hanging knight on [d4].}) 11. Ndb5 ({After} 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {, White is forced to play} 12. Kd1 {in order to prevent the fork on [c2].} Bxc5 {Black's activity is obvious.}) 11... Nc2+ 12. Kd1 Bf5 $1 {Both rooks will be taken, but we want the [d7]-square available for our king in order to take the knight on [a8] as soon as possible!} 13. Nc7+ Kd7 14. Nxa8 Nxa1 15. Bf4 {[%cal Ga8c7]} g5 $1 16. Bg3 (16. Bxg5 {would be a bit naive. After} Bxc5 {, the knight is trapped.}) 16... h5 17. Nc7 h4 18. Bd6 Bxd6 19. cxd6 Nc2 {[%csl Rf1,Rh1][%cal Gd7d6] We will get back the [d6]-pawn and, therefore, get the better chances as we are ahead in development.} *

