1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {A pretty harmless sideline. Knights should be developed before bishops!} e6 $1 {[%cal Gc4f7,Gd7d5] This makes a lot of sense to me as we are preparing ...[d5] and covering the [f7]-square.} 3. Nc3 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 4. a4 {That's a nice insertion for Black as White won’t get any unpleasant check on [b5] when Black goes [d5].} Nf6 {[%cal Gd7d5] A good move with a small trap. What’s not to like? clearly provoking to go ahead with the e-pawn...} 5. e5 (5. d3 d5 6. Ba2 dxe4 {is the simplest way to get a very good endgame.} 7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8. dxe4 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 b6 {The [Ba2]'s prospects are not great... ...[Nd7] and ...[Bb7] is a simple follow-up.}) (5. Nf3 d5 6. exd5 exd5 7. Ba2 Nc6 8. O-O Be7 {Black's centre guarantees us an excellent game.}) 5... d5 $1 {A typical trick everyone should know.} 6. exf6 (6. Ba2 Nfd7 7. f4 Nc6 {and ...[f6] is coming, e.g.:} 8. Nf3 f6 $1 9. exf6 Nxf6 {The best version of a French Defence you will ever get! ...[Bd6] and ...[O-O] are coming next.}) 6... dxc4 7. fxg7 Bxg7 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge6e5] The position we were hoping for while provoking White with 4...Nf6.} 8. Qg4 O-O 9. Qxc4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Ge6e5,Gc8e6] With a huge initiative for Black. Not really sure White can survive this.} *

