1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {A pretty harmless sideline. Knights should be developed before bishops!} e6 $1 {[%cal Gc4f7,Gd7d5] This makes a lot of sense to me as we are preparing ...[d5] and covering the [f7]-square.} 3. Qe2 {Preventing ...[d5].} Be7 {[%cal Gd7d5] Renewing the threat!} 4. Nf3 d5 $5 (4... a6 {is also very decent.} 5. d3 d5 6. Bb3 Nf6 7. c4 $5 {A funny-looking move asking Black to clarify their intentions in the centre.} Nc6 $1 {(, and we don't! This is very playable for both sides, but I got attracted by another and more aggressive idea.)}) 5. Bb5+ Kf8 $1 {[%csl Rb5] Here we go! The main point of that is we want to trap the light-squared bishop.} 6. c3 {[%cal Gb5a4,Ga4c2]} ({Creating an escape route for the bishop.} 6. exd5 a6 $1 7. Bd3 exd5 {is a disaster for White. We have easy development with ...[Nc6] and ...[Bg4]. After 7.d6 Qxd6 8.Bd3 Nf6 , despite the king of [f8], Black has better chances due to the lack of harmony of White's army.}) 6... dxe4 7. Qxe4 a6 8. Ba4 Nf6 9. Qe2 b5 10. Bc2 Bb7 {White lost a lot of tempi, but we have the king of [f8]. Thanks to AI, we have learned how to deal with our inactive rook on [h8]...} 11. O-O h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gh8h5] The rook will get into play, and Black will have a very promising position.} 12. d4 cxd4 13. Nxd4 (13. cxd4 Nc6 14. Rd1 h4 {Black has a very good game and active play with ...[Nb4], ...[h3] and ...[Rh5] ideas. White has an isolated pawn on [d4].}) 13... h4 14. h3 Nc6 15. Nxc6 Qd5 $1 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gd5c6,Gh8h5] A nice little intermezzo thanks to the mate on [g2] which gives Black excellent play.} *

