1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {A pretty harmless sideline. Knights should be developed before bishops!} e6 $1 {[%cal Gc4f7,Gd7d5] This makes a lot of sense to me as we are preparing ...[d5] and covering the [f7]-square.} 3. Nf3 Nf6 $5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd7d5] Attacking the pawn on [e4] and preparing ...[d5]. Obviously, in such cases, White's [e5] push should be checked carefully.} 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. d4 Nxe4 $1 {A typical trick which gives a good game to Black.} 6. Nxe4 d5 7. Bxd5 (7. Bd3 c4 $1 {is stylish and good for Black.} 8. Bxc4 dxe4 {and the [d4]-pawn is falling, or 8.Ng3 cxd3 9.Qxd3 Bd6 and Black has gained the two bishops; therefore, we have the best chances.}) 7... Qxd5 8. Nc3 (8. Nxc5 Nxd4 $1 {We will end up in an endgame where we have the bishop pair.} 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxc5 11. Be3 Bd7 {intending to castle and push ...[e5]. White will suffer.}) 8... Qc4 $1 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gc4f1] Preventing White’s castle.} 9. d5 exd5 10. Qxd5 (10. Nxd5 {is met by} Bd6 $1 11. Nf6+ gxf6 12. Qxd6 Be6 {and Black's initiative/activity is way too strong. White is busted. ...[Rd8] and ...[Rg8] are in the cards, and the white king is in trouble.}) 10... Qxd5 11. Nxd5 Bd6 {[%csl Gc8,Gd6][%cal Ge8g8] And again we got the bishops!} *

