1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {A pretty harmless sideline. Knights should be developed before bishops!} e6 $1 {[%cal Gc4f7,Gd7d5] This makes a lot of sense to me as we are preparing ...[d5] and covering the [f7]-square.} 3. Nf3 Nf6 $5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd7d5] Attacking the pawn on [e4] and preparing ...[d5]. Obviously, in such cases, White's [e5] push should be checked carefully.} 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. d4 Nxe4 $1 {A typical trick which gives a good game to Black.} 6. Nxe4 d5 7. dxc5 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ (8. Ng5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bxc5 10. Nxe4 Be7 {Black is definitely not worse.}) 8... Nxd8 9. Nd2 {Very double-edged position due to the asymmetrical pawn structure.} f5 {We should keep our pawn majority on the kingside.} 10. f3 (10. Nb3 {is the most natural, I guess.} e5 {Black's pawns on the kingside are strong, while the [c5]-pawn is a weakness.}) 10... e3 $1 11. Bb5+ ({The only move! White is busted after} 11. Nb3 f4 $1 {as they cannot complete development.}) 11... Kf7 12. Nc4 a6 13. Ba4 (13. Nb6 {is tempting but the knight will get caught on [a8].} Bxc5 14. Nxa8 axb5 15. Nc7 b4 {Black is simply winning!}) 13... Bxc5 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 14. Bxe3 Bxe3 15. Nxe3 b5 16. Bb3 Kf6 {[%cal Gd8f7,Gc8b7,Gh8d8] Black has a very simple plan and is fine. I don't think White is worse with precise play, though.} *

