1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {A pretty harmless sideline. Knights should be developed before bishops!} e6 $1 {[%cal Gc4f7,Gd7d5] This makes a lot of sense to me as we are preparing ...[d5] and covering the [f7]-square.} 3. Nf3 Nf6 $5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd7d5] Attacking the pawn on [e4] and preparing ...[d5]. Obviously, in such cases, White's [e5] push should be checked carefully.} 4. e5 (4. d3 {is a very modest move which can't pose Black any serious questions.} d5 5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {and if} 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. O-O Be7 {, Black has a good game.}) {7.e5 Ng8! (looks like a French defence Advance Variation except that the light-squared bishops are exchanged, which is obviously a terrific deal for Black.) 8.O-O Nc6 9.c3 Nge7 followed by ...[Nf5] or ...[Ng6] and ...[Be7].} 4... d5 $1 {We have already seen this trick, and it works again!} 5. exf6 dxc4 6. fxg7 Bxg7 7. Na3 {Involves a pawn sac, but the 2 bishops, our nice control on the centre and the upcoming activity guarantee more than enough compensation.} Nc6 8. Nxc4 b5 $1 9. Ne3 f5 {Restricting even more white knights who are poorly placed while all Black pieces and pawns will be active.} 10. d3 O-O 11. a4 b4 {[%csl Gc8,Gf5,Gg7][%cal Ge6e5]} 12. O-O e5 13. Nc4 {It is, of course, possible to continue in a slow manner and claim long-term compensation, but it seems that the direct approach is also working.} e4 $1 14. dxe4 fxe4 15. Ng5 Qxd1 16. Rxd1 Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2]} 17. Nxe4 Nxc2 18. Rb1 Be6 {[%csl Ge6,Gg7][%cal Gf8d8] Who remembers Black is a pawn down? We are actually much better.} *

