1. e4 c5 2. d3 {Apparently an unambitious move, but it is generally connected with the idea to play [f4] and get some early initiative on the kingside.} Nc6 3. g3 {A hybrid line between 2.g3 and 2.d3.} d5 {The most natural way is to react in the centre as White still has to develop a piece!} 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nf3 Qe6+ $5 (5... Nd4 {transposes to this line covered via 2.g3 which leads to a draw.}) 6. Be3 (6. Qe2 Qxe2+ 7. Bxe2 e5 {is a nice endgame for Black, thanks to the space advantage. We control the [d4]-square.}) 6... Nh6 {[%cal Gh6f5]} 7. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3c5]} b6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gh6f5,Gc8b7]} 8. d4 {Otherwise, ...[Nf5] is coming, and it will be impossible to break in the centre.} cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Qxe2+ 11. Bxe2 f6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 12. Bf3 Rb8 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gh6f5,Ge8f7] The endgame is pretty equal.} *

