1. e4 c5 2. d3 {Apparently an unambitious move, but it is generally connected with the idea to play [f4] and get some early initiative on the kingside.} Nc6 3. f4 d5 4. Nf3 (4. e5 {In such positions, it is never recommended to go [e5] as now Black has a superb version of the Advance French!} h5 $5 {Making sure there will be no [g4] when we play ...[Bf5].} 5. Be2 Bf5 6. Bxh5 e6 7. Be2 Qc7 {Black has superb initiative for the pawn. They will castle long and attack White's centre. Meanwhile, the white king will never be safe on the kingside due to the open h-file.}) 4... dxe4 $1 {Contrary to the 4.Be2 line, here I am recommending entering the endgame as the king will be misplaced on [d1], allowing us to win some tempi.} (4... e6 5. c3 Bd6 6. e5 Bc7 7. d4 Nh6 {This setup is less effective vs 4. Nf3, as the light-squared bishop can develop to its natural square [d3] at once. It is playable for Black, though.}) 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gf6g4,Gg4f2]} 7. Nbd2 e5 {[%csl Rd1] Using the fact that the king is on [d1].} 8. fxe5 Ng4 {[%cal Gg4f2,Gg4e3]} 9. Ke2 {[%csl Ge3,Gf2]} Be6 {[%csl Gc4,Re2,Re4,Re5] The white king is not in an ideal place, and the [e4]-pawn will be isolated when we get back the [e5]-pawn.} 10. b3 Ngxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bb2 Nc6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge8c8,Gf7f6,Gc6d4]} 13. Kf2 O-O-O 14. Rd1 h5 $5 {[%cal Gh8h6,Gh5h4] Both camps played natural moves, and now comes the typical manoeuvre inspired by the AI.} 15. Bc4 Rh6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gh6e6] Black is still a tiny better due to the potential weakness of the [e4]-pawn.} *

