1. e4 c5 2. d3 {Apparently an unambitious move, but it is generally connected with the idea to play [f4] and get some early initiative on the kingside.} Nc6 3. f4 d5 4. Nf3 (4. e5 {In such positions, it is never recommended to go [e5] as now Black has a superb version of the Advance French!} h5 $5 {Making sure there will be no [g4] when we play ...[Bf5].} 5. Be2 Bf5 6. Bxh5 e6 7. Be2 Qc7 {Black has superb initiative for the pawn. They will castle long and attack White's centre. Meanwhile, the white king will never be safe on the kingside due to the open h-file.}) 4... dxe4 $1 {Contrary to the 4.Be2 line, here I am recommending entering the endgame as the king will be misplaced on [d1], allowing us to win some tempi.} (4... e6 5. c3 Bd6 6. e5 Bc7 7. d4 Nh6 {This setup is less effective vs 4. Nf3, as the light-squared bishop can develop to its natural square [d3] at once. It is playable for Black, though.}) 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gf6g4,Gg4f2]} 7. Nbd2 e5 {[%csl Rd1] Using the fact that the king is on [d1].} 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. fxe5 Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e3,Gg4f2]} 10. Ke1 {[%cal Ge1f2,Gd2f3]} Nxe5 11. Nc4 Ng6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf8e7,Gb7b6,Gc8b7] The position is quite dull, but I believe it is more comfortable for Black as the [e4]-pawn is always a potential target.} (11... Nxc4 {would make White's task easier.} 12. Bxc4 Bd6 13. Bd5 {with a dominant bishop.}) *

