1. e4 c5 2. d3 {Apparently an unambitious move, but it is generally connected with the idea to play [f4] and get some early initiative on the kingside.} Nc6 3. f4 d5 4. Nf3 (4. e5 {In such positions, it is never recommended to go [e5] as now Black has a superb version of the Advance French!} h5 $5 {Making sure there will be no [g4] when we play ...[Bf5].} 5. Be2 Bf5 6. Bxh5 e6 7. Be2 Qc7 {Black has superb initiative for the pawn. They will castle long and attack White's centre. Meanwhile, the white king will never be safe on the kingside due to the open h-file.}) 4... dxe4 $1 {Contrary to the 4.Be2 line, here I am recommending entering the endgame as the king will be misplaced on [d1], allowing us to win some tempi.} (4... e6 5. c3 Bd6 6. e5 Bc7 7. d4 Nh6 {This setup is less effective vs 4. Nf3, as the light-squared bishop can develop to its natural square [d3] at once. It is playable for Black, though.}) 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gf6g4,Gg4f2]} 7. e5 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5]} ({A very committal decision which gives Black a lot of squares to. After} 7. Bd3 c4 8. Bxc4 Nxe4 9. Re1 Bf5 {, it is pretty obvious that Black has seized the initiative.} 10. Nbd2 Nd6 11. Bb3 e6 {It won't be easy for White to finish their development while it comes naturally for Black.}) 7... Nd5 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gc8g4,Gc8f5]} 8. Bc4 (8. Nc3 Nxc3+ 9. bxc3 Bf5 {followed by ...[O-O-O].}) 8... Be6 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gd5f4] A good developing move threatening to win a pawn and castling long.} 9. f5 {This simply doesn’t work.} Bxf5 10. Bxd5 O-O-O {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge7e6,Rd8d1] And we are getting back the piece immediately. Black is even already winning!} *

