1. e4 c5 2. d3 {Apparently an unambitious move, but it is generally connected with the idea to play [f4] and get some early initiative on the kingside.} Nc6 3. f4 d5 4. Be2 ({Abandoning the fight for the centre with} 4. exd5 $6 {is simply very poor.} Qxd5 5. Nf3 g6 6. Nc3 Qe6+ 7. Be2 Bg7 {Black has a very clear plan and is slightly better.}) 4... e6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7]} ({Now it is less tempting to go for the endgame with} 4... dxe4 {as the queen can be captured with the bishop and therefore White preserved their right to castle after} 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ 6. Bxd1 $1 {.}) 5. Nf3 Bd6 {[%cal Gg8e7] I very much like this setup inviting White to play [e5] with tempo. The point is to target the White's centre as soon as possible.} 6. O-O Nge7 7. c3 {White can keep waiting, but it is way less challenging.} O-O 8. Be3 (8. e5 Bc7 {transposes here.}) 8... f6 $1 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gd5d4]} 9. Nbd2 (9. g3 b6 10. Nbd2 Bb7 {Black is slowly but surely getting ready for actions in the centre with ...[e5], while it is unclear what White has achieved.}) 9... d4 $1 {[%cal Gd6f4]} 10. cxd4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxf4 $1 {A nice trick executed in the right move order.} 12. Rxf4 Nxd4 {[%csl Rd3,Gd4][%cal Ge6e5,Gc8e6,Ge7c6] We got the magnificent square for our knight on [d4], and it is pretty clear that [d3] will remain a permanent weakness.} *

