1. e4 c5 2. d3 {Apparently an unambitious move, but it is generally connected with the idea to play [f4] and get some early initiative on the kingside.} Nc6 3. f4 d5 4. Be2 ({Abandoning the fight for the centre with} 4. exd5 $6 {is simply very poor.} Qxd5 5. Nf3 g6 6. Nc3 Qe6+ 7. Be2 Bg7 {Black has a very clear plan and is slightly better.}) 4... e6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7]} ({Now it is less tempting to go for the endgame with} 4... dxe4 {as the queen can be captured with the bishop and therefore White preserved their right to castle after} 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ 6. Bxd1 $1 {.}) 5. Nf3 Bd6 {[%cal Gg8e7] I very much like this setup inviting White to play [e5] with tempo. The point is to target the White's centre as soon as possible.} 6. O-O Nge7 7. e5 {Obviously, very logical.} Bc7 8. c3 O-O {[%cal Gf7f6]} 9. d4 {That's the natural and ambitious way to play in order to reinforce White's centre, but the [d4]-pawn is easy to attack!} cxd4 10. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3h7]} (10. cxd4 Nf5 {and the [d4]-pawn is already lost, actually, thanks to the pin on the [a7]-[g1] diagonal.}) 10... f6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e5,Gf6g5] Preventing all kinds of nasty [Bxh7], [Ng5], [Qh5] businesses and attacking the strongest part of White's centre.} 11. cxd4 Bb6 {[%cal Gb6g1]} 12. exf6 Rxf6 13. Be3 Bd7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd7e8,Ge8g6,Gb6d4] Black will easily get rid of the famous 'bad French bishop' and don't have any problems as the [d4]-pawn is still under pressure.} *

