1. e4 c5 2. d3 {Apparently an unambitious move, but it is generally connected with the idea to play [f4] and get some early initiative on the kingside.} Nc6 3. f4 d5 4. Be2 ({Abandoning the fight for the centre with} 4. exd5 $6 {is simply very poor.} Qxd5 5. Nf3 g6 6. Nc3 Qe6+ 7. Be2 Bg7 {Black has a very clear plan and is slightly better.}) 4... e6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7]} ({Now it is less tempting to go for the endgame with} 4... dxe4 {as the queen can be captured with the bishop and therefore White preserved their right to castle after} 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ 6. Bxd1 $1 {.}) 5. Nf3 Bd6 {[%cal Gg8e7] I very much like this setup inviting White to play [e5] with tempo. The point is to target the White's centre as soon as possible.} 6. O-O Nge7 7. e5 {Obviously, very logical.} Bc7 8. c3 O-O {[%cal Gf7f6]} 9. Na3 f6 $1 10. d4 ({Keeping the centre intact is the only way to make sense as White. If} 10. exf6 Rxf6 {, the [f4]-pawn is hit, and we will open up our light-squared bishop with ...[e5].}) 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Bd7 {[%cal Gd7e8,Ge8g6,Gc7b6] As in the 9.d4 line, we do have this plan of activating the light-squared bishop, which means we don't have any problems.} 12. Nc2 {[%cal Gb2b4]} Be8 13. Bd3 {This makes a lot of sense, as White doesn't want to see a black bishop on [g6] unchallenged.} Bg6 $1 {We still go for it and exchange our 'bad bishop'.} 14. b4 {[%cal Gb4b5]} (14. exf6 Rxf6 {looks like an amazing French to me. The light-squared bishop is generally on [d7]. We have improved!}) 14... a6 15. a4 {[%cal Gb4b5] White is rightfully being stubborn.} Qe8 {[%cal Gg6d3,Ge8g6]} 16. b5 {This is not really working properly here.} axb5 17. axb5 Rxa1 18. Nxa1 Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4] And Black is getting a very nice square on [c4] for the knight.} *

