1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 {White is toying with move orders, keeping the option of going [g3], [Bg2] or [f4], but play could very well transpose into the Sveshnikov main line.} Nc6 3. Nbc3 Nf6 4. g3 (4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 {is pure transposition to our Sveshnikov.}) 4... d5 5. exd5 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4f3,Gc8g4]} 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Nb5 e5 $1 {A very important move which guarantees Black a long-lasting initiative.} 8. Qe2 (8. dxe6 {Taking en passant does not really help White.} Bxe6 {, and the knight is in trouble.} 9. Bg2 Bc4 $1 {(Black is at least! winning a piece.)}) (8. c4 a6 9. Na3 b5 10. d3 Bf5 {and White can't hold their position together:} 11. Bg2 Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxa3 {and [d3] drops, or 11.Be2 Bxa3 12.bxa3 bxc4 13.dxc4 O-O with ...[Ne4]-...[Nc3] ideas.}) 8... Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8] Offering another pawn.} 9. Bg2 O-O {[%cal Ga7a6]} 10. O-O a6 11. Na3 Re8 {[%cal Ge7a3,Gf6d5]} 12. c4 {[%csl Gd5] Keeping the pawn, but Black is getting the initiative.} e4 $1 13. d3 Bg4 14. Qc2 e3 {[%cal Ge7a3,Ge8e3] Our compensation is obvious and objectively very serious.} 15. fxe3 dxe3 16. Re1 e2 {[%cal Ge7c5,Gd8b6]} 17. d4 Rc8 {[%cal Gb7b5] Getting the last piece into play. We still need to be dynamic before White finishes development.} 18. Qb3 b5 $1 19. c5 (19. cxb5 Qa5 20. Be3 Bb4 {winning material.}) 19... Rxc5 $1 {Not a forced line, obviously, but I think it demonstrates well the potential of the black position.} 20. dxc5 Bxc5+ 21. Kh1 Ne4 {[%cal Ge4f2,Gd8f6] Black is a full rook down but completely winning.} *

