1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 {White is toying with move orders, keeping the option of going [g3], [Bg2] or [f4], but play could very well transpose into the Sveshnikov main line.} Nc6 3. Nbc3 Nf6 4. g3 (4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 {is pure transposition to our Sveshnikov.}) 4... d5 5. exd5 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4f3,Gc8g4]} 6. Bg2 Bg4 7. O-O h5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} ({A novelty with obvious aggressive intentions.} 7... Nxd5 {is the main move, but I think my main line put much more pressure on White.}) 8. h3 Nf3+ 9. Kh1 Qd7 (9... Qd7 {Now,} 10. hxg4 $4 {is obviously way too naive.} hxg4+ {with mate to follow.}) 10. d4 $5 {A very hidden and good defensive move.} Nxd4 ({Not} 10... cxd4 $2 11. Nxd4 {and suddenly, White is better!}) 11. f3 Bxh3 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Qxd4 {A weird position, but it is pretty clear that White won't get mated.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Time to develop.} 14. Re1 Bg7 15. Qb4 O-O $1 {This looks like a pawn sac, but not really.} 16. Rxe7 (16. Qxe7 $4 Rfe8 {is losing material.}) 16... Bxg2+ 17. Kxg2 Nxd5 $1 {Black is OK.} *

