1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 {White is toying with move orders, keeping the option of going [g3], [Bg2] or [f4], but play could very well transpose into the Sveshnikov main line.} Nc6 3. Nbc3 Nf6 4. g3 (4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 {is pure transposition to our Sveshnikov.}) 4... d5 5. exd5 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4f3,Gc8g4]} 6. Bg2 Bg4 7. O-O h5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} ({A novelty with obvious aggressive intentions.} 7... Nxd5 {is the main move, but I think my main line put much more pressure on White.}) 8. h3 Nf3+ 9. Kh1 Qd7 (9... Qd7 {Now,} 10. hxg4 $4 {is obviously way too naive.} hxg4+ {with mate to follow.}) 10. Ng1 Nxg1 11. hxg4 {It looks like Black got tricked, but the engine shows a beautiful resource.} Nh3 $3 (11... Nh3 12. Bxh3 hxg4 {is the main idea and would be winning for Black.}) 12. g5 $1 h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4g3,Gh8h1]} (12... Nxg5 $2 13. d4 {is winning for White.}) 13. g4 Nxg5 {[%cal Gh4h3]} 14. d3 h3 15. Be4 Ngxe4 16. dxe4 Qxg4 {[%csl Gh3] A very sharp and interesting endgame is arising. White has to be careful as the [h3]-pawn is a constant threat.} *

