1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 {White is toying with move orders, keeping the option of going [g3], [Bg2] or [f4], but play could very well transpose into the Sveshnikov main line.} Nc6 3. Nbc3 Nf6 4. g3 (4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 {is pure transposition to our Sveshnikov.}) 4... d5 5. exd5 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4f3,Gc8g4]} 6. Bg2 Bg4 7. O-O h5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} ({A novelty with obvious aggressive intentions.} 7... Nxd5 {is the main move, but I think my main line put much more pressure on White.}) 8. h3 Nf3+ 9. Kh1 Qd7 (9... Qd7 {Now,} 10. hxg4 $4 {is obviously way too naive.} hxg4+ {with mate to follow.}) 10. d3 Nd4 {[%cal Gg4h3] This gives Black excellent play as the [g4]-bishop is still taboo.} 11. hxg4 hxg4+ 12. Kg1 Nf3+ 13. Bxf3 gxf3 14. Nf4 Qg4 {[%cal Gg7g5] Game over as White will get mated on the h-file.} 15. d6 g5 16. Nfd5 Rh1+ $1 {[%cal Gg4h3,Gh3g2] A well-known mating pattern!} *

