1. e4 c5 2. Na3 {A weird developing move which is nevertheless seen at a GM level on a regular basis. White keeps flexibility in the centre, but the knight is misplaced on [a3]! Black won't have any problem if they know what they are doing.} Nc6 3. Nf3 ({Not really in the spirit of the line.} 3. f4 $6 {has also been played at times but way too random as it doesn't seem to connect well with 2.Na3.} d5 $1 {When in doubt, play in the centre!} 4. e5 Bf5 {is immediately very comfortable, with ...[e6] coming once the bishop is out, and after 4.exd5 Qxd5 5.Nf3 g6 , Black has a very sane position and a clear developing plan: ...[Nh6]-...[Nf5] controlling [d4].}) 3... Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Immediately attacking the central pawn. The natural way would have been [Nc3], but the knight is already on another square.} 4. e5 (4. d3 {is a modest way to play which immediately gives Black a comfortable game.} d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 {followed by a kingside fianchetto with control of [d4].}) 4... Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e5,Gc6e5]} 5. Qe2 (5. Nc4 {is quite natural, but after} d5 6. exd6 exd6 {, Black is occupying the centre while winning tempi on the [c4]-knight.}) 5... f6 {[%cal Gf6e5]} 6. Nc4 {White decides not to give up the centre immediately by defending it.} b5 $1 {Accepting the challenge, we want to punish White for their somewhat strange play.} 7. exf6 bxc4 8. f7+ {[%cal Gf3g5,Ge2g4]} Kxf7 9. Ng5+ Ke8 10. Qxg4 d5 {[%csl Gc4,Gc5,Gd5,Ge7] Having already moved the king, Black can no longer castle, but we have such a nice centre that it more than compensates.} 11. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3f7,Gg5f7]} Qd6 $1 {[%cal Gh7h6]} (11... Qd6 {Preventing} 12. Nf7 $4 {due to} Qe6+ {is the most obvious idea.}) 12. Qf7+ (12. d3 {is an attempt to get rid of at least one pawn of Black's amazing centre!} h6 $1 {when} 13. Nf7 Qe6+ {is the same cheapo winning a piece, and 13.Qf7+ Kd8 14.Nf3 Nb4 gives us immediate counterplay and the best chances in the upcoming sharp battle.}) 12... Kd8 13. Qf3 {[%cal Gg5f7] Offering a move repetition, but it's already late!} Nd4 $1 14. Nf7+ Kc7 15. Nxd6 ({Or} 15. Qg3 Qxg3 16. hxg3 Nxc2+ {winning a pawn and the game, basically. An important point is that Black has ...[Bf5].}) 15... Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 exd6 {[%csl Gc4,Gc5,Gd5,Gd6][%cal Gc8f5,Ga8e8] Not only Black's position is pleasant aesthetically, but it is also a very good one!} *

