1. e4 c5 2. Na3 {A weird developing move which is nevertheless seen at a GM level on a regular basis. White keeps flexibility in the centre, but the knight is misplaced on [a3]! Black won't have any problem if they know what they are doing.} Nc6 3. Bb5 {I am giving two options here. In one of them, there is a repetition which is not very reasonable to avoid. So I guess your choice will very much depend on the level of your opponent and your mood on the game's day!} d5 $5 {Pretty rare and with obvious surprise value!} 4. Nf3 {A novelty introducing an interesting pawn sac.} dxe4 5. Ne5 Qd5 {[%cal Gd5c6,Gd5e5]} 6. Nac4 {[%cal Gc4e5]} Nf6 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. b3 {[%csl Gc5,Gc6] It is quite obvious that White gets some compensation as Black's pawn structure is damaged, and we also have better development.} g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Bb2 Ba6 {[%cal Ga6f1] A weird position. The engine is showing zeros, but I would say that White still has full compensation for the missing pawn.} 11. Re1 O-O {[%cal Gf6e8,Gf8d8] We'll follow up with ...[Rd8] and ...[Ne8], with pressure.} *

