1. e4 c5 2. Na3 {A weird developing move which is nevertheless seen at a GM level on a regular basis. White keeps flexibility in the centre, but the knight is misplaced on [a3]! Black won't have any problem if they know what they are doing.} Nc6 3. Bb5 {I am giving two options here. In one of them, there is a repetition which is not very reasonable to avoid. So I guess your choice will very much depend on the level of your opponent and your mood on the game's day!} e6 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gd7d5] Much more standard and making a lot of sense to me as we are preparing ...[d5], controlling [c4] and basically cutting the [a3]-knight out of the game.} 4. Nf3 {Transposing into a 3...e6 Rossolimo where [Na3] is not supposed to scare us, to say the least.} Nge7 {[%cal Ga7a6,Ge7c6]} 5. O-O a6 6. Bxc6 {Giving up the bishop pair and playing on dark squares is always an option in such cases.} Nxc6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qc7 $1 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gc7d6,Gf8d6] Reinforcing the control of the important [d6]-square and preventing [Bf4].} 9. Nxc6 (9. Nc4 b5 {just helps Black. ...[Bb7] comes easier.}) 9... dxc6 10. Nc4 {[%cal Ge4e5]} (10. Be3 b5 {That's the whole point. It will be hard for the knight to come back into the game.} 11. c4 Be7 {followed by ...[O-O].}) 10... b5 11. Nd2 Bd6 {[%csl Gc8,Gd6] The white knight came back on a decent square, but Black is slightly better due to his bishops.} 12. Qh5 O-O 13. Nf3 e5 {[%csl Gc8,Gd6][%cal Gf7f6,Gc8e6] Black is a bit more comfortable: bishops, more space on the queenside, and a clear plan.} *

