1. e4 c5 2. Na3 {A weird developing move which is nevertheless seen at a GM level on a regular basis. White keeps flexibility in the centre, but the knight is misplaced on [a3]! Black won't have any problem if they know what they are doing.} Nc6 3. Bb5 {I am giving two options here. In one of them, there is a repetition which is not very reasonable to avoid. So I guess your choice will very much depend on the level of your opponent and your mood on the game's day!} e6 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gd7d5] Much more standard and making a lot of sense to me as we are preparing ...[d5], controlling [c4] and basically cutting the [a3]-knight out of the game.} 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. e5 $5 {[%cal Ga3c4]} ({The most direct and aggressive approach, which actually loses a pawn.} 5. Nc4 $2 {is simply bad due to} d5 $1 {.}) (5. d3 {fails to impress. Black immediately gets the centre and controls the crucial [c4]-square.} d5 $1 6. Nf3 Ne7 7. O-O Ng6 8. c4 Be7 {We obviously don’t react to the [c4] push. White will lose a lot of tempi trying to reactivate their [a3]-knight.}) 5... Qg5 {[%cal Gg5g2,Gg5e5]} 6. Nf3 $1 Qxg2 7. Rg1 Qh3 {[%cal Gg1g3,Gh3h5,Gg3g5] The queen can't get trapped but also can't avoid being harassed by the white rook Rg3-[Rg5]} 8. d3 {[%cal Ga3c4]} Ba6 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gh3h5,Gh5f7]} 9. Rg3 Qh5 10. Rg5 Qh3 {Both sides should take the repetition.} *

