1. e4 c5 2. Be2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd2d3] This looks very innocent and modest, but many strong GMs have played it, so it should be taken seriously. The idea is generally to continue with [f4] and [d3] and attack on the kingside.} Nc6 3. Nf3 {To my understanding, that move is not in the spirit of the 2.Be2 line, but it is a decent developing, so it should be checked!} Nf6 4. Nc3 ({After} 4. d3 d5 5. Nbd2 e5 {, we get an Old Indian with reversed colours. Even a tempo down, it should be better for Black with such a space advantage.} 6. c3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. a3 {This is how Black generally plays in the Old Indian, a defence which has quite a bad reputation for a reason. This looks very unimpressive.} h6 9. b4 a6 10. Bb2 Be6 {Black has played very logically and the space advantage guarantees us a pleasant edge.If 8.Re1 , we close down the centre with 8...d4 as White obviously wanted to take on [d5] in order to open the e-file for the rook. 9.Nc4 Qc7 10.a4 Be6Ν Logical but new. Black will follow with ...[Nd7] and then expand on the queenside.}) 4... e5 {Same setup than in the 3.Nc3 Anti-Sicilian, and it is pretty clear that White will lose a tempo to put their light-squared bishop on its natural square [c4].} ({Not a fan of opening the centre immediately with} 4... d5 {. White is well developed, after all.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. O-O Nf6 {Now,} 7. d4 {is played anyway, and clearly White has seized the initiative after} cxd4 8. Nb5 {.}) 5. O-O {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4]} Be7 6. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e4,Ge2c4]} (6. Bc4 {immediately gives Black the opportunity to at least equalize.} Nxe4 $1 {and now} 7. Bxf7+ {is simply really bad.} Kxf7 8. Nxe4 d5 {White is getting steamrolled.After 7.Nxe4 d5 8.Bb5 dxe4 9.Nxe5 Qd5! Defence and attack! 10.Nxc6 bxc6 , Black is pretty active but have a lousy pawn structure. Probably gives an equal fight overall. 11.Ba4 O-O with ...[Ba6] and ...[Bf6] as ideas.}) 6... O-O 7. Bc4 d6 8. d3 {Now we are getting a normal line with the same structure as in the 3.Nc3 e5 chapter but obviously, White has lost a tempo by moving the bishop twice, and the rook on [e1] is not ideally placed, as White is losing the [f4] ideas.} Be6 9. a4 ({A typical idea in such structure. Randomly taking space with rook pawns is very fashionable these days! Another typical idea is} 9. Bg5 {to exchange the dark-squared bishop for the knight on [f6] in order to get the control of the [d5]-square.} Nd7 $1 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {and Black has managed to exchange the bishop on [e7], which is not exactly the best piece in our position. The knight will return to [f6]. Black is completely fine.}) 9... h6 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge7d8]} 10. Bd2 Qd7 {[%csl Gc5,Gd6,Ge5][%cal Ge7d8,Gd8a5] Our plan is pretty clear now: activating the bishop on [e7] by getting it out of the barrier we created with [c5], [e5], [d6].} 11. Nd5 Bd8 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ge4d5,Gc6e7]} 12. a5 Bxd5 13. Bxd5 (13. exd5 $6 Ne7 {and we pick up the [d5]-pawn.}) 13... Nxd5 14. exd5 Nb4 $5 {Not forced at all but I like the idea kind of forcing White to take on [b4].} 15. Bxb4 cxb4 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c5] Black has excellent play thanks to the c-line and the weak [a5]-pawn.} 16. d4 exd4 (16... e4 $5 {is also possible.} 17. Rxe4 Qb5 {and we are getting back the [d5]-pawn. The position is equal.}) 17. Qxd4 Rc8 {[%csl Rc2]} 18. Qxa7 Bf6 {[%cal Gf6b2,Gc8c2]} (18... Bf6 {Black has good counterplay. For instance, the tempting} 19. a6 {could end up with Black being a bit better.} Bxb2 20. axb7 Rb8 {and the pawn drops.}) *

