1. e4 c5 2. f4 {Showing aggressive intentions right away. This has been played by many GMs. Once again, if we know what we are doing, this line is not dangerous.} d5 $1 {The principled reaction. Counter attacking in the centre immediately!} 3. Nc3 {Definitely a poor reaction as Black can grab space easily.} d4 $1 4. Nce2 Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 5. d3 e5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4,Ge5,Gf4] Fighting for control of all the dark squares in the centre.} 6. Nf3 exf4 {[%csl Ge5] That's generally the way to do it when White can't capture the g-pawn. The goal is now to occupy the [e5]-square with a minor piece, preferably a knight.} 7. Bxf4 (7. Nxf4 {giving up on the control of the [e5]-square can't be satisfactory for White. 7...[Bd6] 8. [Be2] [Nge7] 9. [O-O] [O-O] and ...[Ng6] fighting for the [e5]-square.}) 7... h6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg7g5,Gf8g7,Gg5g4]} 8. g3 ({In the spirit of the King's Indian.} 8. h4 {stops ...[g5] but weakens the [g4]-square, which looks ideal for the knight. After} Nf6 {, our knight is ready to jump to [g4], from where it eyes [e5] and [e3].}) (8. Ng3 {preparing to finish the development and pretending nothing is happening but it is happening!} g5 $1 9. Bc1 g4 10. Nd2 h5 {Black has an easy follow-up with ...[Be6], ...[Bd6] and ..Ne5, and extremely good!}) ({Counterattacking in the centre makes sense but that's not really doing anything.} 8. c3 Nf6 9. cxd4 cxd4 {and White has to stop ...[Bb4].} 10. a3 Be7 {followed by castle, and White's gesticulations on the queenside didn't really improve their situation.}) 8... g5 $1 {[%csl Ge5]} 9. Bd2 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gg4e5]} 10. Bg2 Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e5]} 11. O-O Bg7 {[%csl Re2,Rg2][%cal Gc8e6,Gg4e5] Black has excellent prospects, while some of White's minor pieces will be hard to activate.} *

