1. e4 c5 2. f4 {Showing aggressive intentions right away. This has been played by many GMs. Once again, if we know what we are doing, this line is not dangerous.} d5 $1 {The principled reaction. Counter attacking in the centre immediately!} 3. Bb5+ {Speeding up development but not really threatening anything.} Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {Again, White has a choice on how to protect the [e4]-pawn.} 5. Nc3 {Once again this allows Black to gain space with a tempo.} d4 6. Nce2 d3 $1 {[%csl Rc1]} 7. cxd3 Qxd3 {[%csl Rc1,Gd3][%cal Gd3e4,Gb8c6,Gc6b4] The queen on [d3] is really annoying, controlling the light squares and preventing the [c1]-bishop's development.} 8. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3e4]} (8. Qa4+ Nc6 9. Nh3 Nf6 10. Nf2 Qd7 11. d3 e5 12. O-O exf4 13. Bxf4 Be7 {and the [d3]-pawn is a clear target for Black, while White doesn't have any. Black is doing well!This is much safer and sane than 9...b5!? , a move for people who are feeling adventurous! 10.Qa6 Qxe4 11.O-O Nf6 Black is doing well with ...[g6] and ...[Bg7] to follow, but the position is very messy.}) 8... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gc6d4]} 9. Nf3 e6 {[%csl Re1]} 10. Qe2 {A sad necessity to be able to castle.} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gb4c2] Not releasing the pressure on White's cramped position.} 11. Rb1 Rd8 {[%cal Gd3e2,Gb4d3]} 12. a3 Qxe2+ 13. Kxe2 Nd3 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gd3f4]} 14. g3 {[%cal Gf3e1]} h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4] A nice prophylactic move as White will have to go [Ne1] at some point in order to get rid of the annoying knight on [d3] giving Black the option to go ...[h4].} 15. Ne1 Nxe1 16. Rxe1 h4 17. g4 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7c6,Gc6d4,Gf8e7] We get another nice square for the other knight on [d4]!} *

