1. e4 c5 2. f4 {Showing aggressive intentions right away. This has been played by many GMs. Once again, if we know what we are doing, this line is not dangerous.} d5 $1 {The principled reaction. Counter attacking in the centre immediately!} 3. Bb5+ {Speeding up development but not really threatening anything.} Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {Again, White has a choice on how to protect the [e4]-pawn.} 5. d3 Nc6 6. Nf3 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ge8c8,Gf8d6] Reinforcing the centre and keeping our options open.} 7. Qe2 {Preventing ...[Bd6] as the [d5]-pawn would be hanging in that case.} ({After} 7. Nc3 O-O-O $5 {, the king is actually very safe on the queenside. This is obviously anything but forced.} 8. O-O f6 $5 {Quite an interesting and fresh position. Once again we have a clear on how to open the kingside while it will require more creativity for White to open the queenside!}) 7... dxe4 $1 8. dxe4 Nd4 $1 (8... Nd4 {A nice idea based on the misplaced queen on e2. If} 9. Nxd4 cxd4 {, Black manages to create a weakness on [c2] without much effort.}) 9. Qd3 Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d3]} 10. Nbd2 Nf6 {It is actually White who has to be careful to keep the balance as the queen on [d3] is very unstable.} 11. O-O ({Or} 11. c3 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 Be7 {followed by ...[O-O] and ...[Qc6].}) 11... Qc6 {[%cal Gd8d3,Gf8e7] We'll complete development with ...[Be7]. The white queen is sitting uncomfortably on [d3].} *

