1. e4 c5 2. f4 {Showing aggressive intentions right away. This has been played by many GMs. Once again, if we know what we are doing, this line is not dangerous.} d5 $1 {The principled reaction. Counter attacking in the centre immediately!} 3. e5 $2 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf5g4] That's simply a very poor version of the French Defence for White.} Nc6 4. Nf3 (4. Bb5 Bd7 {setting up the typical ...[Nxe5] trick.} 5. Nf3 $2 Nxe5 $1 6. fxe5 Bxb5 7. e6 {is a good try pretending everything went according to the plan but two pawns are simply too many.} fxe6 8. d3 Nf6 {followed by ...[g6] and ...[Bg7].}) {5.Bxc6 Bxc6 6.d4 e6 7.Nf3 Nh6 8.c3 Nf5 9.O-O cxd4 10.cxd4 h5 stabilising the knight on [f5].The lack of light-squared bishop means that it will be difficult for White to create any sort of attack. Meanwhile, Black will complete development with ...[Be7] and gain space on the queenside with the a-pawn.} 4... Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e6,Ga8c8]} 5. Bb5 Rc8 6. O-O e6 {[%csl Gd5,Ge6,Gf5] The bishop is out of the pawn chain, which is generally quite bad news for White.} 7. d3 Nge7 {[%cal Gh7h6]} 8. Nh4 h6 9. Nxf5 Nxf5 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Ga7a6] With such a nice knight on [f5] and a good control of the centre, we can conclude that the opening phase has been a success for Black!} *

