1. e4 c5 2. f4 {Showing aggressive intentions right away. This has been played by many GMs. Once again, if we know what we are doing, this line is not dangerous.} d5 $1 {The principled reaction. Counter attacking in the centre immediately!} 3. exd5 (3. d3 Nc6 {transposes here.}) 3... Nf6 $5 {[%cal Gf6d5] The most logical as it is desirable to take back the pawn with the knight, but this involves a pawn sac for which Black will get excellent compensation.} 4. Bb5+ (4. c4 $6 {is simply bad as Black gets wonderful compensation right away.} e6 5. dxe6 Bxe6 {with a quick ...[Nc6] eyeing [d4] and ...[Bd6]. That's a much worse version for White than after 4.Bb5+ as White still have to develop their bishop.}) 4... Bd7 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 6. Nf3 (6. Nc3 Nxd5 7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. Qf3 {White is already trying to liquidate and get an endgame where they'll be worse as they will always regret having pushed the pawn to [f4].} e6 $5 {Playing the endgame is OK... but on our terms! If instead 8.Nf3 Nc6 , as usual, we'll follow up with ...[g6] with a nice control of the [d4]-square.}) 6... Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5f4,Gb8c6]} 7. Ne5 Qe6 8. O-O Nc6 9. Nc3 {Trying to develop quickly and confuse matters.} g6 {Just finishing development, White is not threatening much.} 10. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3d5]} ({Or} 10. Re1 Bg7 {.}) 10... Rd8 $1 {[%cal Gd8d5,Gc6d4,Gd5b4,Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Just protecting [d5] and keeping the options open for any knight jump.} *

