1. e4 c5 2. g3 ({White wants to develop their bishop on g2 as in the Closed Sicilian but without playing} 2. Nc3 {to keep the option to go [c3]-[d4] one day. Sounds clever, but that makes the ...[d5] push available for Black.}) 2... d5 $1 3. exd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Gd5h1]} 4. Nf3 Bg4 (4... Nc6 $5 {is also possible and basically ends up in a quick repetition if both sides are playing the best moves. Guess we are already more ambitious!} 5. d3 Nd4 6. Bg2 Bh3 $1 {Typical but nice tactic.} 7. Bxh3 $1 Nxf3+ 8. Kf1 {looks very promising for Black but [Bg2] is coming, so we don't have anything better than repeating the moves:} Nd2+ 9. Kg1 Nf3+ {.}) 5. Bg2 (5. Be2 $6 {is a painful move to make when you just played [g3] three moves before. Unsurprisingly it is also not very good.} Nc6 6. h3 Bh5 {with very easy development: ...[Nf6] and ..e6.}) 5... Qe6+ $1 6. Kf1 (6. Qe2 Qxe2+ 7. Kxe2 Nc6 {is immediately very good for Black. ...[Nd4] and ...[e5] is a strong follow-up.}) 6... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Ge8c8]} 7. h3 (7. d3 Bh3 {Black is now preventing White's [h3] and will keep developing with long castle and ...[e5] after moving the queen.}) 7... Bh5 8. d3 Qd7 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8f6]} 9. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5]} e6 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gf8e7]} 10. Nbd2 Nf6 {[%csl Rf1,Rh1] Seems like a normal position except for White’s king on [f1] and the rook on [h1].} 11. Nb3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge3c5,Gb3c5]} (11. g4 Bg6 12. Nc4 Bd6 {White seems to be active but the weaknesses remain and they didn't solve the awkward position of the king on [f1]. ...[Nd5] eyeing [f4] is coming.}) 11... Qc7 $1 12. Bxc5 ({After} 12. Nxc5 Nd5 {, ...[Nxe3] threatens to make White's position collapse.} 13. Qd2 Nxe3+ 14. Qxe3 Nb4 {Black is taking over. The [c5]-knight is loose and ...[Nxc2] is a threat.} 15. Nxb7 Qxb7 16. Nd4 {and Black has} Nd5 {with a huge advantage.}) 12... Bxc5 13. Nxc5 O-O {[%cal Gc6d4,Gc7b6] White did win a pawn but the position is opened up now and Black is fully ready for concrete actions as the black king is now in a safe place.} 14. Nb3 (14. c3 Qb6 15. Na4 Qb5 {White may have a way to survive this but for an OTB game that just looks like as a very unpleasant position to play. If instead 15.b4 a5 16.a3 Qc7! ...[b6] will come next, and White has just weakened the queenside.}) 14... e5 {[%cal Ga8d8,Ge5e4,Ga7a5,Ga5a4] White will have a hard time countering Black's active play.} *

