1. e4 c5 2. a4 {To be honest, this move was not supposed to be in the course, but it was played by the very strong theoretician Rustam Kasimdzhanov in a Bundesliga game in 2024.} e6 $1 {That's my favorite and was played by the Iranian GM Amin Tabatabaei.} ({If we go for our regular} 2... Nc6 {, White actually has a point.} 3. Bb5 $1 Nd4 {and now the bishop is protected and White can play} 4. Nf3 {I am actually not sure this is a good version of the Rossolimo. This is clearly White's point. Or 3...g6 4.Bxc6 and again White hasn't commited their knight to [f3] yet, which gives them some extra options.}) 3. f4 (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bb5 Nge7 {We didn't get our Rossolimo . Fair enough, but we get the Rossolimo 3...e6 a tempo up, as the [a4] move doesn't make sense.}) 3... d5 4. d3 {This is actually how the game Kasimdzhanov-Tabatabaei continued. Obviously, it feels playable for White, but we can't say that White got any opening advantage. I just recommend to follow the game but I did prepare an improvement for Black, as White ended up winning.} Nc6 5. Nf3 Be7 6. Be2 Nh6 $1 {[%csl Gf5] I really like this move. If White decides to close down the position with [e5], then we are ready to jump on [f5].} 7. O-O O-O {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7]} 8. Ne5 {Pretty surprising idea from White, but guess it makes sense, as Black was already ready to finish their development with ...[b6]-...[Bb7].} Nd4 $1 {Just collecting the light-squared bishop. Black is doing fine.} 9. Nc3 f6 10. Nf3 Nxe2+ 11. Qxe2 b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] Just finishing our development. Let's see what White does.} 12. f5 {[%cal Gc1h6,Gf5e6,Ge4d5] Trying to get some action before Black is fully developed.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3] Nice intermediate move!} 13. Nb1 Nf7 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7][%cal Ge6f5] White has to make a decision now about their pawn on [f5]. Black has very nice prospects with the bishop pair.} *

