1. e4 c5 2. b3 {Mainly a surprise weapon.} g6 $5 {I've always liked this concept from an aesthetic point of view. White wants to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8] and we immediately make the exact same claim! I've played 1.b3 g6 a lot with very decent results. The addition of 1.e4 c5 doesn’t make it worse for Black.} 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({It's hard to take seriously the double fianchetto.} 4. g3 d6 5. Bg2 e5 $1 {Shutting down both White's bishops at once!} 6. Ne2 Bg7 7. O-O Nc6 {Black has multiple ways to play that lead to a very comfortable position. E.g.: ...[Be6] and ...[h5].}) 4... Bg7 {[%cal Gf6e4] Be aware: both knights c3 and [f6] are potentially pinned and therefore the [e4]-pawn is already hanging!} 5. Nd5 O-O 6. Nxf6+ exf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf8e8] White lost a couple of tempi while Black was developing and already has to be extremely careful.} 7. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4d5] The only decent way to protect the [e4]-pawn.} Re8 8. Bd5 Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ga6c7]} 9. Ne2 Nc7 (9... Nb4 {also possible but it doesn't make any difference as we will anyway take on [d5].}) 10. O-O Nxd5 11. exd5 b5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd7d6,Gh7h5,Gh5h4] Preparing to open lines for the light-squared bishop.} 12. c4 ({After} 12. d4 f5 {, the pin is rather unpleasant for White.}) 12... d6 {Unforced but the pawn sac is promising for Black.} 13. cxb5 a6 14. bxa6 Bxa6 15. Re1 Bb7 16. Nc3 {Trying to keep the extra pawn.} Rxe1+ 17. Qxe1 f5 {[%cal Gg7b2,Gb7d5] Black has active pieces and an excellent game.} *

