1. e4 c5 2. b3 {Mainly a surprise weapon.} g6 $5 {I've always liked this concept from an aesthetic point of view. White wants to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8] and we immediately make the exact same claim! I've played 1.b3 g6 a lot with very decent results. The addition of 1.e4 c5 doesn’t make it worse for Black.} 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({It's hard to take seriously the double fianchetto.} 4. g3 d6 5. Bg2 e5 $1 {Shutting down both White's bishops at once!} 6. Ne2 Bg7 7. O-O Nc6 {Black has multiple ways to play that lead to a very comfortable position. E.g.: ...[Be6] and ...[h5].}) 4... Bg7 {[%cal Gf6e4] Be aware: both knights c3 and [f6] are potentially pinned and therefore the [e4]-pawn is already hanging!} 5. e5 {Natural but too optimistic. The [e5]-pawn will be a weakness.} Nh5 6. d4 (6. g4 Nf4 7. Nge2 Ne6 {The [e5]-pawn is weak.} 8. f4 {is way too optimistic.} d6 9. exd6 Nc6 $1 {and the white king will likely pay a high price for it. Our knight will land on [d4].}) 6... cxd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Qd2 Bxe5 {Can you count? Nevertheless, White will play long castle and have some compensations. Hard to believe it will be enough to compensate the missing extra central pawn.} (8... Bxe5 {Mind that it is a tad too early for} 9. O-O-O {? due to} Bf4 $1 {That's what we call a cold shower!}) 9. Nge2 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gg2g4,Gf2f4,Ge1c1]} Bg7 10. O-O-O Nf6 11. h3 h5 (11... O-O 12. g4 {actually gives White acceptable compensation.}) 12. Kb1 Kf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gd7d6,Gc8d7,Gg7h6] A clever move. The rook on [h8] is very useful preventing [g4] ideas, and the king will find a safe place on [g7].} *

