1. e4 c5 2. b3 {Mainly a surprise weapon.} g6 $5 {I've always liked this concept from an aesthetic point of view. White wants to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8] and we immediately make the exact same claim! I've played 1.b3 g6 a lot with very decent results. The addition of 1.e4 c5 doesn’t make it worse for Black.} 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 ({The immediate} 4. Qf3 {is a very superficial way of playing the position.} d6 $1 {White was threatening [e5], though.} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nd5 O-O $1 7. Nxf6+ Bxf6 8. Bxf6 exf6 {White has weakened their dark squares, and ...[Nc6]-...[Nd4]/...[Ne5] is an idea. Meanwhile, it is very questionable what the queen is doing on [f3].}) 4... Nd5 5. Qf3 {This was tried numerous times by none other than the creative Morozevich} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2]} 6. Na3 Bg7 7. e6 f6 8. c3 (8. exd7+ Bxd7 {helps the bishop get to [c6].}) 8... N4c6 9. Qe3 d5 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gd5d4] Planning to collect the [e6]-pawn without spoiling the pawn structure.} 10. Qxc5 Bxe6 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2][%cal Ge6f7,Gb8d7,Ge7e5] Black will occupy the centre and get a harmonious development while the white pieces on [a3] and [b2] are misplaced.} *

