1. e4 c5 2. b3 {Mainly a surprise weapon.} g6 $5 {I've always liked this concept from an aesthetic point of view. White wants to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8] and we immediately make the exact same claim! I've played 1.b3 g6 a lot with very decent results. The addition of 1.e4 c5 doesn’t make it worse for Black.} 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 ({The immediate} 4. Qf3 {is a very superficial way of playing the position.} d6 $1 {White was threatening [e5], though.} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nd5 O-O $1 7. Nxf6+ Bxf6 8. Bxf6 exf6 {White has weakened their dark squares, and ...[Nc6]-...[Nd4]/...[Ne5] is an idea. Meanwhile, it is very questionable what the queen is doing on [f3].}) 4... Nd5 5. Nc3 (5. e6 $2 {is tempting and bad! It just helps Black developing.} f6 6. exd7+ {Carlsen took with the queen here, and} Qxd7 {(also gives a better game for Black. I do prefer my engine as well! taking with the bishop!) 6...Bxd7 7.Bc4 Bc6 with ...[Nf4] and ...[Bh6] ideas.}) 5... Nxc3 6. dxc3 {[%cal Gd1d2] Counterintuitive, but it does give the [d2]-square for the queen and therefore, it's an effective way to prepare long castle.} Nc6 7. f4 d6 {Challenging White's centre immediately.} 8. Bb5 (8. exd6 {runs into} Bh6 $1 {Fast development for the initiative!} 9. g3 O-O $1 {and White's king in the centre is a major concern. The e-file will soon open. If instead 9.dxe7 , Black gets the pawn back after 9...Qxe7 as [f4] is hanging. Black has the better pawn structure and a lead in development.}) 8... Bh6 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gh6f4,Ge8g8] Winning a tempo on [f4] and making sure we will castle on the next move while the white king is still on [e1].} 9. Ne2 O-O {[%cal Gd6e5]} 10. c4 {[%cal Gb2e5]} (10. exd6 exd6 11. O-O Bg7 $1 {and the [b2]-bishop will be hard to activate. Black is better. 11.c4 opens the long diagonal for the bishop, but 11...Bg4 with ...[Re8] coming is simply bad for White.}) 10... dxe5 11. Bxc6 (11. fxe5 $2 Nb4 {and suddenly White's position collapses! The bishop is stranded on [b5], and [c2] is a problem.}) 11... bxc6 12. Bxe5 Bf5 {[%csl Rc2] White has to be very precise in order to keep the game more or less balanced.} 13. O-O Qxd1 14. Raxd1 f6 (14... Bxc2 {is a bit too hasty.} 15. Rd2 Bf5 16. Ng3 {White will double up on the d-file and is getting decent compensation for the pawn.}) 15. Bc3 Rad8 {[%cal Gf5c2] Keeping the threat of taking on [c2] without giving up the d-line. White will have a tough time defending the endgame.} *

