1. e4 c5 2. b3 {Mainly a surprise weapon.} g6 $5 {I've always liked this concept from an aesthetic point of view. White wants to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8] and we immediately make the exact same claim! I've played 1.b3 g6 a lot with very decent results. The addition of 1.e4 c5 doesn’t make it worse for Black.} 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 ({The immediate} 4. Qf3 {is a very superficial way of playing the position.} d6 $1 {White was threatening [e5], though.} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nd5 O-O $1 7. Nxf6+ Bxf6 8. Bxf6 exf6 {White has weakened their dark squares, and ...[Nc6]-...[Nd4]/...[Ne5] is an idea. Meanwhile, it is very questionable what the queen is doing on [f3].}) 4... Nd5 5. Nc3 (5. e6 $2 {is tempting and bad! It just helps Black developing.} f6 6. exd7+ {Carlsen took with the queen here, and} Qxd7 {(also gives a better game for Black. I do prefer my engine as well! taking with the bishop!) 6...Bxd7 7.Bc4 Bc6 with ...[Nf4] and ...[Bh6] ideas.}) 5... Nxc3 6. Bxc3 Bg7 (6... Bg7 {Now,} 7. Nf3 {is White's most frequent move, but way too slow.} O-O 8. Bc4 Nc6 9. O-O d5 10. exd6 Qxd6 {(Black has a nice development and more space in the centre. The next few moves are very natural ...[Bf5] and ...[Rd8] and Black has the better chances.)}) 7. h4 Nc6 $5 {This feels like the 'simple solution'.} 8. e6 ({The usual trick. If} 8. f4 d5 9. h5 Bh6 {, now that the centre is closed, we are changing our plans: the king will be safer on the queenside.} 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Bb2 Be6 {followed by ...[Qd7] and long castle.}) 8... O-O $1 9. exf7+ Rxf7 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. h5 d5 {Black has the centre and a nice development. The h-file will open up but hard to imagine how White will manage to create a serious attack with such a poor development.} *

