1. e4 c5 2. b3 {Mainly a surprise weapon.} g6 $5 {I've always liked this concept from an aesthetic point of view. White wants to occupy the diagonal [a1]-[h8] and we immediately make the exact same claim! I've played 1.b3 g6 a lot with very decent results. The addition of 1.e4 c5 doesn’t make it worse for Black.} 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 ({The immediate} 4. Qf3 {is a very superficial way of playing the position.} d6 $1 {White was threatening [e5], though.} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nd5 O-O $1 7. Nxf6+ Bxf6 8. Bxf6 exf6 {White has weakened their dark squares, and ...[Nc6]-...[Nd4]/...[Ne5] is an idea. Meanwhile, it is very questionable what the queen is doing on [f3].}) 4... Nd5 5. Nc3 (5. e6 $2 {is tempting and bad! It just helps Black developing.} f6 6. exd7+ {Carlsen took with the queen here, and} Qxd7 {(also gives a better game for Black. I do prefer my engine as well! taking with the bishop!) 6...Bxd7 7.Bc4 Bc6 with ...[Nf4] and ...[Bh6] ideas.}) 5... Nxc3 6. Bxc3 Bg7 (6... Bg7 {Now,} 7. Nf3 {is White's most frequent move, but way too slow.} O-O 8. Bc4 Nc6 9. O-O d5 10. exd6 Qxd6 {(Black has a nice development and more space in the centre. The next few moves are very natural ...[Bf5] and ...[Rd8] and Black has the better chances.)}) 7. h4 d5 $5 {This has been played by my countryman MVL. If you know his style, you have already understood that the position will get as sharp as it gets!} 8. exd6 (8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Qxd4 h5 $1 {Killing White's counterplay on the h-file. ...[Be6] and ...[O-O] are coming next.}) 8... O-O $1 9. dxe7 {if White doesn't take that pawn, Black will just take back on [d6] and get an excellent game.} Re8 10. Qf3 Rxe7+ ({Keeping more flexibility for the black queen to join the attack on the queenside.} 10... Qxe7+ 11. Ne2 {was better for White in a game between Andreikin and MVL.}) 11. Ne2 (11. Be2 Nc6 {with ...[Nd4] ideas.}) 11... Bxc3 12. Qxc3 (12. dxc3 Bf5 {Black is simply winning. White's king is stuck in the centre.}) 12... Nc6 13. O-O-O Bf5 {[%cal Gc6b4]} 14. Qxc5 ({Greed at its best! The engine gives the following line:} 14. h5 Nb4 15. Kb2 Bxc2 16. hxg6 Bxg6 17. Nf4 Nd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 {with a balanced position.}) 14... Rc8 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc8c2,Gc6b4,Gc6d4] Game over! White's position collapses on [c2].} *

